<HTML>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" TEXT="#000000" LINK="cb0005" VLINK="obo370" ALINK="008080">


<HEAD><TITLE>Jackson Hewitt Tax Service..Augusta Georgia..SERVDirect Directory</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<A NAME="jhtop">
You may select one of the following categories:<BR>
<IMG ALIGN=RIGHT HEIGHT=165 WIDTH=150 SRC ="jh.gif"><BR>

<A HREF="#jhse"><IMG BORDER="0" ALT="Self Employed" SRC="jhse.gif"></A>
<A HREF="#jhmp"><IMG BORDER="0" ALT="Military Personnel" SRC="jhmp.gif"></A> 
<A HREF="#jhre"><IMG BORDER="0" ALT="Real Estate" SRC="jhre.gif"></A> 
<A HREF="#jhrp"><IMG BORDER="0" ALT="Rental Property" SRC="jhrp.gif"></A> 
<A HREF="#jhsc"><IMG BORDER="0" ALT="Senior Citizens" SRC="jhsc.gif"></A><BR><BR>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>4115 Columbia Rd<BR>Martinez, Georgia 30907<BR> Ph. 706-855-6726</B></FONT><BR><A HREF="/georgia/augusta/coupons/cp102.html"><I>See our Coupon</I></A><BR><BR>

<CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=5><B>
THE INDUSTRY LEADER<BR><FONT SIZE=3>In Computerized Tax Service</B></FONT>
</CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>
P</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=3>ractically everything connected with the filing of a return is done by computer and over the phone lines at Jackson Hewitt, creating an atmosphere of efficiency. With an emphasis on customer service and quick turnaround, franchise
s and branch offices transmit returns daily to company headquarters. There, every return is double checked for errors before being transmitted to the IRS center.
<P>
Hewitt's program has three important advantages over hand-prepared returns:
<UL>
First, the software is an expert at applying the practical aspects of constantly changing tax laws to a taxpayer's specific circumstances.<P>
Second, no matter how may returns have been done, the program doesn't get tired and forget to ask importants questions.<P>
Finally, it doesn't make mathematical errors.
</UL> 
<BR>
<P><CENTER><FONT SIZE=5>
<B>HIGH TECH PROVIDES THE FREEDOM FOR HIGH TOUCH</B></CENTER>
<P><FONT SIZE =4><B>I</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=3>n today's competitive business environment, service business such as Jackson Hewitt must focus on the needs of the customer. Jackson Hewitt has recognized these needs and is again leading the way to provide the
 best service in the tax preparation industry.
<P>
Jackson Hewitt is showing Americans how today's technology can make filing tax returns less painful. We've been banking, shopping, writing, and keeping books more efficiently through technology for years.
Why not save money by applying computer technology to doing our taxes?
<UL><B>&quot;No one's ever asked me all those questions before.&quot;</B></UL>                                      
That's a common observation among Jackson Hewitt's first - time customers. Not only does the computer - driven tax interview ensure that no deductions are missed, it frees the preparer from the burden of remembering all those questions and from the pressu
re of making mistakes. Instead of wading through stacks of manuals and piles of paperwork, Jackson Hewitt employees can be attentive and dedicated to the customers sitting in front of them. This turns what used to be a painful experience into a friendly, 
comfortable one.

<P>
<A NAME="jhse"><IMG ALT="Self Employed" SRC="jhseline.gif">

<P><CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><B>THINGS TO KNOW:</B></CENTER></FONT><BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4><B>
T</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=3>he tax requirements of a self-employed indiviual are very different from those of an ordinary wage earner. Each situation may present a number of confusing tax questions. Here are some of the things that you need to take into cons
ideration.</FONT><FONT SIZE=3>
<UL>
<LI>How much Social Security and Medicaid taxes, FUTA taxes and Workmen's Compensation will you pay?
<LI>Will you have more than one trade or business?
<LI>What if your attempt to operate a business fails?
<LI>Should your financial calculations be based on a calendar year or a fiscal year?
<LI>Will you operate as a sole proprietor, an independant contractor or a statutory employee?
</UL>
</FONT>
<A HREF="#jhtop"><IMG BORDER="0" ALT="Back to Top" ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="arrow.gif"></A>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4> A qualified tax preparer can help you find answers to these questions.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="jhmp"><IMG ALT="Military Personnel" SRC="jhmpline.gif">
<P>
<P><CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><B>THINGS TO KNOW:</B></FONT></CENTER><BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>A</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=3>s a member of the United States Armed Forces, there are benefits you receive which may not be taxable.
<UL>
<LI>Dependent allowances or education.
<LI>Combat Pay
<LI>Disability Benefits
<LI>Medical Benefits
<LI>Family separation allowances
<LI>Educational assistance
<LI>Burial and death services
<LI>Overseas cost-of-living allowances
</UL>
Also, state tax laws differ greatly which makes it difficult to keep track of what you need to do as far as your state tax return is concerned.  Individual states do not tax their residents' military pay if they are stationed out of state and spent 30 day
s or less in the state.
<P>
<A HREF="#jhtop"><IMG BORDER="0" ALT="Back to Top" ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="arrow.gif"></A>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4>If you are unsure about your tax obligations, the Professionals at Jackson Hewitt Tax Service are ready to help.
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="jhre"><IMG ALT="Real Estate" SRC="jhreline.gif">
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><B>BUYING A HOME</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>T</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=3>here's a lot to consider when first purchasing a home. The tax implications of the following items is very important to the bottom line on your tax return.
<P>
Most of the costs incurred when buying a new home are not deductible.  However, payments such as mortgage interest, real estate taxes, and most points paid on your loan value are in fact deductible on SCHEDULE A.<BR>  These items are listed on your settle
ment statement. If you purchase a home after December 31, 1990, you may now deduct seller-paid points.<BR>  You can amend your returns for 1991, 1992, and 1993 in order to take advantage of this change.


<P>
<A HREF="#jhtop"><IMG BORDER="0" ALT="Back to Top" ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="arrow.gif"></A>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4>Consult your local Jackson Hewitt Tax Service professional for more information about real estate and your taxes. 
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="jhrp"><IMG ALT="Rental Property" SRC="jhrpline.gif">
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><B>THINGS TO KNOW:</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>

<FONT SIZE=4><B>I</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=3>f you rent only part of your property, certain expenses must be divided between the part used for profit and the part used for personal purposes.  Treat the two as separate properties.  The same applies to a vacati
on home which you use for both rental and personal purposes.
<P>  
If you share ownership of rental property, you may deduct your share of the rental expenses paid.
<P>
Some of the cost of your rental property may be deducted each year when you file your tax return.  Use of a depreciation method, as it is called, is based on the recovery period for the property and your basis in the property.  There are three depreciatio
n methods.  The choice of which to use depends on the type of property and when it was first rented. 
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3><B>Possible deductions relating to rental property</B></FONT>
<UL><FONT SIZE=3>
<LI>Advertising
<LI>Auto and Travel
<LI>Cleaning and Maintenance
<LI>Depreciation of appliances purchased as replacements
<LI>Depreciation of property
<LI>Fees paid to real estate company for collection of rent
<LI>Fire insurance
<LI>General Repairs
<LI>Heating, lighting, and sewage costs if paid by you
<LI>Legal and other professional fees
<LI>Mortgage interest
<LI>Other interest
<LI>Real estate taxes imposed and paid in 1994
<LI>Trash collection fee
<LI>Supplies
<LI>Expenses allocated to preparing tax schedules relating to rentals
</UL>
<P>
<A HREF="#jhtop"><IMG BORDER="0" ALT="Back to Top" ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="arrow.gif"></A>
<BR>
<P><FONT SIZE=4>For indepth information regarding rental property tax obligations, consult your Jackson Hewitt Tax Service professionals. 
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="jhsc"><IMG ALT="Senior Citizens" SRC="jhscline.gif">
<P>
<CENTER><FONT SIZE=4><B>THINGS TO KNOW:</B></FONT></CENTER>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><B>T</B></FONT><FONT SIZE=3>here are considerable tax saving advantages for individuals 55 and older.  It is important that you understand the way the tax law affect your return to ensure you get every dollar you deserve. 
<P>With a lot of foresight and a little planning, many taxpayers can lessen if not completely avoid the tax impact.<P>
Some of the ways this can be done include:
<UL>
<LI>Leave the money in the employers plan.  This will keep future options open on what to do with the funds.
<LI>Have the employer directly transfer the funds from the plan into a rollover or conduit IRA.  This type of account keeps the plan money separate from other IRA funds and preserves the taxpayers right to roll the money into another employer's plan at so
me later date, thereby, not losing the ability to use five or ten year averaging.
<LI>Have the employer directly transfer the funds to the new employer's plan (again maintaining it's ability to use averaging at sometime in the future).
<LI>Have the funds transferred to an existing or newly established IRA.
</UL><FONT SIZE=3>
<P>
<P>
<A HREF="#jhtop"><IMG BORDER="0" ALT="Back to Top" ALIGN=RIGHT SRC="arrow.gif"></A>
<P><FONT SIZE=4>If you are unsure about your tax obligations, the Professionals at Jackson Hewitt Tax Service are ready to help.
<BR>
