<P>
<a href="http://www.prs.net/midi.html">Classical MIDI Archives</a> - Over 60Mb (2,200+ files) of mostly Classical Music in Midi Format
<P>
<a href="http://www.worldnet.fr/~jpa/midigb.shtml">Jean-Pierre AMRINGER's Piano-Jazz midi Page</a>

<a href="http://www.music.indiana.edu/music_resources/">Music Resources on the Internet</a> From the Indiana University Music Library 
<p>
<a href="http://www.hike.te.chiba-u.ac.jp:80/cons1/">Renaissance Consort</a> Demonstration of renaissance consort and renaissance instruments. 
<p>
<a href="http://www.dtx.net/~raborn/">The Classical Midi Connection</a>
You can browse the site and listen to and/or save any of the sequences available. 
 <P>
<a href="http://classicalmus.com/bmgclassics/comp-index/index.html">The Great Composers</a> Biographies of composers.
<P>
<A HREF="http://www.rpmseattle.com/rpm/efx.html">Sound	Effects Library</a>
<P><a href="http://www.geocities.com/Paris/3486/">The Internet Piano Page</a> This Webpage contains lots of classical Piano files in the common General MIDI format.. Most of the pieces have been played by professional concert pianists so that best quality

 is guaranteed. 
<P>
<A HREF="http://sunsite.unc.edu/wm/snd/">The WebMuseum Auditorium</A> 
Listen to Classical Music
<p>
<a href="http://www.cyberspace.com/~benson/EarTrainer/EarTrainer.html">WWW Ear Trainer</a> This is an experimental game that tests your ablity to distinguish musical intervals. You will receive
a MIDI file that consists of two notes, and a form to guess the interval. You may continue for as long as you like, the program will keep track of your total number of guesses and the number of
correct answers. 
<p>
<a href="http://www.xmission.com/~mgm/misc/keyboard.html">WWW Virtual Keyboard</a> Click on the piano keys below to hear the notes they represent. It's just like a real piano, except that it's slower, smaller, sillier, and doesn't sound nearly as good. 
