<html>
 <BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" BACKGROUND="bohrbg.gif" TEXT="#200073" 
LINK="#830083" ALINK="#FFCC00" VLINK="#009C00"> <head>
    <title>Mr. Bohr's Answer Page...Einstein's Chalkboard</title>
  </head>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 
"http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" 1 gen true comment "RSACi North 
America Server" by "mark@sdirect.com" for "http://sdirect.com/einstein" 
on "1996.04.04T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 1 
0))'>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" 
content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.classify.org/safesurf/" l gen t for
"http://http://www.sdirect.com/einstein/" r (SS~~000 1 SS~~100 1))'>
<meta name="rating" content="safe for kids">
  <body>
    <center>
      <img src="bohrans.gif">
    
<BR><BR> <font size=4><b> You may ask Mr. Bohr a Math, Science or Biology 
question at<BR>
 <a href="http://sdirect.com/einstein/ask.html">Mr. Bohr's 
Question Page</a> </B></CENTER></FONT>    <BR><BR><P><HR NOSHADE>
<!--begin-->

<b>TO:Kristy Weatherilt</b><br>
<ul><b>Your 
Question:</b><br><li>I am doing an essay or poem for my Englishclass. I was
wondering if you could help me in finding a good topic for it.
The big topic is SHIFTING SANDS,CHANGING TIMES. Now I need 
to expand on that and am stumped. I have left it late and
it is due on Monday. All I am asking is if you could help me 
in selecting some points to start my poem...ie. A little boy 
growing up into a man....</ul><p>
<ul><b>The 
Answer:</b><br><li>How about comparing and contrasting the values and norms of a generation or two ago with the  values and norms of today?  
Or compare/contrast what teens of  40-50 years ago with what teens do today.
If you need more help, just send more mail........and hey, never wait 
until the the last minute to do something, start at least the night before! 
(not)</ul><br> <b>SIGNED--Mr.Bohr</b><br>
<hr>
<b>TO:nadav hekselman</b><br>
<ul><b>Your 
Question:</b><br><li>a week ago i read this theory which i 
didn't understand, the theory says that a beam of charged
atoms (ion) is accelerated and fired from a device through a 
container with some gas that removes the additonal 
electron and you get a beam of accelerated atoms that can
be used as a weapon, but i didnt understand why is it so
important to get rid of the additional electron , why
can't you fire just a beam of ion?.</ul><p>
<ul><b>The 
Answer:</b><br><li>You could just fire a "beam" of ions, but the beam would have a poor focus and would be made of  ions of  varing charges.  By firing the beam through gas, probably an inert gas like xenon,  you are able to filter out the ions with lower


 energy levels and to project a beam with a much tighter focus.  If you think about X-rays as an example,  when you get a  chest x-ray, you don't want the radiation  bathing your entire body, you want a tight focus only on the area to be viewed.</ul><br>



<b>SIGNED--Mr.Bohr</b><br>
<hr>
<b>TO:Sha'Ree</b><br>
<ul><b>Your 
Question:</b><br><li>I want to know how the theory of relativity helps
 people today. In other words what modern day strides have
 been made in this field and how has the theory 
of relativity contributed to them. I am 18 years old. I amd
doing a 8pg typed report on this subject.  Please get back 
to me as soon as possible. I go to the Universisty of South
Carolina</ul><p>
<ul><b>The 
Answer:</b><br><li>Well if you are doing a college paper, you are going 
to need a better source than this forum.  Baring that, here it goes...
Einstein theory deals with speeds and time being relative to the observer.  He speculates what a person would see "if he were riding a beam of light."  Spin offs of this theory, and of the physics of "speed of light" travel are many.  Applications?  Notta






.  It may be nice to know that if you travel the speed of light, you 
could cross the universe in a sec and outside of your vehicle, millions of years will have passed, but no one outside of star trek can do that.  And as you approach the speed of light, i
t'd increase your mass toward infinity, and decrease your length to almost 0.
Hope this helps.</ul><br>
<b>SIGNED--Mr.Bohr</b><br>
<hr>
<b>Einy</b><br>
<ul><b>Your 
Question:</b><br><li>What does the Square root mean?
What are sqaure roots "exactly"?
</ul><p>
<ul><b>The 
Answer:</b><br><li>A square root of a number (x) would be another number, that when multiplied by itself (y) would give you the first number.  ex   y (multiplied) y = x     
y would be the square root of x.
This works fine untill you try to take the square of a negative number since a negative multiplied by a negative = a positive number.
Square roots are important for solving quadratic equations and for finding the 3rd side of a right triangle when two sides are known (see pathagerian theorium).

</ul><br>
<b>SIGNED--Mr.Bohr</b><br>
<hr>
<b>TO:Roger Wayne</b><br>
<ul><b>Your 
Question:</b><br><li>I am 8 yrs old and need to know why the leaves change color.  What causes it to happen?  Thank You.</ul><p>
<ul><b>The 
Answer:</b><br><li>In the fall, as certain, the tree becomes dormant for 
the winter, it forms a seal between the branches and leaves.
This seal prevents food and water from getting to the leaves.  As a 
result, the main pigment in leaves which is green begins to break down.  As 
this pigment  breaks 
down, it allows the lighter pigments to show up resulting in the myriad 
colors of fall.
You can do an experiment in your science class by having your  teacher 
crush up some green leaves  with some ether or  alcohol and brushing a  strip on some blotter  paper.  The different colors separate out forming bands of various colors.</ul><br>
<b>SIGNED--Mr.Bohr</b><br>
 - <hr>

<b>TO:Jimmy K.</b><br>
<ul><b>Your 
Question:</b><br><li>I am studying matter in Science class and got a wrong 
answer on my test. 
 The question was,  Symbols are used to represent __________, 
whereas formulas are used to represent ________. 
 Do you know the answer?</ul><p>
<ul><b>The 
Answer:</b><br><li>Yes, I do.
In the context that she gave you, symbols represent Elements
and formulas represents a Molecule or molecular structure.
Fe and Mg for Iron and Magnesium.
H2O and C6H12O6 for water and carbohydrate ( which means
"carbonated" water.  You can reduce C6H12O6 to 
CH2O which is water with a carbon on it.)
You get the clue for answering the question  by the  fact the 
question asks " Symbols represent this, BUT formulas represent
this.   If you miss that, you might say Symbols can represent
ANYTHING but formulas  can only represent WHAT?"  And
then you've missed the point of the question and missed
the points for the question!
</ul><br>
<b>SIGNED--Mr.Bohr</b><br>
 - <hr>


<b>TO:Matthew</b><br>
<ul><b>Your 
Question:</b><br><li>I am in 4th Grade and am learning estimation in math class. 
 I would like to know why we are taught this -
 I mean, what is the point of it?
</ul><p>
<ul><b>The 
Answer:</b><br><li>  Every time you do something you are probably estimating,
you just may not know it.  When you throw a ball, you estimate
how hard to throw it to get it to it's end point.  As you get
more experience you can estimate better and get better results.
  We estimate with numbers when we need a result that is close
to the final figure, but doesn't have to be  exact.  If you were going
to buy a baseball card and you knew the book value, that would be
a good place to start with -  you   estimate.  If the book value was $10 
you might  want to bring along  $12.  The extra $2 would be an estimate
of the changing conditions affecting the price of the cards.
Much of what we are taught in school, we just incorporate into
our daily living and never think about the fact that we once studied
the subject in school.
</ul><br>
<b>SIGNED--Mr.Bohr</b><br>
 - <hr>

<b>TO:gabe</b><br>
<ul><b>Your 
Question:</b><br><li>I would really like to know what the "speed of light" is.</ul><p>
<ul><b>The 
Answer:</b><br><li>The speed of light is approx 186,300 miles per sec.
Traveling at the speed of light you could circle the earth
7 times in 1 sec.  The scientifc constant of the speed of light
is c, as in E=mc^2.
The speed of light, unlike other velocities are not communitive.
ex. if you stood on a train going 5 mph and threw a ball at
10mph (relative to the thrower) the ball would be traveling at
15mph (relative to an observer on the ground.)
Light travels as packets/particles traveling in a wave.
For more info, look up Einstein.  He did a lot of  research based
on light.
</ul><br>
<b>SIGNED--Mr.Bohr</b><br>
<P> 


