<HTML>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FFFFFF" TEXT="#6A10BD" LINK="#00EE00" VLINK="#FF4100" ALINK="#FFCCOO">
<HEAD><TITLE>Einsteins Chalkboard..In My Imagination..Stories and Poetry For Kids..SERVDirect</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 
"http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" 1 gen true comment "RSACi North 
America Server" by "mark@sdirect.com" for "http://sdirect.com/einstein" 
on "1996.04.04T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 1 
0))'>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" 
content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.classify.org/safesurf/" l gen t for
"http://http://www.sdirect.com/einstein/" r (SS~~000 1 SS~~100 1))'>
<meta name="rating" content="safe for kids">
<body>

<IMG SRC="smpcenter.gif"><BR>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="imagine.gif">
<FONT SIZE=5>

<P>
/ <A HREF="gameslinks.html">Games</A>  / <A HREF="riddles.html">Riddles &AMP Jokes</A>  / <A HREF="project.html"> Project Center</A>  / <A HREF="sports.html"> Sports</A>  /
</CENTER></FONT>
<P>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=4>
 <FONT SIZE=5><B> D</B><FONT SIZE=4><B>o you exercise your imagination from time to time?</B><BR>
 Here is your chance to do so. You may read stories and poems sent in by other kids on the web and view drawings as well. If you would like, you may <a href="story.html">send us</a> your orignal story or poem and we will print it here <FONT COLOR=MAGENTA>

In My Imagination</FONT><FONT SIZE=4>. If you want us to dispay your drawing, just attatch it to your email in either jpeg or gif format and send it in to <a href=email.html>einstein@sdirect.com</a>!
These poems,stories and drawings belong to the young authors and artists that sent them.
<P>
<BR>
<TABLE BORDER=0><TH>
"The Little Sons" <BR>
by Brian L<BR>
Age 10, Georgia</TH>
<TR><TD>

Once upon a time, long ago, and far away... there were three little sons.  Little Buffalo, Little Steer, and Little Lion.  They all lived on the Great Plains.  They also had a very, very kind mother.</TD><TR><TD> 
    The three sons loved the excitement of traveling everywhere they did.  The three sons enjoyed excitement more than anything else, of course besides spending time with their mother. </TD><TR><TD> 
    One day, their mother was out gathering food to cook with, when she found this beautiful stone.  It was smooth, shiny, and it had a sort of a glow.  Their mother finished gathering food and went home. </TD><TR><TD> 
   The next day, the three little sons and their mother woke up in a beautiful castle, everywhere was paradise!  The castle was huge!  The sons wondered what had happened, so their mother told them the story of the mysterious stone that she had found whil
e gathering food. </TD><TR><TD> 
    The sons went to this mysterious place and took a look at it.
    They looked around and saw an old man.  The little sons went to the man and asked, "Do you know about this mysterious place?"  The old man replied. "Yes, I do.  You beat me into finding that stone.  Just remember to be cruel and unfair.  That is the o
nly way to handle the stone correctly!"  The sons looked at each other and didn't want to take part in that.  The old man looked at them and said, "Here, drink this and all of your problems will be over." </TD><TR><TD>  
   The sons looked at each other again.  They said, "Ok, we'll drink it."  The old man gave them the potion, and they drank.  Little did they know, they had been tricked into being mean for the rest of their lives!</TD><TR><TD>   
   When they went home, they in fact WERE cruel and unfair.  When their mother looked at them and asked, "Why are you being so cruel?", they just looked at each other and left the room. </TD><TR><TD>  
  The spirits where watching the chaos that the sons were causing and doing.  They became very,very angry!  With that, they would test the little sons to see how cruel they really were. </TD><TR><TD> 
  The first tester posed as a fly and went to the palace.  When it supposingly accidentally flew into their drinks, they smashed it into the ground.  This made the spirits even more angry than they already were.  </TD><TR><TD> 
   The second tester posed as an old man who needed money.  When he asked, they slammed the door in his face and laughed.  This made the spirits want to burst into hatred, but there was one more test to go.  </TD><TR><TD> 
    The third tester posed as a young boy who needed money, like the second tester.  The sons slammed the door in his face also and roared with laughter. </TD><TR><TD>  
   The spirits were so angry that they went down to the Great Plains and threw the sons into the stars.  Their mother was so kind, she went with them. </TD><TR><TD>  
   If you look closely at night, you can see them too.  The spirits called them "The Little Dipper".</TD><TR><TD ALIGN="CENTER"> 

                 THE END</TD></TABLE>  
<BR>
