<HTML>

<BODY BGCOLOR="FF6600" TEXT="#FFFFFF" LINK="#OOFFOO" VLINK="#00CCFF" ALINK="#FF4100">
<HEAD><TITLE>Einsteins Chalkboard..SERVDirect</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" content='(PICS-1.0 
"http://www.rsac.org/ratingsv01.html" 1 gen true comment "RSACi North 
America Server" by "mark@sdirect.com" for "http://sdirect.com/einstein" 
on "1996.04.04T08:15-0500" exp "1997.01.01T08:15-0500" r (n 0 s 0 v 0 1 
0))'>
<META http-equiv="PICS-Label" 
content='(PICS-1.0 "http://www.classify.org/safesurf/" l gen t for
"http://http://www.sdirect.com/einstein/" r (SS~~000 1 SS~~100 1))'>
<meta name="rating" content="safe for kids">
<body>
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="formula.gif">
<BR>
<P>
<FONT SIZE =5>
/ <A HREF="gameslinks.html">Games</A>  / <A HREF="riddles.html">Riddles &AMP Jokes</A>  / <A HREF="project.html"> Project Center</A>  / <A HREF="sports.html"> Sports</A>  /
</CENTER>
</FONT>
<B>
<FONT SIZE=4>
<P>  
<BR>
Welcome to <a href="cprojects.html">Einstein's Cool Projects</a>.  Here are<FONT COLOR=YELLOW> Four Favorite Formulas For Fun</FONT>.  Make sure you have an adult to help you with these so you and your family stay safe!  Hey, they might even have some fun
 too! 
<P>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="mgrn.gif">
<BR>
<FONT COLOR=YELLOW>PLAY PUTTY </FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>You will need:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3>
One Adult at least (or more if you choose)
<P>
2 Tablespoons of water
<P>
2 Tablespoons of white glue (Elmers type)
<P>
A couple drops of food coloring  *Note The food coloring can stain material and carpet use with care.
<P>
	2 Teaspoons of Borax
<P>
plastic bags
<P>
A plastic container with a tight fitting lid for storage. Old margerine tubs work well.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>Directions:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3>
<P>
1.  Mix the white glue and water in an old plastic container.
<P>
2. Mix in a couple drops of food coloring.
<P>
3. Add the borax, it will start to form right away.
<P> 
4. Put the putty into the plastic bag  close and knead for about 4 minutes or so until the  Play Putty is smooth. 
<P>	
5.store the play clay in a plastic container with a tight fitting lid. Old margerine tubs work well.
<P>
<IMG SRC="mgrn.gif">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><FONT COLOR=YELLOW> Play Bubbles</FONT> 
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>You will need:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3>
One Adult at least (or more if you choose)
<P>
1 Cup of liquid dishwashing detergent
<P>
2 Cups of water 
<P>
3-4 Tablespoons of GLYERINE (you can find this at drugstores)
<P>
1 Teaspoon Sugar
<P>
A container to keep the bubble formula in 
<P>
Pipe cleaners,straws or a kitchen funnel to blow the bubbles with.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>Directions:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3>
1. Mix all the ingredients together.
<P>
2.Then put the Bubble Formula in a plastic container with a lid for
storage 
<P>
3.To blow the bubbles you may use a straw, or pipe cleaners that you can bend into different shapes, or even a kitchen funnel.
<P>
<IMG SRC="mgrn.gif">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><FONT COLOR=YELLOW>PLAY CLAY</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>You will need:</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=3>
<P>
One Adult at least (or more if you choose)
<P>
2 Cups of flour
<P>
1 Cup of salt
<P>
2 Cups of water
<P>
2 Tablespoons of  Vegetable Oil
<P>
2 Teaspoons of Cream of Tartar
<P>
A couple of drops of food coloring. *Note The food coloring can stain material and carpet use with care.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>Directions:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3>
1. Mix all the ingredients
<P>
2. Put mixture into a sause pan.
<P>
3. Stir the mixture over a very low heat until it has come together into a nice doughy ball. 
<P>
4. Remove it from its heat source and set it aside until it has cooled completely before handling!
<P>
5.  After it has completely cooled, store the play clay in a plastic container with a tight fitting lid. Old margerine tubs work well.
<P>
<IMG SRC="mgrn.gif">
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4><FONT COLOR=YELLOW>Slime Formula</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=3>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>You will need:</FONT>
<FONT SIZE=3>
<P>
One Adult at least (or more if you choose)
<P>
Borax
<P>
1/8 Cup Of Borax
<P>
2 Cups of Water
<P>
1/4 Cup of Water for each batch
<P>
1/4 Cup of White Glue for each batch 
<P>
Food Coloring
<P>
Some plastic bags that zip close.
<P>
<FONT SIZE=4>Directions:</FONT>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=3>
<P>
*Do not let this get on rugs or fabric because food coloring STAINS!
<P>
1.	Mix together 1/8 cup of Borax and 2 cups of water and heat them over low heat in a small saucepan stir until the Borax has  dissolved.
<P> 
2. After the mixture is dissolved remove it from its heat source and set it aside until it has cooled completley!
<P>
3. Mix together in an old container 1/4 cup of White Glue and 1/4 cup of water, stir until well combined.
<P>
4. Pour the White glue/water mixture into a baggy  *It is  easier to fill the baggies with the liquids if you line a standing plastic  cup with the  plastic baggie first. Leave an inch or so of the baggie folded over the rim of the tumbler to prevent the 
liquids from spilling inside the cup when they are being poured in.
<P>
5. Now add 2 Tablespoons of the Borax/Water solution into the baggie that has the glue/water mixture in it. Add a drop of food coloring.
<P>
6. Zip close the bag carefully, removing as much air as possible.
<P>
7. Knead until the SLIME has formed.
<P>
8. Store in  a plastic container (old margerine tubs are great for this). 
<P>
<IMG SRC="mgrn.gif">
<P>
</B>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="mark.html">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALT="Making the Mark" SRC="markbt.gif"></A>
<A HREF="homeref.html">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALT="Homework References" SRC="homerefbt.gif"></A>
<A HREF="ask.html">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALT="Ask Mr. Bohr" SRC="askbt.gif"></A>
<A HREF="teens.html">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALT="Teens" SRC="teensbt.gif"></A>
<A HREF="klinks.html">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALT="Kid Links" SRC="linksbt.gif"></A>
<A HREF="pt.html">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALT="Parents &AMP Teachers" SRC="ptbt.gif"></A>
<A HREF="email.html">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALT="Email" SRC="einymailbt.gif"></A>
<A HREF="index.html">
<IMG BORDER=0 ALT="Home Page" SRC="ehomebt.gif"></A>
