<TITLE>
FOCUS: Product Liability
</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="./images/cbs.gif" text="#000000" link="#f00000" vlink="#2f4f4f">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="./images/rglogo.gif" width="606" height="105">
</CENTER>
<B><IMG SRC="./images/product.gif" align="left" hspace="10" vspace="0" border="1" width="202" height="173"><B><I><font size="4">C</font>aveat <font size="4">E</font>mptor.</I> Let the buyer beware.

<P><font size="4">T</font>his well-known phrase has taken on new meaning in recent times, as some manufacturers have shown a willingness to cut corners in product design and safety in order to add to their profits. The problem has been compounded by the changing nature and structure of the corporate world, which has grown in complexity -- often making it difficult to assign blame or place responsiblity.

<P><font size="4">U</font>nder these conditions, the threat of serious injury from products which have not been properly designed, tested, or manufactured is very real.

<P><font size="4">R</font>obles &amp; <font size="4">G</font>onzalez has represented many individuals who have been victimized by defective products, and the firm has developed an organization and procedural system that is well-suited to pursuing these types of cases.
</B>


