<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Specialition Leads to Efficiency
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#f00000" vlink="#2f4f4f">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="./images/njlj.gif" width="419" height="84">

<H2>Concentrating on One Area of the Law <BR>Leads to an Efficient Practice</H2>


<table align=center units="pixels" width="400" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" border="0">
<tr>

<td valign=top width="400">
<P><B>By Louis S. Robles</B><BR>

<P>When I first made the decision to go solo, I opened shop in the living room of my home, with my wife as my secretary. I am now the senior partner in a downtown Miami firm that employs 50 people and represents clients in more than 30 states.
The reason for my success is, in large part, my decision not to operate a general practice of law for an indefinite period of time. As with most service-related businesses, my first challenge was attracting new business, and during my startup phase I accepted many different types of cases. This practice served two needs.
<P>First, it paid the bills. Without cash flow -- or considerable savings to act as a cushion -- you're dead from the start. In addition, the actual experience I obtained while handling whatever cases came through the door gave me some fresh ideas about what I most enjoyed in law practice. And being open to anything permitted me to sample a range of areas, including the ones in which I now concentrate.
<P>A good approach to getting the word out about your new enterprise is to compile a list of all the people you've known through personal and professional contacts, and then notify everyone on the list of your decision to hang out a shingle.
At times you will have to handle a lot of matters that you do not particularly like -- or for which you are not particularly well-suited. However, the fees generated by such work will be critical to your survival in the beginning.
<P>Avoid burning bridges from the outset.
<P>Although stealing clients from your present firm may be a tempting route, it is tacky and unsporting.

<H3>Limiting Your Practice</H3>


<P>The phrase "jack of all trades and master of none" is especially applicable to the practice of law. You cannot continue to be all things to all people if you hope to develop a level of expertise that will allow you to prosper.
<P>Ultimately, the only way to develop a truly efficient solo or small practice is to limit it to one area of the law.
One of the myths of law practice is that lawyers select the areas of law in which they practice. In reality, the areas of law in which we practice select us.
<P>I have found that it is usually a set of circumstances over which you may have little control that dictates your path and offers the greatest reward for your practice.
<P>Even if you are not initially enamored of a particular field of law, you might change your mind once you start to make a decent living. And, at that point, you may have the resources to develop other areas in which you have greater interest.
<P>As early as possible, select an area of the law that you have been exposed to by virtue of the work that comes your way.
<P>Such a decision need not be as restricting as it sounds. Although you may emphasize a particular area of the law, there are generally sub-specialties within that area that draw from the same body of law, and may even have similar fact patterns.


<H3>Some Diversification Needed</H3>


<P>Naturally, some diversification within an area of law will be necessary for continued success and for your peace of mind. Especially when the economy is uncertain, it is disconcerting to realize that you have placed all your eggs in one basket.
<P>For example, if you represent plaintiffs in tort actions, you may be representing people who have been injured by various toxic substances, such as asbestos. Once you have mastered the basic issues involved in asbestos cases, you may expand into other areas such as lead and chemical exposure.
<P>Although the disease processes differ among these cases, the body of law with which you will be dealing is the same: the law of products liability.
<P>My own career illustrates this. In 1975, I began representing plaintiffs in asbestos litigation. I found this area of the law to be fascinating. One client eventually led to hundreds, then thousands. Within two years, it became clear that toxic torts would be my area of practice.
<P>However, even though my initial exposure to the field was through asbestos cases, from discussions with clients and medical professionals I soon realized that there were many substances that caused injury.
<P>At that point, I branched out to include other areas of toxic exposure. Though the facts varied from case to case, the body of law remained the same. This allowed me to develop an office system and staff that is well-suited to the cases I take. And, should any one area falter, I have the others to fall back on.

<H3>The Importance of Efficiency</H3>


<P>One of the greatest benefits of emphasizing a specific area of law within your practice is that it gives you control over your rate and direction of growth.
<P>In contrast, a general practice means you must reinvent the wheel with each new matter that comes into your office. This prevents you from reaching the level of efficiency critical to financial success. Further, this use of resources does not help a new practitioner to achieve healthy economy of scale in his or her new endeavor.
<P>"Economy of scale" is a term that is not often applied to the practice of law. However, it does have its place in our vocabulary. Handling repetitive matters will lead to the development of standard procedures, which will then lead to increased efficiency and, eventually, greater take-home pay.
If you work in the same area of law on a regular basis, the standardized procedures you create and develop will allow you to take on a greater workload, allowing for greater productivity and earning potential.
<P>In the final analysis, the key to your success will be the quality of your work, your sincerity, and your accessibility to clients. In law, as in other service-related businesses, clients beget clients. A satisfied personal injury client is bound to pass on information about his lawyer's successes to acquaintances and friends who are themselves injured.

<H3>The Power of Positive Thinking</H3>


<P>You must be prepared to commit at least five years to developing a specialized law practice. To this end, you must be consistent in your work ethic in order to build momentum and a client base. In time, this will allow you to make greater strides with less effort. Nothing is less conducive to long-range success than starting and stopping.
<P>The best advice for those early days is to maintain a steady pace and not to become discouraged. Keep your law practice objectives in mind and visualize. When times get tough, just picture yourself sitting in the office you want, involved with cases you care about and conducting business in the way you see fit.
<P>A business commitment to concentrate on one area of the law and a personal commitment to excellence will make it happen.
</table>

<P><I>The New Jersey Law Journal</I>, September 5, 1991<BR>


