<TITLE>
Robles Wins Record Asbestos Award
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#f00000" vlink="#2f4f4f">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="./images/miarevu.gif" width="396" height="123">
<H1>Lawyer Robles Wins <BR>Record Asbestos Award</H1>

<table align=center units="pixels" width="400" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" border="0">
<tr>

<td valign=top width="400">
<P>Louis Robles, the Miami lawyer who has built a practice on plaintiffs' asbestos litigation, last week claimed a record verdict: compensatory damages of $2.6 million.

<P>It's the largest that he knows of in the national litigation's 20-year history, Robles says. Susan J. Cole, who represented defendant Eagle Picher Industries, confirms it's the largest she knows about in Florida.

<P>"The size of the verdict was certainly unexpected," said Cole, of Blair and Cole in Coral Gables. But she wasn't in mourning. The judge granted her motion of a directed verdict on punitive damages, which means she saved her client from potentially astronomical liability.

<P>The $2.6 million went to a Panama City man, John Oakes, who worked as an insulator at a Port St. Joe paper mill for 30 years, until lung disease forced his retirement in 1985.

<P>During the four-day trial, Oakes, 65, had to be wheeled to the witness stand for his 90-minute testimony. He carried a portable oxygen tank. Defense cousel Robert A. Hannah cross-examined him "gingerly," Robles said.

<P>A Dade Circuit Court jury decided after deliberating for about 2 1/2 hours that Oakes and his wife should be awarded the $2.6 million, including $180,000 in lost wages, $140,000 in future medical expenses, $175,000 for the wife's loss of consortium, and the rest for pain and suffering.
</table>

<P>
<I>Miami Review</I>, January 29 1988<BR>


