<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Tax Unfair to Divorced Couples
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#f00000" vlink="#2f4f4f">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="./images/divorced.gif" width="322" height="161">

<table align=center units="pixels" width="400" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" border="0">
<tr>

<td valign=top width="400">
<P><B>By DAVID LYONS</B><BR>
Herald Staff Writer
<P>When Nariela Bauta and her husband, Juan, split up, she got the couple's South Dade home. What she didn't count on was a $282 bill at the Dade County Clerk's office -- for document stamps. That was the price for transferring her ex-spouse's half of the deed to her name only. No payment, no transfer.
<P>Reluctantly, she paid. Then she filed a class-action lawsuit against the state Department of Revenue.
<P>In a ruling this month, Dade Circuit Judge Juan Ramirez, Jr. came down on Bauta's side. The judge not only deemed the state's excise tax "illegal and improper," but he said that countless people in situations similar to Bauta's may join the lawsuit - a move that could mean millions of dollars in refunds.
<P>"The state has been improperly taking document stamps in cases where there is a divorce and property is exchanged," said Miami attorney Ervin Gonzalez, who represents Bauta. "You shouldn't have to pay for document stamps."
<P>Now, coutless people who were forced to pay similar fees since that tax took effect in 1990 could get a rebate if Ramirez's ruling is upheld on appeal.
<P>Gonzalez said he intends to notify those affected by mail and through notices in newspapers. Over the past five years, he said, there have been 480,000 divorces statewide. He estimates that 40 to 50 percent of those breakups resulted in the transfer of property - property that was illegally taxed by the state.
<P>Gonzalez figures divorced spouses in Florida have been paying between $300 to $1,000 over the years to transfer home mortgages. "It's going to end up being millions of dollars the state has to repay because of the numbers involved," he said.
<P>The state doesn't intend to let the case get that far. It will fight - all the way to the Florida Supreme Court if necessary. Already, government lawyers have filed an appeal with the Third District Court of Appeal in Miami.
<P>"The collection of the documentary stamp taxes was a valid collection," said Jarell L. Murchison, an assistant attorney general in Tallahassee.
<P>In court papers, he argued that Bauta failed to seek a timely refund, and that the class action should not be allowed because there is no evidence of anyone else applying for a refund.
"No class should be considered for certificaiton unless and until there is a large enough group of persons to justify certification," Murchison wrote.
<P>Gonzalez acknowledged that few people know about the case, or even sought refunds. "Who's going to think the state is improperly taking their money?" he asked. "They make you feel that if you don't pay the fee, you can't have your deed registered and recorded."
<P>The Bautas bought their house a year after they were married in 1985. Under the terms of the mortgage, each was liable for payment.
<P>Nariela Bauta, a legal assistant, and her husband, an attorney, divorced in 1994. Under their settlement agreement, she received the house.
<P>That's when the state stepped in, charging Nariela Bauta $282 on the half of the existing $94,000 mortgage she received from her husband.
<P>Under the law authorizing the tax, a fee is collected when something of value is paid in exchange for property. But in the Bautas' case, Gonzalez argued, the wife received the second half of the morgtgage without paying anything to her ex-husband.
<P>"They're charging for documentary stamps without her getting anything she didn't already have," Gonzalez said. "And, she's being taxed on it."
<P>The state countered that the transferred portion of the mortgage itself is taxable.
Not so, Gonzalez said. If anything, the husband shifted an "economic burden" to his wife.
<P>Arguments before the Third District Court of Appeal are pending.
</table>

<P><I>The Miami Herald</I>, January 29, 1996<BR>


<A HREF="inthenew.html"><P><IMG SRC="./images/toindex.gif" border="0" width="173" height="20" hspace="10"></A>
<A HREF="contact1.html"><IMG SRC="./images/contact.gif" border="0" width="173" height="20" hspace="10"></A>
<A HREF="premail2.html"><IMG SRC="./images/sendmail.gif" border="0" width="173" height="20" hspace="10"></A>

