<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Suit Says GM sold Cars with Faulty Brakes
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#f00000" vlink="#2f4f4f">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="./images/gmhead.gif" width="343" height="186">

<table align=center units="pixels" width="400" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" border="0">
<tr>

<td valign=top width="400">
<P>General Motors knowingly manufactured automobiles with defective brakes but still advertised and sold the faulty cars, a lawyer charged Thursday.
<P>The Powermaster brake system installed in some GM models from 1985 to 1987 had defects that could result in brake failure or a constantly illuminated brake warning light, the Dade Circuit Court suit charged. "We believe that there have been accidents caused by this brake system, although we have not been able to pinpoint them," said attorney Ervin Gonzalez.
GM spokesman Ed Lechtzin said he had not seen the lawsuit and had no comment because the company does "not comment on press releases."

<P>Gonzalez wants the suit, filed Wednesday against GM and Tropical Chevrolet in Miami Shores, to be certified as a class action, estimating 126,700 autos were affected. The suit was filed on behalf of Caprice station wagon owner Estelle Schuster. She bought the car from Tropical and replaced the brake system six times, Gonzalez said. The car has been in storage since Schuster decided it was not safely drivable.
<P>Tropical Chevrolet attorney Ferdie Ainsley denied Tropical knowingly sold defective cars and said Gonzalez does not have a case.

</table>

<P><I>The Miami Herald</I>, May 20, 1994<BR>


<A HREF="inthenew.html"><P><IMG SRC="./images/toindex.gif" border="0" width="173" height="20" hspace="10"></A>
