<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Woman Sues Manufacturer of Norplant
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#f00000" vlink="#2f4f4f">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="./images/herald.gif" width="409" height="176">

<table align=center units="pixels" width="400" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" border="0">
<tr>

<td valign=top width="400">
<P><B>By STEPHEN SMITH</B><BR>
Herald Staff Writer
<P>Heralded as the greatest thing since the pill, Norplant was a contraceptive for the '90s: put it in and forget about it. Now the makers of Norplant are manufacturing damage control as much as birth control.

<P>A Fort Lauderdale woman is suing Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories in federal court, claiming she was scarred and traumatized after it took five surgeries and more than a year to extract a Norplant strip intractably embedded in her upper left arm.

<P>But it's not just she, Earserlene Smith said: It has happened to lots of women, and they all want justice. Her atorney filed a class-action lawsuit last week.

<P>"If anybody had told her it's  going to take a bunch of procedures to get this out, she wouldn't have done it, and I don't think any women would have," said Smith's attorney, Ervin Gonzalez.

<P>Wyeth denies its product is inherently dangerous or regularly difficult to remove. In a prepared statement, Wyeth executives said Monday they have not reviewed Smith's case. The Wyeth statement maintains "the vast majority of Norplant removals are not difficult."
<P>Hundreds of women across America disagree. Another class-action lawsuit, filed in Chicago, has attracted about 400 women who report more problems than panacea.

<P>And Gonzalez already has spoken with 25 to 30 women in Broward and Dade who related experiences paralleling Smith's.

<P>She had six Norplant strips, each the size of a matchstick, inserted in her left arm in June 1992. Not long after, Smith, 23, found out she was pregnant. She's not sure whether she became pregnant before or after getting Norplant, Gonzalez said.

<P>Her physician recommended removing Norplant during pregnancy, fearful it might affect the unborn child. Smith agreed, making an appointment for a procedure that's supposed to take less than half an hour.

<P>The doctor succeeded in removing five strips, but the sixth remained stubbornly implanted. More than a year later - after Smith's baby was born - the doctor finally yanked the sixth Norplant from her arm.

<P>The baby has no apparent complications, although physicians can't be sure about neurological damage until the child is older, Gonzalez said.

<P>Smith's lawsuit alleges Wyeth failed to train doctors adequately about Norplant and didn't disclose potential dangers.

<P>Wyeth's medical director, Dr. Marc W. Deitch, calls class-action lawsuits "inappropriate" because Norplant removal can be affected by many variables, including how the strips were inserted, what removal procedures are used, and circumstances particular to each patient.

</table>

<P><I>The Miami Herald</I>, July 19, 1994<BR>


<A HREF="inthenew.html"><P><IMG SRC="./images/toindex.gif" border="0" width="173" height="20" hspace="10"></A>
<A HREF="contact1.html"><IMG SRC="./images/contact.gif" border="0" width="173" height="20" hspace="10"></A>
<A HREF="premail2.html"><IMG SRC="./images/sendmail.gif" border="0" width="173" height="20" hspace="10"></A>

</CENTER>
</BODY>
</HTML>
