<HEAD>
<TITLE>
Train Derailment Case Brings $2.25 Million
</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" text="#000000" link="#f00000" vlink="#2f4f4f">
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="./images/busrev.gif" width="395" height="131">

<table align=center units="pixels" width="400" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" border="0">
<tr>

<td valign=top width="400">

<P>A suit brought by a Miami lawyer over a 1992 Wisconsin train derailment that spilled more than 30,000 gallons of toxic liquids into the Nemadji River has been settled for $2.25 million.

<P>Robles &amp; Gonzalez attorney Louis S. Robles, who represented the class of plaintiffs comprising homeowners and businesses in the area surrounding the spill, as well as people injured by exposure to the chemicals, said the settlement includes damages for inconvenience, evacuation expenses, economic losses, and future illnesses.

<P>The 1992 suit, filed in the circuit court in Douglas County, Wis., alleged negligence on the part of the Burlington Northern Railroad, the company shipping the chemicals and the owner of the ruptured tank car.

<P>The accident occured on June 30, 1992, when a Burlington freight train shipping benzene solution, gasoline additives and other hazardous chemicals derailed over the river south of Superior, Wis., rupturing a tanker and spilling the hazardous contents.

<P>The spill caused a gas cloud to form over rural areas of the county, forcing evacuation of thousands of residents.


<P>The complaint alleged Burlington was negligent because the train lacked a pusher locomotive that would have supplied more power to the 57-car train. The suit also claimed improper assembly of the train and inadequate inspection and maintenance of the track.

<P>The plaintiffs were represented by Robles and co-counsel Tobe E. Marcovich of Marcovich, Cochrane &amp; Milliken in Superior, Wis.

<P>Burlington Northern was represented by Timothy R. Thornton and Scott G. Knudson of Briggs and Morgan in St. Paul and Minneapolis, Minn.; and by Thomas W. Spence of Spence, Ricke &amp; Thurmer in St. Paul.

<P>Novacor Chemicals was represented by George E. Yokitis of Babst, Calland, Clements &amp; Zomnir in Pittsburgh; and by Gaylord W. Swelbar of Hanft, Fride, O'Brien, Harries, Swelbar &amp; Burns in Duluth, Minn.

<P>GLNX Corp, which owned the ruptured tanker, was represented by Gerard W. Cook of O'Halloran, Kosoff, Helander, Geitner &amp; Cook in Northbrook, Ill; and by David B. Potter of Oppenheimer, Wolff &amp; Donnelly in St. Paul.

<P>

</table>

<P><I>Miami Daily Business Review</I>, November 5, 1993<BR>


<A HREF="inthenew.html"><P><IMG SRC="./images/toindex.gif" border="0" width="173" height="20" hspace="10"></A>
