<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Trial Tips - Florida's Offer of Judgment and Settlement Statute Revisited</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/cbs.gif" text="#000000" link="#f00000" >
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/rglogo.gif" width="606" height="105" >
<BR>
<H1>
<HR size="7" width="150">Trial Tips
<HR size="7" width="150"></H1>

<I>By:  Ervin A. Gonzalez</I>

<H1>Florida's Offer of Judgment and Settlement Statute Revisited</H1>
</CENTER>

<P>In the case of <I>Timmons v. Combs</I>, 608 So.2d 1 (Fla. 1992), the Florida Supreme Court repealed Florida Rule of Civil Procedure, 1.442, and noted that Florida Statute &#167;45.061 no longer applies to causes of action accruing after October 1, 1990.  Thus, the only "Offer of Judgment/Settlement" Statute currently available is Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79.

<P>The <I>Timmons</I> Court adopted the procedural portions of Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79 as its own. Id.  By doing this, the Supreme Court avoided any challenge against the Statute based on the Legislature's possible violation of the Supreme Court's sole rule-making authority.  See Art. V, &#167;2(a) Fla. Const. (1972).

<P>The Supreme Court clarified the status of Florida law with respect to offers of judgments/settlements.  Prior to that, the available offer of judgment rule and statutes (Rule 1.442, Fla.R.Civ.Pro.; Fla.Stat. &#167;&#167;45.061; 768.79) created much confusion and were the subject of great criticism by many legal commentators.  While much of the confusion has been cleared up, it is critical to remember that Fla. Stat. &#167;768.79 does not apply to offers of judgment when the underlying cause of action accrued prior to the statute's effective date of July 1, 1986. <I>Metropolitan Dade County v. Jones Boatyard, Inc.</I>, 611 So.2d 512 (Fla. 1993), <I>State Farm Mutual Automobile Insurance Co. v. Malmberg</I>, 623 So.2d 755, 757 (Fla. 5th DCA 1993).  The Supreme Court's action will also avoid the need to file and serve multiple offers of judgments/ settlements under the rule and statutes.  Attorneys often filed offers under Fla.Stat. &#167;&#167;45.061; 768.79, and Rule 1.442, Fla. R. Civ.Pro., in seeking to perfect their clients' rights to attorneys' fees and costs.

<P>The following summarizes the significant portions of Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79:
<H2>Application</H2>
<P>The Offer of Judgment and Demand for Judgment Statute applies in any civil action for damages whether in tort or contract.  It also applies in actions for damages involving policies issued or renewed on or after October 1, 1990.  See Note 1 to Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79.
<H2>Time for Making Offer/Demand</H2>
<P>The Offer/Demand for Judgment Statute does not state when it
may be first made in a case.  Nevertheless, it should not be made before the opposing party has made an appearance in the lawsuit by virtue of a responsive pleading or motion.
<H2>How to Make the Offer/Demand for Judgment</H2>
<UL>
<LI>The Offer/Demand for Judgment must be in writing.  It must state that it is made pursuant to Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79.
<LI>It must name the party making the offer/demand and the party to whom it is being made.
<LI>It must specifically state the amount offered to settle the claim for punitive damages, if any.
<LI>It must state the total amount offered or demanded and any conditions or terms related to the offer/demand.
<LI>The offer/demand shall be served upon the party to whom it is made, but it shall not be filed in court unless it is accepted; or unless it is necessary to enforce the provisions of Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79.
</UL>
<H2>Acceptance</H2>

<P>The offer/demand is accepted by filing a written acceptance with the Court within 30 days after service of the offer was made on the opposing party.  The accepting party needs to file the acceptance as well as the offer or demand for judgment with the court.  Once the offer is accepted, either party may submit a proposed final judgment to the trial court for entry consistent with the terms of the accepted offer/demand.

<P>The offer/demand may be withdrawn, but only in writing.  The withdrawal must be served on the party to whom the offer/demand was made before it is accepted.  If the offer/demand is accepted before it is withdrawn, then the case is settled and the terms will be enforced.  If the offer/demand is timely withdrawn, the offer/demand becomes void and has no force or effect.
<H2>Sanctions</H2>


<P>A trial court shall sanction a party unreasonably rejecting an offer when the judgment entered is at least 25 percent less than the offer made by the defendant, or 25 percent more than the demand made by the plaintiff.  The party sanctioned shall be required to pay the reasonable costs and attorneys' fees incurred by the offering party from the date the offer was made.

<P>If the court determines, on its own discretion, that the Offer/Demand for Judgment made pursuant to Fla. Stat. &#167;768.79 was not made in "good faith", the court may disallow an award of costs and attorneys' fees.  It is important that Offers/Demands be bona fide "good faith" proposals.  The Fourth District Court of Appeal has held an offer of settlement of $10,000.00 unreasonable and insufficient where the plaintiff's attorney had expended approximately $20,000.00 worth of fees. <I>Stewart Select Cars, Inc</I>., 619 So.2d 1037, 1039 (Fla. 4th DCA 1993).

<P>The obligation of "good faith" requires that the offeror have some reasonable foundation on which to base the offer made.  <I>Schmidt v. Fortner</I>, 629 So.2d 1036, 1039 (Fla. 4th DCA 1993).  The demand for judgment will not be considered to be made in "bad faith" if the offeror fully intended to conclude the case by settlement. Id. at 1040, n. 5.

<H2>Admissibility of Offer/Demand for Judgment</H2>

<P>The Offer/Demand for Judgment Statute does not allow the offer/demand to be mentioned, discussed or admitted into evidence during trial.  If sanctions are sought, or enforcement of the settlement is being requested, then the Offer/Demand for Judgment is admissible in a post-trial proceeding.  The party seeking sanctions under the statute must file a motion with the court within 30 days after the entry of judgment or after a voluntary dismissal requesting fees and costs under the statute.  Evidence of the Offer/Demand for Judgment is admissible only in proceedings to enforce the accepted offer/demand, or to determine the imposition of sanctions under the Statute.

<H2>Court-Ordered Mediation and Offers of Judgment</H2>

<P>In 1990, the Florida Legislature enacted the recently redesignated Fla. Stat. &#167;44.102(6)(b) which states: "Sections 45.061 and 768.79 notwithstanding, an offer of settlement or an offer or demand for judgment may be made at any time after an impasse has been declared by the mediator, or the mediator has reported no agreement was reached.  An offer is deemed rejected as of commencement of trial." Fla. Stat. &#167;44.102(6)(b) (1993).

<P>In the only case on point, the First District Court of Appeal denied an award of attorneys' fees and costs pursuant to &#167;44.102(6)(b), because the offering party failed to inform the opposing party that it intended to rely upon the statute. <I>Nordyne v. Florida Mobile Home Supply</I>, 625 So.2d 1283, 1290 (Fla. 1st DCA 1993).  As important, the Court in <I>Nordyne</I> stated that &#167;44.102(6)(b) may be unconstitutional since it intrudes upon the rule-making power of the judicial branch which should yield to those provisions of &#167;768.79 which have been adopted as a court rule. Id.  The Court characterized the provision as "a trap set by the legislature for those not fortunate enough to previously have stumbled across it." Id.

<P>As a result of the <I>Nordyne</I> opinion, the effectiveness of &#167;44.102(6)(b) as a method of attempting to evade the thirty day time period for accepting an Offer/Demand enunciated in &#167;768.79 is in doubt.

<H2>Promotes Settlement</H2>

<P>The purpose of the Offer/Demand for Judgment Statute is to encourage settlement among litigants by punishing those that unreasonably refuse fair Offers/Demands, and by rewarding those that make reasonable Offers/Demands by awarding them attorneys' fees and costs.  A trial lawyer is not limited in the number of Offers/Demands that may be made, nor the amount that may be offered.  An Offer may be filed for a certain amount and when the time for acceptance expires, another Offer/Demand may be filed offering a different amount.  If used strategically and reasonably, the Offer/Demand for Judgment Statute can be a very helpful tool in attaining fair and reasonable settlements of civil cases.
<CENTER>
<BR>
<A HREF="../ttindex.html"><IMG SRC="../images/toindex.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>
<A HREF="contact.html"><IMG SRC="../images/contact.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>
<A HREF="premail.html"><IMG SRC="../images/sendmail.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>

</CENTER>
</BODY>
