<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Trial Tips - Florida's Only Offer of Judgment and Settlement Statute</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/cbs.gif" text="#000000" link="#f00000" >
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/rglogo.gif" width="606" height="105" >
<BR>
<H1>
<HR size="7" width="150">Trial Tips
<HR size="7" width="150"></H1>

<I>By:  Ervin A. Gonzalez</I>

<H1>Florida's Only Offer of Judgment and Settlement Statute</H1>
</CENTER>

Recently, the Florida Supreme Court repealed Florida Rule of Civil Procedure, 1.442, and noted that Florida Statute &#167;45.061 no longer applies to causes of action accruing after October 1, 1990.  Thus, the only "Offer of Judgment/Settlement" Statute currently available is Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79.  This was decided in the Supreme Court case of <I>Timmons v. Combs</I>, 17 F.L.W. S.443 (Fla. 1992).

The <I>Timmons</I> Court adopted the procedural portions of Fla.Stat. &#167; 768.79 as its own. Id.  By doing this, the Supreme Court has avoided any challenge against the Statute based on the Legislature's possible violation of the Supreme Court's sole rule making authority.  See Art. V, &#167; 2(a) Fla.Const. (1972).

<P>The Supreme Court's action finally clarifies the status of Florida law with respect to offers of judgments/settlements.  Prior to that, the available offer of judgment rule and statutes (Rule 1.442, Fla.R.Civ.Pro.; Fla.Stat. &#167;&#167;45.061; 768.79) created much confusion and were the subject of great criticism by many legal commentators.  The Supreme Court's action will also avoid the need to file and serve multiple offers of judgments/settlements under the rule and statutes.  Attorneys often filed offers under Fla.Stat. &#167;&#167;45.061; 768.79, and Rule 1.442, Fla.R.Civ.Pro., in seeking to perfect their clients' rights to attorneys' fees and costs.

<P>The following summarizes the significant portions of Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79 which you should keep on file for future reference:

<H2>Application</H2>

<P>The Offer of Judgment and Demand for Judgment Statute applies in any civil action for damages whether in tort or contract.  It also applies in actions for damages involving policies issued or renewed on or after October 1, 1990.  See Note 1 to Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79.

<H2>Time for Making Offer/Demand</H2>

<P>The Offer/Demand for Judgment Statue does not state when it may be first made in a case.  Nevertheless, it should not be made before the opposing party has made an appearance in the lawsuit by virtue of a responsive pleading or motion.

<H2>How to Make the Offer/Demand for Judgment  </H2>
</UL>
<LI>The Offer/Demand for Judgment must be in writing.  It must state that it is made pursuant to Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79.

<LI>It must name the party making the offer/demand and the party to whom it is being made.

<LI>It must specifically state the amount offered to settle the claim for punitive damages, if any.

<LI>It must state the total amount offered or demanded and any conditions or terms related to the offer/demand.

<LI>The offer/demand shall be served upon the party to whom it is made, but it shall not be filed in court unless it is accepted; or unless it is necessary to enforce the provisions of Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79.

<H2>Acceptance</H2>

<P>The offer/demand is accepted by filing a written acceptance with the Court within 30 days after service of the offer was made on the opposing party.  The accepting party needs to file the acceptance as well as the offer or demand for judgment with the court.

<P>Once the offer is accepted, either party may submit a proposed final judgment to the trial court for entry consistent with the terms of the accepted offer/demand.

<P>The offer/demand may be withdrawn, but only in writing.  The withdrawal must be served on the party to whom the offer/demand was made before it is accepted.  If the offer/demand is accepted before it is withdrawn, then the case is settled and the terms will be enforced.  On the other hand, if the offer/demand is timely withdrawn, the offer/demand becomes void and has no force or effect.

<H2>Sanctions</H2>
<P>A trial court shall sanction a party unreasonably rejecting an offer when the judgment entered is at least 25 percent less than the offer made by the defendant, or 25 percent more than the demand made by the plaintiff.  The party sanctioned shall be required to pay the reasonable costs and attorneys' fees incurred by the offering party from the date the offer was made.

<P>If the court determines, in its own discretion, that the Offer of Judgment, Demand for Judgment made under Fla.Stat. &#167;768.79 was not made in good faith, the court may disallow an award of costs and attorneys' fees.

<H2>Admissibility of Offer/Demand for Judgment</H2>

<P>The Offer/Demand for Judgment Statute does not allow the offer/demand to be mentioned, discussed or admitted into evidence during trial.  If sanctions are sought, or enforcement of the settlement is being requested, then the Offer/Demand for Judgment is admissible in a post-trial proceeding.  The party seeking sanctions under the statute must file a motion with the court within 30 days after the entry of judgment or after a voluntary dismissal requesting fees and costs under the statute.  Evidence of the Offer/Demand for Judgment is admissible only in proceedings to enforce the accepted offer/demand, or to determine the imposition of sanctions under the Statute.

<H2>Promotes Settlement</H2>


<P>The purpose of the Offer/Demand for Judgment Statute is to encourage settlement among litigants by punishing those that unreasonably refuse fair Offers/Demands, and by rewarding those that make reasonable Offers/Demands by awarding them attorneys' fees and costs.  A trial lawyer is not limited in the number of Offers/Demands that may be made, nor the amount that may be offered.  An Offer may be filed for a certain amount and when the time for acceptance expires, another Offer/Demand may be filed offering a different amount.

<P>Hopefully, the confusion surrounding Offers/Demands for Judgment in Florida will now disappear since there is only one available  statute that is in effect.  If used strategically, the Offer/Demand for Judgment Statute can be a very helpful tool in attaining fair and reasonable settlements of civil cases.
<CENTER>
