<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Trial Tips - Work Product Privilege</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/cbs.gif" text="#000000" link="#f00000" >
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/rglogo.gif" width="606" height="105" >
<BR>
<H1>
<HR size="7" width="150">Trial Tips
<HR size="7" width="150"></H1>

<I>By:  Ervin A. Gonzalez</I>

<H1>Work-Product Privilege</H1>
</CENTER>
<P>Rule 1.280 of the Florida Rules of Civil Procedure codified what is commonly referred to as the "work-product privilege."  Generally speaking, documents prepared in anticipation of litigation be discovered by an opposing side "...only upon a showing that the party seeking the discovery has a need for the materials in the preparation of the case and is unable, without undue hardship, to obtain the substantial equivalent of the materials by other means."  Rule 1.280(b)(3).  Normally any work done in anticipation of litigation, or in furtherance of litigation, is protected unless the party seeking the discovery is able to establish that there is no other reasonable way of obtaining the factual information and that the information is necessary.

<P>If a party seeks to raise the work-product privilege as a basis for not divulging information or turning over documents, the party must specifically identify the documents which are to be protected and object on the basis of work product.  <I>Nationwide Mutual Fire Ins. Co. v. Harmon</I>, 587 So.2d 192 (Fla. 4th DCA 1991).  If the specific documents are not identified, and if a specific objection is not raised for each, then the work product privilege is not properly presented and the Court will not be able to rule in favor of the party attempting to protect the work product.

<P>If the discovering party is attempting to establish that there is a need for the documents or materials being sought and that they cannot be duplicated without undue hardship, it would be best for the discovering party to file an affidavit establishing the factual basis as to why the documents or materials are necessary and why it would be undue hardship in attempting to find a substantial equivalent to the materials by other means.  <I>North Broward Hospital District v. Button</I>, 592 So.2d 367, 368 (Fla. 4th DCA 1992).

<P>The work-product privilege may encompass witness statements, photographs of relevant scenes or items, sketches, drawings, opinions, theories, etc.  The work-product privilege does not protect the party's and opposing party's statement.  Rule 1.280(b)(3) specifically allows a party to obtain a copy of a statement concerning the action or a subsequent matter previously made by that party.  A witness who has had their statement taken may also request a copy of the statement without having to show need for the documents or undue hardship to obtain the substantial equivalent by other means.  Id.

<P>If the documents being sought were not prepared in anticipation of litigation, then the work-product privilege does not apply.  <I>Cotton States Mutual Ins. Co. v. Turtle Reef Associates, Inc.</I>, 444 So.2d 595 (Fla. 4th DCA 1984).  Even if it appears likely that there will be litigation, the work-product privilege will not attach unless the materials and documents were prepared in anticipation of litigation.  Id.  Nevertheless, a strong argument may be made in cases where it is obvious that litigation will arise, that any investigation done should be covered under the work-product privilege referred to in Rule 1.280(b)(3) of the Florida Rules of Civil Procedure.  If a party intends on presenting any of the "work-product documents" at trial, then the privilege is non-existent and the documents must be produced to the other side upon request. Once a party intends to use documents as evidence in a case, it becomes discoverable.  <I>Florida Power &amp; Light Co. v. Limeburner</I>, 390 So.2d 133 (Fla. 4th DCA 1980).

<P>The landmark case on work product in Florida is <I>Surf Drugs, Inc. v. Vermette</I>, 236 So.2d 108 (Fla. 1970).  In that case, the Florida Supreme Court outlines what is protected and what is not.  The names and addresses of persons having relevant information concerning a particular case and a request for the general statement about what those persons know is deemed not protected under the work-product privilege.  Id.

<P>If the opposing side is attempting to discover work product that includes opinions or attorney's thought processes and theories, then those documents are not discoverable, even if the discovering side shows a need for the documents and undue hardship in seeking the substantial equivalent.  <I>Dodson v. Persell</I>, 390 So.2d 704 (Fla. 1980).  Rule 1.280(b)(3) specifically states that a court shall "in ordering discovery of the materials when the required showing has been made, the court shall protect against disclosure of the mental impressions, conclusions, opinions or legal theories of an attorney or other representative of a party concerning the litigation."  Thus, even if there is a showing by an opposing side of the need for the factual information that would constitute work-product discovery and an inability to find a substantial equivalent without undue hardship, the court will protect those documents containing the mental impressions, conclusions, opinions or legal theories of the attorney.  Id. <I>Dodson v. Persell</I>, 390 So.2d at 707.

If an attorney inadvertently discloses work-product material, chances are that the work-product privilege has been waived.  <I>St. Paul Fire &amp; Marine Ins. Co. v. Welsh</I>, 501 So.2d 54 (Fla. 4th DCA 1987).  Nevertheless, if the work-product privilege is not raised initially, but is raised before the documents are turned over, followed by subsequent raising of the work-product privilege, the failure to raise the work-product privilege initially will not require the disclosure of the information.  <I>Truly Nolen Exterminating, Inc. v. Thomasson</I>, 554 So.2d 5 (Fla. 3d DCA 1989).  It is extremely important to protect the work-product privilege at the first available opportunity so that there is no question that the documents are not intended to be produced.

<CENTER>
<BR>
