<HEAD>
<TITLE>Lead Based Paint Manufacturers May Be Next Major Target of Litigation</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/cbs.gif" text="#000000" link="#f00000" >
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/rglogo.gif" width="606" height="105" >
<BR>



<H1>Lead Based Paint Manufacturers May Be The Next Major Target of Florida Product Liability Lawsuits in the 1990s</H1>
<I>By:  Louis S. Robles and Ervin A. Gonzalez</I>
</CENTER>

<P>Certain lead based paint manufacturers who did business in Florida before 1977 should brace themselves for an expected barrage of products liability lawsuits that will probably be brought against them in the 1990s as a result of their failure to warn Floridians about the dangers of lead-containing paint that they apparently knew about for at least 60 years. Despite the paint manufacturers long standing knowledge of the dangers of lead on human beings, and specifically to children, they failed to substitute lead in the paint with non-toxic substances until very recently. Furthermore, these paint manufacturers refused to post any warnings on the paint cans and fought against any regulations restricting their ability to make, sell and market the lead-based paint.

<P>Leading experts in the Toxic Tort field in south Florida and throughout the nation believe that the personal injury claims to be brought by brain damaged victims of lead poisoning against the paint manufacturers may parallel or even exceed the number of claims brought by the asbestos victims in the 1970s and 80s against the asbestos manufacturers for failing to warn them of the dangers of exposure to asbestos.

<H2>Lead Poisoned Children</H2>


<P>Throughout this century, hundreds of thousands of very young children have suffered lead poisoning and brain damage as a result of eating lead-based paint or as a result of breathing lead contaminated household dust.

<P>Childhood lead poisoning usually occurs in children five years old or under. It is most prevalent in young children of very poor families. This is because people who fit this category often live in very old, dilapidated, and poorly maintained apartment buildings and houses where the lead paint has oxidized, thereby releasing lead particles into the air, contaminating household dust that is later breathed by the young children. Moreover, lead-containing paint chips are often found in the homes of the poor where the children peel the chips off the wall and eat them. As a result, high levels of lead are commonly found in the blood of many poor children in needy areas of the country. The United States Congress estimates that about four million children in this country have unacceptable levels of lead in their blood.
Young children also develop lead poisoning as a result of ingesting lead after chewing on their cribs, toys, and other household items that contain lead in paint. Children often accidentally digest lead as a result of a craving to eat nonfood items, many of which contain lead.

<P>Children may also ingest lead and suffer plubism as a result of drinking lead in water released from water pipes containing lead solder; eating lead contaminated food from dishes containing lead laced in the pottery; breathing lead dust in the air from industrial and automobile pollutants; and eating foods canned in lead-containing containers. Nevertheless, the majority of lead poisoning cases in children result from the ingestion of lead-based paint either through eating paint chips or breathing lead containing dust in their own home. Congress estimates that there are about 20 million households that currently have lead paint in their interiors. Thousand of south Florida homes build before 1977 may also have lead-based paint on their walls.

<H2>Medical Consequences</H2>

<P>Overwhelming evidence exists establishing that even low amounts of lead in children can be devastating to their health. Adults can also be poisoned by lead, but children are at a much higher risk because their undeveloped brains absorb lead at a much faster rate. Lead poisoning in children usually results in one or more of the following serious medical problems:
<UL>
<LI>Seizures followed by a coma and often accompanied by cardiorespiratory arrest and sometimes death;
<LI>Brain damage evidenced by a lower IQ, mental retardation, convulsive disorders and/or learning disabilities;
<LI>Nervous system dysfunctions affecting motor skills such as the ability to walk, reach, and manipulate;
<LI>Anemia or other blood deficiencies usually demonstrated by lack of activity, excessive laziness, or constant tired appearance;
<LI>Kidney diseases and eventual total kidney failure;
<LI>Blindness; and
<LI>Hyperactivity accompanied by short attention span, increased excitability and uncontrolled behavior
</UL>

<H2>Knowledge of Danger</H2>


<P>The available medical and scientific literature and evidence on this subject indicates that the lead paint manufacturers have know or should have known about the dangers of lead poisoning to children for many years and well before the turn of the 20th century. In fact, there was so much medical literature and scientific evidence available in the 1920s that a ban on the use of lead based paint was implemented by several European countries after the International Labor Organization adopted a convention banning the use of leaded interior paints in buildings and houses. In the United States, the Lead Industrial Association in the 1930s recommended the banning of lead-based paint on all children's toys and furniture in an attempt to prevent further physical harm to children as a result of lead poisoning.

<H2>Preventable Injuries</H2>


<P>The saddest part of all of this is that in most cases, the children's lead poisoning could have been prevented if the paint manufacturers would have substituted the lead in paint with available non-toxic substances, or if they would have adequately warned the public of the hazards presented by lead to children. The paint manufacturers apparently knew of the dangers, but made, sold, distributed and marketed their unreasonably dangerous products anyway. As a result, hundreds of thousands of children have suffered and will suffer the horrible effects of lead poisoning that deprives them of their intelligence, cognitive abilities, motor skills, sight, and often lives. The effects of lead poisoning are more often than not irreversible.

<P>The lead paint manufacturers aggressively fought any and all restrictions on their use of lead in paint for several decades. During the 1940s through the 1970s, the manufacturers made a conscious effort to lobby against any governmental regulation or restriction that might affect their ability to make, sell, distribute, and market the lead-containing paint or that might require them to post warnings on the paint's containers. Lead paint for residential use was finally restricted in the United States in 1977.

<H2>Litigation</H2>


<P>The lead paint manufacturers have already been sued in numerous cases throughout several states including California, Idaho, Louisiana, New York, New Jersey, and Massachusetts. These products liability lawsuits allege that the lead paint manufacturers are strictly liable to the injured victims as a result of making, selling, and marketing unreasonably dangerous products without warning the purchaser and user of the dangers and hazards of the products. The personal injury lawsuits also allege negligence in failing to use reasonable care by not substituting lead in the paint with available non-toxic substance and by failing to warn those who used or came into contact with lead-based paint products of the hazards.

<P>In many respects, the lead poisoning lawsuits are very similar to the lawsuits brought by asbestos victims against asbestos manufacturers. Florida is a leader in Asbestos Litigation, but is not yet a leader in lead poisoning cases; however, many Florida law firms specializing in toxic torts anticipate a substantial increase in this type of litigation after the legal issues are more clearly defined by the appellate courts throughout the country. It is anticipated that a great number of similar products liability lawsuits will be filed in Florida once a pattern of favorable plaintiff rulings emerge from the litigation in other states.

<CENTER>
<BR>
<A HREF="../ttindex.html"><IMG SRC="../images/toindex.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>
<A HREF="contact.html"><IMG SRC="../images/contact.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>
<A HREF="premail.html"><IMG SRC="../images/sendmail.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>

</CENTER>
