<HEAD>
<TITLE>Trial Tips - The 1993 Legislative Session</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/cbs.gif" text="#000000" link="#f00000" >
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/rglogo.gif" width="606" height="105" >
<BR>



<H1>The 1993 Legislative Session</H1>
<I>By:  Ervin A. Gonzalez</I>
</CENTER>
<P>The Collateral Sources Law was amended during the 1993 Legislative Session.  The changes will take effect in October, 1993.

<P>As a result of the amended Collateral Source Law, the Automobile Collateral Source Act will no longer be in effect.  All will be governed under the general Collateral Source Statute found at Fla.Stat. &#167;768.76.

<P>In conjunction with this change, there has been an amendment to Florida Statute &#167;641.31, relating to the Health Maintenance Organization Act.  HMOs will be now treated like all other collateral sources under Florida Statute Section 768.76.  Thus, there is no set off for collateral sources for HMO benefits since there exists a right of subrogation.

<P>The principles of equitable distribution shall be used to determine the amounts that the collateral source claimant may be entitled to recover from a particular settlement.   The new collateral source law specifically states that the health care provider or collateral source provider will not have any right of subrogation or reimbursement for collateral sources paid after the date of the settlement or judgment.

<P>The amended collateral source law specifies that a provider's right of reimbursement shall be limited to the actual amount of collateral sources recovered by the claimant from the tort feasor, minus its pro-rata share of costs and attorney's fees incurred by the claimant.  The new law requires the claimant to send the provider of the collateral source benefits a copy of the complaint as official notice of the law suit by certified or registered mail.  The collateral source provider will then have 30 days within which to assert it notice of payment and right of subrogation reimbursement.  If the collateral source provider fails to provide the information within 30 days, then the collateral source provider will have waived any claim it may have had available.

<P>Florida Statute Section 768.76, commonly known as the Collateral Source Act, requires that the court reduce the amount of damages awarded in negligence cases by the amounts which have been paid to the claimant from other sources of insurance or other collateral benefits sources.  The Statute specifically excludes from the set-off any collateral source provider that has the right of subrogation or the right of reimbursement.  Included in that scenario, are medicare, or any other federal program providing for a federal government lien or right of reimbursement from the plaintiff's recovery.  Worker compensation benefits shall not be considered a collateral source of indemnify.

<P>The changes to the collateral source law are significant and important.  The amended collateral source law should be read, understood and referred to anytime a collateral issue arise in a case that accrues after October 1, 1993.
<CENTER>
<BR>
<A HREF="../ttindex.html"><IMG SRC="../images/toindex.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>
<A HREF="contact.html"><IMG SRC="../images/contact.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>
<A HREF="premail.html"><IMG SRC="../images/sendmail.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>

</CENTER>
</BODY>
</HTML>
