<HEAD>
<TITLE>Trial Tips - It's Time to Build Good Homes in Dade County</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/cbs.gif" text="#000000" link="#f00000" >
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/rglogo.gif" width="606" height="105" >
<BR>



<H1>It's Time to Build Good Homes in Dade County</H1>
<I>By:  Ervin A. Gonzalez</I>
</CENTER>

<P>It is time that we focus on building safe, stable and good houses in Dade County, Florida.  The time for talking is over, and the time for acting is here.  Hopefully, we have learned a very valuable lesson after Hurricane Andrew - South Florida homes must be built to withstand strong winds, rain and storms.  It is inevitable that another hurricane like "Andrew" will strike South Florida in the future.  We must prepare now so that we will not suffer the devastation that our community went through on August 24, 1992.

<P>The South Florida building code was recently strengthened.  We must now make sure that it is not amended, weakened, ignored, and abused by contractors and developers trying to make a profit instead of good homes.  The finger of fault points not only to the developers and contractors but also to the County in allowing the past version of the code to be weakened and for not properly inspecting the homes.  If we do not all wake up and clean up the mess created by lax building standards, insufficient and improper planning, the fault will belong to all of us and we will all pay the price the next time a strong wind blows into town.

<P>Fortunately for us, we are now in a position to correct the problems and to prevent any further harm.  The South Florida Building Code should continue to be updated and strengthened and should require the use of only the materials that can best withstand hurricane winds.  There should be no substitutions or amendments allowed unless they have been proven successful in storm and hurricane conditions.  Special interests and politics need to step aside and make room for the welfare of the people of Dade County.

<P>As part of the rebuilding effort, it is important to separate the Board of Rules and Appeals from the construction industry.  Undue influence over the Board of Rules and Appeals should not be allowed.  Any impropriety or appearance of impropriety must be avoided and eliminated.  The County Commission will need to deal with this in the very near future so as to ensure that the Board will work as a friend and not a foe of the homeowners.  The trust of the homeowner and home buyer must never be betrayed.

<P>Home developers and general contractors must focus on safety and proper home building techniques.  This will benefit everyone in the long run.  Quality control is also essential.  Home builders should aggressively inspect their own projects to ensure that the houses are being built safely and consistent with the new and improved South Florida Building Code.  Surely homeowners will be willing to pay a little more to get better, safer homes in which they and their families can seek refuge should another storm or hurricane approach South Florida.

<P>During the rebuilding effort, many people have been in a hurry to rebuild their homes.  To-date, the results have not been encouraging.  Many of the construction related problems that existed before the hurricane struck that led to the crumbling of the houses, exist now as a result of the rebuilding effort.  Shabby construction, improper materials, nails that are too short or not properly hammered, unsupported roof trusses, gable ends without bracing, unqualified workers, and uncaring contractors are all common predicaments.

<P>The problems with these hastily and improperly rebuilt and repaired homes will be hidden and soon forgotten, but the latent defects will become painfully evident when the next hurricane smashes into Dade County.  At that point, all of the builders' errors will be unveiled and the naked truth will be exposed.  Unsecured roofs will fly off, unsupported walls will come crashing down, and the massive destruction suffered after Hurricane Andrew will be revisited.

<P>This scene can and should be prevented.  We must avoid it in order to save our homes, communities and lives.  We need to pay attention to detail and safety in our building, repairing and rebuilding efforts.  Let us focus our thoughts and energies on rebuilding and repairing Dade County's homes correctly.  Let us build good, safe, new homes in the future.

<CENTER>
<BR>
<A HREF="../ttindex.html"><IMG SRC="../images/toindex.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>
<A HREF="contact.html"><IMG SRC="../images/contact.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>
<A HREF="premail.html"><IMG SRC="../images/sendmail.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>

</CENTER>
</BODY>
</HTML>

