<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Trial Tips - "Tort Reform" and the New Assault on the American Consumers</TITLE>
</HEAD>

<BODY background="../images/cbs.gif" text="#000000" link="#f00000" >
<CENTER>
<IMG SRC="../images/rglogo.gif" width="606" height="105" >
<BR>




<H1>"Tort Reform" and the New Assault on the American Consumers</H1>
<I>By:  Ervin A. Gonzalez and O. Oliver Wragg</I>
</CENTER>

<P>There is a wolf in sheep's clothing prowling the corridors of Congress these days that threatens to devour all of the American consumers' hard-won legal rights and protections.  It goes by the curious name "tort reform" and was let in through the front door by ambitious Republicans and their big business supporters.  The same folks, you may remember, who were elected last fall promising to cut government interference and rely instead on the "invisible hand" of the marketplace to regulate industry.  It's more efficient that way, they say, and will make business stronger and we all know a strong industry benefits consumers.

<P>Funny thing is, now they want to make sure that there is no private regulation of big business, either.  The new marketplace they envision is uncluttered with standards of conduct or penalties for corporations that act unreasonably.  The new private regulatory scheme will be skewed clearly in favor of corporate defendants.  After all, big business just wants to make sure it gets a good return on the $23 million it invested in Congressional candidates during 1994-1995.

<P>So far, corporate America is getting its money's worth: last week the House of Representatives passed its legal reform plan, ingeniously titled "Common Sense Product Liability and Legal Reform."  Now it will be up to the Senate.  The admitted goal of this tort reform plan is to make it harder for Americans to get into court when they are injured by unreasonably dangerous products.

<P>There are four main proposals:  (1) cap punitive damages at $250,000; (2) cap noneconomic damages at $250,000; (3) force losing parties to a lawsuit to pay the attorneys fees of the winning party, and, (4) protect manufacturers from being sued over products made more than 15 years earlier.  If these ideas are passed by the Senate and become law, it will effectively roll back much of the hard-won consumer safeguards of the past 30 years.

<H2>Cap Punitive Damages at $250,000</H2>

<P>The linchpin of this corporate welfare agenda is the proposal to cap a corporation's punitive damages at $250,000.  Punitive damages are supposed to punish a business or individual who acted in a reckless, wanton or deliberate manner.  Many times, especially when the injuries have been caused by a huge corporation, the amount of liability for one person's injuries is so inconsequential to that corporation that the business has no incentive to discontinue the activity that caused the injury.  This is especially so if it is cheaper for the corporation to pay the claims to injured persons, rather than spend the money to fix the product or change the dangerous behavior.

<P>Compensatory damages, including pain and suffering, are predictable, often with enough accuracy to permit corporations to factor those payouts into a cost-benefit analysis for new products.  But the amount of potential punitive damages penalties is always uncertain; corporations can never predict what a jury will do.

<P>Remember the famous Ford Pinto exploding gas tank case in the 1970's?  The Pinto's gas tank had a design flaw that caused it to burst into flames, even after minor accidents.  Turned out Ford's engineers had discovered the flaw long before the Pinto was offered for sale to public.  But top management concluded that it would be cheaper to settle the suits from people injured by the defective tank than to redesign the Pinto.  Ford knowingly allowed people to suffer serious, horrible injuries, because it was more cost-efficient to pay them off.  What Ford could not predict, however, was how much they would be forced to pay in punitive damages.  Only punitive damages far in excess of the actual cost of the injuries forced Ford to design safer gas tanks.

<P>Don't think for a moment that the lesson of the Pinto case was lost on the rest of corporate America.  Fear of the unknown serves as the "invisible hand" helping to convince corporate bean-counters that it is, indeed, better to produce a safe product than to pay off the people that their products injure.  Punitive damages prevent corporations from putting profits over people and sales over society.

<H2>Cap Non-economic Damages at $250,000</H2>

<P>A second prong of this attack on the rights of American consumers is the plan to limit noneconomic damages to $250,000.  "Noneconomic" means pain and suffering, as opposed to lost wages and medical expenses.  This will blatantly discriminate between the rich and the poor.  By limiting pain and suffering awards, only well-to-do victims of negligence, with their high earnings and potential lost wages, pose financial problems to defendants.  The lesson is clear: be careful when you are dealing with a business person or a banker, but don't worry if it's only a sales clerk or a teller.

<P>Many of our leaders have forgotten that the value of a human life is worth more than the aggregate of his or her paychecks.  Under the proposed system all persons are not created equal and only the rich shall be entitled to recover full compensation if injured as a result of a dangerous product.

<H2>"Loser Pays"</H2>

<P>One of the most beguiling of these anti-consumer proposals is the "loser pays" rule.  It is seductive in its simplicity: whoever loses the lawsuit should pay the costs and attorneys' fees incurred by the winner.  People call it the "English rule" because it is used in the court system in Great Britain, but its roots are even deeper: remember the ancient Mayans, who sponsored athletic contests where the captain of the losing team was sacrificed to the gods, usually by having his heart cut out?

<P>What the business interests don't tell you is that the "loser pays" rule serves to virtually eliminate the ability of anyone but the wealthy and large corporations to stand up for their rights in court.  A recent survey commissioned by the Florida Bar Foundation revealed that lower-income and moderate-income Floridians are the most under-represented in the state.  The study by Temple University's Institute for Survey Research reported a large unmet demand among our state's poorest citizens for legal help with housing, personal finance and consumer problems.  The reason, of course, is the cost of hiring a lawyer, so high that most ordinary working people can't possibly hope to ever afford an attorney;  yet, while Florida's lawyers struggle to provide affordable representation to consumers, large corporations and their lobbyists and attorneys are actively seeking to deny consumers access to courts with the "loser pays" laws.

<P>If a consumer is injured by a corporation, and takes that company to court and loses, then the consumer will be liable for the tens of thousands of dollars that the corporation paid its lawyers.  Of course, the corporation starts off with the ability to pay its lawyers several hundred dollars an hour, whereas the consumer cannot, so "loser pays" means nothing to the business interests.  What this law will do is give big business a clear advantage when it comes to product safety and consumer satisfaction; the only lawsuits that will ever be brought by consumers will be "perfect" cases with no doubt about the outcome.  And don't forget all those corporate lawyers available to make sure there is never any such thing as a "perfect" case against one of their clients.

<H2>15-Year Statute of Repose</H2>

<P>The fourth prong of this attack on the rights of consumers is more complicated but no less dangerous, the 15-year "statute of repose."  Here's how it works: once a product rolls off a company's assembly line, a magic clock starts to tick.  As soon as that clock reaches 15 years, then anybody who is hurt by the product may not file suit.  This is true even if the product poisoned you over time and the cancer or other latent deadly disease did not appear until more than 15 years later.

<P>The problem is, there are a staggering variety of products out there that cause latent injuries: the damage has been done, you just don't know it yet.  Asbestos is a classic example.  Thousands of insulation workers inhaled asbestos fibers, not knowing that to do so was dangerous.  The companies that made and sold those asbestos insulation products didn't tell the workers that once those fibers became embedded in their lungs they started a physiological chain reaction, the first stage of lung cancer.  Not until 20 or 30 years later, when workers began dying by the thousands from cancer, did the public realize what had happened.  But if the wolves have their way, it would have been too late for those workers.

<P>This 15-year statute of repose ignores the realities of 20th- and 21st-century America.  We live in a society of chemicals and technologically advanced products, which we are exposed to and interact with in countless obscure ways.  There are 60,000 chemicals in wide use today, and only about two percent have been comprehensively tested by scientists, and there is no research data at all on 50,000 of those substances.  Do we really want to absolve businesses making products with these chemicals without testing them of responsibility if they end up hurting unknowing consumers?

<H2>The Myth of the Litigation Explosion</H2>

<P>What makes this new assault on the American consumer so remarkable is how effectively the public has been misled about the need for these supposed "reforms."  Through widespread advertising campaigns, business interests have created the impression of a legal system out of control, and sketched a portrait of armies of lawyers rising from the mists like the undead to bring down the mighty houses of industry.  Where the facts don't fit, they are discarded.  Image is everything; sound bites are the rule.  It is a ruthlessly capable mechanism for swaying public opinion, and is all too reminiscent of the way political campaigns are run.

<P>For example, the McDonald's coffee case has become the poster child for the tort reform campaign, in much the same way Willie Horton was exploited during the 1988 presidential campaign.  By now we all know the story: the 81-year-old New Mexico woman who spilled boiled coffee in her lap, sued, and was awarded $2.9 million, $200,000 in compensatory damages and $2.7 million in punitive damages.  Pretty outrageous, if that's all you've been told.

<P>Of course, the big corporations didn't tell you the coffee's temperature was 180 degrees.  Or that company records revealed McDonald's had received more than 700 complaints about the temperature of its coffee and had been routinely settling claims from burn victims for years.  Or that the woman received third degree burns to her buttocks, thighs and labia from the coffee, spent a week in the hospital and had to undergo several skin grafts.  Or that she only sued after McDonald's refused to reimburse her out of pocket medical expenses, about $2,000.  Even after all that, the judge reduced the punitive damages to $480,000 and the compensatory damages to $160,000.  In the end, she was awarded $640,000, not $2.7 million.

<P>The business interests and their lawyers and lobbyists have worked very hard to convince the public that cases like this are an everyday occurrence and the result of a litigation explosion brought by suit-happy trial lawyers with nothing better to do.  In fact, this "crisis" exists only in the minds of CEOs and insurance company executives looking to maximize profits and minimize liability in return for the American consumer's health and well-being.

<P>For example, product liability lawsuits are just three-tenths of one percent of all civil cases and the corporations win more of these cases than they lose.  Moreover, the National Association of Insurance Commissioners estimates that the cost to American business of this litigation is only one-fifth of one percent of retail sales.  Or, put another way, less than what all Americans spend annually on dog food.

<P>Overall, personal injury lawsuits make up less than nine percent of all civil cases, and those numbers have declined every year since 1990.  The average personal injury jury verdict dropped in 1993 to $62,000, an 11 percent decrease from four years earlier.   The number of medical malpractice suits declined at an annual rate of 8.9 percent from 1985 to 1990.  Hardly the stuff of which "explosions" are made.

<P>But the phalanx of lawyers and lobbyists hired by big businesses haven't let facts get in the way of their aggressive marketing campaign.  These are, after all, the same people who brought you Joe Camel to sell cigarettes to pre-teens.  That is what brings us to the perilous position we are in.

<P>American consumers have fought long and hard to protect their rights and deserve better than to be hoodwinked by lobbyists in Washington.  We need to get the message out to the public that these proposals are not in the public's best interest.

<P>Of course, there will be temptation here to slay the messenger.  After all, some will say, the trial lawyers who raise these objections have a financial interest in being able to bring these lawsuits and collect multimillion dollar judgments from corporations.  These trial lawyers' clients are the very consumers whose rights are under attack.  But look carefully at who exactly is defending these propositions.  Are the product liability defense lawyers and lobbyists hired by large businesses acting for the public good, or on behalf of their own clients' pecuniary interests?  Then ask yourself, which of these two types of clients are you more likely to become one day, the large corporation or the consumer?

<P>What if it was your father whose respirator was accidentally turned off by a hospital worker who couldn't be bothered to make sure she was "pulling the plug" on the right patient?  Or your brother who drank a malted soda laced with toxic chemicals and who now lies, brain-dead, in a coma?  Imagine looking at your teenage son in the wheelchair he will wear for the rest of his life because of an accident caused by a joyriding teen driving with a license illegally obtained for him by his father - would you be willing to settle for having the insurance company buy your son the wheelchair, and call it even?  Is that all that has been lost?

<P>The time to make a stand is now.  Call or write your Senators in Washington and don't let them forget who it is that will really pay for this misguided attempt at "reform."  Do not allow your individual rights to be stolen by big business.  Once the consumers' protection is stripped away, it won't be coming back, at least not in our lifetimes.<CENTER>
<BR>
<A HREF="../ttindex.html"><IMG SRC="../images/toindex.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>
<A HREF="contact.html"><IMG SRC="../images/contact.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>
<A HREF="premail.html"><IMG SRC="../images/sendmail.gif" hspace="10" border="0" width="173" height="20"></A>

</CENTER>
</BODY>
