<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: 1SL's Message</title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<H2>1SL's Message</H2>

<H4>Admiral Sir Jock Slater GCB LVO ADC</H4>

<img align=left hspace=6 hspace=6 src="../graphics/sealord.gif">

 I am very pleased to welcome you to the Royal Navy and Royal Marines' World
Wide Web Site.  I attach great importance to it as a means of updating you
about the service for which you pay.</P>
<P>The Armed Forces are engaged on a period of restructuring on an
unprecedented scale and the Royal Navy is no exception with radical surgery
underway to improve the balance between front line, support and people.  This is
a process inevitably fraught with turbulence and upheaval but absolutely
essential if we are to take the Services lean and fit into the next century with
a finite budget.</P>
<P>The strategic scene is changing fast;  sporadic conflicts have replaced the
monolithic threat.  However, the need for the versatility and reach of
balanced maritime forces, usually within joint and combined operations with our
allies and sister services, is clear.  Looking to the future, we are programmed
to update and enhance the Royal Navy's three core capabilities for power
projection - aircraft carriers and their embarked air groups, amphibious forces
and nuclear powered submarines.  Furthermore, plans are in train to continue
modernising our vital escort forces of frigates, destroyers and other specialist
ships, including a new generation of air defence ship, our mine countermeasures
force and the Royal Fleet Auxiliary.</P>
<P>I welcome the many and varied tasks placed on the Royal Navy and Royal
Marines but obviously, with fewer ships available, the Fleet is stretched and so
are its people.  Leaner manned ships also demand more from their ship's
companies and those who support them.  Furthermore, we have to work harder to
maintain our training and maintenance standards, already the envy of the world.</P>
<P>In these Internet pages you will gain a feel for, and I hope be impressed by, the
sheer range of our activities.  As I write, many ships and submarines of
the Royal Navy and Royal Fleet Auxiliary, Royal Marines Commando Units and a
streamlined Divisional Headquarters and much of the front line Fleet Air Arm are
playing leading roles in a considerable number of operations across the globe.  I have no doubt
that, as I come to update this introduction over the coming months, the pace of
life for the Royal Navy will change very little.  One thing never changes: 
however much we strive for a leaner manned force, we will always have a need for
people of the highest calibre and we continue to offer one of the most varied
and rewarding careers available anywhere.  These pages will also show you the
enormous range of opportunities open to young - and some not so young - people
of vastly differing skill levels.</P>
<P>
I hope that you will find on the Internet a great deal to inform you about the Royal Navy, one of the nation's
most important assets.  


Whatever your point of view about the Royal Navy, please
let us know by completing the <A TARGET="_parent" HREF="../feedback/index.htm"> feedback facility</A>; we would welcome
your comments.</P>

&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;<img  hspace=6 src="../graphics/slsig.gif">





</P>
<P>
<center>
