<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: About the Royal Navy </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<H2><img align=right hspace=6 src="../graphics/surfcov.gif">About the Royal Navy</H2>

The Royal Navy has a glorious <A TARGET="contents" HREF="../history/surface.htm"> history</A> which can be traced back for a thousand years. Through times of danger, it has often stood as the only bastion between continued freedom and continental foe. It has faced and overcome challenges in the near oceans and the far seas. The words of the great Victorian anthem - `Rule Britannia, Britannia rule the waves, Britons never, never, never shall be slaves!' - were no more than a recognition of our dependence on sea power.</P>

But times change, and the last great monolith - the Soviet Union -   which seemed for nearly half this century to threaten our Western    liberty and values, has dissolved. In the absence of an obvious enemy, people are once again asking about our Defence needs, just as they have always done in times of peace and stability.</P>

Issues are raised that look at every aspect of the United Kingdom's security. In terms of the Royal Navy, they include:</P>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../history/surface.htm"> <H4>A  Short History</H4> </A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="surface.htm"> <H4>What sort of Navy do we have today?</H4></A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="invest.htm"> <H4>Why do we invest in a Navy?</H4> </A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../future/surface.htm"> <H4>What sort of Navy will we need for the future?</H4> </A>

These pages set out to answer these questions objectively, realistically and honestly. In so doing it also aims to introduce the greatest single     factor in our ability to defend Britain's interests world-wide, the men and women who go down to   the sea in ships.











</P>
<P>
<center>
