<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Future: Surface Fleet </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<H2>Surface Fleet</H2>

<H4>What sort of Navy will we need for the future?</H4>



<table align=right>
<tr>
<td><img hspace=6 src="../graphics/focean.gif"> 
<BR><I>HMS Ocean (artists impression)</I></TD></TR></table>

The new era that has been described, and the role of the Royal Navy in the United Kingdom's foreign and security policy, means that the size and shape of the fleet will continue to evolve. The driving factors are not simply those of need: the Royal Navy is very conscious of the requirement to operate within as a small a budget as possible, and to do so cost-effectively avoiding waste and unnecessary expense.</P>

This philosophy has been carried through into the design of the next generation of ships which have much smaller crews, a high degree of computer automation and are multi-role.</P>

They need to be multi-role to face the wide range of tasks that they will be called upon to perform around the world. But they must also be capable of carrying out specialist roles when needed. This section therefore offers a glimpse of what sort of Navy we will require and how that translates into specific ships, aircraft and submarines.

<H4>Maritime Organic Air Power</H4>
The first of the three core capabilities is expected to remain an essential component of most operations - be they deterrent, hostilities, peace-keeping or major humanitarian efforts. The ability to put combat aircraft, or support helicopters, into the air over international waters or inland during littoral operations is likely to be a key factor in determining success. Thus the Royal Navy intends to retain, and ultimately to look to replace, its three aircraft carriers.</P>

But the aircraft carriers themselves would be of little use without effective aircraft. The present Sea Harrier FA2, with its advanced radar and AMRAAM medium range air to air missiles, 
Sea Eagle anti ship missiles and laser guided bombs, is one of the most advanced packages in Europe. But studies indicate that it will be outclassed by 2010. So work is underway, 
with the United States, to develop an Advanced Strike Technology aircraft, that can fly from our smaller aircraft carriers, and that will be both stealthy and supersonic. This futuristic but realistic and affordable joint project will be of great importance to the United Kingdom if it is to retain a truly global ability to deploy air power.

<H4>Amphibious Forces</H4>
<table align=left>
<tr>
<td><img hspace=6 src="../graphics/flpd.gif"> 
<BR><I>Artist's impression of the new Landing Platform Dock</I></TD></TR></table>


 The emphasis that future operations will place upon the ability to insert and extract troops into a country from the sea - either as deterrent forces or as part of a peacekeeping or humanitarian mission - demands that the specialist shipping we posses must be up to the job. HMS Ocean, launched in October 1995, is a step in this direction. She is the United Kingdom's first purpose built Landing Platform, Helicopter, designed to take Royal Marines and Army units anywhere in the world and land them by large helicopters and by landing craft. A very versatile ship, she cannot however land heavy tanks and for that role the Royal Navy is looking to acquire replacements for Fearless and Intrepid (which are some thirty years old) in the shape of two new Landing Platform Dock ships. These will operate with new high speed landing craft to enable the insertion or withdrawal of vehicles, troops, refugees or evacuees to be conducted swiftly with the minimum of risk.

<H4>Project Horizon</H4>
The twelve Type 42 air defence destroyers will need replacing in the first few years of the next century. This will be achieved through twelve Common New Generation Frigates which will be built as part of Project Horizon. This is a joint Anglo/French/Italian venture that marks an important European dimension to Naval construction and philosophy.

<H4>Nuclear-powered Attack Submarines</H4>
The role of these submarines, with Tomahawk, has already been described, and it is considered axiomatic that the United Kingdom will continue to rely on the options that these fast and stealthy boats provide. Replacements for the older
S-Class will be necessary, however, so the Royal Navy is seeking to acquire up to five new Batch 2 Trafalgar Class submarines to maintain a flotilla of twelve units. In the longer term, the earlier Batch 1 Trafalgar Class will need to be replaced and studies are in hand to determine the most effective design. This may well mean a collaborative project, possibly with the French Navy.

<H4>Merlin Helicopters</H4>
This type of European collaboration has already come to fruition in the Anglo/Italian Merlin helicopter project that
will provide the replacement for the venerable
Sea King. Merlins will operate from frigates and destroyers as well as the aircraft carriers. They will be configured for anti-submarine, anti-surface and personnel/troop carrying duties.


<H4>Mine Warfare Vessels</H4>
The five Sandown class minehunters have proved very successful in service, but the number is insufficient for the demands placed upon them. As a result, an order has recently been placed for additional ships, which will be built be Vosper Thornycroft
at Woolston, Southampton. They will enter
RN service between 1997 and 2001.

<H4><table align=right>
<tr>
<td><img hspace=6 src="../graphics/fsurvey.gif"> 
<BR><I>HMS Scott (artists impression)</I></TD></TR></table>Ocean Survey Ship</H4>
An order has been placed for an ice strengthened ocean survey ship which will commission in 1997. Displacing 13,000 tonnes this will be the largest survey ship ever built for the Royal Navy. The ship will be named HMS Scott after the legendary explorer Captain Robert Falcon Scott, RN - 'Scott of the Antarctic'. 

<H4>Overall</H4>
The demands of the next century are recognised in the United Kingdom's continuing strategy for the development
of the Royal Navy. Against a realistic recognition of affordability, the Royal Navy intends to equip, man and train its front line forces to world class standards. To do anything less, with the scope and range of global challenges that the Royal Navy's personnel will have to face, would be folly.</P>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../history/surface.htm"> <H4>A  Short History</H4> </A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../today/surface.htm"> <H4>What sort of Navy do we have today?</H4></A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../today/invest.htm"> <H4>Why do we invest in a Navy?</H4> </A>



</P>
<P>
<center>
<HR WIDTH="50%">



