<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Future: Fleet Air Arm </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<H2>Fleet Air Arm</H2>

In 1979, the governments of Italy and the United Kingdom reached an agreement to launch a collaborative project to develop a helicopter to meet the demands of the 1990s and beyond. </P>
The EH101 Merlin was the outcome and the Royal Navy has now ordered some 44 airframes to replace and supplement the in-service Sea King and Lynx anti-submarine and anti-surface helicopters. Although heavier than the Sea King, the Merlin possesses a deck landing agility equal to that of the much smaller Lynx.  It has an extensive sensor package including   a 360 degree radar, passive sonar processor and sonobuoy dispensing carousel, Electronic Support Measures (radar detection) and a low frequency active dipping sonar. It has a fully integrated tactical and secure communications system, data highway and linkage to surface ships' action information systems. It will operate from the Type 23 frigates, aircraft carriers and some of our Royal Fleet Auxiliaries. A most sophisticated and capable aircraft, Merlin is the way ahead for the Fleet Air Arm and options for Airborne Early Warning, Search and Rescue and, possibly, Commando variants of this aircraft are under consideration.</P>

<img align=right hspace=6 src="../graphics/lynx.gif"> The arrival of the Lynx Mark 8, with its computerised tactical system and Passive Identification Device will give the Fleet a  greatly enhanced capability. Currently flying from the Naval Air Station at Portland with      its Operational Evaluation Unit, the first operational flights will be at sea by the end of 1996. This aircraft will complement the Merlin as it enters service operating from the smaller of the Royal Navy's escorts unable to accommodate the rather larger Merlin.</P>

Finally, looking ahead to the more distant future, the Ministry of Defence is now considering a spectrum of options for 2010 and beyond. Britain's wider security interests and the likely trends in the international world are key considerations. Affordability is crucial and effectiveness issues are at the very forefront. Options for the future are being kept open; the key perspective is one of alternatives rather than firm avenues. Replacements for the Sea Harrier are being studied and a promising possibility is an Advanced Short Take Off and Vertical Landing aircraft which could be produced in collaboration with NATO partners.  A replacement for our INVINCIBLE class aircraft carriers is also under consideration.</P>

Air superiority supports the establishment       of robust sea control, air supremacy is a necessary precondition of command of the   sea and the Fleet Air Arm provides both of these requirements. During peacetime operations the availability of organic Naval Air Power contributes an ability to enforce a no-fly zone and combat air support, as has been shown during operations in 1995 in the Adriatic Sea. The Fleet Air Arm's ability to provide in-theatre movement of peacekeeping forces and humanitarian aid, and casualty evacuation  have been most evident ashore in the former Yugoslavia. Meanwhile, the ever present worldwide submarine threat is further addressed by our current and future aircraft.</P>

There is no doubt that operations in support   of the United Nations and NATO will be increasingly prevalent for British forces. The Fleet Air Arm has shown and will show its ability to meet this challenge in the 21st Century.</P>

One of Nelson's great strengths as a commander was his confident willingness to amend established doctrine when necessary. Before Trafalgar he explained, as he put it,  'not only to the commanders of the fleet but   to every individual' how he was going to  deviate from the standard single line of battle. In modern warfare the flexibility of the Fleet Air Arm offers our sea commanders that additional capability from the air.</P>

Undoubtedly Naval Air Power has been at the very forefront of the United Kingdom's ability   to project power and will continue to do so. New aircraft and ships from which to fly offer exciting potential for a new era of air power from the sea.</P>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../today/faa.htm"><H4>Fleet Air Arm</H4></A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../today/faapeople.htm"><h4>Our People</h4></A>



<tr><td> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="../history/faa.htm"><H4>History</H4></A>







</P>
