<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: History: Fleet Air Arm </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<H2>Fleet Air Arm</H2>


In 1907 the Wright Brothers offered the patents for their aeroplane to the Admiralty and received the following reply:</P>

<B>'Their Lordships are of the opinion that they would not be any practical use to the Naval Service'</B> </P>

History has since proved how wrong those gentlemen were and it turned out that aviation  was not to be ignored. First the Navy went ahead with the building of a rigid airship, meanwhile various naval officers were    learning to fly at their own expense and      were responsible for the application of    aircraft to Naval use by their somewhat daring experiments. In 1912 Lieutenant Samson   took off from a stationary ship for the first  time, from HMS AFRICA in a Shorts S27. </P>

In 1912 the Royal Flying Corps was formed with separate Naval and Military Wings and plans were approved for a chain of Naval
Air Stations around the coast.
On 1 July 1914 the Naval Wing of the Royal Flying Corps (RFC) became the Royal Naval Air Service (RNAS) and this marked the real birth  of Naval flying. It had 228 officers, 700 ratings, with 40 aeroplanes, 31 seaplanes and            7 airships - a force to be reckoned with, as it was soon to show. Successful bombing raids were carried out against German Zeppelin sheds and the first night aerial bombing raid was against the German gun batteries of Oostende. In 1915 the first Victoria Cross to  be awarded to a Naval airman was gained by Sub Lieutenant Warneford who attacked and destroyed, in the air, Zeppelin LZ 37 and overnight became a national hero.</P>

What was needed most of all, however,       was to be able to take aeroplanes to sea with the Fleet. This began with seaplane carriers,    HMS ENGADINE, RIVIERA and EMPRESS, but rough seas too often prevented effective flying. Experiments subsequently took place with conventional wheeled aircraft taking off from platforms mounted on the gun turrets of battleships and from lighters towed behind destroyers. 
<img align=right hspace=6 src="../graphics/hfaasp.gif"> On 2 August 1917 Squadron Commander Dunning made the first deck landing by flying   a Sopwith Pup on to a flight deck built over the forward section of HMS FURIOUS. This event laid the foundations for future purpose built aircraft carriers.</P>
In 1918 the RNAS and RFC were merged into  one service, the Royal Air Force but, after a long struggle, the Naval Air Branch, later known as  the Fleet Air Arm, was returned eventually to Admiralty control in 1937. World War 2 gave       a new impetus to naval flying which gradually changed naval tactics from a ship versus ship conflict to aircraft versus ships, with devastating effect. The crippling of the Italian Fleet in Taranto Harbour by Swordfish biplanes carrying torpedoes in a night attack in 1940 was undoubtedly the most notable Fleet Air Arm success of the war. </P>

<img align=left hspace=6 src="../graphics/hfaasf.gif"> By the end of the World War 2 the strength of  the Fleet Air Arm was: 59 aircraft carriers, 3,700 aircraft, 72,000 officers and men and 56 air stations all over the world. The aircraft carrier had replaced the battleship as the Fleet's capital ship and its aircraft were strike weapons in their own right. However, piston engined aircraft were reaching the limits of their development. The Sea Fury together with the Firefly, bore the brunt of the next conflict - the Korean War. From the Fleet Air Arm's point of view the light Fleet carrier had more than proved its worth. The squadrons had brought their efficiency to new heights and the experience would serve in good stead for a new generation of jet aircraft about to come into service on the larger strike carriers ARK ROYAL and EAGLE.</P>

The Sea Hawk single seat ground attack fighter, was the first jet fighter developed to a naval specification. It entered service in 1951 and was joined shortly afterwards by the Sea Venom, the Fleet's first radar equipped, two seat, all weather fighter. Airborne early warning was a new role for the Fleet Air Arm introduced at that time. The first aircraft used was the American built Skyraider which was subsequently replaced by the specially developed Gannet AEW3. With several hundred Soviet submarines in service there was no neglect of anti-submarine effort, as there had been between the wars, and the Gannet AS I took on this most important task. </P>

<img align=right hspace=6 src="../graphics/hfaahel.gif"> About this time, too, a significant change took place with the expansion of helicopter flying in the Royal Navy. The Navy had been the first service in the world, in 1943, to order helicopters for operational use and trials of American built Sikorsky helicopters were carried out in the following year as part of the anti     U-boat campaign. The world of the helicopter has expanded in a most extraordinary way since those years, with the Fleet Air Arm frequently pioneering its uses, and the entire Royal Navy benefiting and becoming dependent on many aspects of its operations. The first helicopter landing at sea was made by Lieutenant Alan Bristow in 1946 and the first naval helicopter squadron was formed the following year at RNAS Gosport. By 1950 the Westland built Dragonfly became available and was used     for air/sea rescue. A bigger helicopter,         the Westland Whirlwind, came into service in 1952 and in the following 3 years proved itself in the Far East during the Malayan emergency. The next important stride in helicopter development was the adaption of the Whirlwind for anti-submarine warfare duties. The Wessex followed and subsequently saw some 26 years of service in the Navy with roles of anti-submarine, troop carrying and search and rescue. 
</P>
Together with the new faster and heavier aircraft there were revolutionary advances in carrier operating techniques such as the angled flight deck and mirror landing sight. Both were British inventions which radically changed flight deck operations not only in the Fleet Air Arm, but in every Navy operating aircraft at sea. Following the Suez operation in 1956 the Fleet Air Arm was on the threshold of another new era with more powerful strike and all-weather fighters coming along, the Sea Vixen, the Scimitar and the Buccaneer. A tremendous addition to the Navy's capability was made     by the introduction of the Phantom in 1968.     It had an impressive range and a capability    for carrying heavy loads, including air to air missiles and conventional or nuclear bombs. </P>


<img align=left hspace=6 src="../graphics/hfaaar.gif"> In 1970 the Sea King helicopter came into service to replace the Wessex, primarily intended for the anti-submarine role, it was later adapted for commando and other tasks. Also during this period the Lynx helicopter replaced the Wasp as the airborne part of the weapon system for the Navy's destroyers and frigates, giving them much longer reach in anti-submarine and anti-surface warfare.</P>

1978 saw the end of conventional fixed wing flying with the withdrawal of HMS ARK ROYAL.   A new generation began with the commissioning in 1980 of the first of three light aircraft carriers, HMS INVINCIBLE. These carriers are fitted with another British invention, the ski jump, which enables vertical take off Sea Harriers to carry a much greater load when taking off with forward thrust.</P>

The Sea Harrier brings the Fleet Air Arm story  up to date. Beginning operational service in 1980 aboard the INVINCIBLE class carriers,   the Sea Harrier is the aircraft which comes closest to being the Navy's answer to all the demands of seaborne air power. The Sea Harrier can be used to intercept enemy aircraft, search for and attack enemy ships, carry out sea and land reconnaissance and support land forces  as a close support bomber. Recently the Sea Harrier has been updated to the FA2 standard and is now even more capable with the Blue Vixen pulse doppler radar associated with the Advanced Medium Range Air to Air Missile (AMRAAM). 
Within the past two decades the Fleet Air Arm's greatest test was its role in the Falklands conflict of 1982. Sea King and Lynx helicopters were kept in the air continuously in the anti-submarine and anti-surface roles. The commando Sea Kings and Wessex helicopters conducted an impressive cross deck operation afloat prior to the Falklands landings, moving men and equipment to the right vessels at the right time. Some 80 helicopters played a vital part in the land force's success ashore as they deployed troops, ammunition, food and fuel across the most inhospitable terrain, often in appalling weather conditions and under enemy fire. Air superiority was the cornerstone of the campaign and it was the versatility and performance of the Sea Harrier that helped to sway the balance in our favour. </P>

Even more recently, in 1991, naval aircraft formed a significant part of the coalition  forces during the fighting in Kuwait. Sea King and Lynx helicopters were employed in all their roles both at sea and ashore in support of the ground forces and the Lynx was responsible   for sinking a number of Iraqi naval vessels. Immediately after the Gulf crisis naval commando Sea Kings were deployed to assist in the Kurdistan relief operation where humanitarian aid was provided to thousands  of refugees. Naval Aviation continues to be    at the very forefront of our Nation's worldwide commitments with commando Sea Kings based in Split being the longest serving unit  in the former Yugoslavia as part of the United Nations and later the NATO Implementation Force, while Sea Harriers, ASW and AEW Sea Kings and Lynx helicopters were at sea as  part of the multi national fleet patrolling the Adriatic.</P>

The Falklands War, the Gulf, Kurdistan and Bosnia have all come at crucial times for the Royal Navy and the Fleet Air Arm. The lessons learnt during these conflicts have been used   to shape the future of Naval Aviation.


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../today/faa.htm"><H4>Fleet Air Arm</H4></A>

