<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Latest News 091</title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<H2>Latest News</H2>
<HR>
<A HREF="../archive/archive.htm" TARGET="contents"> News Archive</A>&#160;&#128;&#160;<A HREF="../navynews.htm" TARGET="contents"> Navy News</A>
<HR></P>

19/12/96 


<H4>OCEAN WAVE 97 - ROYAL NAVY TO THE ASIA PACIFIC REGION</H4>

A Royal Navy Task Group will be deploying to the Asia Pacific region during
1997. Led by the aircraft carrier HMS Illustrious, it will comprise some 20
surface ships, submarines and support vessels.</P>

The deployment, known as OCEAN WAVE 97, will be commanded by Rear Admiral
Alan West, the Commander United Kingdom Task Group, who will be embarked in
HMS ILLUSTRIOUS. The Task Group will depart the United Kingdom on Monday 13
January returning during August.</P>

The aim of Ocean Wave 97 is to demonstrate the UK's continuing commitment to
the region and the Royal Navy's ability to deploy an operationally effective
and self sustaining maritime force for a prolonged period. This force
demonstrates the three key capabilities of the Royal Navy, namely a carrier
task group, nuclear powered submarines and amphibious forces.</P>

The exact composition of the group will change during the course of the
deployment but, assigned for the duration, will be: the aircraft carrier HMS
ILLUSTRIOUS, the assault ship HMS FEARLESS with Commodore Paul Stone,
Commodore Amphibious Warfare,. embarked: the guided missile destroyer HMS
GLOUCESTER, the frigates HMS BEAVER and HMS RICHMOND, the fleet submarine
HMS TRENCHANT and seven Royal Fleet Auxiliaries. These are the replenishment
ships RFAs FORT AUSTIN and FORT GEORGE, the logistic landing ships RFAs SIR
GALAHAD, SIR PERCIVALE  and  SIR GERIANT, the fleet tanker RFA OLNA and the
forward repair ship RFA DILIGENCE.</P>

The Royal Marine will also be taking part in OCEAN WAVE 97. 40 Commando
group will be with the deployment for the entire period, while Headquarters
3 Commando Brigade and elements of 42 and 45 Commandos join the group at
various stages. This will give the Royal Marines an opportunity to exercise
with our friends in the region and demonstrate an important aspect of the
Royal Navy's overall capability.</P>

During the deployment the Task Group will be joined for periods of up to
three months by the frigates HMS CHATHAM and HMS IRON DUKE, the fleet
submarine HMS TRAFALGAR and the survey ship HMS HERALD. The three Hong Kong
patrol boats, HM ships PEACOCK, PLOVER and STARLING will also join the Task
Group at the end of June.</P>

One of the prime reasons for the OCEAN WAVE 97 deployment is to maintain
experience of deployed carrier and Task Group operations. To achieve this
the group will be taking part in several exercises. The two most important
being FLYING FISH, an air defence and anti submarine exercise off Malaysia
with forces from our Five Power Defence Arrangements partners (Malaysia,
Singapore, Australia and New Zealand) and exercise SETIA KAWAN, an
amphibious exercise with The Royal Brunei Armed Forces.</P>

OCEAN WAVE 97 ships will also exercise with a number of other regional
navies and will gain further experience of operating both the Sear Harrier
F/A 2 and the Lynx MK8 helicopter in hot weather conditions. Royal Air Force
Harrier GR7s, embarked in HMS ILLUSTRIOUS, will undertake hot weather trials
in the Indian Ocean in March.</P>

There will be visits, usually by one or two ships, to many countries during
the deployment. The exact programme still has to be finalised, but it is
hoped to include visits to Abu Dhabi, Pakistan, India, Malaysia, Singapore,
Thailand, Indonesia, Japan, Vietnam, South Korea, Russia, the Philippines,
New Zealand, Australia and South Africa. On current plans HMS CHATHAM and
the RFA SIR PERCIVALE will be in Hong Kong in June 1997 when the territory
is handed back to China.</P>

Ends
</P>

