30/04/96 


<H4>ARRIVAL OF NEW ADMIRAL MARKS CULMINATION OF CHANGES AT BASE</H4>

The last of the major changes at <A HREF="../../uk/clyde.htm" TARGET="contents"> HMNB Clyde</A> took place today (Tue 30 Apr) with the arrival of the new Flag Officer for Scotland, Northern England and Northern Ireland (FOSNNI) and Naval Base Commander, Clyde.</p>

Rear Admiral John Tolhurst CB took the salute at Faslane from outgoing FOSNNI Vice Admiral Sir Christopher Morgan at a brief ceremony outside the Base's new Command Building.</p>

In his previous appointment Admiral Tolhurst moved the Royal Navy's Sea Training Headquarters to its new location at Devonport Naval Base after  the closure of its former home at Portland Naval Base.  Earlier this year, following the abolition of Area Flag Officers in England, he became the most senior RN officer in the South West.</P>

The arrival of Admiral Tolhurst marks the culmination of six months of radical change for Clyde base.  In October last year the base changed its name from Clyde Submarine Base to HM Naval Base Clyde, reflecting its enhanced status as a fully integrated naval base serving surface ships as well as traditional sub-surface assets, including the nuclear deterrent.</P>

The following month saw the arrival of the 3rd Mine Countermeasures Squadron and Minewarfare and Patrol Vessel Training staff from Rosyth as the east coast naval base prepared to close.  Then, in March, outgoing Vice Admiral Morgan transferred to Faslane as the flag at his old headquarters at Pitreavie was hauled down in the rationalisation following the Defence Cost Study, and his appointment merged with the Naval Base Commander Clyde.
</P>

<A HREF="../latest.htm" TARGET="contents"> Back to Latest News</A>

</P>
