<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: Structure: Surface Fleet </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="struct.htm"> <H2>Royal Navy Structure</H2></A>

<H4>Surface Fleet</H4>



<table align=right border=2>
<tr><TD>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="aircraft.htm"> <B>Aircraft Carriers</B></A></TD></TR>


<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="amph.htm"> <B>Amphibious Ships</B> </A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="type23.htm"> <B>Type 23 Frigates</B> </A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="type42.htm"> <B>Type 42 Destroyers </B>Batch 1 and 2 </A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD>
<A TARGET="contents" HREF="type42.htm"> <B>Type 42 Destroyers </B> Batch 3 (Stretched)</A> </TD></TR>


<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="type22.htm"> <B>Type 22 Frigates</B> Batch 1 and 2 </A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="type22.htm"> <B>Type 22 Frigates</B> Batch 3 </A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="hunt.htm"> <B>Hunt Class MCMV</B></A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="river.htm"> <B>River Class MCMV (MSP)</B></A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="sandown.htm"> <B>Sandown Class MCMV's</B></A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="castle.htm"> <B>Castle Class Offshore Patrol Vessels</B></A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="island.htm"> <B>Island Class Offshore Patrol Vessels </B></A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="hongkong.htm"> <B>Hong Kong Patrol Craft </B></A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="fast.htm"> <B>Fast Patrol Boats (Archer Class) </B></A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="royalyac.htm"> <B>Royal Yacht </B></A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="ocean.htm"> <B>Ocean Survey Ships </B></A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="coastal.htm"> <B>Coastal Survey Vessels</B></A> </TD></TR>

<tr><TD> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="ice.htm"> <B>Ice Patrol Ship </B></A> </TD></TR></table>

<H4>Today's Royal Navy</H4>

At the apex of the Royal Navy's role is the United Kingdom's strategic deterrent. The latest Vanguard class nuclear-powered submarines, carrying Trident ballistic missiles that can be fired from beneath the sea, are our ultimate insurance against all-out warfare, however unlikely that may thankfully now appear.</P>

In conventional terms, however, the Royal Navy  is structured around three core capabilities: organic maritime air power, amphibious forces and nuclear powered attack submarines.    These, like the supporting destroyers, frigates, auxiliaries and survey ships, all have global range and reach and are designed to act independently or jointly wherever the need arises.
<H4>Aircraft Carriers
and the Fleet Air Arm </H4>
The first of the core capabilities, organic maritime air power, 
is based on our three aircraft carriers, HM Ships Invincible, Illustrious and Ark Royal. At sea, with their aircraft (known as the Carrier Air Group) embarked, they offer a very potent and flexible form of sea power.
They are a very visible and unequivocal statement of the United Kingdom's foreign, security and defence policy. 
In international waters off Bosnia, for instance, where they maintained a continuous patrol throughout the conflict, the aircraft carriers can remain for very long periods independent from local support, yet only a very short distance from the front line. </P>
This clear capability  is well supported by 
the flexibility in the air group - in addition 
to advanced Sea Harrier FA2 fighter/attack aircraft, the aircraft carriers can carry a varied mix of Naval and Army helicopters and even RAF short take off ground attack Harriers or large Chinook support helicopters. The mix   can be tailored to whatever the operation needs and is supported by sophisticated command and control communications. This permits the role of sea based air power to extend far inland whenever the necessity arises. </P>

Maritime organic air power, and the role of the Fleet Air Arm, goes much further than just the aircraft carriers. Almost every one of the Royal Navy's 100 surface ships can carry or operate with a helicopter. Every ship from Frigate size upwards has a flight deck and hangar for one or two Lynx, Sea King or (soon) Merlin helicopters. They all have varied roles, from surface attack to anti-submarine warfare, and from special forces insertion to search and rescue. Thus the Royal Navy has become truly three-dimensional in its operational outlook through its commitment to aviation at every level.

<H4><img align=left hspace=6 src="../graphics/surfp8.gif">Amphibious Forces</H4>
Flying also plays a crucial part in the second   of the United Kingdom's core maritime capabilities, her amphibious forces. From
the outset, it must be emphasised that 'amphibious' no longer means simply putting forces on to a beach. Our amphibious forces are based on specialist shipping, sea-based aircraft and landing craft and can operate
under the control of the mother ships
hundreds of miles inland. The United Kingdom's amphibious landing force is drawn from 3 Commando Brigade Royal Marines and
its supporting Marines and Army units. </P>

There are three elements to amphibious forces: specialist shipping, the landing force and the escorting units. Our specialist shipping is currently based around two Landing Platforms Docks, HM Ships Fearless and Intrepid, together with five Landing Ships Logistic operated by the Royal Fleet Auxiliary. These ships can land (or extract) men, vehicles and even tanks using landing craft, helicopters and hovercraft or directly onto a beach. Time is of the essence
in these operations, especially when there is
a risk of opposition. Thus the ability to land
the landing force quickly is an essential requirement if the chances of success are
to be maximised. </P>

Equally, once ashore, the landing force must be mobile. The Royal Marines, with newly acquired protected mobility vehicles to supplement the ubiquitous Land Rovers, have that asset. Highly trained, elite soldiers, they are able to operate in the frozen wastes of the Arctic or the jungles of the world. Their role in bringing aid to the Iraqi Kurds or restoring the essentials of life in hurricane-wrecked Anguilla in recent times has also demonstrated their great ability to provide a humanitarian force from the sea.

<H4>Nuclear-powered Attack Submarines</H4>
It is the influence that the third core capability, nuclear-powered attack submarines, can bring from the sea that is its greatest asset as well. The Royal Navy has twelve such submarines. They roam the world beneath the waves unseen and undeclared for months on end. Their locations are rarely revealed. Their missions remain secret. But they offer the United Kingdom enormously powerful options. </P>
As intelligence gathering platforms, they provide a covert means of monitoring,
optically or electronically, the development of world affairs. As sea denial weapons, nuclear submarines have an unrivalled capacity to
force an aggressor to return to port or face destruction. They can insert special forces
and detect and trail suspected arms smugglers. Crucially, they also provide cover and protection for the ballistic missile submarines of our nuclear deterrent. </P>

But there is a key emerging role for these remarkable high-technology vessels. In the 
fast moving and complex world of international relations there is sometimes the need to demonstrate resolve without committing significant forces. To meet this need, the United Kingdom now possesses a new way of exerting persuasive influence to avoid major conflict, based on our nuclear-powered submarines. The purchase from 
the United States of Tomahawk Land Attack missiles, which are conventionally armed but fired from these submarines with great accuracy, has given the United Kingdom the means surgically to interdict - or to be able to threaten to do so, when necessary. It is judged that this will significantly increase our ability to deter aggression with minimum risk to life.


<H4>Escort Ships</H4>
These core capabilities must be supported and very much in the front line are the thirty-five destroyers and frigates which make up the Royal Navy's escort ships. A far cry numerically from the days only ten years ago when fifty or more such warships could be seen involved in anti-submarine duties, the contemporary surface flotilla is smaller, but very hard-working around the globe on a wide variety of tasks. </P>

Typically, on a quiet day, there will be one frigate or destroyer on anti-drugs patrol in the West Indies, two more in the Arabian Gulf protecting international oil tankers, two frigates in the Adriatic under NATO operational control and another in the South Atlantic offering reassurance to British citizens. Another frigate will be on a trade mission to the Far East, a destroyer supporting a United Nations relief operation in Africa and a frigate  on a goodwill visit to India. Add to these four training at sea off Plymouth, two on duty with NATO and another three engaged in multi-national exercises and more than half our ships are away at sea. The remainder are being serviced, operating in local waters or on port visits or giving their ship's company leave. </P>
This level of activity demands much of the frigates and destroyers, their supporting infrastructure and maintenance - but most
of all it requires the utter commitment of the sailors, young men and women whose average age at sea is only twenty-two. This the Royal Navy gets by having in its number some of the finest men and women of their generation at every level of the Service - and a genuine and rewarding series of tasks for them to perform. </P>

The thirty-five frigates and destroyers they operate can be divided into four groups, all of them either modern or indeed new. There are ten Type 22 frigates, of which six (the `Batch 2') are optimised for anti-submarine warfare and four (the `Batch 3') are general purpose frigates with a 4.5 inch gun and Harpoon anti-ship missiles. There are twelve Type 42 guided missile destroyers which are designed for air defence duties and thirteen Type 23 general purpose frigates with more to follow. The Type 23s, which have highly automated systems requiring less than 175 people to man them, pack a very strong punch. They are amongst  the finest such ships in any navy.

<H4>Mine Warfare</H4>
So too are the very sophisticated Hunt and Sandown class mine warfare ships. Small, made of glass reinforced plastic and able
to track down the most deadly as well as
the crude but lethal mines that many nations possess and deploy, these ships are often engaged in live operations around the world. British mine countermeasures vessels have, since 1974, been sent to troublespots to clear live mines on average once every three years. Their success on each occasion has allowed merchant ships and oil tankers of every nation to continue using the sea lanes safe in the knowledge that their passage will not be hazardous.


<H4>The Royal Fleet Auxiliary</H4>
The Royal Fleet Auxiliary - which is civilian manned - often finds itself in hazardous waters. It is responsible for the world-wide logistic support of the ships of the Royal Navy. This means getting everything from aviation parts to medical supplies, fuels and food to the twenty or so warships that are generally to be found in different quadrants of the globe. </P>

The two new Auxiliary Oiler Replenishment  ships are the pride of the fleet. Displacing
over 36,000 tons they can fuel and feed the appetite of the most voracious aircraft carriers around the clock. They do this in peace and hostilities, often in atrocious weather, at close quarters using hose pipes to transfer fuel and helicopters and jackstays to send stores across to warships that steam but metres away.
The same applies to the eleven other supply ships with more specialised roles such as the Leaf class tankers or Fort class stores ships. There are also specialised ships - the landing ships mentioned previously, the aviation support ship RFA Argus which doubled as a forward medical centre during the Gulf War, and the repair ship RFA Diligence which can provide instant servicing to damaged ships in remote areas.


<H4>Antarctic and Hydrographic Work</H4>
Pioneers in remote areas, however, are the ice patrol ship HMS Endurance and the ships of the Hydrographic Survey Squadron. Endurance, which is strengthened for the rigours of the south polar ice, supports the United Kingdom's work in preserving and conserving the last great wilderness. The survey ships go wherever mariners may need to venture and prepare the Admiralty charts which are a by-word for safe navigation. Two hundred years after starting work, the Squadron has amassed comprehensive data on much of the world's oceans but there are continual changes that require careful hydrography. In a recent development, charts are now available on CD-ROMs    so that ships can be navigated on and by computers.</P>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../history/surface.htm"> <H4>A  Short History</H4> </A>


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="invest.htm"> <H4>`Why do we invest in a Navy?'</H4> </A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../future/surface.htm"> <H4>`What sort of Navy will we need for the future?'</H4> </A>


</P>
<P>
<center>
<HR WIDTH="50%">



<A TARGET="_parent" HREF="../index.htm">Home Page</A>





