HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 06-Jan-97 10:31:51 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 25-Oct-96 18:12:10 GMT
Content-length: 5934
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: Investing in the navy </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">




<H4><img align=right hspace=6 src="../graphics/surfp1.gif">Why do we invest in a Navy?</H4>


Having charted the history of the Royal Navy, and its present size and shape, it is appropriate to examine why that Navy is required and what we can expect of the United Kingdom's investment in sea power. Again, an historical perspective is helpful. Key events influencing our foreign and security policy in these islands have followed cycles that have broadly lasted for around five hundred years.</P>

In Roman times, Britain was an island of Europe controlled from the European continent. Then, after the fall of the Roman empire Britain became an island off Europe which was the object of designs on it from the European continent. From the Norman invasion until the final loss of Calais as a British possession, we were again an island of Europe but with our designs on land in the European continent. In all these phases, there was no significant role for a Navy to play. In consequence, naval power was haphazard and generally weak.</P>

Matters changed with the next phase of growth which lasted from the late fifteenth century until, arguably, the mid-twentieth century. During this time, the role of the Navy became paramount as first England, then the United Kingdom, acted as an island off Europe with global designs away from the European continent. The wealth, prosperity and safety of the nation depended on the Royal Navy's ability to protect first colonies then empire.</P>

That phase has passed, and in recent years 
the United Kingdom has become once again 
an island of Europe, but with very real trade, commercial and security interests in Europe and around the globe. So too, therefore, has the role of the Navy changed - and not simply 
in response to the end of the Cold War, although clearly that has been a major catalyst. The Royal Navy now has three clear roles to perform: to defend the United Kingdom, to defend our allies and treaty partners, and to protect the United Kingdom's interests abroad be they through United Nations peacekeeping operations, humanitarian work or other joint missions.
In practice, and despite the occasional need to go to war as in 1991 in the Gulf, the majority of work is centred around protecting and developing the United Kingdom's interest abroad. As a nation, we depend on trade and most of our needs arrive by sea. This includes oil as well as raw materials and it is obviously essential that neither pirates nor rogue states should interfere with our sea borne trade.
The Royal Navy deploys - for instance to the Arabian Gulf and the Far East - to demonstrate our determination to keep the trade routes open.</P>

<img align=left hspace=6 src="../graphics/surfp23.gif"> The flag, in our case the White Ensign, also follows trade missions to ensure that the United Kingdom's commitment to our trading partners is clearly visible. This is highly effective in purely business terms, but also brings rewards in terms of the ability of the United Kingdom to act as an agent for peace and stability world-wide. The use of our frigates and destroyers around the globe is sometimes described as forward presence
and it permits the United Kingdom to have capable, independent and self-reliant assets on hand whenever a crisis or emergency arises.</P>

Thus when a military dictator decides to threaten a neighbouring state to deflect attention from a crisis at home, the Royal Navy is often able to show support to the threatened state by moving a frigate or destroyer close to, or even into that country's waters. The ship acts as a tripwire also as a rapid conduit for reliable intelligence back to London. This can be done overtly or covertly.</P>

Equally, the ability of Royal Navy ships to respond to a natural disaster - such as hurricanes or volcanoes in the West Indies, 
or earthquakes and typhoon flooding in Asia - makes them excellent ambassadors for the United Kingdom. The moden frigate and destroyer's communications, helicopter resources and equipment make them very capable emergency services thousands of miles from home in often appalling conditions.</P>

Of course, the United Kingdom does not
expect to act alone in most circumstances
and the majority of the Royal Navy's world-wide operations are as part of multi-national groups with Air Force and Army involvement. Whether
it be as part of a NATO force in Bosnia or a United Nations effort in Angola, the Royal Navy can and does represent all that is best in the United Kingdom's role in world affairs. There are many challenges but through rigorous preparation and training, outstanding efforts by its people and with the right equipment, the Royal Navy and Royal Marines rise to them.</P>

The United Kingdom's investment in the Royal Navy is therefore as a coherent part  of a self-confident post-Cold War foreign   and security policy that seeks to protect   our interests abroad. These interests are    in reality a closely related mix of trade
and commerce, of commitments to our dependent territories and to our allies,
and of the United Kingdom's wider and
clear objective of world peace and stability. In each case, the Royal Navy offers a cost-effective set of options, be they through covert coercion or overt co-operation, through deterrence or the delivery of aid.
It is a sound investment, and one tailored
for the new era in which we live.



<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../history/surface.htm"> <H4>A  Short History</H4> </A>


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="surface.htm"> <H4>What sort of Navy do we have today?</H4> </A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../future/surface.htm"> <H4>What sort of Navy will we need for the future?</H4> </A>


</P>
