<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: Structure: Royal Naval Reserve </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="struct.htm"> <H2>Royal Navy Structure</H2></A>

<H4>Royal Naval Reserve</H4>


<img hspace=6 align=right src="../graphics/reslogo.gif"> 

<H3>A Double Life</H3>

Nearly 3,500 men and women throughout the United Kingdom  are enjoying a
double existence.
Throughout the working week they are ordinary civilians; machine operators,
doctors, clerks, secretaries, engineers, people just like you, doing a
regular job. But sometimes when their work is done, and their time becomes
their own, they take on a completely different guise as members of the
Royal Naval Reserve (RNR)

<H3>Training for the RNR</H3>
The RNR trains to support the Royal Navy in meeting its operational
commitments in times of stretch crisis, tension and war by the timely
provision of the required number of trained personnel. You will earn your
place as a trusted team member and that means a lot of hard work. Your
annual training programme will be demanding, you will be expected to put in
between 50-100 hours, additionally, you will receive a further fourteen
days continous training. Drills occur on one or two nights a week and also
at weekends. It is not a commitment to be taken lightly.</P>

However, with expert guidance and your own determination, you will soon
feel confident enough to take your place alongside other Reservists.
For example you could serve at sea in an RN ship or ashore at Maritime
Headquarters.

<H3>The Work of the RNR</H3>
Duties include manning ships of the fleet, the provision of crew for
requisitioned vessels, and training for Merchant Navy officers. On land,
Reservists fulfil a host of functions alongside the RN, for example, as
plotters, comunicators or writers. RNR personnel may be sent to serve in
ships and shore HQs abroad.



<H3>Embarking on a double life</H3>
To qualify as a reservist you must be a British Citizen between the ages of
16 and 33. Those with special skills or previous service may be excepted
beyond these limits. You must also be educated to acceptable Royal Navy
standards and pass an entry test, interview and medical examination. If you
are interested in finding out more then you should complete and return the
 <A HREF="../careers/contact.htm" TARGET="contents"> Contact Form</A> in the <A TARGET="_parent" HREF="../careers/index.htm"> Careers section</A>, or contact any Royal Navy Careers Information Office. 
</P>
<P>
<center>







</P>
