<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: Structure: Hydrographic Service </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="struct.htm"> <H2>Royal Navy Structure</H2></A>

<H4>The UK Hydrographic Office</H4>


The Hydrographic  Office is located in Taunton in Somerset, and employs a staff of around 800 civilians and a small number of serving Royal Navy personnel.  It is a defence agency whose Chief Executive is the Hydrographer of the Navy.  The Office under his direction meets national hydrographic needs and provides the hydrographic products and services, both digital and analogue, that mariners need to go about their business at sea, safely and effectively.  To this end, the Hydrographic Office has developed the "Three Strand Business Approach" which is summarized as follows:-</P>

	<B>The National Hydrographic Programme</B> meets the national need for a hydrographic infrastructure.  Activities undertaken include the provision of charts and publications, data base management and the promulgation of urgent dangers to navigation by Radio Navigation Warnings.</P>

	<B>The Defence-Specific Programme</B> meets the specialist hydrographic, oceanographic and geophysical needs of the Royal Navy and other MOD customers.</P>

	<B>The Charts and Publications Programme</B> meets the civil and defence customers' demands for a world-wide series of hydrographic products and services.  There are currently nearly 3,300 charts in its inventory.</P>

	Performance is measured against a wide range of key targets in the Office's Business Plan.</P>

	In addition to the Taunton location the Hydrographic Office has Chart Maintenance Units at a number of sites including, Devonport, Portsmouth and Faslane.  These units maintain chart and publication stocks for local supply to the Fleet to meet immediate and emergency requirements.  They ensure that no Royal Navy ship sails without the required outfit of charts and publications.</P>

	The Royal Naval Hydrographic Surveying Squadron is an integral part of the Fleet and does not form part of the Hydrographic Office although there are close links between them.  The squadron gathers hydrographic, oceanographic and geophysical data.  It comprises two ocean survey ships, three coastal survey vessels and one survey motor launch.  These vessels are augmented by two naval parties of surveying personnel embarked in chartered civilian vessels.  The Squadron is commanded by the Captain, Hydrographic Surveying Squadron (Captain(H)) based ashore in Devonport.  Also in Devonport is the Royal Naval specialist hydrographic surveying training to the Royal Navy, Commonwealth and foreign students.






</P>
<P>
<center>
