<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: Structure: URNU </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="struct.htm"> <H2>Royal Navy Structure</H2></A>

<H3>
UNIVERSITY ROYAL NAVAL UNITS<BR> 
URNUs</H3>

<H4>What is an URNU?</H4>

<img align=right hspace=6 src="../graphics/urnu.gif"> It is a Naval training establishment on or near a university campus, with its own offices, classroom and Officers' Mess.  Each unit has also a training vessel, usually a turbo charged fast patrol craft, fitted with modern navigational equipment.  Each craft has a full time Royal Navy crew and accommodation for twelve people.  The first University Royal Navy Unit was formed at Aberdeen in 1967, with the aim of encouraging undergraduates to find out more about the Royal Navy and its role in maritime affairs.  Since then 13 others have been formed throughout the UK.

<H4>A Sense of the Sea</H4>

Undergraduates join the units with the rank of Honorary Midshipman in the Royal Naval Reserve.  If you decide to join your university unit, your introduction will include both theoretical and practical instruction, emphasizing a 'hands-on' approach.  You will learn to navigate and respond to all kinds of situations, including standing watch and performing emergency manoeuvres.  Through a regular programme of drill nights, weekends and short shore-based courses, you will find that working in a team provides opportunities for self-assessment, builds self confidence and instills a sense of the sea.

<H4>Travel and Training</H4>

During Easter and Summer vacations the training craft deploy abroad  to destinations in the Channel Islands, Norway, France, Germany and many other European countries.  This will give you the chance to become familiar with your ship, and put theory into practice during a longer voyage.  Typical training exercises on such deployments include vessel towing, replenishment at sea, and life saving instruction.  Then there is the excitement of going ashore at the various ports of call - interesting places to see and new people to meet.  While overseas, members of the URNUs also act as ambassadors for Britain, as well as consolidating training and friendships in what is, for most, uncharted territory.  Summer activities also include a week at the Britannia Royal Naval College in Dartmouth, alongside new entry junior Royal Navy Officers.







</P>
<P>
