<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: Structure: Fleet Air Arm </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="struct.htm"> <H2>Royal Navy Structure</H2></A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="faa.htm"> <H3>Fleet Air Arm</H3></A>



<H4>Our People</H4>

Supporting the aircraft of the Fleet Air Arm   and to ensure its ability to respond rapidly and effectively to many varied situations, are our people. Every man and woman is highly trained in their specialisation from aircrew to firefighters. </P>
<img align=left hspace=6 src="../graphics/fleet1.gif"> Aircrew undergo a rigorous selection process before joining the Britannia Royal Naval College, prior to undergoing flying training  which takes a minimum of 18 months. This time varies according to the type of aircraft the person is destined to fly, be it the Sea Harrier, the Sea King or the Lynx and whether they are training to be a pilot or observer.</P>

The naval aviation logistic and engineering support organisation encompasses diverse and specialised operations irrespective of location or environmental constraints. Fleet Air Arm aircraft have to be repaired all over the world. </P>

Naval air engineers are well equipped and trained to provide serviceable aircraft ready to fly and operate in conditions as diverse as the arctic and the desert, on land or at sea. Fleet Air Arm engineers can be of three main trades: radio, weapons-electrical or mechanical but, if selected, may undergo all-trade training which is proving to be highly successful and popular.</P>

Fleet Air Arm personnel and units deploying in support of combat operations are capable of operating as self contained autonomous units, which puts a premium on self reliance.</P>

At sea flight decks are often operating 24 hours a day. Thus most embarked aviation units are configured to support and sustain activity for long periods. Constraints of space onboard ship have always meant lean manning, but even so the engineering support to aircraft is conducted to exacting standards.</P>

Specialist aircraft handling, crash rescue and fire fighting are required at sea on all ships with aircraft embarked. These skills are provided by aircraft handler ratings who are also employed ashore for fire fighting duties, principally at naval air stations.
Air Traffic Control provides services ashore at the naval air stations and afloat in warships  and Royal Fleet Auxiliaries, air safety in maritime exercises and the tactical control of maritime aircraft together with embarked anti-submarine and anti-surface aircraft. 
At the same time we must never forget the support given by arms of the General Service, such as the Supply department, which procures spares for aircraft, makes sure our people are fed and clothed and, very importantly, paid.</P>

<tr><td> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="faa.htm"><H4>Fleet Air Arm</H4></A>

<tr><td> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="../history/faa.htm"><H4>History</H4></A>

<tr><td> <A TARGET="contents" HREF="../future/faa.htm"><H4>The Future</H4></A>



</P>
<P>
