<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: Structure: Royal Marines </title>

</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../graphics/mbgnd.gif"
text="#000000">


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="struct.htm"> <H4>Royal Navy Structure</A><img align=right border=0 hspace=6 src="../graphics/rmlogo.gif"></H4>

<H2>
<A TARGET="contents" HREF="marines.htm"> Royal Marines</A></H2>




<H4> Royal Marines Commando - An Overview</h4>
<H4>
Who are the Royal marines? </H4>

<table>
<tr valign=top><td>

<B>Definition:</B>  </td><td>           UK's Amphibious Infantry</td></tr>

<tr valign=top><td> <B> Key Strengths</B>:</td><td> Mobility<BR>                                       
                        Self Sufficiency<BR>
                        Flexibility<BR>
                        Rapid Response </td></tr>

<tr valign=top><td> <B>Main Role:</B> </td><td> Amphibious Operations </td></tr>

<tr valign=top><td> <B>Numbers:</B> </td><td> 7000 </td></tr></table>

<img align=left hspace=6 src="../graphics/focean.gif"> The Royal Marines are the Royal Navy's infantry, and provide a Commando Brigade for amphibious operations.</P>

On permanent readiness, Royal Marines operational units are self-contained to enable them to be deployed anywhere in the world, either in amphibious shipping or by air if necessary, to conduct a variety of military operations, ranging from peacekeeping to full-scale war.</P>

This ability to project military power around the world will be enhanced by the introduction of HMS OCEAN, a helicopter assault ship which can carry 600 Royal Marines and their supporting equipment and the order of two new Landing Platforms Dock, which carry assault landing craft.



<H4>What makes us different ?<img align=right hspace=6 src="../graphics/camof.gif"> </H4>

The Royal Marines are unique in that all officers and men carry out their basic training in the same establishment, the Commando Training Centre Royal Marines, near Exeter. Both officers and men are required to complete all the Commando tests which include a 30 mile march against the clock, before being awarded the coveted green beret. The comprehensive and thorough training required to train a recruit into a Royal Marines Commando takes 30 weeks - one of the longest and best initial training courses in Europe.

        <H4>What makes us the best ?</H4>


<table>
<tr valign=top><td>

      
                                        
                                        <B>Selection: </B> </td><td> Designed to test physical fitness, mental                                               aptitude and motivation.</td></tr>



<tr valign=top><td> <B>Training:</B> </td><td> Challenging and interesting training designed                                   to make you fit and make you think.</td></tr>

<tr valign=top><td> <B>Teamwork:</B> </td><td> Trained to work as a team for maximum                                           effectiveness.</td></tr>

<tr valign=top><td> <B>Reputation:</B> </td><td> Formed in 1664 the Royal Marines have                                           fought in conflicts world-wide, including the Falkland Islands in1982, and enjoy a reputation second to none.</td></tr> </table>







   </P>
<A TARGET="contents" HREF="who.htm"> <B>Who are the Royal Marines?</B></A><BR>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="../careers/marines/structure.htm"> <B>Royal Marines Structure</B></A><BR>

