<head><title>Royal Marines: Careers: Reserve</title>

</head>

<BODY BACKGROUND="../../graphics/mbgnd.gif"  
text="#000000">

<H2>Royal Marines Reserve </H2>



<H4><img align=right hspace=6 src="../../graphics/gunwater.gif">THE RMR CHALLENGE</H4>




If you want a real challenge at the same time as contributing to the country's defence, join the RMR.  The Royal Marines are the Royal Navy's amphibious infantry and the role of the RMR is to support the regular Royal Marines, and therefore many exciting challenges and opportunities are available to the Royal Marines Reservist.  However, you must be committed and prepared to give up some of your free time for which you will be well paid.

<H4>INITIAL TRAINING</H4>

In his first year, an RMR recruit learns about weapon handling, map reading, field craft, signals, first aid and tactics, as well as the basics of dress and drill, and, of course, physical fitness.  Training takes place one evening a week at an RMR unit or detachment near you. There are units based in Newcastle upon Tyne, London, Glasgow, Bristol and Merseyside, as well as detachments covering most of Britain.  Recruits also attend weekends at training areas such as Dartmoor, Otterburn and Longmoor.  In addition, each new recruit attends two two week courses at the Commando Training Centre Royal Marines in Devon.  If he passes the first course (Phase 1), he returns to his unit to prepare for the Commando Course, which includes a demanding 3 day field exercise, physical tests and more advanced tactics.  If a recruit passes this he earns the famous green beret the RM's much coveted reward for fitness, skill, and commitment and the right to serve alongside regular Royal Marines.

<H4><img align=left hspace=6 src="../../graphics/rope.gif">SPECIALISATIONS</H4>

When he reaches this stage, usually after a year or so, a reservist begins more advanced winter training, in particular learning arctic warfare drills, initially in Scotland, and then, if he proves suitable, in the remote regions of Norway, where he may be required to serve.</P>

Those who want to develop these kind of skills even further can train to become a ski instructor or cold weather warfare specialist.  But there are many other specialisations in which a reservist can train:  parachutist, swimmer/canoeist, PT or drill instructor, heavy weapons specialist, small arms instructor, assault engineer, or a number of other options.  The number of skills a reservist can learn is only limited by the time he can afford to commit to the RMR usually one night a week, one or more weekends a month, and a full fortnight every year, for which most employers will allow time off work.

<H4>QUALIFICATIONS</H4>

To join the RMR, you only need to be between 17 and 39 years of age and reasonably fit.  Royal Marine Reservists come from all walks of life they may be unemployed or bored with sitting behind a desk every day.  What they have in common is a desire to spend their leisure time developing their skills and personalities in a highly professional and committed environment.

<H4><img align=right hspace=6 src="../../graphics/build.gif">PAY</H4>

RMR recruits are paid at around regular RM rates for the days they spend in training.  They also receive an allowance to cover out of pocket expenses, like travel.  In addition, at the end of each year's satisfactory service, they receive a tax free bounty, which can amount to several hundred pounds.</P>

As well as providing training, travel abroad, adventure and comradeship, the RMR also offers opportunities for promotion possibly as far as commanding your own unit as a Lieutenant Colonel.  Besides the specialisations open to all ranks, officers can also train as Forward Air Controllers, Raiding Squadron Officers, or Liaison Officers.</P>

Most RMR officers are drawn from the ranks, although ex regular officers from the RM and other services may enter direct.  To be considered for a commission, you must be between 18 and 26 years of age, and have 5 acceptable GCSE grades (including maths and english).  Once you have been recommended by your Commanding Officer, you will undergo special officer training.  If you are successful, you will be commissioned as a Second Lieutenant.

<H4>YOUR NEXT STEP</H4>

The RMR is set to remain at a total strength of about 1000 with an exciting range of tasks.  If you think that you can meet the challenge, fill out the <A TARGET="contents" HREF="contact.htm"> Online Contact Form.</A> or contact one of the RMR units listed below:</P>

<table>
<tr valign=top><td>

<B>RMR City of London </B><BR>           
