<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Worldwide: UK Plymouth </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">



<A HREF="britain.htm" TARGET="contents"> <H4>United Kingdom</A> &#160;&#128;&#160; <A HREF="../today/bases.htm" TARGET="contents"> Naval Bases</H4></A>

<H4>HM Naval Base, Devonport, Plymouth </H4>



<A HREF="plyfost.htm" TARGET="contents">Flag Officer Sea Training</A><BR>

<HR>

</P>


For over 300 years the City of Plymouth has played host to ships and men of the Royal Navy.  During this time, strong and important links have been developed between Devonport naval base and the Plymouth community.  These links are actively encouraged and continue to grow.</P>

Devonport is the biggest Naval Base in Western Europe covering an area of some 622 acres.  It contains 25 tidal berths and 5 basins (44 alongside berths), and 12 dry docks of varying sizes that are capable of docking frigates, submarines and through deck carriers.  In recent times the scale of investment at Devonport has been considerable, and the technical, engineering and support facilities have all benefited from a broad modernisation and expansion programme.  The frigate Refit Complex, built in 1977, provides the only covered docks in Devonport Royal Dockyard and can accommodate any of the Navy's Frigates and Destroyers.  Other recent works include the building of the Jetty at Weston Mill Lake for the Fleet's latest Type 23 Frigates, and development of the existing Fleet Maintenance Base and the well established Submarine Refitting Complex.  The welfare of the ships' personnel has also been given due consideration, with the provision of the "Lowden" facilities.  These are satellites of the main Fleet Accommodation Centre (FAC) and are strategically sited in close proximity to ships undergoing refit to provide alongside offices, galley and accommodation for the crews.  </P>

Since the early formation of the Dockyard a number of different organisations have evolved within its walls, each responsible for providing specialist services to the Naval Fleet.  On arrival in Devonport, ships used to encounter a bewildering array of Service and civilian authorities to provide their alongside requirements.  However, on 1 April 1994 these disparate elements were amalgamated to form an integrated Naval Base dedicated to providing seamless support to the fleet.  The name chosen for the entire Naval Base was HMS DRAKE, thus perpetuating the name of the Naval Barracks, and the West Country's most famous seafarer.  This unified structure is headed by the Naval Base Commander (NBC), who is "Chief Executive" of the Base.  HMS DRAKE provides the full range of support services to the ships and submarines based at Devonport, their ships' companies and dependants, ships undergoing Operational Sea Training and other visiting ships of the Fleet, Royal Fleet Auxiliary, NATO and other foreign navies.</P>

This integrated concept has proved to be a highly successful platform from which to manage Naval Base business and has yielded dividends through increased efficiency, quality of service and sense of purpose.  HMS DRAKE boasts the complete range of technical, berthing, engineering and support facilities necessary to accommodate all the requirements of the Royal Navy well into the next millennium, and is flexible enough to respond quickly and effectively to any further challenge.  September 1995 marked the beginning of a new phase at Devonport with the commencement of Operational Sea Training which transferred from Portland.  The Director of Logistics post was created during 1996, integrating Director Supply (West) with the Base Supply Officer to provide a single point of contact for all logistics support to the Fleet.







</P>
<P>
<center>
<HR WIDTH="50%">



<A TARGET="_parent" HREF="../index.htm">Home Page</A>





</BODY>
</HTML>







