<DOCHDR>
http://royal-navy-http.pipex.net:80/today/faa2.htm 194.202.195.115 19970106104221 text/html 9095
HTTP/1.0 200 OK
Server: Netscape-Commerce/1.12
Date: Monday, 06-Jan-97 10:39:14 GMT
Last-modified: Friday, 22-Nov-96 09:19:03 GMT
Content-length: 8912
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: Structure: Fleet Air Arm </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="struct.htm"> <H2>Royal Navy Structure</H2></A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="faa.htm"> <H3>Fleet Air Arm</H3></A>


<A NAME="sh"> <H4>THE SEA HARRIER</H4></A>

<img align=left hspace=6 src="../graphics/airp10.gif"> The Navy's new Sea Harrier FA2 is a combat proven, single seat, single engine, subsonic   jet with the full range of modern weapons and advanced fighter capability which embodies look-down shoot-down capability tied to the Advanced Medium Range Air to Air Missile.   The aircraft is also able to operate, very successfully, with the laser guided bomb        as has been shown during operations in       the former Yugoslavia.</P>

This versatile all weather, day or night aircraft can also carry out a variety of other tasks which include close air support of ground forces, anti-ship attack with the    Sea Eagle missile and reconnaissance.
The parent or Typed Air Station is the Royal Naval Air Station Yeovilton where there are   a total of three Squadrons, two front line and one training. The training squadron's task is to train new pilots and convert and refresh others to full operational status. The other two squadrons are the front line aircraft which form part of the Carrier Air Groups which embark in the 'INVINCIBLE' class aircraft carriers.</P>

These most capable aircraft form an important part of our potent and very flexible organic air power essential in the rapidly changing world in which we live.

<A NAME="m"> <H4>MERLIN</H4></A>

This new anglo-Italian helicopter is scheduled to enter service in the late 1990's. With a fully-autonomous, all weather day and night operational capability it will feature advanced avionics and improved performance over the Sea King which it is designed to succeed. Length 22.9 metres, rotor diameter 18.6 metres, speed approximately 150 knots, powered by 3 Rolls Royce RTM 22 engines.





<A NAME="sk"> <H4>THE SEA KING</H4></A>

The workhorse of the Fleet Air Arm for the 
past two and a half decades, the Sea King has proved to be a most reliable and able asset capable of conducting many and various tasks in a variety of roles. Primarily procured as an Anti-Submarine Warfare platform, this rugged airframe has been developed into both Airborne Early Warning and Commando variants. </P>

<img align=right hspace=6 src="../graphics/seaking.gif"> The current Anti-Submarine airframe is known as the Mk 6 and is completely autonomous with a modern weapons, sonics and avionics suite. These include an advanced integrated passive sonar system using aircraft-dropped sonar buoys, an active dipping sonar, a radar system, a tactical navigation system and electronic support measures equipment which detects radar transmissions from other units. It carries the Sting Ray lightweight torpedo and depth charges to 'prosecute' its targets. </P>

The Royal Naval Air Station Culdrose is the parent air station to both training and front line Sea King squadrons which form part of the Carrier Air Groups assigned to aircraft carriers, and also to some frigates and Royal Fleet Auxiliary ships. The station also hosts the renowned Search and Rescue squadron responsible for saving countless lives, frequently in appalling weather conditions. </P>

The Airborne Early Warning Sea King was rapidly brought into service post the Falklands conflict when it became clear that organic Airborne Early Warning was an essential part of air power at sea. Once again the venerable airframe fitted the bill and, using the Searchwater radar, quickly entered service. The platform offers tactical control to the   Sea Harrier, and other shore and carrier  based aircraft, and assists with anti-air and anti-surface operations. This aircraft also forms the third element of a Carrier Air Group.
The primary role of the Commando Mk4 variant of the Sea King, is to satisfy the medium lift requirements of the Royal Marines in the crucial role of Amphibious Warfare. This includes the carriage of troops, underslung loads and the 105mm Light Gun from ship to shore. It is fitted with a variety of self defensive equipment which include: decoy dispensers to avoid missiles locking-on to the aircraft, missile approach warners and missile jamming systems.    The aircraft has a full Night Vision Goggle capability enabling operations to be conducted with minimal chance of detection, at very low level in almost any weather conditions. Annual winter training with the Royal Marines in Norway proved to be invaluable when the Gulf crisis emerged as, surprisingly, flying techniques in snow are very similar to those required in the sands  of a desert. It is also interesting to know that the night temperature in the desert often drops far below zero. </P>


This aircraft has served in the former Yugoslavia, supporting initially the United Nations and then the NATO Implementation Force and its squadron has been the longest serving unit in theatre.</P>

The parent air station of the Commando  Sea King is the Royal Naval Air Station Yeovilton where there are a total of three squadrons. These ever flexible aircraft can deploy and operate at sea or over land in conditions from the Arctic wastes to the deserts of the Gulf.


<A NAME="lynx"> <H4>THE LYNX </H4></A>

Primarily an anti-surface and anti-submarine helicopter designed to operate from frigates and destroyers of the Fleet, this fast and capable aircraft is currently being updated to the Mk8 standard. The aircraft is being fitted with a very advanced Central Tactical System and Passive Identification Device in addition   to the equipment currently fitted. Each independent flight comprises a pilot,
an observer and a team of 7 maintainers.        They embark in their ship whenever it sails. Able to fire the Sea Skua anti-surface missile, which was so successful during the Gulf war, the Lynx forms an integral part of the ships detection and weapon system and can project the influence of a ship over great distances with the key element of surprise. In addition   to the Sea Skua the Lynx has the Sting Ray torpedo and the older technology but nevertheless most effective depth charge for anti-submarine warfare. The aircraft may also  be fitted with a machine gun pod. The home base for all seaborne Lynx is the Royal Naval Air Station Portland but will in the future be Yeovilton. </P>

A second variant of the Lynx is in service     with the Royal Navy. The attack/utility version   is operated in support of the Royal Marines     in conjunction with the Commando Sea King.   It fires the TOW anti-armour missile and gives    an autonomous and flexible response against tanks and armoured personnel carriers to the Land Force Commander during Amphibious Operations. 


<A NAME="gazelle"> <H4>THE GAZELLE</H4></A>

Mostly used for helicopter pilot initial training, the Gazelle really is the 'sports car' of our aircraft. A superb aircraft to introduce young pilots into the rotary-wing world of Naval Aviation, its flying qualities and splendid forgiving nature make it a much loved vehicle, fondly remembered by all who have flown it.  The Gazelle Basic Helicopter Flying Training Squadron is parented at the Air Station at Culdrose, which is the largest helicopter base  in Europe. </P>


The Navy also uses the Gazelle in the reconnaissance and communications role which it combines with the Lynx attack aircraft to form the composite squadron in support of the Royal Marines based at the Yeovilton Naval Air Station.


<A NAME="jet"> <H4>THE JETSTREAM</H4></A>

The Jetstream is used to train the all important Observers of the Fleet Air Arm who eventually become the tacticians of our Sea King anti-submarine and Lynx anti-surface helicopters.  To facilitate this training, the Jetstream is fitted with a nose mounted radar and two navigation consoles for the student and instructor. A fixed wing aircraft powered by twin gas turbine engines and with spare passenger capacity,
it is from time to time used in the communications role.

<H4>THE FLEET REQUIREMENTS
AND AIR DIRECTION UNIT</H4>

The elements of this unit are operated under direct contract to the Royal Navy by the civilian firms Hunting Aviation Limited operating Hawks from Culdrose and Flight Refuelling Services flying Falcons from Bournemouth Airport.</P>


The unit provides a vital service to ships of   the Royal Navy assisting them to work up to operational readiness, both individually and collectively. They fly sorties for radar and radio assessments, electronic warfare exercises, provide a variety of towed targets for live gun and missile firing and fly as simulated hostile aircraft to test ships' air defence systems. 





</P>
<P>
<center>
<HR WIDTH="50%">



<A TARGET="_parent" HREF="../index.htm">Home Page</A>





</BODY>
