<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Todays Royal Navy: Structure: Fleet Air Arm </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">


<A TARGET="contents" HREF="struct.htm"> <H2>Royal Navy Structure</H2></A>

<A TARGET="contents" HREF="faa.htm"> <H3>Fleet Air Arm</H3></A>


<B>Our ships</B><BR>

At sea all our major warships embark their   own organic aircraft to support and project  their fighting ability. </P>


<img align=right src="../graphics/invinc.gif"></p> The most capable units we have at sea are      the 3 'INVINCIBLE' class aircraft carriers. The advantages of Carrier Air Power, fulfilling both defensive and power projection roles, are a key element of maritime forces. Aircraft can be launched from international waters and are free to operate outside the airspace of sovereign nations. The carrier is a floating airfield able      to be held at a continual high state of readiness   for action. It is equipped with autonomous self defence, sophisticated command, control and intelligence systems and supporting infrastructure. The ability to maintain and service aircraft that are increasingly dependent on sophisticated sensor and weapon systems in a purpose-built environment, as well as the facility to provide the range and sheer quantity of ordnance necessary for effective operations,     are hallmarks of the carrier. In support of    forces ashore in the former Yugoslavia, carrier operations in the Adriatic sea have demonstrated the unique ability to escape adverse weather and fog which periodically close shorebased airfields. </P>

Carrier led forces are political and diplomatic tools that provide the Government with options covering contingency operations, through gentle international pressure, to full military action.  They can sail in a blaze of publicity as a highly visible statement of political intent. The ability    to operate autonomously in international waters, free from any need for local host nation support while maintaining a high degree of readiness, provides great flexibility for the protection of    the UK's worldwide trading interests and our Dependent Territories.
The aircraft embarked to achieve all of these aims are known as the Carrier Air Group which has a flexible composition. Normally there will be a squadron of Sea Harrier fighter aircraft,   a squadron of Sea King anti-submarine helicopters and flight of Sea King Airborne Early Warning helicopters. However, depending upon the task given to the carrier, it may very easily embark a Commando squadron and operate in an amphibious role.</P>

HMS OCEAN our newest arrival, is a Landing Platform Helicopter not to be confused with a conventional aircraft carrier. Currently fitting out, the Fleet's capability to provide a multi-spot helicopter deck for amphibious operations, absent for some time, will be restored. This exciting new platform will be the heart of one of the Royal Navy's core functions, Amphibious Warfare, and enable a tactically significant, large scale helicopter assault to be generated during an amphibious landing.</P>

Primarily designed to transport up to 12 Commando Sea King and 6 attack helicopters, her size will enable 6 support and 6 attack aircraft to be on deck at any one time with a further 12 in the hangar. Also fitted with landing craft she will be able to contribute to the surface assault.</P>

Ample accommodation will enable an embarked force of 500 men and an air group of 180 personnel to be carried.</P>

Finally, by far the most numerous flight     decks we have at sea are on the frigates and destroyers of the Fleet. Currently all ships at sea are allocated a Lynx or Sea King flight, which form an integral part of the ship's fighting ability and enables projection in detection and engagement as well as the, much needed, communications role.</P>

Escort ships which have embarked flights include the Air Defence Type 42 destroyers and the General Purpose Type 22 and 23 frigates. In the future, many of these ships will carry the updated Mk8 Lynx or the Merlin, which is the Sea King and Lynx replacement.









</P>
<P>
<center>
