<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Worldwide: TRAINING ESTABLISHMENTS </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">



<A HREF="britain.htm" TARGET="contents"> <H4>United Kingdom</A> &#160;&#128;&#160; <A HREF="../today/bases.htm" TARGET="contents"> Naval Bases</H4></A>

<H4>ROYAL NAVY TRAINING ESTABLISHMENTS</H4>

<B>HMS SULTAN</B><BR>

From its beginnings in the 1950s as the Mechanical Training and Repair Establishment, HMS SULTAN has developed as a centre of excellence in Engineering training for the Royal Navy.  Using the most modern facilities and procedures, it prepares men and women to operate and maintain the extensive and highly sophisticated range of equipment and machinery found in RN ships, submarines, aircraft and ashore.  The establishment also places considerable emphasis on resource and initiative training as a means of developing the leadership and management skills necessary to react quickly and correctly to emergencies and adapt to unforeseen circumstances.</P>

The establishment, which occupies about 179 acres of land within a 3.5 mile perimeter in Gosport, is the largest of the RN training establishments, with around 4,000 Service and civilian personnel.  It comprises two sites divided by Military Road.  In any given week there are over 1,400 students undergoing instruction on a significant proportion of the 260 courses on offer.  Courses vary in length from less than one day to over three years and many attract civilian accreditation such as City and Guilds or Higher National Diploma level.</P>

The Officers' Training Department was formed in the summer of 1995 following the closure of the RN Engineering College, Manadon.</P>

<B>HMS DRYAD</B><BR>

The School of Maritime Operations was formed in 1974 and is now one of the principal shore establishments of the Royal Navy providing warfare training for naval officers and ratings from an elementary stage to the most advanced levels.  The school is divided into 4 departments Above Water Warfare, Under Water Warfare, Navigation and Training Support housed at DRYAD.  Also located at HMS DRYAD is the Maritime Warfare Centre (North).</P>

Southwick House, now the Wardroom in HMS DRYAD, was once the ancestral home of the Thistlethwayte family.  Requisitioned by the Navy in 1941, the House became the forward planning and operational Headquarters of the Supreme Commander of the Allied Expeditionary Force, General Dwight Eisenhower and the Naval Commander for Operation Overlord, Admiral Sir Bertram Ramsey.  The D-Day Normandy landings were planned from the House and original Wall Map used remains in situ in the Wardroom.</p>

<B>HMS COLLINGWOOD</B><BR>

HMS COLLINGWOOD's primary role is to train officers and ratings of the Weapon Engineering and Warfare Branches to the high standards required by the Fleet.  The establishment runs approximately 1000 courses each year ranging from one day familiarization's to 4 year apprenticeships.  On a typical day, some 2,500 people, including 1,400 trainees, work on the 200 acre site situated to the south of Fareham.</P>

The Weapon Engineering branches raison d'&ecirc;tre is the "maintenance of combat system availability".  This involves preventative maintenance, system health monitoring and providing advice on system capabilities as a member of the Command Team.  The Warfare Branch was formed in 1993 merging the functions of the Operations Branch and WE Mechanics Branch reflecting advances in technology which called for junior rates who could both operate and maintain their equipment.</P>

Training execution within COLLINGWOOD is tasked to 3 faculties, each responsible for different stages in the training of Mechanics, Artificers and Officers.  These are; Communications (transferred on the closure of HMS MERCURY in 1993); Engineering Principles and Training Support; and Weapon Engineering.  All Weapon Engineering officers complete the final part of their career training at HMS COLLINGWOOD along with Executive Officers of the Communications sub-specialization.</P>

<B>HMS TEMERAIRE</B><BR>

On 11 June 1971 the Royal Naval School of Physical Training was commissioned as HMS TEMERAIRE.  The PT Branch, which had previously been a sub-specialization of the Seaman Branch, became a branch of its own.  In 1984 TEMERAIRE also became home to RN Sport and Adventure Training.  The establishment is now housed in a purpose built complex in Burnaby Road Portsmouth, with excellent facilities including an outdoor all weather athletics track and hockey pitches as well as the well-known United Services rugby and cricket ground and indoor tennis centre (a facility shared with Portsmouth City Council).</P>

<B>HMS EXCELLENT</B><BR>

HMS EXCELLENT, former Naval Gunnery School (founded in 1832), has enjoyed a revival since recommissioning in 1994 as a centre for naval training.  It houses the Nuclear, Biological and Chemical Defence School, the RN School of Leadership and Management and the Headquarters of the Commandant General Royal Marines.  There are also a number of lodger units including the Portsmouth Field Gun Crew; the RNR unit HMS KING ALFRED; the Regulating School (Naval Police); the harbour training vessel HMS BRISTOL; the Naval Military Training School; and the Portsmouth Command Sailing Centre.</P>

The establishment is housed on Whale Island, an 84 acre site made by convict labour between 1856 and 1902.  It has the unique distinction of being the first shore establishment where the sailors slept in bunks rather than hammocks.</P>

<B>HMS CAMBRIDGE </B><BR>

HMS CAMBRIDGE is the Royal Navy's Gunnery and Naval Military Training School at Wembury Point overlooking the approaches to Plymouth Sound.  Gunnery training covers both medium range (4.5" calibre) and close range (20mm and 30mm calibre) guns.  The Naval Military Training School teaches small arms and basic military skills, and board and search techniques.</P>

The School's aim is to teach the techniques and procedures of conducting gunnery safely.  At sea, ships' crews are trained to be fast and accurate enough to be operationally effective.  Men and women are trained in all aspects of gunnery, from loading and aiming, through gun direction and fire control, to the safe conduct of multi-weapon system engagements and tactical firings.  Live gunnery training ashore is the safest and most economical way to teach the basic principles of what is a highly stressful activity.</P>

<B>BRITANNIA ROYAL NAVAL COLLEGE</B><BR>

The very word DARTMOUTH is synonymous with the training of officers for the Royal Navy.  The college is renowned throughout the world as a centre of excellence with a reputation second to none.  It is here that virtually all officers start their careers.  While the style of training has changed markedly during its 90 years, as Dartmouth has evolved to meet the Navy's needs, it retains a unique atmosphere and a special place in the heart of each officer who passes out.  Dartmouth is more that a Training Establishment, it is a vibrant community, a Naval College and part of our heritage.</P>

The primary purpose of BRNC is to train and educate active service and reserve officers within agreed resources, to the standards set by Flag Officer Training and Recruiting, and prepare them for their next stage of training so that they are fit for a career in the Royal Navy.</P>

<B>HMS RALEIGH</B><BR>

HMS RALEIGH is situated a mile west of Torpoint on raised ground in Cornwall overlooking St John's lake, an inlet of the Tamar River which opens out into Plymouth Sound.  It is situated in an area of outstanding natural beauty.  The close proximity of the rugged Cornish coast, sheltered inlets and the open spaces of Dartmoor provide the ideal training environment afloat and for adventurous training of all kinds.</P>

HMS RALEIGH is the new entry training establishment for all men and women joining the Royal Navy, the Queen Alexandra's Royal Naval Nursing Service (QARNNS) and the Royal Naval Reserve (RNR).  This initial 7 week course (2 weeks for RNR) is designed to cover those things which recruits must know in order to enjoy the naval environment and provide the foundation for their subsequent professional training.  The course therefore ranges from the domestic detail of how to wear uniform and the traditions of the Service to firefighting and becoming physically fit.  HMS RALEIGH is also  the home for the Royal Navy Supply and Cookery School, Royal Navy School of Seamanship and the Plymouth Area NBCD School, providing Firefighting, Nuclear, Biological and Chemical Defence, Shooting and First Aid facilities for ships and establishments.  It also provides extensive training for Cadets of the SCC and CCF.




<CENTER>
</P>
<P>

