<html>
<head><title>Royal Navy: Worldwide: UK Portsmouth </title>

</head>

<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF"  
text="#000000">



<A HREF="britain.htm" TARGET="contents"> <H4>United Kingdom</A> &#160;&#128;&#160; <A HREF="../today/bases.htm" TARGET="contents"> Naval Bases</H4></A>

<A HREF="ports.htm" TARGET="contents"> <H4>HM Naval Base Portsmouth </H4></A>

<H4>History</H4>




Portsmouth  has been a centre for Naval ship building and repair since 1194, when King Richard I ordered the building of the first dock here. From that date facilities grew and evolved with the growing importance of the Royal Navy and with the changing technology of warships; the process of change continues as rapidly as ever, but the tradition of providing seagoing warships with the best possible support is maintained.</P>


Some of the milestones in the history of the base are:</P>
<table>
<tr valign=top><td>
1212</td><TD> King John ordered the building of a wall around the dockyard.</td></tr>
<tr valign=top><td> 1495</TD><TD> World's first dry dock built.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1509 </TD><TD> Mary Rose keel laid down.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1655 </TD><TD> Mast Pond excavated (present boat pool)</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1698 </TD><TD> NO 1 Basin and No 5 dock excavated, Basin later enlarged to its present size in 1795-1801.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1711 </TD><TD> Dockyard wall and Victory Gate constructed.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1733 </TD><TD> Old Naval academy completed.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1760s </TD><TD> 3 storehouses along Main Road (at present housing the royal Naval Museum) built.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1776 </TD><TD> Dockyard worker hanged for arson in the yard, (an attempt to aid the cause of American independence).</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1789 </TD><TD> No 1 Dock built.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1808 </TD><TD> Block Mills opened; the world's first factory designed with steam powered machine tools. Block making  machinery by Brunel.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1824 </TD><TD> Semaphore tower built; rebuilt after fire in 1930.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1829 </TD><TD> HMS FOX built, yard's first steam powered screw warship.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1845 </TD><TD> No 6 Boathouse built.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1846 </TD><TD> First lecturer in Electrics appointed.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1850 </TD><TD> dockyard was world's largest industrial site (99 acres).</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1860's </TD><TD> Lord Palmerston ordered construction of ring defensive forts around Portsmouth.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1882 </TD><TD> N0 5 Boathouse built. HMS COLOSSUS launched, first steel warship.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1893 </TD><TD> Royal Railway Shelter built, South Railway Jetty.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1906 </TD><TD> HMS DREADNOUGHT built in a year and a day.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1913 </TD><TD> Super-Dreadnought HMS QUEEN ELIZABETH built, first oil fired battleship.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1915 </TD><TD> Women recruited to work in the yard to fill vacancies left by volunteering for the Services.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1916 </TD><TD> First air raid, by a  Zeppelin, on the yard.
<tr valign=top><td> 1922 </TD><TD> HMS VICTORY docked in No2 Dock.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1967 </TD><TD> NMS ANDROMEDA built, last  warship in a line of 286 completed in the Dockyard.</TD></TR>
<tr valign=top><td> 1984 </TD><TD> dockyard became Naval base and Fleet Maintenance and repair Organisation set up.</TD></TR></TABLE>


	Today, as a Naval Base on a site of nearly 300 acres, which includes 3 miles of wharfage, 15 working Dry Docks, and 62 acres of fitting out basins, Portsmouth offers ships full facilities for maintenance and repair, training, rest and recreation and for preparing in every way to put to sea as effective fighting units.     
 
 

<center>
</P>
<P>

<HR WIDTH="50%">



<A TARGET="_parent" HREF="../index.htm">Home Page</A>





</BODY>
</HTML>







