<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1296.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1296.Supplement2.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H4Editor.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH=
"363" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1296.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" 
HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Are You a Bully? </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>If You Are, You're Probably<BR>
Dragging Down Productivity inYour Workplace</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</I></B> </CENTER>
<P><HR>Marti Smye makes a living telling companies how they can im-prove
their workplaces and their performance. From a mile away, she can spot a
bully in the corner office. And she says bullies are nothing but trouble.
<UL>
  <LI>He displays uncontrolled anger, sometimes shouting obscenities.
  <LI>She humiliates others privately or in public.
  <LI>He persistently criticizes and uses sarcasm.
  <LI>She deliberately ignores or isolates people and excludes them from
taking an active part in discussions.
  <LI>He sets impossible deadlines and changes instructions without consultation,
for no other apparent reason than to make failure inevitable.
  <LI>She has difficulty delegating because of a belief that no one else
can do the job to the required standard.
  <LI>He takes credit for other people's ideas and success but never shoulders
the blame when things go wrong.
  <LI>She refuses reasonable requests.
  <LI>He continually undermines others' authority.
  <LI>She blocks a promotion.
</UL>
<BR>
Hopefully, this doesn't describe you. In some cases, it might.<BR>
<BR>
Smye, who with Lesley Wright has coauthored the book &quot;Corporate Abuse:
How 'Lean and Mean' Robs People and Profits,&quot; says the acts listed
above are those of many of our corporate heroes, the eminently successful
business leaders of our era. But Smye and Wright also say the era in which
these corporate heroes have thrived is quickly ending. And those who don't
change their thinking will see their companies and their own star fall.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It takes a courageous person,&quot; says Smye, an expert on creating
21st century organizations and president of PeopleTech Inc., a division
of Right Management Consultants Inc. She specializes in planning, implementing
and accelerating large-scale organizational change. <BR>
<BR>
Her coauthor, Wright, is a marketing and advertising creative consultant
and an independent adviser promoting idea-generating cultures. <BR>
<BR>
The two authors say there are three kinds of employee abuse common in the
modern workplace: <BR>
u Systemic: stemming from a company's procedures and policies. For example,
everything is forbidden, unless expressly permitted.<BR>
 <BR>
u Structural: linked to the pressure of layoffs and technological changes.
You can call this paranoia of being downsized.<BR>
<BR>
u Deliberate: These are premeditated behaviors on the part of management
geared to motivate by fear and produce short-term results. This is the bully
syndrome.<BR>
<BR>
Smye and Wright feel the effects of corporate abuse can be accurately measured,
especially in today's information-based economy in which individual innovation
and creativity is at a premium. Abuse produces dispirited, exhausted, demoralized
and often angry employees who do not make a productive work force.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If we believe we are great, we will do things that support that belief,&quot;
Wright and Smye write in Corporate Abuse. &quot;If we believe we are less
than great, we will do things that are consistent with that belief.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The fear and mistrust workers feel leads to stress that has been estimated
to cost corporations more than $ 150 million a year, according to the authors.<BR>
<BR>
So how do you change your company? <BR>
<BR>
Start by changing your management style. Don't be a bully.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's very tough to realize that you are half the problem,&quot; Smye
says. <BR>
<BR>
Nevertheless, take that first step: Stop for a moment and look in the mirror
with your employees' eyes.  <BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1296.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> 
