<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0"
ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H5Guest.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40" 
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1296.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Lawsuit Alternatives</FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Mediation and Arbitration are <BR>
Less Expensive Ways to Resolve Employment Disputes </FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Louis B. Kushner</I></B><HR></CENTER>
<P>In today's workplace, employers and employees know that it's only a matter
of time before a disagreement between them arises. Though some might consider
this a pessimistic view, it is smart to have realistic expectations of how
likely it is that an employment dispute will occur at some point in your
career. <BR>
<BR>
If and when a dispute arises, many employers and employees believe that
their only option is to take the case to court. However, the time and expense
of formal litigation may not always be necessary. More and more companies
are settling their disagreements not in lengthy court battles, but through
an Alternative Dispute Resolution approach. These &quot;alternatives&quot;
- arbitration and mediation - are gaining more respect in the workplace
and more power in the courts. In many cases, parties who settle through
ADR can get the same results they would by going to court - at a fraction
of the time and expense.<BR>
<BR>
Arbitration is one of the most effective ways of settling employment issues
out of court. In arbitration, both parties (the employer and the employee)
submit their version of the facts to a neutral arbitrator. This arbitrator
is a professional who generally has extensive experience in employment issues
and a detailed knowledge of the laws that apply. The arbitrator considers
the facts and evidence presented - like a jury would - considers the application
of the law to the facts and offers his or her decision. The decision of
the arbitrator is binding, and is almost never appealed.<BR>
<BR>
There are several advantages to pursuing legal issues in this manner. First,
arbitration is much less expensive than court. Formal litigation of a case
may cost $50,000 to $100,000, but parties settling though arbitration can
do so for much less expense. In fact, some parties attempting to resolve
the dispute through litigation never make it to court, because the pretrial
procedures are so costly that they no longer have the financial resources
to see the case through. <BR>
<BR>
The second major advantage to arbitration is the timeliness of the process.
Litigation is incredibly time-consuming: It is common for a case to take
three years or more before it is resolved. In arbitration, however, the
parties cover the issues at a much faster rate, often reaching a final agreement
within a year. Arbitration is also favored by people who value their privacy.
Arbitration helps to reduce media publicity and to keep the case out of
the public forum. It also provides a more confidential arena for dealing
with sensitive issues.<BR>
<BR>
Another form of ADR is mediation. In mediation, parties discuss their side
of the case with a neutral mediator. This mediator is a trained professional
who tries to facilitate a negotiated agreement with which both sides can
be content. It is not as formal as arbitration, and tries to take the personal
dynamic of the relationship between the parties into consideration. All
parties work together with the mediator to try to work out a resolution.
<BR>
<BR>
Mediation is appealing for many reasons. First, it is the least expensive
method of having a case professionally settled. Also, the process is less
adversarial than either litigation or arbitration, and the approach allows
more freedom, creativity and flexibility. Many issues can be resolved, even
if they are not directly related. Some also value the fact that mediation
is non-binding, unless both parties come to a mutual agreement resolution.<BR>
<BR>
However, there are some disadvantages to mediation as well. Sometimes, the
parties are not able to reach an agreement, and the case winds up in litigation
anyway. Mediation is not useful if the employee wants a more public case
and lastly, a satisfactory result is directly related to the skill of the
mediator. <BR>
<BR>
When trying to decide between arbitration and mediation, a prospective client
should consider the following comparisons: Arbitration is binding; mediation
is not. Arbitration has more structure; mediation has more flexibility and
creativity. Arbitration creates an atmosphere of litigation and lets each
party have its day in court, but is more adversarial. Mediation focuses
on a more voluntary resolution. <BR>
<BR>
Clearly, mediation and arbitration have both pros and cons and the specific
needs of the parties involved must be considered.<BR>
<BR>
Alternative Dispute Resolution may not always be the best choice for everyone,
but it is important to realize that litigation is no longer the only option
for dealing with employment disputes. Choosing ADR will yield faster, less
expensive results that are equally valid and binding. <BR>
<BR>
Louis B. Kushner is a partner with the Pittsburgh law firm of Rothman Gordon
Foreman &amp; Groudine, P.C. <BR>
