"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" 
HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT SIZE></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>
<H4>The Virtual duffer</H4>
Hey desperate duffers - despair the winter months no longer. McGolf's Indoor
Links, the Pittsburgh area's first virtual reality golf course, wants to
bring relief to the snowbound golfer, and year-round frustration for golf
widows all over western Pennsylvania.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;It's really something,&quot; says first-time McGolf patron Lee Bent,
veteran of links across the country and holder of a 22 handicap. &quot;I
spent all afternoon playing. I hit one in the water and you could hear it
go, 'plunk!' It's so real.&quot; Bent also appreciated the electronic caddy's
frequent compliments  on good shots.<BR>
<BR>
It's not quite like the great outdoors: McGolf's players stand before a
10 foot by 14 foot screen and swing away (with their own clubs and balls)
on one of 37 different computer-generated courses. Players have all the
real-life hazards to contend with - sand, water, deep rough and all. It's
so real, in fact, that players hitting a virtual tree have been tempted
to duck. Unlike some virtual golf set-ups, the video ball comes rebounding
back.<BR>
<BR>
McGolf's four different levels range from &quot;moderate&quot; to &quot;legend&quot;
in difficulty. Some courses are &quot;very similar&quot; to real courses
- one of which may or may not bear a striking resemblance to Muirfield in
Ohio - but the names have been changed for copyright reasons. Ellen Belisle,
co-owner and -operator, says versions of Pebble Beach and other famous courses
may be available soon.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The simulators have been around for some time, but they were only
marketed in Europe and Japan, and to a few pro shops at private clubs. They
were extremely successful overseas. It wasn't until two or three years ago
people began opening centers here,&quot; she says. Now, simulators are springing
up everywhere, from stand alone shops like McGolf to sports bars across
the country. Altoona hosts the next closest regional simulator.<BR>
<BR>
McGolf has four systems, each  capable of handling up to a foursome at a
time. In one hour, one person can play 18 holes, or two people can play
nine; a foursome could play a round in about four hours. &quot;Green fees&quot;
are $25 per hour per group. Groups can play stroke, match or even skins
games.<BR>
<BR>
The system can double as a golf instructor, too, enabling golfers to actually
improve their games through the winter doldrums.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It tracks your swing,&quot; says Belisle, &quot;and it'll give you
stats on the path of the stroke, your wrist rotation, if you hit the sweet
spot on the clubhead or not, the speed and length of your shot ... the camera
digitizes everything. We can play your swing back for you in slow motion
or even frame by frame.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The simulator runs on a Macintosh computer and even features the ability
to program in custom courses. Belisle is thinking about adding a par-3 executive
course and forming a lunch league for business folks in the airport corridor.
<BR>
<BR>
The system can also stick a small window for television broadcasts in a
corner, so players can golf and catch the Steelers game at the same time.
<BR>
<BR>
Larry Hawk, a PGA authorized repair person, is on hand to make licensed
club clones and do club repair. And Belisle says a couple of pros are interested
in giving lessons. <BR>
<BR>
McGolf has a couple of custom-made tournament pool tables in addition to
the golf simulators. The establishment serves snacks, and the alcohol policy
is BYOB for now. McGolf is open 10 a.m. to 10 p.m., seven days a week, but
call ahead.<BR>
 <BR>
You may have to book tee times on busy weekends. 	<BR>
