<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Ann Devlin</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1296.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1296.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0"
ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="1296.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" 
HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Loving Lucy</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>She Used the Past as a Solid Base From Which<BR>
To Challenge the Future. We Must, too.<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>Ann Devlin - Columnist</I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>During my first months in Pittsburgh, my husband Bill took me to
meet a woman who had helped make him feel at home here. <BR>
<BR>
Lucy was the step-mother of a family friend. We met for dinner the first
time and before dessert, I knew Bill was right. Lucy was bright and funny
and wonderfully curious about just about everything. She became my friend.
And as friends often do, we celebrated the things we had in common. We were
both transplants to this region. We both found love here. And we both fell
in love here a second time. <BR>
<BR>
With Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
Her romance had a bit of a head-start on mine. And as a result, I had a
lot to learn from her. I learned lessons about the life of this city. I
learned lessons about life. <BR>
 <BR>
You, too, may have known Lucy. Her full name was Lucille Anderson Smallwood
McClements. And while you've heard now of some of the similarities in our
stories, there were divergences. She came to Pittsburgh to attend what was
then the Carnegie Institute of Technology. Lucy was born and raised in Falconer,
N.Y. Her first husband worked in the steel industry. His professional life,
and therefore their family life, was in Pittsburgh in the dark &quot;Hell
with the lid off&quot; days. That's when the street lamps came on at noon,
just about the time her husband would change into his extra white shirt,
which she dutifully tucked into his briefcase each day to help him shed
the morning's soot. <BR>
While the men made the metal for the rest of the world and made fortunes
in this city, the process tested the mettle of anyone with an appreciation
of the aesthetic. Lucy had that indeed, and even decades later, as she told
Bill and myself vivid stories about those dark days, she recounted them
with an ever so gentle shudder. Lucy was a first-hand witness to the fact
that the great wealth all that grit brought to Pittsburgh also enabled a
commensurate style. While her three daughters were still growing up, Lucy
was widowed. Time passed. Then she and a family friend, who had also lost
his spouse, brought their two families together. He was James B. McClements
Jr., a well-known restaurateur in East Liberty, then the place where the
chic and elite shopped and dined. The restaurant was the Joyce McClements,
and was the setting for its share of social events. After a fire, it moved
to the Kenmawr in Shadyside. Lucy would tell stories about debutante teas,
white-gloved ladies luncheons, and special events carefully executed. Decades
later, she still had the individually designed ice cream molds that shaped
the hand-crafted desserts, some even bearing prominent family monograms.
<BR>
<BR>
They were small pieces of her personal history ... and the history of this
city. A reminder that almost as fast as money was made here, so was history.<BR>
<BR>
Lucy knew how to tell that history. She was a woman who literally matched
the times of this century. As the '90s advanced, Lucy advanced to her nineties.<BR>
<BR>
Yet, sharing her detailed memories allowed listeners to be transported to
times gone-by in Pittsburgh. But history did not have hold of Lucy. Lucy
put history in its place. It was an important place, infinitely expandable.
But she warily maintained its perimeter and guarded it with a gate. Almost
as fast as she allowed a recollection to emerge, she would say, &quot;Now!&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It was the impatient punctuation point she used in conversation to jog both
herself and her listeners back to the present and forward to the future.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Now! About the Mayor...&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Now!  What do you think would be the best plan to develop the riverfronts?&quot;
<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Now!  How about those robots they are developing at CMU?&quot; <BR>
 <BR>
The slight, gently aged woman, would strain against almost translucent skin
to lean forward, her cigarette in one hand, her evening cocktail in the
other, to press for the latest news and opinions. She listened hungrily.
She devoured new information; it was never enough. She wanted to anticipate
what might come next in the politics and the economy of this city. Logic
would actually have it that way. You just don't thrive in your nineties
without having a pretty firm commitment to the future. The past comforted
Lucy. The present made her restless. The future kept her reaching and growing
and learning and questioning. <BR>
<BR>
She cherished Pittsburgh - but believed that what it once was, what it is
now, should never stop it from transforming itself to what it should be.
Better.<BR>
 <BR>
Now, she has left it up to us to ask the questions. On one starry night
of this Autumn, Lucy went to sleep and, in peace, left us. <BR>
I loved Lucy.<BR>
