<HEAD>
    <TITLE>EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1296.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1296.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT=
"Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H14EyeonH.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1296.Diner.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>The Challenger</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT size=+1>A Rival for Ridge, But Who Will It Be?<BR>
</FONT><BR>
<I>By Jim Strader </I><HR></CENTER>
<P>As Tom Ridge nears the half-way point of his first term in office, there
is little doubt that he wants another four years. Politically young at age
51, and with his share of successes in the past two years to build on, he
clearly has further public ambition.<BR>
<BR>
While it's not likely that Ridge will face opposition from within the Republican
Party, the Democrats are sure to field a challenger: The current hot political
question in Harrisburg and around the state is, 'Who?' <BR>
<BR>
Ridge's incumbency, party support and the millions of dollars his campaign
already has on hand are not the only reasons Pennsylvania Republicans are
not eager to run against him. Two years from now the ballot also will feature
Republican Arlen Specter's U.S. Senate seat, which he has held the last
16 years and appears interested in keeping. Taking on Specter seems more
attractive to some of the state's up-and-coming Republicans than taking
on Ridge. <BR>
<BR>
Already, state Sen. Melissa Hart and outgoing Attorney General Tom Corbett,
both of Allegheny County, have given indications that they will run against
Specter for the GOP nomination. That would take them out of contention for
the governor's office and further solidify Ridge's position.<BR>
Democrats have been unwilling to jump into the race for governor thus far.
<BR>
<BR>
Instead, they spent the year working toward what they said was a more important
objective than the governor's office - keeping Bill Clinton in the White
House. Party leaders steered clear of talking publicly about future campaigns,
and some even privately preferred to keep the focus presidential. <BR>
In addition, GOP presidential nominee Bob Dole's interest in Ridge as a
possible running mate over the summer boosted the governor's popularity,
and a speaking role at the Republican National Convention gave him national
publicity.<BR>
<BR>
Among Democrats who have started talking about 1998, many have been touting
Philadelphia Mayor Edward G. Rendell as the man to beat Ridge. (Many also
believe Rendell could beat Specter - giving the mayor a hypothetical choice.)
One important Democrat who is not talking that way is Rendell, who says
he will finish his term in office, taking him out of the political playing
field until 2000. Some, however, don't believe Rendell will pass up the
chance at one of the open spots. Half of the state's population lives close
enough to Philadelphia to know his name, and his money-raising ability is
on a par with Ridge. <BR>
<BR>
Also mentioned, almost reluctantly by some, is Mark Singel. A former state
senator from Johnstown and two-term lieutenant governor under Gov. Robert
P. Casey, Singel has kept his hand in politics as the state Democratic chairman.
A Singel-Ridge race would be a rematch of 1994, which was Singel's second
loss in as many campaigns. In the view of some political types who are well
aware of Ridge's millions, these poor showings in his last two electoral
outings could hurt his ability to raise campaign money.<BR>
<BR>
Another Democrat whose name has been mentioned by more than a few people
is Treasurer Catherine Baker Knoll, leaving office after two terms. A loyal
Democrat with tremendous party support, she would share with Singel the
problem of running in 1998 without a public platform once she is out of
office.<BR>
<BR>
None of the Democratic legislators would seem to have a shot at a run for
governor. State representatives have such small constituencies that building
name recognition would be tough. The ranking Senate Democrat, Robert Mellow
of Lackawanna County, backed away from a run for auditor general this year.<BR>
<BR>
And Philadelphia's influential Vincent Fumo seems content in the Senate
as well, having said he won't run for governor.<BR>
<BR>
Whatever Democrat considers running for governor has a quandary. The party
can't ignore Ridge's history of appealing to enough voters to represent
a largely Democratic congressional district for a dozen years and winning
the governor's race against Singel, who ran as a de facto incumbent.<BR>
And in a state where Democrats hold a fairly large edge in registered voters
- still nearly 400,000 - Ridge has made a career in public life of defying
political conventional wisdom. <BR>
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1296.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> </CENTER>
