<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Fly Fish</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>The Upscale Steelhead Grill Relies on <BR>
Both Entrees and Clientele Flown in Fresh Daily</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Lydia Strohl </I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>Seafood at hotel restaurants has come a long way since fried clams
at HoJo's. At the Steelhead Grill, a collaboration between New York restau-
rateur Drew Nieporent and Interstate Hotel Group, owners of the downtown
Marriot, bass, salmon, lobster, cod, and other deep sea delights are flown
in fresh daily, like most of the hotel's guests, via USAir and other carriers.<BR>
<BR>
Nieporent's Myriad Restaurant Group, whose New York restaurants (among them
the fabulous Montrachet and the Tribeca Grill, owned in conjunction with
actor Robert DiNiro) dominated Gourmet magazine's top New York restaurant
poll this fall, saw a need for an upscale seafood restaurant in Pittsburgh.
Given the area's heritage and the existence of the Steelhead salmon, a restaurant
was born.<BR>
<BR>
As was a signature dish. And according to chef John DiLeo, who worked in
Manhattan for 12 years before making the move to Pittsburgh, where his fiancee's
family hails from, the grilled Steelhead salmon, accompanied by Yukon Gold
mashed potatoes with capers and chive butter, accounts for 25 to 30 percent
of sales. <BR>
<BR>
But that's not the be all of fish at the Steelhead Grill. A variety of sea-food,
which DiLeo flatters with innovative preparation and unusual sides, arr-ives
daily from the Pacific Northwest, Florida, New England and Hawaii.<BR>
<BR>
It's a small menu, with no specials offered until the staff's up to snuff
on the regular items, according to DiLeo. The barbecued shrimp cocktail
is a twist on the norm - huge shrimp, dripping with tangy sauce, a side
of citrus butter for dipping. The Steelhead chowder is creamy, but a bit
light on the seafood. The Steelhead salmon tasting trio is a treat - salmon
canolli, lox and  tartar, all so  fresh. <BR>
<BR>
Seafood also dominates the entrees. One star is the Maine Lobster, steamed
or grilled with wasabi butter, a delicate balance of the Japanese horseradish
paste with melted butter. Panko-crusted cod features a light and seasoned
Japanese breadcrumb crust, beautifully pan-seared, leaving the fish moist
and flaky - totally detaching my 20-year association of &quot;Mrs. Paul's&quot;
and &quot;cod&quot;. The Pittsburgh charred tuna is a take-off on the preparation
tricks of iron workers, who legend has it seared their food on the furnaces.
Surely they never sauced it with the beautiful plum wine glaze that DiLeo
does. Careful here, ask the server for it cooked medium unless you're a
fan of raw tuna - and enforce it, ours still was real red. Pan-seared bass,
like the cod, was cooked to perfection, but both were a little on the oily
side. <BR>
<BR>
With the influx of a la carte restaurants, it's nice to get sides - especially
here. Accompanying the entrees are creative treats like olive mashed potatoes,
Yukon Gold mashed potatoes (the Yukon Gold is a variety of potato, so creamy
they just melt in your mouth) or crisp sweet potato cakes. Our server was
happy to substitute sides, too, so everyone chose their favorite.<BR>
<BR>
If you're not a fish lover, fear not. One palate pleaser is a endive and
arugula salad with roquefort. Topping it are pecans baked with a spiced
crust, which are little morsels of dream. Another appetizer pairs intensely
roasted shitake mushrooms atop a creamy risotto cake. There are a variety
of entree options too, such as the opulent New York strip steak with porter
beer sauce, accompanied by a stack of thin fried onions. There's also penne
with wilted arugula, oven dried tomatoes (though they were fresh the day
we tried the dish) and asiago cheese - not remarkable, but fresh and light.<BR>
<BR>
Save room for dessert. Cutlery clashed over ricotta cheesecake with spiced
berries, a rough-textured savory concoction which DiLeo pirated from his
grandmother. Close behind was a silky coffee creme brulee, smooth and deceptively
light. The chocolate hazelnut cake was like a nutty warm Yodel, moist and
densely paired with rich homemade peanut butter ice cream. <BR>
<BR>
The restaurant is oddly classy: white-table clothed, yet questionably adorned
with sports paraphenalia and huge blowups of deep sea fishing and coastal
scenes. DiLeo says its philosophy mirrors Myriad's Tribeca Grill: &quot;The
similarity lies in that we're trying to produce high quality, where we're
very concerned with the service and wines, but leaving a casual atmosphere
where people feel just as comfortable in jeans as all dressed up.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It apparently works. DiLeo says that though weeknights, Marriot guests dominate,
on the weekends, the Steelhead Grill is crowded to capacity with locals,
and generally booked a week in advance. So call ahead. This is no fish story.<BR>
<BR>
The Steelhead Grill<BR>
at the Downtown Marriot<BR>
112 Washington Place<BR>
394-3474<BR>
<BR>
Hours: <BR>
Lunch: 11:30 - 2 p.m. daily<BR>
Dinner: 5 - 11 p.m. nightly <BR>
<BR>
Appetizers and Salads: $5-$9<BR>
Entrees: $9.95 - $18.95<BR>
