<HEAD>
    <TITLE>People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1296.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1296.Diner.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT=
"Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H10People.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1296.Sports.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2></I>Scott Hanley<I></FONT></I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Name: Scott Hanley<BR>
Occupation: General Manager, WDUQ<BR>
Age: 37<BR>
Personal: Lives in Ross Township with his wife<BR>
Donna as well as Michael, 9, and Jonathan, 6<BR>
Education: B.S., Music, Eastern Michigan University,1982<BR>
Last Book Read: &quot;Hotel America&quot; by Lewis Lapham<BR>
Last Vacation: Florida Last Summer<BR>
</B><HR>A couple of years ago, WDUQ-FM, along with public broadcasters nationwide,
went through one of the scariest whirlwinds in its almost half-century existence,
when Congress campaigned to cut funding for the arts. Out of the ashes rose
a DUQ more focused on its significance to listeners and the challenges of
relying on public support. Scott Hanley, now general manager, joined the
station then and since has allowed his audience to tell him how useful the
station is. Listeners tell him during pledge drives and now through a significant
research project. It's all aimed at reinventing the formerly hit-and-miss
attitude of noncommercial radio into a sincerely professional venue. In
the last two years, the station's audience has grown over 50 percent. Hanley
told Lydia Strohl how.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Executive Report:</B> How old is the station?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Scott Hanley: </B>47 years - we went on the air in 1949. It was largely
an educational outlet, trying to give professional broadcasting skills to
people, back in the time when television was Milton Berle and test patterns.
We have evolved over the years into more of a professional audience. Course
back then we were only 1,500 - 2,000 watts. Now we're 25,000 watts, reaching
out to a whole lot more people. As commercial broadcasting becomes more
niche oriented, there's actually a broader niche for us to serve.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>How does DUQ stack up to other stations in the market?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH</B>: We have a significant signal. I can't give you direct comparisons
to the numbers because as a public radio station we have access to the numbers
but are not supposed to compare ourselves to them. Suffice to say we have
a significant audience. We're not the number one station in Pittsburgh but
we reach 100,000 people, very educated people, 25 to 54 demographic. Oddly
enough our biggest bump in demographic seems to be 35 to 44, the average
listener is in the mid-40s. They have higher household incomes, tend to
be more highly educated than the average in Pittsburgh. Some people call
them socially conscious people, if you get into the psychographics of it.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>How does NPR fit into the mix?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH:</B> It's our network, not just our supplier. We're an NPR member
station, we actually help in the guidance and care and feeding of the network.
Its news programming is a significant reason why people listen to us; at
the same time, we're trying to augment our local news programming to present
things in southwestern Pennsylvania. We've made significant strides in that
- we also won a couple of Golden Quill awards back in September.<BR>
<BR>
News and information, and the context we put all this information into,
is very important to us. Jazz is also an important part of our programming;
jazz is very important to the story of Pittsburgh. But at the same time,
we're not just a jazz and news station, we try to be a station for engaged
people. <BR>
Keeping in mind a broader citizenship, we're really focused on serving the
needs of interested people. The mission of Duquesne gets into serving the
heart, mind and soul. That's not a bad way of thinking about public radio.
It's not just information; it's context, it's serving the community and
being responsible. That doesn't have to make it dull, it can make it interesting.<BR>
<BR>
Our station has more luxury of time than most stations have, we can give
more than police blotter items. We can send a reporter to investigate an
issue that deals with crime and have them spend a whole day or more learning
the many different sides, finding sources, finding the different sides of
an issue. Then we can package that into a 10-minute feature and play it
during Morning Edition or All Things Considered. That's where we're trying
to get beyond reportage, the information, to the here's what people are
doing to try and change the way this is. We're trying to move forward to
some positive direction. We are not a proponent of any direction, but there
are stories that need to be told. If we are just looking at the list of
crimes and statistics, that doesn't tell you what's going on in the various
neighborhoods in Pittsburgh and what possible solutions there are.<BR>
<BR>
ER: Talk about the physical DUQ.<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH:</B> We have a staff of 15 people full time, another dozen student
assistants, and about a half-dozen very talented volunteers assisting on-air
and whatnot. Then when the pledge period hits another 300 volunteers come
into play.<BR>
<BR>
We have five people full time in news and public affairs, program director,
two people engaged in jazz programming. Our membership and development staff
is all of three to raise $1 million a year, so that's a busy task. The division
of labor is focused on what we do on the air, so the pledge drive becomes
everyone's duty. <BR>
<BR>
We pay our student assistants and they're based on merit. Duquesne has a
student station, and that's where you get to make your mistakes. For us
to use 25,000 watts for that purpose is probably not the best application,
especially since 95 percent of our cash revenues come from someplace other
than Duquesne. However we do have a number of fine students that make it
on the air. We probably have the longest list of reporters under the age
of 20 that have been on NPR nationwide. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What's the total budget?<BR>
<BR>
S<B>H:</B> Our cash budget is about $1.3 million. A little less than a quarter
million is from the corporation for Public Broadcasting, the rest is from
fund raising, business and foundation support and membership support. Sixty
percent is actually from listeners who make pledges, raised during pledge
drives, mailings, end-of-year gifts. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What's being a member station of NPR mean?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH:</B> They have a staff in Washington, D.C., with bureaus across the
country and parts of overseas. Based on our size we pay them dues, about
$250,000 in dues, and part of that is because DUQ has grown. That's doing
our share of what it costs to produce NPR. NPR has a board made up mostly
of radio station managers and they set policy - it's an interesting blend.
They have to be a producer, they have to take care of their day-to-day things,
and they have to be responsible to their members.<BR>
NPR culminated out of the rough assemblage of educational radio stations
that existed back in the sixties and early seventies. DUQ was one of the
founding member stations of NPR, which over the last 25 years has evolved
into one of the finest news services in the country. <BR>
<BR>
Back in '70 there were still networks that had large bureaus specifically
for radio news. For the most part those are now dedicated to television
news, and NPR is the one big provider of long-form radio in the country.
<BR>
<BR>
I grew up listening to commercial radio, and what was there 25 years ago
can be heard only on NPR today. They call NPR the legacy of Murrow, because
it carries forward his embodiment of what broadcast journalism should be.<BR>
<BR>
I think what's going on on FOX and some of the cable TV channels, though,
shows that some commercial broadcasters think long-form broadcasting is
viable. It's fascinating, and it's good and bad. The days of having one
network tie up a third of the audience on any given night are gone. I grew
up listening to Arthur Godfrey - he was still on the radio back in the '60s.
There were things people had in common back then. We don't have an Ed Sullivan
show that will play rock and roll and still have a juggler and opera. The
stations are finding competitive niches, and by increasing their efficiency
they can be profitable with just a two share of audience, because they can
really target their audience and deliver that to an advertiser. The challenge
is going to be maintaining community, a broader community. That's where
I have real hopes for us. <BR>
<BR>
The funding crisis of a year and a half ago - when members of congress tried
to eliminate all our funding in eight months - really forced us to look
at the future of public broadcasting. Here at DUQ we are looking at how
we can grow the station, while maintaining our values, to not needing that
support. I'm not sure there will be support at the federal level in five
years. But I'm sure there is a level of support in Pittsburgh that will
allow us to maintain the quality of service that Pittsburgh deserves. We
can do better as a radio station and should to be as significant as we want
to be. It's an interesting challenge - as soon as what we do becomes viable,
someone in the commercial media will take advantage of that opportunity
and seize it. It's a delicate balance, but we rely on our listeners, and
to them we must be true.<BR>
<BR>
What if there's commercial entertainment that is no longer deemed appropriate
for commercial media? If there was no urban radio station in Pittsburgh,
would it be appropriate for public radio to broadcast it? I would argue
yes. That's where serving the community where needs are unmet comes in,
that we become an institution like the BBC, where what we provide are resources,
but we aren't competing in the same framework. Otherwise, a public radio
station could be changing formats every six months. <BR>
<BR>
We have one of the few non-commercial radio licenses in Pittsburgh, and
have to treat that as a long term asset. We don't have the flexibility,
as some commercial stations do, to sell off the asset because it becomes
more marketable in some other way. We'll be a public radio station for as
far as I can ever see. We're outfitted to be a resource. <BR>
<BR>
Would it be bad for bookstores if more people went to the library? In the
long term, if it means that more people are reading, probably not. And that's
the type of resource we can be. Thing is, we just have to have more people
reading.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How do you differentiate yourself from the other non-commercial
stations in the market?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH:</B> We're really fortunate the way it's shaken out in the market.
There was a time when both WDUQ and WQED broadcast All Things Considered,
when neither of us were really doing any local news. Over the years there's
been much less duplication of what we do. There's an understanding that
we are better off to serve the audiences that we have, rather than being
all things to all people. We share audience. If someone enjoys Morning Edition
but prefers classical in the middle of the day, it makes sense for them
to listen to WQED. If they like All Things Considered, then they want to
hear Rusted Root, they'll go to WYEP. <BR>
<BR>
We each have a brand we've taken on. Classical music is very important and
WQED is a treasure in preserving that. YEP is on the cutting edge - I've
moved around a bit over the years and the Pittsburgh popular music scene
is very exciting, and it's great to have YEP help in part by formatting
contemporary music. Jazz is also a very important part of Pittsburgh's past
and present. <BR>
<BR>
There you have three stations that reflect some important parts of Pittsburgh
- and if one station tried to do it all, they wouldn't do it as well. We're
very fortunate that there isn't really competition. Do we sometimes all
want to be popular? Sure. None of us would want fewer listeners. But at
the same time, we're able to share radio riches with our listeners that
other markets don't really have. So we have cordial relations with both
WQED and WYEP, which is more and more common around the country, because
our real enemy is not each other. Our real enemy is apathy.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How does your membership compare with your listening audience?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH:</B> The rule of thumb is one member for every ten listeners, it's
about that for us. That one member may represent two or three people, so
it may actually be eight to one. <BR>
<BR>
We have about 9,000 members. In the last two years that's gone up about
50 percent. The congressional discussions about the future of public broadcasting
really drove home the need for listener support. We hope those folks will
continue to support - but we're very encouraged.<BR>
<BR>
The constant discussions help drive home the issue, but at the same time
the station had been going through an evolution to become more significant.
Many of our listeners had been relying on us more and more.<BR>
<BR>
But there's another part to that - we've had to work diligently not just
to be an obligation. We have to fulfill our obligation to improve what we
do. That's where increasing the size of our news staff and the making sure
what we do on the air is of the highest quality - those investments in things
our listeners hear, in equipment to make sure we stay on the air, raise
expectations so we're not just that college station that's there sometimes
but a news and information station that people rely on. <BR>
<BR>
It's a reasonable expectation of a radio station, but it hasn't always been
true of a public radio station. If we are going to be significant we need
to take on that expectation so that people rely on us more and are more
likely to support us.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER</B>: I would think that with the whole retro appearance of lounge
and martini madness there's really an opportunity to capitalize and expand
your jazz audience.<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH:</B> Oh yes. We're doing a research project with 13 other public radio
stations, trying to define the language of jazz as it relates to our listeners.
People understand what we mean but often that communication just isn't as
effective as it could be. What is mainstream jazz, what is traditional jazz?
People disagree. What is it that makes it more successful or less successful
on the radio? <BR>
We have a budget of $160,000. We did music testing of essentially mainstream
jazz pieces in Seattle and Philadelphia, we're also having in-depth audience
research done on each of our stations and jazz on public radio in general.
And we're looking at the financial inflows and outflows - how many underwriting
people do you think we need to have, how large a membership department,
things like that. It may seem mundane, but if you don't take care of the
nuts and bolts all the dreaming you want to do may never happen if you can't
keep the doors open.<BR>
<BR>
I think in many public media things we're afraid of being successful. <BR>
<BR>
What's good about radio is that everyone can listen and have an opinion.
What's rough about radio is that we've got hundreds of thousands of potential
listeners and it's hard to talk to all of them. We're not becoming research
driven but we do want to have some tools.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How do you reach out to your audience?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH:</B> Starting on October 15, with the on-air fund raiser. That's one
method that can keep us very honest, since 60 percent of our income comes
from our listeners. That helps guide us in some very important ways. We
try to do surveys, we've done focus groups in the past. But DUQ has 100,000
listeners, so it's hard to listen to every individual. But we're getting
more significant so we have to try.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How is the Telecommunica-tions Act affecting broadcasting?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH:</B> Almost $22 billion of radio and television stations have been
sold in the last nine months. It has raised the stakes substantially for
what any piece of spectrum is expected to return to investors. Since a non-commercial
station is not quite the same as a commercial station, it's not quite the
same thing. But just look at the transfers in Pittsburgh alone. There's
been a tremendous shifting of assets. <BR>
There's going to be a lot of business consolidation, some programmatic consolidation,
and fewer players. In Madison, Wisconsin, there are essentially four owners
that own all the stations in town. But 25 years ago, there were four stations.
So it's essentially going back to where we were. We went through an incredible
period of growth in the '70s and had stations coming out all over the place.
Now that fragmentation seems to be ratcheting back because stations are
buying out or merging, the control is in fewer hands.<BR>
<BR>
What's going to happen with that? I don't know, because people will still
need something to listen to, but I'm not sure how much different everything
will be, because people don't have more spare time. <BR>
There's a crisis in cable television about expectations of increased revenues
not being met by reality. But for all of us in media, trying to make sure
that we're all doing something significant to make people pay attention
is the biggest challenge.<BR>
<BR>
So maybe in the long run the consolidation and the changes will actually
be good. There's only so many prurient things that can be done. The ones
who succeed are going to be the ones doing something substantial.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Will this ratcheting down of control lead to monopolies that
challenge free speech?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH:</B> I wonder about that. You look at Fox - Rupert Murdoch now owns
a a number of substantial newspapers, TV Guide, his television network,
and is about to make another merger, plus his ties with cable. <BR>
<BR>
But then again, commercial speech has never been free speech. It is the
speech of the owner of that station or that paper. <BR>
<BR>
Whether every voice in the community will be heard - I don't know that every
voice in the community is being heard now. I think that is a facilitation
role that public broadcasting can help, and one of the reasons we're here.
But at the same time, democracy is never going to be pretty. It's still
very much like making sausage. Once all of these shakeouts happen, there
will be more. And there will be failures, very big failures. Whatever's
changing now will change again.<BR>
<BR>
By having research tools, we can understand how we're being significant.
But having a constant fissure forward about our role in the community is
is going to keep us from being able to buffet quite so effectively those
changes that are going to affect media. There's a stability there by not
being leveraged by significant debt - but there's also not going to be the
kind of revenue streams that commercial stations can leverage. So we have
to be prudent and frugal, and still have to be significant.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Do you think people are aware of the power that the media outlet
has over its content, or do they trust it just because it's the news?<BR>
<BR>
<B>SH:</B> I would say if you look at what goes on, people are quite skeptical
anyway. If it disagrees with what they believe they may investigate it further,
but I don't think a newscast is going to dramatically change a mind from
a belief that's been reinforced and built up over time. <BR>
<BR>
Maybe it's because I'm not a news director any more, but I'm becoming less
of a cynic. I have to believe that in the long run, truth will out. <BR>
