<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Selling Basketball</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>At Duquesne and Robert Morris, Selling<BR>
Tickets Can be a Challenge at Times<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Bill Modoono</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Brian Colleary fully realizes the difficulty of the marketing task
he faces. He just doesn't consider it unique.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Everybody in Pittsburgh - except the Steelers - has to fight for their
place in the market,&quot; says Colleary, Duquesne University's athletic
director and the man who oversees the marketing efforts of the school's
athletic teams.<BR>
<BR>
Selling tickets in this town is difficult even for pro teams, but the fight
for a place in the sports market is tougher in some places than others.
Like at Duquesne, and at Robert Morris, another NCAA Division I basketball
program in the region.<BR>
<BR>
Consider the problems facing the people responsible for selling the men's
basketball teams at Duquesne and Robert Morris. First, you have the city's
legendary resistance to basketball. Then, there's the sizable commuter populations
of both schools: Com-muters are notoriously poor supporters of sports teams.<BR>
 <BR>
Both schools play in conferences that get relatively little national TV
exposure, Robert Morris in the Northeast Conference and Duquesne in the
Atlantic 10.<BR>
<BR>
And, most important, both must compete for fans and media attention with
Pitt, which plays in the Big East, the most-televised and perhaps best-known
conference in the country.<BR>
<BR>
Pitt has had some disappointing seasons the past few years, but they are
consistent winners at the box office. Each year, the Panthers' home schedule
at Fitzgerald Field House - capacity 6,798 - is a virtual sellout. And for
the four or so games Pitt normally plays at the Civic Arena, the Panthers
average crowds of 15,000 in the 17,000-capacity facility.<BR>
<BR>
In contrast, Robert Morris, which won only nine games the past two seasons
combined, has averaged 1,100 to 1,200 per game at the 3,000-seat Sewell
Center. Duquesne, in its first season under new coach Scott Edgar, averaged
just over 4,000 in the 6,200-seat Palumbo Center. The numbers are slightly
misleading, however, because after the initial optimism wore off, the Dukes
only averaged 3,200 for games in January and February.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Pittsburgh is very much a pro sports town,&quot; says Marty Galosi,
who wears many hats at Robert Morris, including marketing director for athletics.
&quot;Media attention is driven by the pros. It's difficult to find your
niche.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Robert Morris, which plays in the little-known Northeast Conference, does
not expect basketball to be a major revenue producer, but does want the
team to enhance student life and give the business school vital exposure
to attract students. That could be why the school plays Division I basketball.
As Galosi sees it, the Colonials' appearance in the NCAA Tournament in 1992
gave the school &quot;coast-to-coast attention,&quot; albeit briefly.<BR>
<BR>
Galosi says marketing plans focus attention both on the student body as
well as the residents of Moon Township and neighboring Beaver County. Players
are often used as team ambassadors, doing clinics in area schools and working
in local summer camps.<BR>
<BR>
Galosi admits marketing is &quot;not super advanced,&quot; but Colonials'
games are included in area entertainment coupon books with bargains, such
as two admissions for one price. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We like to emphasize that it's easy to get into our games, we play
entertaining Division I basketball and it's easy to get out afterwards,&quot;
Galosi says.<BR>
<BR>
Duquesne's marketing is more ambitious. Colleary says the team's target
audience includes students, alumni and the general public, most especially
young people ages 12 through 16. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We want the young kids who might aspire to be college basketball players
to get exposure to our campus,&quot; Colleary says.<BR>
<BR>
Duquesne makes it a point to invite players from every high school and junior
high school in the WPIAL to its games.Undergraduates are admitted free,
but their attendance is not taken for granted. Athletic department officials,
including Colleary, visit the dorms every year spreading the basketball
gospel. Game notices are even sent via campus e-mail. &quot;Students have
legitimate reasons for not attending, but it's not because they're unaware
we're playing.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Colleary does not see Duquesne as being in competition with Pitt for fans.
&quot;There's not a tremendous crossover in fans,&quot; he says. In fact,
Duquesne is looking to work with Pitt to get corporate sponsorship for their
Dec. 21 game with the Panthers - the so-called &quot;City Game.&quot; The
more attention the game gets, the better for Duquesne.<BR>
<BR>
The Dukes play in the Atlantic 10, a tough conference that gets less publicity
and media attention than it probably deserves. But, as conference member
Massachusetts has demonstrated, the best marketing plan is winning.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The impact of winning and losing goes across the board,&quot; says
Colleary. &quot;This will be a critical year for us to make strides in the
A-10.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
