<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Unemployment Compensation</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>A Court Clarifies Situations That KeepTerminated Employees
from Compensation Benefits<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Jim Urban</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>An expense report submitted by a Pittsburgh-based manager for Sun
Co. showed him working at home during one week in March 1992. Actually,
the manager was attending the Big East Conference basketball tournament
at Madison Square Garden in New York, according to an audit the company
conducted. An expense report from July of that same year showed the manager
working in Harrisburg and York. Actually, he was at his beach home in Avalon,
N.J., according to the same audit.<BR>
<BR>
Sun terminated the manager by the end of the year, but quickly found itself
the subject of an unemployment compensation claim. The manager claimed he
was entitled to unemployment compensation because he had not submitted false
expenses, but had only inaccurately listed his whereabouts on the days in
question. <BR>
<BR>
No harm, no foul, the manager said.<BR>
<BR>
Under the Pennsylvania Un-employment Compensation Act, an employee is not
eligible for unemployment compensation benefits when the employer discharges
or temporarily suspends the employee from work for willful misconduct. <BR>
<BR>
In the Sun Co. case, it came down to whether the manager's misstatement
of his whereabouts amounted to willful misconduct. An unemployment compensation
referee sided with the employer, but the Commonwealth Court of Pennsylvania
later sided with the manager, finding his conduct was not detrimental to
Sun, and that he did not intend to defraud Sun.<BR>
 <BR>
Fortunately for employers, the state Supreme Court finally settled the issue
in July by reversing the Commonwealth Court's finding, further clarifying
what is defined as &quot;willful misconduct&quot; under the unemployment
compensation law.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We decline to adopt a standard that requires an employer to show a
specific detriment resulting from an employee's infraction or an employee's
intent to defraud,&quot; Justice Russell Nigro wrote on behalf of the Supreme
Court. &quot;In many cases, it is not the specific harm to the employer
that disqualifies an employee from benefits but rather the employee's abrogation
of duties.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Specific to Sun's situation, it had a right to expect that employees would
accurately record information requested on expense reports, including the
whereabouts of the employee.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It does make clear that the employer does not have to show the company
has been harmed in order to avoid having to pay unemployment compensation,&quot;
says Mary Ellen Krober, an attorney with Buchanan Ingersoll. &quot;If that
case had gone the other way, it would have expanded the circumstances in
which employers are held liable for unemployment compensation.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In all unemployment compensation cases, the employer can first contest the
claim by setting forth in writing why the former employee is not eligible.
Many employers mistakenly believe that the process ends there.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They don't understand that once you get the initial determination
in their favor, that is not necessarily the end of the ballgame,&quot; says
attorney Robert L. McTiernan of Pittsburgh's Tucker Arensberg.<BR>
<BR>
In fact, if either party appeals the initial finding, the matter proceeds
to a referee, who grants or denies unemployment compensation after considering
the evidence. Some employers simply don't show for the referee's hearing,
who then rule for  the employee. Those that do show, McTiernan says, often
mistakenly rely on hearsay testimony, which is not admissible.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They try to defend the decision with statements or affidavits of people
who did not have first-hand knowledge of the circumstances,&quot; McTiernan
says.<BR>
<BR>
The referee's decision can then be reviewed by the Unemployment Compensation
Board of Review and subsequently the Commonwealth and Supreme Courts. But
all reviews beyond the referee level are limited solely to the evidence
and testimony presented at the referee's initial hearing. So it's important
for employers to cover all the bases at the initial hearing.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's a pretty fact intensive inquiry,&quot; says Buchanan Ingersoll's
Krober. &quot;When employers go to these hearings, they need to establish
that willful misconduct took place.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
In the Sun case, the employer did just that, stretching the referee's hearing
over three days as it painstakingly laid out its case.  <BR>
<BR>
<B> What is Willful Misconduct?<BR>
</B><BR>
The Pennsylvania Supreme Court, in the 1978 case McLean v. Unemployment
Compensation Board of Review, said any of the following constitutes willful
misconduct:<BR>
1. An act of wanton or willful disregard of the employer's interest, <BR>
2. A deliberate violation of the employer's rules, <BR>
3. A disregard of standards of behavior which the employer has a right to
expect of an employee, or <BR>
4. Negligence indicating an intentional disregard of the employer's interest
or of the employee's duties and obligations to the employer.  <BR>
