<HEAD>
    <TITLE>HEALTH BEAT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1296.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1296.Law.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT=
"Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H15Health.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1296.Education.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2></I>Power and Price<BR>
<I></FONT></I><FONT size =+1>Physicians Who Sell Their Practices Want Market
Value,But They Also Want to Retain Decision-Making Power<BR>
</B></FONT><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Almost five years ago, Dr. Frank Keller and the other four partners
making up the University Family Practice Association began to survey options
for the practice's future. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We were heavily involved in managed care, which mostly capitates payment,
so we learned to accept risk early,&quot; says Keller, who was also medical
director of a large health plan during that time. <BR>
&quot;I saw changes, some subtle, some less subtle. We knew that to operate
on a large scale, we would have to provide many services and have a large
patient base. And we realized as physicians we were poorly undercapitalized
to meet those demands of the future.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;[That] is ironic,&quot; Keller adds. &quot;Physicians are always thought
of as making a good living - but it's puppy play compared to what's needed
to fund a good system.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Keller and company, whose practice was 65 to 70 percent managed care by
the time they finally sold it in June 1994 to the University of Pittsburgh
Medical Center, were one of the first practices in the region to face the
specter of managed care head on - and hence, one of the first practices
sold in the region. <BR>
<BR>
Now, five years later, health care providers all over the region are facing
facts: To be able to accept the most profitable managed care contracts,
they'll have to accept more financial risk and provide more services. To
doctors, that means hooking up with a larger entity.<BR>
<BR>
A recent study in the Journal of the American Medical Association showed
that from 1983 through 1994, the number of patient care physicians practicing
as employees rose from 24.2 percent to 42.3 percent, while the number of
physicians practicing solo fell from 40.5 percent to 29.3 percent. Most
of the change occurred in the latter part of the study period, leading the
authors to conclude the change is accelerating. <BR>
<BR>
And that holds true in Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's almost a shark frenzy of everyone trying to acquire, buy or merge,&quot;
says Kent Culley, an attorney at Tucker Arensberg in Pittsburgh. &quot;So
there's this mentality of 'sell now or the price will drop.' &quot;<BR>
<BR>
Few statistics exist to categorize the transition regionally other than
the number of doctors the hospitals say they've acquired: Allegheny General
says it brought on 150 physicians while UPMC acquired 200 physicians in
100 practices. <BR>
<BR>
Blue Cross, meanwhile, projects by year's end it will have 330 physicians
affiliated by either acquisition or partnering. Community Health Partners,
an alignment of West Penn and Mercy Health Systems, has 150 primary care
physicians, and is shooting for 300 to 400. <BR>
From the physicians' perspective, power is crucial to any sale.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We wanted to be aligned with the provider where we thought physicians
had input, rather than a business organization with offices on the 34th
floor that no one gets to unless they're a Mellon or a Scaife,&quot; Keller
says.<BR>
<BR>
But there's no doubt that price is important, too. Reports of $20 million
buyouts have doctors wondering what their life work is worth.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;It's a sellers' market for groups with strategic importance,&quot;
says Mike Cassidy, an attorney with Dickie McCamey &amp; Chilcote. &quot;Federal
IRS guidelines state the hospitals can't pay for referrals or base the purchase
price on admissions. So if purchase price is fair market value, then it's
justified. If not, they'll lose tax exempt status.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The most popular method, one specified by the IRS, is discounted cash flow,
which takes into account not only the practice's hard assets, earnings and
projected earnings, but &quot;goodwill,&quot; an intangible asset determined
by such factors as the doctor's status in the community and their quality
of care. <BR>
<BR>
Deals also must be set up to skirt the Corporate Practice of Medicine Law,
which says any corporation that is going to practice medicine must be physician
governed. According to Tom Timko, associate vice president at UPMC, it purchases
practices through a sub-corporation headed by staff physicians. They're
not alone in out-maneuvering the law, though.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's such a quagmire - every hospital has their own way to get around
it,&quot; says Tucker Arensberg's Culley. &quot;[The law] seems to be eroded.
t was traditionally a boundary for monopolies and antitrust but it's on
the shelf because the effort is to reduce costs and provide quality care,
and networks are still perceived to be doing that.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Once terms are struck, physicians are generally given a lump sum for the
practice, plus a salary for a five- to 10-year contract and perhaps incentives
based on profits or other factors. Despite the IRS guidelines, though, numbers
from competing bidders vary.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Sometimes there is competition, depending on geographic location,&quot;
says Timko. &quot;Other times it's a little easier for the physician to
see his or her way. I think what the physician is most concerned about is
what's going to happen with their office staff, and how they are going to
be governed.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
UPMC makes a commitment not to make any changes in staff for one year, according
to Timko. The negotiation is a long process - up to a year or more - indicative
of the life-changing nature of the decision for physicians.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If they had their way they'd prefer not to do this at all,&quot; says
Cassidy. &quot;They've always decided everything, so it's difficult to simply
merge.&quot; <HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
