<BR>
<B><FONT size =+2>War Stories<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+1></I>Working Professionals Take Instruction Beyond Theory,<BR>
Telling Students How to Apply What They've Learned<BR>
<BR>
<I></FONT></I></B><BR>
<I>By Gretchen McKay</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Experience, the saying goes, is the world's best teacher.<BR>
<BR>
Business schools at Pittsburgh colleges and universities are following that
adage by bringing working professionals into the classroom to teach everything
from law, taxation and marketing to programming and information systems
management.<BR>
<BR>
It's simple: Schools hire working professionals or executives as adjunct
professors. Students, who get more than their fill of business theory over
the course of an MBA program, experience first-hand the &quot;real-world&quot;
application of a particular concept.<BR>
<BR>
A working tax attorney at Robert Morris College, for example, may offer
the latest changes to the Internal Revenue Code. A marketing executive at
the University of Pittsburgh might discuss a recent coupon campaign, and
the reasons for its success - or failure.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;[Using professionals] builds a nice bridge between actual practice
and the theoretical aspects of a discipline,&quot; says William Presutti,
associate dean and director of graduate studies at Duquesne's Graduate School
of Business Administration, which uses upwards of 20 such instructors over
the course of a school year. <BR>
<BR>
At a time when MBA students must grapple with ever-changing technology and
business practice, the policy makes good sense. In fact, as more and more
MBA programs adopt a corporate flavor, both faculty and students reach out
to the business world to access knowledge.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We're always striving for the golden mean - the perfect balance of
theory and practical experience,&quot; says Dimitris Kraniou, director of
the International MBA program at Point Park College.<BR>
 <BR>
Though it is difficult to conceptualize the business world without theory,
Kraniou notes, a business school must also &quot;make an effort to say 'Here
is what the theorists were explaining, and this is how an executive is applying
x, y and z.' &quot;<BR>
<BR>
It is especially important in subjects where specialized skills are required
or where there is constant change in the business world, such as law, taxation,
auditing or marketing.<BR>
<BR>
Students at Pitt's Katz Graduate School of Business, for example, learn
advertising from Mike Walsh, a senior vice president for operations and
finance at Ketchum Advertising.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Advertising is such a fluid topic - it's always changing,&quot; says
Walsh, who earned Pitt's executive MBA in 1990. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I try to show them how it works in the real world,&quot; says Walsh.
His expertise, he says, gives the students &quot;tools for their tool box
for when they actually get started [in careers] and attempt to focus on
the application.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Carnegie Mellon University, too, fills its adjunct staff with working executives.
For instance, students can take courses on leadership and crisis management
from Gerald Meyers, former chairman of American Motors Corp. and learn about
U.S. economic policy performance by drawing on the expertise of Norman Robertson,
retired chief economist at Mellon Bank.<BR>
Robertson approached CMU with the idea for his course six years ago.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Business students get a very heavy dose of economic theory,&quot;
Robertson says. In his course, he asks, &quot;How does it all work - and
does it all work?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
At Robert Morris, commercial tax attorney Bill Brucker talks frankly with
students about the ins and outs of dealing one-on-one with the IRS and U.S.
Attorney's office.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is an area a strict academician without an active practice wouldn't
be able to bring to the classroom,&quot; Brucker says. <BR>
<BR>
Yet, how do the schools determine which working professionals to invite
into the world of academia? Just because someone has good business experience
doesn't mean they're going to be successful in the classroom. <BR>
<BR>
Larry Feick, associate professor and former associate dean at Pitt's Katz
School says, &quot;good instruction is good instruction. [An executive teacher]
can't get away with just telling war stories . . . there has to be substance.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Consequently, at Pitt, all new teachers work with seasoned instructors to
design their syllabus and standards for tests. The process can be time-consuming
- especially for the adjuncts whose regular jobs require them to work more
than the standard 40 hours - but the instructors say they get a return of
their own.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's terribly enlightening,&quot; says Pitt's Walsh, who considers
his students an informal focus group. <BR>
&quot;They critique your ads, tell you what they like and don't like ...
it's a nice way of forcing myself to listen to the consumer,&quot; Walsh
says.<BR>
<BR>
Teaching also allows them the chance to clarify their thinking on a topic
because, as Feick explains, &quot;You never know what you don't know until
you try to teach it.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
