<P><HR>
<H4>The Next Chief?</H4>
The  Attorney Art Rooney II Manages a Law Firm While Lending a Hand With
the Family Business: The Steelers <BR>
<BR>
<I>By Pohla Smith<BR>
</I><HR>Like many kids, baby boomer Art Rooney II grew up dreading Sundays.
Part of it was the usual, Sunday-means-that-tomorrow-is-Monday crap. The
rest was much more personal. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I hated Sunday because it meant two things,&quot; he says. &quot;The
Steelers would lose, and I had school the next day.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
To add insult to injury, chances were his dad, Dan, would insist on providing
him and his sisters with transportation. &quot;I guess this was back in
the early days of sponsorships, but we used to have cars, and emblazoned
on the sides of the cars about as big as you could imagine was 'Buick, Official
Car of the Pittsburgh Steelers,'&quot; Rooney recalls. &quot;Dad would drive
us to school in this car with this on the side of it. We used to take some
abuse pulling up at school with that on the side of it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Art Rooney II is reserved, like his father and late grandfather, Steelers'
founder Art Rooney Sr., so he didn't provide any examples of the abuse.
But, unless you were born post-Immaculate Reception, you know the catcalls
must have been cutting and cruel, for the Steelers of the '50s and '60s
were absolutely dreadful. So were the Steelers of the '30s and '40s, for
that matter, but young Art didn't have to suffer through them. <BR>
<BR>
There was no prestige in being the oldest grandson and namesake of the owner
of the worst team in the National Football League. The team that even cut
Johnny Unitas because Buddy Parker thought he was dumb. Imagine what the
smart-mouths at young Art's school did with that. <BR>
&quot;It wasn't always easy. I sometimes kid my younger brothers and sisters
about how easy they had it compared to the older kids,&quot; Rooney said.
<BR>
<BR>
Conversely, though, the siblings and cousins who came along 10 or 15 years
behind him - there are 29 living grandkids - probably never savored those
four Super Bowl victories of the '70s quite as intensely as he.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I probably appreciated the whole thing more than the young members
of the family because I remembered how it used to be,&quot; says Rooney,
who was by then grown and making his way through the University of Pittsburgh
and Duquesne University School of Law. &quot;We had more fun than anybody
had a right to have over those years. You had to pinch yourself to figure
if this was really happening.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Now as general counsel and vice president of the Pittsburgh Steelers, the
44-year-old attorney - who bears   eerie resemblance to both his father
and grandfather - has a real chance to help make it happen again and again.
That's one reason he's spearheading negotiations for the family's proposed
$600 million North Shore retail and entertainment complex, which Mayor Murphy
opposes since it centers around the Nordstrom's department store he wants
downtown. <BR>
<BR>
Ditto young Rooney's threat to invoke a stadium lease escape clause that
kicks in next spring and head to the suburbs (the current Rooneys would
never totally abandon the general Pittsburgh area that Art Sr. loved) if
the city doesn't meet demands for stadium improvements. Art II believes
both are necessary to keep the Steelers competitive enough financially to
remain competitive on the field. <BR>
&quot;The Steelers feel that the development is an important part of the
lease negotiations,&quot; he says. &quot;If we're going to be in a position
where we can start to generate the kinds of revenues to compete with some
of these other cities that have shot way ahead of the pack in the NFL, that's
the kind of opportunity we need to have. In a city like Pittsburgh, the
opportunity to charge the kind of money for luxury seats and market the
club seating is not the same as it is in other cities.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
It's true nobody needs to have a tag sale for the Steelers, or the Rooneys,
for that matter. But it's also true that, despite its long string of sellouts
and reputation for prudent, some would say penurious, contract negotiations,
the team comes out on the low end of NFL money-makers. According to Financial
World magazine, the Steelers' operating income in 1995 was $6.4 million,
seventh-lowest in the NFL. Stadium revenues totaled $1.3 million - chump
change compared to America's team, the Dallas Cowboys, who collected $43.6
million.<BR>
<BR>
Besides, as various family members and newspapers have pointed out, the
North Shore project would expand the Steelers' holdings and give the many
grandkids reason to maintain the team as the family-owned, Mom-and-Pop operation
Dan Rooney likes to think of it as.<BR>
 <BR>
But will Art II be the next Pop? And, if so, who elected him? Those are
questions many people have been asking since he seemed to burst upon the
public scene from nowhere as the point man on the North Shore project, though
he has, in fact, quietly been handling legal business for the team - and
building a good reputation in sports, corporate law and political circles
- for more than 15 years. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The Big Question</B><BR>
<BR>
Is Art II the next Steelers president? The answer is probably, but not necessarily,
for Art II has other choices. He enjoys very much what right now is his
main job: managing partner at Klett Lieber Rooney &amp; Schorling, a corporate
law firm with offices in Pittsburgh, Harrisburg and Philadelphia. <BR>
He also has enjoyed his venture into real estate development. There also
is the possibility he might eventually be drafted into politics. <BR>
<BR>
He said &quot;no thanks&quot; in 1991, when Gov. Casey offered to appoint
him to fill the U.S. Senate seat vacated by the death of John Heinz, but
only because his family still was young and expanding. At that time, he
and his wife, Greta, had one daughter and one son. Since then, Meghan, 9,
and Daniel, 6, have been joined by Mary Greta, 5, and Ann, 4, and as far
as Rooney II is concerned the kids still are too young for him to run for
office.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;I realize that there's only so many years you have that your kids
are growing up and need you. I understand that for now, what free time I
have, that's where I have to spend it,&quot; he says. &quot;That's clearly
most important.&quot; <BR>
His belief was reinforced when he underwent delicate surgery for removal
of a benign brain tumor in 1994. It was, he said, &quot;a sort of life-changing
experience ... that really makes you stop and think about your life, what's
important and who is important to you.&quot; But after the kids are grown,
who knows? <BR>
<BR>
A political science major in college who always was interested in government
and politics, he might answer differently if he were drafted to fill or
run for some office somewhere down the road. With his name, Irish good looks,
legal skills and connections, he would be a formidable opponent for any
politician. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I haven't lived my life or career that (the team) is the only thing
I would ever want or do with my life. It's starting only recently to appear
to me that that's certainly a stronger possibility than I ever considered
it to be,&quot; Art II said.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think a lot depends on what happens as far as the development, what
happens with the team,&quot; says Art's father and current Steelers President
Dan Rooney. &quot;He is well-respected by my brothers, so I think they see
him in that light and really the only one there. He definitely is the person
having the experience, the ability and now, of course, his law degree, which
seems to be all we're doing.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The NFL apparently also looks at Art II as the heir apparent. &quot;There
have been many people in the league and owners who have said to me that
when I'm not there, which is not often, (at league meetings), 'he really
represents you well because he gets up and he can speak on the various subjects,'&quot;
the elder Rooney adds. &quot;There again, he has grown up in the business,
which I think differentiates him from some of the other young people that
are in there. I know it was a big advantage to me to have been on the scene
as a youngster all the way up.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
 The way Art II sees it, there is no reason to make a decision for some
time to come. In the first place, he is not given to hasty decisions. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;He focuses on the long term and doesn't get caught up worrying about
the short term very much,&quot; Jack Barbour, his friend and colleague,
said. In the second place, Art Rooney figures such a decision &quot;can
wait until my father decides he's going to slow down.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Consensus in the Steelers front office is that won't be for quite some time
yet, considering the example set by the Chief, as the late Art Rooney Sr.
was known. <BR>
<BR>
Dan Rooney is only 64, and the transition of power to him from his father
was a gradual and lengthy one. It began in 1969 with the sudden death of
the Steelers' business manager and continued until Art Rooney Sr. died at
age 87 in 1988. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The Next Question</B><BR>
<BR>
Who elected Art II potential Chief No. 3? Well, the answer is, no one and
every one. As both father and son explain it, it's just kind of happened
by family consensus because of a number of circumstances, the old-fashioned
tradition of primogeniture being  one. <BR>
<BR>
Art II is the oldest child of the oldest son, closer in age to Dan's youngest
brothers, twins John and Pat, than to many of his cousins. &quot;It's more
like I grew up with them than the next generation,&quot; Art says. Besides,
he added, &quot;this probably would sound chauvinistic, but the next three
grandchildren after me were girls, and, like it or not, back then they weren't
in the running.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
In addition, though many of the grandkids, including Art II, worked as teen-agers
as ball boys and press box statisticians, the Chief advised all of them
to go out and find their own profession. There just wasn't room on the Steelers'
payroll for all of them as adults. With similar advice and encouragement
from his father, Art II decided on the law - a profession that became increasingly
valuable to the Steelers in the '70s and '80s, as football became big business.
<BR>
<BR>
Art's eight brothers and sisters also followed their dad's counsel, finding
their own professional niches in the world while managing to stay involved
with the team in related businesses or as avid fans:
<UL>
  <LI>Dan Jr. became a high school football coach. 
  <LI>Jim is in the computer business, working with others at Carnegie Mellon
to develop a way for the NFL to digitize all its film to make all old plays
instantly recallable. 
  <LI>John also is a computer expert but works for Federated Investors.
  <LI>Rita and Joan are lawyers; the firm Joan works for represents Steelers
defensive end Ray Seals.
  <LI>Duffy and the late Kathleen became teachers. 
  <LI>Pat is studying to be a medical assistant. 
</UL>
<BR>
Dan says a number of his nephews also have shown interest in the Steelers
and football. Most intimately involved is Shawn, a son of John, who is in
charge of a huge division of Aramark, the concessionaire serving the Steelers.
<BR>
<BR>
But Art II wasn't even through law school when Dan began giving him league
legal cases to read and asking for his recommendations. Later, after he
graduated from Duquesne in 1982, Dan began having Art II handle the &quot;more
difficult, more high-profile&quot; contract negotiations. <BR>
<BR>
Then, he became the Steelers' lead lawyer when they sued the city for breaching
their lease by renting to the erstwhile Maulers of the defunct USFL. Art
also was the team's head negotiator in lease talks and various other lawsuits
involving the Steelers, Pirates and stadium authority over the years. It
was in the settlement of the Maulers' case, though, that he marked himself
as a comer by winning the lease escape clause that gives the Steelers such
a strong bargaining tool. It was a remarkable achievement for someone just
six years out of law school. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Art's a very tough negotiator,&quot; says his friend and colleague
Bill Titelman, who works in Klett Lieber Rooney &amp; Schorling's Harrisburg
office. &quot;He'll stake out a position because he believes in it. You've
got to make a good case to get him to move from it. If you can't make a
good case, he's not likely to move from it.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
While he no doubt frustrates a lot of opponents, it is doubtful that any
of them find themselves taking it personally, for Rooney seems to be a genuinely
nice guy, in the mold of his wonderfully down-to-earth, warm-hearted grandfather.
When friends and colleagues talk about him they use words like &quot;honest,&quot;
&quot;solid,&quot; &quot;discreet,&quot; and &quot;salt of the earth.&quot;
Those adjectives also were applied to his grandfather and to his father.
<BR>
<BR>
It was natural that his grandfather be a big influence, for Art II spent
much time with him. As a kid, he was always hanging around his grandparents'
house, the offices or training camp. He accompanied the Chief on trips to
Canada, as well as to the family horse farm in Maryland. The friendship
continued after Art II grew up, especially after his grandmother died.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;He had a lot of time on his hands and nobody to really hang out with,&quot;
Rooney II said. &quot;So I loafed with him a lot. You'd meet so many people.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Indeed, loafing with the Chief was like sitting at the right hand of a pope
or president granting audiences, except that Art Sr. always made the visitor
feel he or she was the VIP. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The number one thing I feel like I learned from him is appreciation
for people,&quot; Art Rooney says. &quot;Every person is an important person.
It didn't matter to him what social class you came from. He was interested
as much in the janitor as he was in the big shots, as he called them. I
hope that I have been able to carry on being interested in people, understanding
them. Everyone has importance.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I guess the other thing was he always in particular taught me not
to get too big a head,&quot; Art Rooney adds. &quot;Being a Rooney didn't
mean anything. It was how good a person you were.&quot; Considering how
Art II has turned out - good family man, hard worker, a reputation as an
ethical and honest lawyer, and a genuinely nice man - the senior Art probably
would think him very good, indeed. But he probably wouldn't tell him so.
<BR>
<BR>
After all, wouldn't want the kid to get a big head.	 <BR>
<HR>
<H4>Just Like Home</H4>
<BR>
Once Home to Smelly Slaughterhouses, Now Washington's Landing Mixes Upscale
Townhomes With Affordable Office Space <BR>
<BR>
<I>By Gretchen McKay</I><BR>
<HR>Thirty-five years ago, Herrs Island on the Allegheny River was notable
for just one thing: the nauseating smells generated by the animal rendering
plant housed there. <BR>
What a difference a few decades - and a vision - can make.<BR>
<BR>
Today, the 42-acre stretch of land just two miles north of the Golden Triangle
is home to Pittsburgh's first  &quot;mixed use&quot; riverfront development,
Washington's Landing.<BR>
<BR>
The $26.6 million project, a joint venture between the Urban Redevelopment
Authority and developers Montgomery &amp; Rust and The Rubinoff Co., currently
includes three office buildings, recreational facilities and luxury waterfront
housing.<BR>
<BR>
When completed in the spring of 1997, The Village at Washington's Landing
will boast 100 two- and four-bedroom luxury townhomes ranging in price from
$142,000 to $330,000. There are also plans for three 3,400-square-foot single-family
homes along the Allegheny's back channel. 	<BR>
Homeowners aren't the only ones able to enjoy stunning views of the downtown
skyline. <BR>
<BR>
Commercial tenants include the Pennsylvania Depart-ment of Environmental
Services, Gamma Sports, the Three Rivers Rowing Association and most recently
Silicon Graphics, a California-based high-technology company. And there
will soon be more: a fourth office building was approved by Pittsburgh City
Council last fall, and options have been taken on the two remaining two-acre
lots. <BR>
<BR>
By all accounts, the development is a crowning achievement in Pittsburgh's
developing waterfront.<BR>
Yet Washington's Landing's success was anything but a given, especially
in the early days of the undertaking, says Mark Schneider, Rubinoff vice
president for development.<BR>
<BR>
The island, abandoned in the '60s, was something of a white elephant until
taken over by the Urban Redevelopment Authority in 1978, which spent millions
trying to develop a plan to reuse the prime waterfront property.<BR>
<BR>
Schneider, a former North Side Civic Development Council member, became
interested in the site when he noticed that the city was &quot;pumping a
lot of money into the island, but nothing was happening.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Most saw only problems in developing the island, which once housed a scrap
yard, a firm that refurbished old railroad cars and the memorable slaughterhouses.<BR>
 <BR>
Schneider and partner Tom Cox, now deputy mayor for policy and development
in the Murphy administration, however, saw opportunity.<BR>
<BR>
Still, Schneider says, they were only interested in marketing Herrs Island
if they also would be allowed to develop the first building there.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We knew we weren't going to be able to convince people to come here
unless we had a product,&quot; says Schneider, who envisioned a commercial
structure with office, research and light industrial space.<BR>
<BR>
The authority agreed, and in 1987, The Rubinoff Co. signed on as the developer
for the first of three office buildings.<BR>
<BR>
The company had their work cut out for them: Not only did old buildings
have to be torn down and new water and sewer lines put in, but an access
bridge coupled to the 31st Street Bridge had to be constructed, as well
as a new spine road.<BR>
<BR>
Then within a year, Schneider recalls, came several unexpected environmental
problems.<BR>
Electrical transformers had once been stripped on the island, causing light
soil surface contamination. Workers also discovered buried waste, including
decayed animal carcasses from the Pittsburgh Zoo.<BR>
<BR>
Where there's a will, however, there's a way. <BR>
<BR>
The animal remains were shipped to a landfill in Ohio; the toxic PCBs from
the transformers were sealed and buried under tennis courts at a cost of
$5 million. And in 1991, the island's first commercial venture in years
was completed, namely a $2.8 million, 44,500-square-foot office building.
Plans for another building as well as a $3.5 million marina soon followed.<BR>
<BR>
By 1994, the largest project -waterfront housing in the form of 100 townhouses
- was also well under way, with Montgomery &amp; Rust signing on as Rubinoff's
co-developer.<BR>
<BR>
Schneider credits the city, which committed $2.9 million for road improvements,
utility lines, the public park and continuation of the riverfront trail,
with help in getting the projects completed. National City Bank provided
the construction loans and is now offering special financing for townhouse
buyers. The Urban Redevelopment Authority is also offering discounted financing.<BR>
The townhouse project was especially risky, says Schneider, because construction
was started without lease agreements with any tenants and &quot;Pittsburgh
is a conservative, `show me' market . . . before people buy, they want to
see it, touch it, feel it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
By fall, the first two phases had been completely sold out, a clear indication,
Schneider says, that &quot;the market is working.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Residents aren't even daunted by the possibility of being flooded. Remarkably,
the island stayed above water during the floods of 1972 and 1996, a good
sign the site is resistant to nature. <BR>
Among the many empty-nesters and young professionals who now call the island
home are Joe and Joyce Rutter, who have gladly traded in their house of
16 years in Bethel Park for a chance to live on the water.<BR>
<BR>
Joe, vice president of telecommunications for PNC Bank, says it took about
&quot;five minutes&quot; to decide on a $205,000 two-bedroom townhouse,
mostly because the secluded island is like a &quot;vacation spot.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
No wonder: just a few feet from their front door is a 7.5 acre park with
a mile-long jogging and bike trail, five tennis courts, a rowing and fitness
center, as well as a full-service marina with 150 slips.<BR>
&quot;Everything we do is in the city, so we figured we might as well live
in the city,&quot; notes Joyce, a financial officer at PNC, who quickly
adds, &quot;It was never a matter of whether to buy here . . . it was a
matter of which townhouse.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Residents and commercial tenants aren't the only ones singing the island's
praises; the development has been lauded by Pittsburgh Mayor Tom Murphy,
as well as Northside City Councilman Dan Onorato.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Who would have ever thought there would be a market for houses like
this on an island in the middle of the Allegheny, and yet we're watching
it,&quot; Murphy marveled this October at a ribbon-cutting ceremony to celebrate
the opening of 600 Waterfront Drive, Rubinoff's newest 30,000 square-feet,
two-story office building.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This shows what we can do on the riverfront in this city if we believe
in ourselves,&quot; he says, &quot;and ask for excellence rather than simply
mediocrity.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The way to grow the city is not by raising taxes, but by increasing
the tax base, being competitive and offering something that people want,&quot;
Councilman Onorato added.  Washington's Landing, he noted, fits the bill
completely.  <BR>
<HR>
<H4>A Chip Off the Old Clip</H4>
<BR>
Ever Try to Reinvent the Mousetrap?<BR>
A McKees Rocks Firm Reinvented the Paper Clip <BR>
<BR>
<I>By Catherine Dressler</I><BR>
<HR>Forget, for one moment, the high-tech advances redefining our limits.
Forget the silicon chip, the CD-ROM, the whole world of electronics. This
is the story of one local company trying to make it big with a decidedly
low-tech product: a paper clip. <BR>
<BR>
Oh, this is no ordinary paper clip. Not to hear its backers tell it. This
is the Super Clip, and it puts those pathetic little clips in your desk
drawer to shame. <BR>
<BR>
It's 4 inches long, about three times longer than the most common paper
clip. Its sturdy metal - finished in gold or silver - defies bending, and
it can hold more than 100 sheets at a time.  <BR>
&quot;I have a passion for this product,&quot; Linda Froehlich says. &quot;I've
always <BR>
loved it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
She's not exaggerating. Froehlich and her husband, Richard, fought nine
years and paid more than $35,000 in legal fees to convince the U.S. Patent
Office the Super Clip was unique and, therefore, deserving of a patent.
In July 1994, they finally did it when an appeals board overruled a patent
examiner. The Super Clip got the patent because of its strong metal makeup
and because its arms extend nearly all the way to the end of the clip, not
halfway down like an ordinary paper clip. <BR>
 <BR>
The Froehlichs' McKees Rocks company, Ace Wire Spring &amp; Form Co., put
it on the market in August 1995. Now, at least 5 million clips later, the
Froehlichs have had some successes and some disappointments. And they have
learned a lot about the intensely competitive office-supply industry. Super
stores like Office Depot, Staples and Office Max dominate the market. Because
they order huge amounts at deep discounts, they prefer to work with big
manufacturers with large product lines. <BR>
<BR>
<B>A Big Hit</B> <BR>
<BR>
Froehlich scored big when she convinced Office Depot to sell the Super Clip
even though Ace only has one product now. But Office Max recently began
selling a new competitor, the Mega Clip, which is made by a much bigger
manufacturer in Taiwan. Froehlich insists the Super Clip is far superior,
but at $2.59 a pack, it could be a hard sell against the Mega Clip, which
goes for 99 cents.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;With this, you're going to rip your document,&quot; Froehlich says,
holding up the despised Mega Clip. Ace plans to launch an advertising campaign
showing the difference between the two clips. The company also is working
on a line of Super Clips in primary colors. <BR>
<BR>
Fortunately for the Froehlichs, the office-supply market is vast, with many
fronts to tackle. K-Mart is selling the Super Clip, and Wal-Mart is evaluating
it. The Froehlichs also plan to package the clip in large bins for sale
to schools and companies. The clip is listed on the state's list of suppliers
and is expected to be added to the federal list soon. <BR>
<BR>
Contract stationers and mail-order companies are another avenue. &quot;It's
a big world out there, and everybody uses a paper clip,&quot; Froehlich
says.  <BR>
<BR>
With projected sales of $500,000 to $1 million this year, the Super Clip
comprises only about 5 percent of the business at Ace Wire. At its plant
along railroad tracks in McKees Rocks, Ace's more than 50 employees make
the clip, as well as wire forms for items such as bucket handles and coiled
springs used in products from coffins to swimming pool covers. The plant
saw a little campaign excitement when Bob Dole made a stop there in July
to tout his stand on business. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Idea </B><BR>
<BR>
Froehlich began toying with designs for the Super Clip after a customer
asked Ace to make a large clip that would attach to a base and hold papers
on a desk top. She was far from the first to try to improve on one of the
simplest designs in history. <BR>
<BR>
The paper clip was invented around the turn of the century and became an
office staple, so to speak, by the early 1900s. The standard paper clip
used today is known as the Gem because it was first made by the now-defunct
Gem Ltd. of Britain.<BR>
<BR>
The Gem is praised for its elegant curves, but it has a few shortcomings,
according to Henry Petroski, a civil engineering professor at Duke University
who wrote &quot;The Evolution of Useful Things.&quot; The Gem sometimes
tears the paper it is holding, bends easily and is not easy to put on, Petroski
says. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The paper clip is very complicated,&quot; he says. &quot;It looks
so simple.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Several hundred patents have been filed for the paper clip in the United
States alone. The Gem and a slightly larger version are still the most popular
today. The butterfly-shaped Ideal clip is a common fastener, along with
the Bulldog clip (a clamp with a round-ended handle) and the binder clip
(a two-pronged clamp with a black rectangular base). The Gothic clip, which
is less common, has a peaked tip and a squared end.<BR>
<BR>
Froehlich admits the Gem is more suited for a couple sheets of paper, but
otherwise she believes the Super Clip surpasses all the classics because
it can hold so much without popping off or slipping. And the Super Clip
is useful in so many ways. Customers use it to seal potato chip bags and
attach hems or curlers. Others make necklaces, belts and clips for money
and ties. One young boy bragged he had fashioned a set of makeshift brass
knuckles. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;There isn't anyone who can't use it,&quot; Froehlich says.<BR>
<HR>
<H4>Inside Your Head</H4>
<BR>
Neurosurgeon Julian Bailes May Be 100 Miles Away,<BR>
But Technology Puts Him Right Inside a Patient's Brain<BR>
<BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl<BR>
</I><HR>When Julian Bailes' beeper goes off, he rushes not to the phone,
but the nearest computer. Plugging in the beeper, which is also a wireless
modem, allows high tech brain images to be transmitted onto the screen.
<BR>
<BR>
So Dr. Bailes, whether he's at home or at work in the neurosurgery department
of Allegheny General Hospital, can be tapped for surgical consult from any
of the 23 western Pennsylvania hospitals and five overseas sites in the
Neurolink network, 24 hours a day, seven days a week.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Neurolink is a way to teleconsult to hospitals that don't have someone
to take care of neurological emergencies,&quot; says Bailes, 40, creator
and medical director of the Neurolink network. He clicks his mouse through
several angles of a brain scan from Elk County Memorial Hospital in Ridgway,
of an 80-year-old man whom Bailes recommended to remain at the local hospital
- his health was badly deteriorated, and there was no indication of serious
abnormality.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Neurosurgery is a very image-dependent specialty. If the abnormality
is not on the scan, almost never will we crack someone's head to look for
it. I don't want to look at the patient, I want to look at the scans to
see if there's anything operating on will help.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I thought in the era of fax machines and portable phones it made sense
that a board-certified surgeon could make himself available to outlying,
under-served areas by using simple and affordable and presently here technologies.
It's saving lives and money.&quot;<BR>
 <BR>
Bailes finds that about one-third of the patients, who previously would
probably have been immediately life-flighted to the nearest tertiary hospital,
don't need to go anywhere. They can be treated just as well or better at
their local hospitals. Patients who do need to come to AGH may not need
the helicopter ride, saving $4,000 - $6,000. And in dire emergencies, the
OR and surgical team can be prepared to go as soon as the life-flight touches
down. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;For every 100 consultations, there's about $500,000 in cost savings,&quot;
says Bailes, who estimates that several hundred patients have been handled
by the network since its inception in 1993. The system costs about $15,000
per outpost and is a boon to AGH, creating strategically strong ties with
these community hospitals. And though overseas links in Qatar, Japan, Hawaii,
Egypt and Brazil use Neurolink mostly for second opinion, they do occasionally
send patients.<BR>
<BR>
So why hasn't it been done before? Bailes shrugs and says drily, a tinge
of a drawl giving away his New Orleans nativity: &quot;I do it for free.
That's why I'm a real pioneer. Nobody else wanted to do it. But I wanted
it to work.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Worry not - there is recompense. Because of the telecommunications expertise
he demonstrated establishing Neurolink, Bailes has been appointed clinical
principal investigator of the National Medical Knowledge Bank. The project,
a consortium of AT&amp;T, Carnegie Mellon University and Allegheny Health
Education and Research Foundation, AGH's parent, has received a grant of
$21.3 million from the U.S. Department of Commerce, matched by participants
for a total of $51 million.<BR>
<BR>
Bailes and his colleagues are creating a virtual, multi-media textbook of
neurology, which will be accessible online and continually updated. Just
a year into development, the end product will allow users access to such
futuristic technologies as synthetic reasoning and virtual reality, combining
them with case histories, interactive expertise and videos of actual procedures.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's the largest project of its type in medicine, to create a dynamic
system with the capability to deliver experts and knowledge, coordination
of case management - to bring to bear all the knowledge we have on the subject
to apply to a particular condition,&quot; explains Bailes. &quot;The latest
updated information, particularly new treatments in drugs, genetics and
in side effects, without the usual two-year delay in publishing a textbook.
It's going to change the way we do things.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Medical students, residents in training, allied professionals, as well as
primary care physicians who need more information on neurological conditions,
neurosurgeons who do an operation infrequently, specialists who need very
esoteric information - all will benefit from the effort. Other specialties
also will be brought on line.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's reaffirmed my belief that all of healthcare, including a so-called
lifetime medical record, is going to be on line and accessible. If you're
traveling through Bismark, North Dakota and you want to buy a mink coat
you can hand them your Visa and they can tell you every purchase you've
made and whether you're able to make that one. But if you have a chest pain,
the ER has no idea what other medical conditions you have, what you're allergic
to or anything,&quot; says Bailes, who believes one day we'll all have universal
medical cards. &quot;Telemedicine is here to stay.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
To wit, Bailes has also garnered a $450,000 rural medicine grant to install
high speed T1 data lines that run flicker-free video to three outlying hospitals
in Sharon, Clarion and St. Mary's. The connection allows them to run clinics
and see patients without anyone having to drive to Pittsburgh. <BR>
Bailes uses technology to help both patients and doctors where they are,
when they need it. In this fast-changing and complicated new era of medicine,
he's homing in on the real essence of managed care. <BR>
<HR>
<H4>Planet Visionary</H4>
<BR>
The Internet's Top Source of Environmental Information,<BR>
Not Far From Where Steels Mills Used to Pollute <BR>
<BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I><BR>
<HR>It's hard to imagine that the Internet's primary source for environmental
information is generated from Pittsburgh, former showcase of the gritty
and stinky, but it's true. The EnviroLink Network, better known as http://www.envirolink.org,
has now topped 4.2 million visitors a month, up from 1 million a year ago.
The network links 32,000 environmentally related Internet sites, 400 of
which are hosted by EnviroLink at little or no charge.<BR>
<BR>
And that promises to grow; Josh Knauer, executive director of EnviroLink,
is now in production with America OnLine to create an AOL environmental
information area, through which all groups wanting to provide environmental
information on AOL must link. That promises big numbers, and potentially
some cash rewards, as EnviroLink will be paid for the traffic on AOL.<BR>
<BR>
Knauer and EnviroLink are also spinning off a for-profit company called
Planetvision, which has developed the technology to compress large amounts
of data from NASA and other environmental sources and represent them on
a global scale in a cool and very user-friendly graphic format.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is the next step in Java applet application, for people to better
understand information,&quot; says Knauer, 24, who started EnviroLink in
1991 while a freshman at CMU. &quot;We're taking insane amounts of data
and quickly compressing them into a graphically beautiful user interface.
Melding graphic design with programming for function is the way the Internet
should be going.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Planetvision is earth science education for kids. The site's focus is a
high-resolution globe, which the user turns with a mouse to zero in on geographic
areas of interest. Clicking icons beside the globe brings up information
about that locale, including minimum and maximum temperature, cloud cover
and precipitation levels, evaporation and earthquake activity - provided
through direct linkages into NASA supercomputers and other internationally
known resources. <BR>
<BR>
Knauer's plan is to build capital by licensing Planetvision to science centers,
whose visitors will access the program via lobby kiosks. Public users of
the program will pay an annual licensing fee contingent upon their needs,
and the software will be continually updated, says Knauer, which constantly
changes the site for visitors. There will also be installation costs; efficient
use of the program will require much increased bandwidth (which is basically
to the Internet as pipes are to plumbing), as the program relies on high-speed
compression of large amounts of data. The program will be free on the Internet
for private use, through EnviroLink, of course - though access on most home
PCs will be slow.<BR>
<BR>
Knauer's vision for Planetvision is astronomical. And thus far, the response
has been too. Two weeks before its completion, at an October meeting of
ASTC, the Association of Science and Technology Centers, a pilot demonstration
garnered attention from science center administrators worldwide.  Knauer
went without even a sign for the display, and came away with fistfuls of
business cards. <BR>
<BR>
But its capability of compressing such large amounts of data means the program
can be applied to any data sets, making it useful in a variety of settings,
as in marketing for a global company. He's already talking with an overnight
delivery service about possible applications.<BR>
<BR>
And though others clearly will be on the same trail, Knauer is confident
that he's leading the pack.<BR>
&quot;We got off with a head start in that we have full access to the data
sets in the supercomputer,&quot; says Knauer with not a little bit of confidence.
&quot;Now, we've reached a level of efficiency with the data that will take
a long time to catch up to.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In fact, the technology's so exciting that Knauer's heard Bill Gates is
interested in looking at it. That's okay with him. His excitement for PlanetVision
is palpable, but Knauer's first love is EnviroLink, and he makes no bones
that Planetvision is for sale. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We haven't found an industry sector that it couldn't be useful for,&quot;
says Knauer. &quot;The concept is worth tens of millions of dollars - its
profit potential is tremendous.&quot;<BR>
<HR>
<H4>Bringing Hollywood Here</H4>
A Handful of Multimedia Companies are Bringing <BR>
Money to the Region; Some of it Comes from Hollywood<BR>
<BR>
<I>By Cynthia Bent</I><BR>
<HR><BR>
The Latrobe-based company Take 2 has just wrapped up a $4 million project,
&quot;Ripper,&quot; with stars Christopher Walken, Karen Allen, Burgess
Meredith and others, and with a soundtrack by Blue Oyster Cult. Hollywood
blockbuster? No, &quot;Ripper&quot; is a new interactive computer game produced
by Take 2 Interactive Software, makers of mega-success Hell: A Cyberpunk
Thriller, starring Dennis Hopper. <BR>
<BR>
Sounds more like something you'd expect from Silicon Valley than from  Pittsburgh.
But the 21st century is already here for a few high-tech multimedia firms
in the area, and it seems very plausible that Pittsburgh could be the Hollywood
of new media.<BR>
<BR>
Multimedia is a loose term these days. Strictly speaking, of course, multimedia
is any form of communication using several forms of expression - like a
slide show with printed text thrown in, some audio in the form of music
or a speaker, maybe some video clips as well. <BR>
<BR>
Computers have shaken up the communications industry like they have every
other. In fact, multimedia in many ways means computers - and interactivity,
a powerful teaching tool. Where a slide projector that could synch with
sound used to be high-tech, now a laptop computer runs a sales presentation
with sound, video, animated charts and graphs. It's even able to interact
with the audience's individual questions and answers. Interactivity is the
key: Multimedia producers like to trot out the old maxim, &quot;Teach me,
I'll learn, show me, I'll remember, involve me, I'll understand.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;What's important,&quot; says Marco Cardamone, president of Electronic
Images, a  local design and marketing communications firm,  &quot;is we
render a service in the communications field for clients that need to get
their messages out as a package and distributed by multiple media, whether
it's ink on paper or electronic dots on the screen or whatever.&quot; Computer-generated
work, he says, often accomplishes that goal better and faster than ever.<BR>
<BR>
It's this wave that has the communications industry changing faster than
just about any other, except maybe high-tech hardware and software itself.
And as this wave grows by leaps and bounds, so do companies that can keep
up with it, including Pittsburgh companies, even in a town that has a bad
reputation for being behind the times. <BR>
<BR>
Cardamone has seen the big time. He grew up in Pittsburgh, moved away in
the early '70s and spent 10 years working in New York City in the communications
industry with clients like ABC Sports, AT&amp;T and the Central Intelligence
Agency. <BR>
<BR>
In 1986, family called, and Cardamone moved back to Pittsburgh, starting
Electronic Images in 1988. As the name suggests, EI produces content with
cutting-edge technology.<BR>
<BR>
EI has been growing at around 25 percent per year for the last eight or
nine years. The staff of 40 keeps expanding, pushing at the walls of their
Carson Street offices. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's a little scary,&quot; says Cardamone, &quot;because you can't
really keep that rate up.&quot; EI's first efforts were mostly print-oriented,
but Cardamone had his eye on the future. Around four years ago, the company
started investing heavily in high-tech systems, and 1990 saw their first
multimedia projects. Now, EI is focusing forward, on projects like CD-ROMs,
kiosks and other new media forms, as well as digital video and audio production
and World Wide Web pages. <BR>
<BR>
Just this spring, EI added an elaborate non-linear digital editing studio,
allowing all their video and audio production to be done in-house. Some
of their large local clients include ServiceStar, FORE Systems and the Steel
Recycling Institute.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;What we're doing,&quot; says Cardamone, &quot;is we're growing with
our clients. We're providing more services to our existing client base.
So we're really very vertical - we start out doing say, print projects for
ServiceStar. Then it was, you know, electronic presentations for them, then
it was multimedia, then it was video. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;All of our clients kind of profile that.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
More and more, when Cardamone finds new clients, they're from all over the
country. He says the shrinking of the market over the last 10 years has
forced him to look outside of Pittsburgh to drum up new business.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think the idea is that it doesn't matter where you are, because
market place is becoming market space. I thought I'd never leave New York,
I thought that was where it was all happening. But coming back to Pittsburgh
I realized it doesn't matter where you are, it's what you're doing, and
nowadays the barriers to being a global company are practically zero.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
The digital nature of the medium and advancement of communications technology
make it relatively easy to produce, say, a web page here in Pittsburgh that
can be viewed by a client anywhere in the world. Furthermore, e-mail, videoconferencing
and the like make it feasible to communicate about projects more easily
than ever.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;So if I want to do business in Japan, I can, in terms of having the
infrastructure to make that a very cost efficient thing to do. I think there's
enough resources in Pittsburgh, in terms of university resources, corporate
resources, entrepreneurial resources, heritage here ... Really it's all
about content, creating original content for new markets coming around.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Other faces in the Pittsburgh multimedia crowd include a flurry of smaller
firms taking advantage of technology booms to carve out new niches for themselves.
Mind Over Media, for instance, is another communications company with a
similar mission to Electronic Images: marketing and communications services
using new techniques and technology.<BR>
<BR>
A bit smaller than EI, Mind Over Media is 4 years old, with five employees.
They're already earning notice, winning several advertising and design awards,
not to mention contracts. Projects include CD-ROM marketing tools for Heinz
USA, kiosks for University of Pittsburgh Medical Center and Management Science
Associates, and training systems for Federated Investors and the Carnegie
Science Center, among others. <BR>
<BR>
President Keith Saft says Mind Over Media was a company of one - himself
- until about a year ago, when new media projects began gaining more recognition
in Pittsburgh. He says he hasn't had to stray too far from western Pennsylvania
to stay busy.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Once people pick up on what we do, we face little resistance,&quot;
says Saft. &quot;Some people try to sell the technology. We try hard to
impress that our solutions are technology based, but it's communication
we're providing, ways to pull your message together that are easy to use
and engaging.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Another is Halo Technologies Ltd. a 2-year-old communications and information
technology firm comprised of only four people. Halo offers services for
commercial clients ranging from database creation and maintenance to computer
security to graphic and multimedia design. Size and youth - President Sean
Seibel is 22 years of age - notwithstanding, Halo already has its eye on
the global market, with clients in San Francisco, San Diego, Israel and
Tokyo. Rather than diving into big debt, Seibel says his company bootstrapped
itself forward one client at a time, using only home equipment at first,
adding on technology when it could afford it.<BR>
<BR>
The computer industry is thriving with little companies like these.  Not
all will survive, of course, but those that do will form the backbone of
the next century's information-based industry. All agree that Pittsburgh
has the raw material - the schools, the corporate culture, the local talent
- to propel the region to the top of the heap of new media production towns.
The schools in particular, of course, have national reputations for technical
prowess, and they're already jumping into the next century aggressively<BR>
<BR>
Duquesne University has a brand new program in multimedia - a Masters and
a certificate program. It started in the fall of 1995, and the first class
graduates in May. John Shepard, director of the program, says there's already
interest in the grads-to-be. USAir, for instance, has three on practicum,
and has moved all its pilot training here. The bad news - several out of
town companies have shown most of the interest, one more example of Pittsburgh
training talent for export.<BR>
<BR>
That brain drain is the one of a couple of problems that could hinder growth
in this new industry. Another is lack of awareness in the corporate world
of the potential already here. Solve these, and market could really take
off, spawning more companies and a national reputation, insiders say. <BR>
&quot;There's already a mini-Hollywood here,&quot; says Duquesne's Shepard,
&quot;but no one knows it's here.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Latrobe's Take 2  is one of the largest, most prestigious computer game
producers in the country. Source W,  a Westinghouse derivative, provides
a vast array of cutting-edge services to national clients like CBS. Visual
Symphony is another giant, in RIDC industrial park, just to name a couple.
Many have been around for years, and were formed, like EI, by natives who
left for the big city but returned for the lifestyle.<BR>
<BR>
Cardamone says, &quot;I don't get a strong sense that anyone knows what's
going on, or that there's a 'scene.' I know in New York, it's definitely
cooler, and they're really cultivating their image intelligently as a city.
Their thing is they're trying to compete with Silicon Valley, they view
themselves as the media capital of the world, and they don't want to get
left out. I don't see that kind of thing going on here.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Halo's Seibel agrees there is an awareness problem, at least in the corporate
world. He thinks it stems from bad first experiences with the new media.
&quot;Most people see the 'net as a place to waste time. The best way I
can arouse awareness is to show someone how to use the 'net well - like
I'll show them how they can track Fed Ex packages on the Web.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
There's also a general consensus in the field that when companies do go
looking for a web site designer or multimedia producer, they go looking
in the hot spots like New York or San Francisco for companies of equal or
lesser talent to what's already here. The attitude seems to be, &quot;If
you're so good, why are you in Pittsburgh?&quot; This from Pittsburgh firms
who could be asked the same question themselves, point out the new media
companies. Awareness of these issues is the creed of a new non-profit dedicated
to growing an industry, the Multimedia Foundry. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We're coming from the premise that interactive multimedia will be
a huge industry. Either Pittsburgh will have a piece of that business or
it won't. We think it can,&quot; says Foundry President John Cosgrove. The
idea is to raise awareness through outreach initiatives like classes in
new media, galleries and libraries, low-rent studios for companies just
starting up and more, all centered in a high-profile downtown building.
It was incorporated last June, and fundraising has just begun. The Foundry
already has some dedicated backers - PNC provided seed money, and FORE Systems
has promised a powerful backbone communications system for the future center.<BR>
<BR>
First on the agenda is a web site, already under development. Nauticom,
another Pittsburgh company, has agreed to host the site, and FORE has designated
a couple of designers for the project. The site will be a compendium of
all Pittsburgh has to offer, a directory of who's who in area multimedia
producers - a public relations vehicle to reach corporations here and all
over the country.<BR>
<BR>
Cardamone, Saft and the others agree that some unifying force like the Foundry
would be greatly appreciated. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It would be nice if there were some sense of community for the industry,&quot;
says Saft. &quot;You could know there are others succeeding, and learn from
them how to deal with your own issues.&quot;<BR>
In the end, the entrepreneurial spirit that launched this city through two
renaissances could push Pittsburgh as the new Hollywood.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I grew this company,&quot; says Cardamone, &quot;by riding to some
extent this whole DTP publishing curve, being able to understand what it
was and how it could be used to do things that other people were doing in
more traditional ways. I'm just betting that we can run fast, faster than
our competitors and certainly our customers. Because this stuff changes
very fast.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
