"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Quality<BR>
Comes<BR>
First</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1></B>The Winners in This Year's Q-Net Awards Include<BR>
A School District, a Steelmaker and Two Hotels<BR>
<B></FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Henry Lipput</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Question: What do a hospital, a school district, two hotels, a steel
mill, an insurance company and a bank all have in common?<BR>
<BR>
Answer: These seven are the recipients of this year's Greater Pittsburgh
Total Quality Awards.<BR>
Since 1992, the Greater Pittsburgh Chamber of Commerce, through its Quest
for Quality Network (Q-NET) program, has recognized organizations for the
delivery of ever improving value to their customers while maximizing their
overall effectiveness and productivity.<BR>
<BR>
Candidates for the total quality awards undergo a rigorous evaluation process
by an independent board of examiners comprised of senior executives who
have undergone total quality training. Organizations are measured against
the criteria established for the Malcolm Baldrige National Quality Award,
a nationally accepted standard for total quality. The seven criteria used
to evaluate each application include leadership, information and analysis,
strategic planning, human resource development and management, process management,
business results, and customer focus and satisfaction.<BR>
<BR>
Each of the companies chosen this year have programs in place that go far
beyond simply giving lip service to the importance of quality initiatives
in the workplace. For example, many are proactive in their approach to quality.
They don't wait for problems to appear, but instead have systems in place
that recognize potential problem areas and act on them. A number of the
companies have adopted not just corporate quality programs, but internationally
recognized standards of quality that can be independently verified. And
almost all of them have empowerment programs that allow their employees
to make suggestions and implement quality procedures that directly affect
their jobs.<BR>
The awards were presented on Nov. 20 at a banquet held at the Hilton Hotel
and Towers in Downtown Pittsburgh. Here's an overview of each of the winners:
  	<BR>
<H4>Honoree: Mellon Bank's Electronic Services Business Unit (ESBU)<BR>
Location: Pittsburgh<BR>
Primary Industry: Banking<BR>
Award: Significant Progress</H4>
Mellon's Electronic Services Business Unit is part of the bank's Global
Cash Management department, providing electronic cash management services
to large corporations, government and other businesses. ESBU moves funds,
initiates transaction and receipt processes and provides information reporting
and other related activities. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We have some fairly stiff competition,&quot; says David Taddeo, vice
president and director of operations for GCM at Mellon. &quot;And one of
the criteria that our customers use to rate our proposals for new business
is, 'How do you stand from a quality perspective?' &quot; <BR>
<BR>
Because ESBU's business consists of the moving and reporting of money, its
customers demand total quality and consistency in delivery. The information
that is provided to clients, in addition to the products that ESBU produces,
has to be exact because there are risks associated with errors or incorrect
data.<BR>
<BR>
Established in 1992, ESBU has made the employment of total quality standards
an integral part of its operations. It began using a Total Quality process
in 1993 and, under the direction of the Mellon Total Quality Center, adopted
W. Edward Deming's TQ principles, with an emphasis on customer orientation
and satisfaction. &quot;The Deming principles are one of the many aspects
of quality that we use,&quot; said Taddeo. ESBU also utilizes statistical
measurements, benchmarking and industry-wide surveys to compare its processes
to those of the competition and to get customer satisfaction feedback.<BR>
 <BR>
ESBU follows up on customer comments in an effort to obtain more information
on how to make improvements. &quot;We have a sales force, we have product
management people and we have operations people all talking to the customers
on a daily basis,&quot; Taddeo said. &quot;Whenever we pick up on what tends
to be a problem, that information is circulated and we try to attack it
as soon as we can.&quot;<BR>
<H4>Honoree: Pittsburgh Airport Marriott<BR>
Location: Coraopolis<BR>
Primary Industry: Service<BR>
Award: Significant Progress</H4>
Eric DeStefano, general manager of the Pittsburgh Airport Marriott, describes
the hotel as being &quot;a very intensive service culture in which people
genuinely want to take care of our customers.&quot;<BR>
An important element of this culture is the job satisfaction of the hotel's
employees. &quot;We want our associates to be happy,&quot; says DeStefano.
&quot;The way we look at it is if our associates really enjoy being at work,
it's going to be displayed to our guests. I put equal emphasis on associate
satisfaction as I do on guest satisfaction.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Pittsburgh Airport Marriott has integrated a Total Quality Management
philosophy into the daily operations of the hotel. The hotel utilizes financial
results, market share data, associate satisfaction and information on guest
satisfaction to measure the success of its services. Customer feedback,
obtained through the use of a variety of comment cards and surveys, is an
essential part of the quality improvement process. &quot;We've just installed
a new comment card system which is linked with our in-room television where
the guests can fill out the comment card via television on the remote control,&quot;
said DeStefano. &quot;The results are instantly printed behind our front
desk so that if there is a problem of any kind we respond to it instantly.&quot;
<BR>
<H4>Honoree: Pittsburgh Green Tree Marriott<BR>
Location: Pittsburgh<BR>
Primary Industry: Service<BR>
Award: Significant Progress</H4>
This is the third straight year that the Pittsburgh Green Tree Marriott
is getting the quality award. It received a Serious Commitment Award in
1994 and a Significant Progress Award in 1995. This is despite the fact
that the hotel is undergoing major renovations and went for four months
without a lobby and front entrance. The most important item for the hotel
is customer satisfaction and, according to its general manager, service
has improved in spite of the interruptions caused by the remodeling efforts.
&quot;The staff really went out of its way, and probably worked harder than
it ever had, to come up with unique ways to make sure the guest was satisfied,&quot;
said Ted Knighton, general manager for the Green Tree Marriott. &quot;A
lot of our total quality efforts were focused on those four months of construction
and how to minimize the disruption.&quot;  <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Quality in a hotel means excellent guest service,&quot; Knighton says.
&quot;It's living up to a guest's expectations, from what they think they
should get from a value standpoint at a hotel.&quot; The Green Tree Marriott
controls its quality through the use of Quality Teams and seven cross-functional
service teams that concentrate on specific service functions.<BR>
<BR>
The hotel measures customer satisfaction by the Marriott Corp.'s mail survey
of guests as well as a mail survey taken of guests of all Interstate hotels.
&quot;A big part of the process is giving our associates, who are serving
our guests and are around them every day, a means to express their ideas
on how to make things better,&quot; says Knighton. <BR>
<BR>
Because guest satisfaction is so dependent upon the performance of the staff,
human resources is an important element in the hotel's overall quality program.
The Green Tree Marriott works hard to select, train and retain the most
capable associates. As a result, it has a high degree of employee satisfaction
and a very low turnover rate compared to the rest of the hotel industry.<BR>
<BR>
Knighton says: &quot;I think that when you allow people to be involved in
the overall scope of the operation - and that's what we're doing here -
rather than limit them to one particular job, it gives associates a lot
of satisfaction in their work, knowing that they're trusted to make decisions.
They're empowered to make decisions and they can also see their ideas and
their improvements happen.&quot;   <BR>
<H4>Honoree: Allegheny General Hospital<BR>
Location: Pittsburgh<BR>
Primary Industry: Health Care<BR>
Award: Serious Commitment</H4>
&quot;Like many organizations, Allegheny has always had a platform for excellence,&quot;
says Anthony Sanzo, president and CEO of the hospital,  &quot;and we said
that what we were trying to do always was look for new and better ways of
delivering care or teaching or investigating.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Allegheny General Hospital is a 777-bed academic medical facility serving
Pittsburgh and the surrounding five-state area. The hospital has been recognized
for its expertise in many specialty areas and has been designated as a regional
resource trauma center.<BR>
 <BR>
In addition, Allegheny General is the Allegheny Campus of the Philadelphia-based
Medical College of Pennsylvania and Hahnemann University. Located on the
North Side of Pittsburgh, the hospital admits more than 29,000 patients
annually and has had as many as 390,000 outpatient visits in a single year.
<BR>
<BR>
Several years ago, the hospital staff realized that the processes of quality
assessment that were being put forth by Deming and others were really an
application of the scientific method. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Given the vast number of nurses and physicians employed throughout
the hospital, we had a group of people who were not only familiar with the
scientific method and comfortable with it, but employed it daily,&quot;
says Sanzo. &quot;So we tried to take the concepts of Continuous Quality
Improvement and apply them to everything that we did throughout the organization.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The hospital's CQI program emphasizes the involvement of all employees to
suggest and maintain the quality procedures that will directly affect them.
Every employee receives CQI education and has the potential to play a role
in finding ways to improve services and participate in the decision-making
process. <BR>
<BR>
Allegheny General Hospital's quality programs and services have had to deal
with the rise of managed health care programs in the Pittsburgh area, which
increasingly challenges the institution's ability to offer affordable, high-quality
care in the most effective way possible. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think that the conventional thinking is there's a tradeoff with
cost and quality,&quot; says Sanzo. &quot;When one thinks of managed care,
one normally thinks of being able to provide the needed service for less
expense. I absolutely do not see a trade off between cost and quality. I
think that poor quality is added cost.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<H4>Honoree: North Allegheny School District<BR>
Location: Pittsburgh<BR>
Primary Industry: Education<BR>
Award: Serious Commitment</H4>
&quot;What we believe sets us apart from our competition is that we truly
believe in continuous improvement in everything we do, academics, athletics
and the arts,&quot; said Dr. Lawrence Bozzomo, superintendent of the North
Allegheny School District. &quot;And we try to interpret and deal with and
respond to our clients' needs.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
North Allegheny is one of the largest school districts in western Pennsylvania
with eight elementary schools, three middle schools, an intermediate high
school, a senior high school, a 5,000-seat stadium and a transportation
facility.<BR>
<BR>
The district's test scores are consistently above the national average and
its pursuit of a quality education for all students is being realized through
a process of continuous improvement. Each year, teachers and administrators
gather test data and other relevant information to develop improvement plans
for their schools. They use these plans to set goals for the following year
in areas such as improving third grade spelling scores or, at the high school
level, increasing the number of girls that take physics.<BR>
 <BR>
Four of North Allegheny's schools have achieved Blue Ribbon Status in a
national award process sponsored by the Department of Education. Of the
537 graduates in 1995, 86 percent went on to attend a two- or four-year
college (well above the state average), six were finalists for National
Merit, three were Scholars for National Merit, 95 were members of the National
Honor Society and 113 received scholarships. In athletic competition, representation
by students in the 22 varsity sports resulted in 14 section titles, seven
WPIAL regional titles, and two PIAA State titles.<BR>
<BR>
The district counts its students and parents as its most important clients
and its paramount objectives include improving student achievement, improving
student self esteem, developing students' talents and abilities and developing
life-long learners and responsible citizens.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If anything saves public education in Pennsylvania, it's going to
be an understanding that we need to be driven by two factors: Continuous
improvement and client orientation,&quot; says Bozzomo. &quot;I feel very
proud that we have a leg up on that.&quot;<BR>
<H4>Honoree: Sedgwick James of Pennsylvania, Inc.<BR>
Location: Pittsburgh<BR>
Primary Industry: Insurance<BR>
Award: Serious Commitment</H4>
Sedgwick James of Pennsylvania is an insurance broker, risk management and
employee benefit consultant and claim service provider. The Pittsburgh office,
formerly known as the Fred S. James Co., has been providing insurance services
to businesses and individuals in Pittsburgh and western Pennsylvania since
1929. Its principal clients include Fortune 100 international companies,
Fortune 1000 Main Street (Business America) companies, small businesses,
individuals and families. <BR>
<BR>
The Pittsburgh office has recently been certified in the ISO 9000 program,
an internationally <BR>
recognized quality standard. Normally used by the manufacturing industry,
Sedgwick translated elements of the ISO so that it would apply to the service
industry. &quot;We're the first insurance broker to have achieved this,&quot;
says Dave Crooks, the Pittsburgh office's quality director.<BR>
<BR>
According to Crooks, ISO 9000 certification is verified by an independent
third party and ensures that Sedgwick's quality systems are &quot;in place
and that they are in fact working as we say they are.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
This emphasis on quality is something that Sedgwick's customers insist on.
&quot;Quality is something that our customers know a lot about,&quot; says
Crooks. &quot;They demand quality and they know that quality is the best
value.&quot;<BR>
<H4>Honoree: USS Mon Valley Works<BR>
Location: Dravosburg<BR>
Primary Industry: Manufacturing<BR>
Award: Serious Commitment</H4>
<BR>
The U.S. Steel Mon Valley Works is the lone survivor in the integrated steelmaking
market in the Pittsburgh area. A concerted quality effort, culminating in
the company's APEX Quality System (All People Excellence-All Process Excellence-All
Product Excellence), along with a new found supportive working relationship
with the United Steel Workers of America, has helped to foster the turnaround.<BR>
The company's APEX Quality System was created by Mon Valley employees in
the mid-1980s to meet the rigid quality demands of the appliance industry.
In the late 1980s, the system was adapted to meet the requirements of the
automotive industry and now stands for Automotive Product Excellence as
well. <BR>
<BR>
The APEX philosophy has since expanded to include all of the product lines
and employee disciplines within the USS Group.<BR>
<BR>
The Mon Valley Works, in addition to being ISO certified, is the first U.S.
Steel plant to also be QS 9000 certified. QS 9000 brings together the quality
programs of the three major U.S. auto makers. <BR>
&quot;This is their way of incorporating their individual plans in combination
with the ISO requirements, [and] getting an umbrella standard,&quot; says
U.S. Steel's David Kruszka.<BR>
<BR>
Currently, the major product line for the Mon Valley Works is appliance
materials. Its customers include General Electric, Whirlpool, Amana and
Maytag, among others. Based on its quality performance, the Mon Valley Works
is routinely recognized by these customers as the leadership quality mill.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In 1995, we received both the General Electric and Whirlpool quality
awards,&quot; said Kruszka, &quot;which is pretty much unheard of considering
the competition between the two major domestic appliance makers.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Mon Valley Works has continuous improvement work teams with extensive
employee involvement. This approach addresses individual problems and tries
to find solutions.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Once a month we have employees visit anywhere from three to four customers,&quot;
Kruszka says. &quot;We'll go and actually see our material being utilized
at the customer's plants. We get a lot of feedback between our employees
and the customer's employees. They understand what's really going on with
the product, how important their part of the process is, and they will come
back and spread the word in terms of what's important to the customer.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our best asset is our employees,&quot; he continued, &quot;and the
more we can educate them as to the big picture, the better off we're going
to be.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
