HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>The Lions<BR>
of the Bar </FONT></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>David J. Armstrong<BR>
Judge Gustave Diamond<BR>
Judge Robert E. Dauer<BR>
Robert S. Grigsby<BR>
Marvin S. Lieber<BR>
<BR>
Two Veteran Judges and Three Veteran Attorneys Say Practicing Law Today
Is Vastly Different Than  When They Entered the Bar in the Late '50s; Some
Think There Are Problems to be Addressed, But Others Believe the Problems
are Overstated<BR>
<BR>
By Jim Urban<BR>
</B><BR>
<HR>If you ask Bob Grigsby what he remembers most about law school some
40 years ago, one of the things the veteran trial attorney mentions is the
smell. Back then, Duquesne University's law school was exclusively an evening
program, housed in a former office building that is now a parking lot on
Fourth Avenue in downtown Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
Right across the street was the venerable Klein's Restaurant.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Every night, the odor of lobster and steak came across Fourth Avenue.
It's a wonder that none of us had ulcers,&quot; Grigsby says with a chuckle
at CNG Tower, which today is home to the law firm he co-founded in 1981,
Cohen &amp; Grigsby. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It was very tough on all of us,&quot; Grigsby says, &quot;because
none of us could afford dinner.&quot;<BR>
Tough indeed. And the curriculum was no piece of cake either. Two-thirds
of the students who started law school in the '50s never finished. At orientation,
the dean wasn't lying when he told students that the person on either side
of them would not make it to graduation. Nevertheless, Grigsby made it through
both the hunger pain and the Socratic drain. So did David Armstrong, today
the long-time president of Dickie McCamey &amp; Chilcote, and Gustave Diamond,
a one-time U.S. Attorney and current federal judge in Pittsburgh. Both were
several years  behind Grigsby at Duquesne.<BR>
<BR>
Up Forbes Avenue, meanwhile, a Korean War veteran by the name of Robert
Dauer was finishing his law degree at the University of Pittsburgh. He now
sits as president judge of the Court of Common Pleas of Allegheny County.
A few years behind him was Marvin Lieber, today a highly sought-after tax
and mergers/acquisitions attorney with Lieber Lieber and Tarantine downtown.<BR>
<BR>
Four decades after these two judges and three veteran attorneys earned their
law degrees in the city, we asked them to look introspectively at their
careers and their profession. Most notable among their comments: None of
them say they entered the profession to make money. <BR>
<BR>
All agree that the legal profession today is vastly different than it was
when they started practicing in the late '50s. Some think the profession
has problems for which it can only blame itself. But others think the problems
are overstated and that the profession gets a bad rap.<BR>
<BR>
Our experts also note the tough atmosphere for young people entering law
today and offer advice to those who want to become attorneys.<BR>
<BR>
This is a look at the legal profession through their eyes.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Why Law School?</B><BR>
<BR>
When David Armstrong was growing up in Hazelwood, he wanted to be a psychiatrist.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;But in seventh grade,&quot; Armstrong says, &quot;I learned that psychiatrists
are medical doctors. In those days, you had to be wealthy to go to medical
school and you had to have connections with medical doctors. I had neither,
so I would not become a psychiatrist. Then, I was reading a lot of criminology
and eventually decided I would become a criminal defense lawyer.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That would change. Armstrong worked for Mellon Bank during the day and would
slip over to the courthouse on his lunch hours to watch trials. He eventually
decided that he would be a trial lawyer instead of just concentrating on
criminal defense. <BR>
<BR>
Grigsby, like Armstrong, says he also got the law school idea from books
he had read.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I wanted to go into a courtroom and try cases,&quot; Grigsby says.
&quot;My reading had led me to that. I had read novels and true accounts
about lawyers who tried cases. That, to me, was a draw. The challenge and
the competition is what kept me going.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
He initially worked for an insurance company downtown, but later hooked
up with U.S. District Judge Rabe F. Marsh, for whom he worked throughout
the remainder of school. Grigsby sat in Marsh's courtroom, watching the
top practitioners of the day advocate for clients.<BR>
<BR>
Like Grigsby, Diamond also worked for an insurance company before taking
a job with Marsh. Diamond can't pinpoint what pushed him into law, but says
he can't remember wanting to enter any profession other than law. &quot;As
early as I can remember wanting to do anything,&quot; Diamond says, &quot;I
wanted to be an attorney.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Lieber and Dauer, meanwhile, point to role models. For Lieber, it was his
brother, Jerome, who today remains at Klett Lieber Rooney and Schorling,
the firm Marvin Lieber co-chaired before leaving in 1994.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There is a wide age gap between us,&quot; Marvin Lieber says, &quot;so
I was able to grow up seeing how he enjoyed the law, and I decided I would
do the same.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Dauer, meanwhile, says an uncle, attorney James F. Callaghan, pointed him
toward law school.<BR>
&quot;He and my aunt had no children, I was their son, too. I was very close
to them,&quot; Dauer says.<BR>
Today, our experts say, a variety of other factors push young people to
law school. Some do it for money. Others go to law school to make themselves
more marketable in careers unrelated to the legal profession.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think many of them go for the same reason I did,&quot; says Grigsby,
who teaches trial tactics at Pitt's law school. &quot;But also, I think
they see it as means of carrying on their lives from an economic standpoint.
Or they see it as a means of aligning themselves with the government or
with a business.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Another change is the number of graduates that law schools generate today.
Pitt accepts about 250 into a class, while Duquesne accepts about 100 day
students and 100 night students annually. About 75 percent eventually graduate,
much more than the 33 percent or so who made it through in the '50s. Today,
admission to law school is very competitive. Back then, law schools let
students in, then the curriculum weeded out those who didn't belong.<BR>
<BR>
About thirteen people graduated in the Duquesne class that included Diamond
and Armstrong. As Dauer remembers, about 130 people were originally in his
class at Pitt, but only 36 or so graduated. Lieber remembers 31 or 32 accepting
diplomas with him in 1958. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Then vs. Now</B><BR>
<BR>
&quot;Lawyering was a respected profession,&quot; Marvin Lieber says, thinking
back to his early years in practice. &quot;You didn't have the barbs and
jokes that you see and hear today.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
You didn't see attorneys treat each other with so little respect, either,
our experts say. Nor did you see the number of disbarments that occur today.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The public perception of lawyers is very poor,&quot; says Dauer, who
as president judge in Allegheny County sees a handful of disbarments come
across his desk each week. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;In my opinion, it's the fault of the profession itself. I think the
legal profession has tried to police itself, but has not done a very good
job,&quot; says Dauer. &quot;I get a good many cases in which lawyers have
fleeced their clients. These disbarments come across my desk. I am amazed
by the number.<BR>
&quot;It's really a shame because most attorneys have spent years and years
studying the law, then building their practices, doing their very best for
the clients. Nevertheless, I think the public perceives the legal profession
as a bunch of money grabbers and thieves.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And that's a far cry from the '50s, our experts say.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We were really looked up to,&quot; says David Armstrong. &quot;We
were like the clergy. We were very highly respected. It was like we were
in public service.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Adds Grigsby: &quot;Lawyers in those days were much more dignified in their
ways than they are today. We have more informality today than there once
was. There has been a very pronounced change in the attitudes of lawyers
toward each other. Even in the most heated and complex cases, lawyers always
maintained an air of respect toward their opponents. Today, lawyers are
much more given to the use of harsh language, attacks on their opponents.
There's much more an attitude of win at all cost.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
What changed the profession and its public image? A combination of factors,
according to our experts.<BR>
 &quot;Advertising,&quot; says Lieber, without much hesitation. &quot;You
started to hock your wares. It demeaned the profession. I'm not saying that
it was bad. I'm saying that this was an evolution that occurred. As a result,
the profession does not have that high pedestal that it once had.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Grigsby agrees in part.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Advertising is not a good part of the change, in my mind,&quot; Grigsby
says. &quot;It's a bad part. Those who advocate it say it is a means of
letting the world know about talented people. The fact of the matter is
that the most talented people don't need to advertise and don't advertise.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But Grigsby also points to another part of the change: the transition of
law over the years from a profession to a business. With that transition,
he says, came diminished professionalism.<BR>
&quot;Some of the changes taking place are directly related to the attempt
to be business-like, which takes away from the professionalism,&quot; he
says. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Many of the big law firms with substantial clients made the billable
hour the holy grail,&quot; adds Diamond. &quot;It certainly remains a learned
profession, but there is now a business aspect to it.&quot;<BR>
And part of any business is the profit it makes: money. In recent years,
the public has grown uncomfortable with the amount of money some attorneys
make, Armstrong thinks.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Law has changed from being a profession to a business, and lawyers
have been way overcompensated,&quot; Armstrong says. &quot;They make too
much money, and people resent it. We don't make as much money as athletes
or talk show hosts, but we make more money than we should.<BR>
&quot;The average partner at [Wall Street law firm] Cravath Swaine &amp;
Moore makes $1.5 million a year - the average partner, every partner. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;That's bullshit. They don't deserve it,&quot; Armstrong says.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Law Firm Business</B> <BR>
<BR>
The thing about operating like a business is that you face the same battles
that all businesses face, our experts say. Supply and demand. Customer satisfaction.
Employee retention. Tough competition. <BR>
<BR>
In law, firms laid off attorneys in droves earlier this decade when demand
dropped, and the field became crowded. Clients started complaining about
high bills. Some attorneys quit the profession or moved laterally to a competitor.
The competing firms, meanwhile, lured business away from other firms.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The marketplace takes care of people who act like businesses,&quot;
says David Armstrong. &quot;When you become a business, you become subject
to the laws of the jungle. There's an oversupply of lawyers, there's diminishing
demand. Incomes are going down. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;If you want to be a business,&quot; Armstrong says, &quot;be a business.
But, know that you are subject to the laws of the jungle.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That means law firms have to adapt and change, and some are doing just that.
Grigsby characterizes it as a swing of the pendulum that all professions
experience. He's confident the pendulum is swinging back to the way law
once was.<BR>
<BR>
Diamond, meanwhile, points out that a handful of law firms, for instance,
have put an emphasis on quality of life instead of the billable hour. He
expects to see more of that.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You see young people who have said they don't want to do it anymore,&quot;
says Diamond. &quot;Their quality of life has been diminished. They can't
spend time with their families. The market takes care of things like that.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And there also are efforts to improve attorney behavior while better educating
the public about the accomplishments of the profession.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They now teach ethics at practically every law school,&quot; Dauer
says, adding that few schools taught ethics while he was in school. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;And the professionals,&quot; the judge adds, &quot;have continuing
legal education that requires so many hours of ethics every year.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think a lot of things are being done,&quot; adds Lieber, who with
Diamond strongly feels the lawyers receive more criticism than they deserve.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We are educating the public as to what lawyers are doing,&quot; says
Lieber. &quot;We have lay people on the disciplinary board. We have mandatory
continuing legal education. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;In addition, the county bar associations have taken steps to show
the lawyer in a true light - the community participant, the pro bono work
that is done. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;That is all a help, in my mind, to change things so the image is fair,&quot;
Lieber says.<BR>
<BR>
Diamond says: &quot;The law profession has always been the subject of public
skepticism. The profession suffers the worst bum rap of all professions.
You have corrupt people in all professions, including the ministry. But
I know of no profession that performs more pro bono service than the legal
profession. You will find few professions that have contributed more to
our quality of life.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Back at School</B><BR>
<BR>
Pittsburgh is second only to Washington, D.C., in the number of lawyers
per capita, one for every 180 citizens. Despite the crowded field both here
and nationally, law schools are reluctant to cut admissions. Pitt and Duquesne
are no exceptions.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Law schools are profit centers,&quot; says David Armstrong. &quot;Law
schools are one of the few schools that make money for universities. And
in the law of jungle, where everyone has to compete to survive, and all
universities compete for the dollars and the students, universities have
supported law schools because they make money. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The law schools are belching out lawyers at unbelievable numbers,
and most of these very bright young people are out on the street looking
for jobs, and they can't find them. There aren't jobs for some of the top
students coming out of top law schools. There certainly aren't jobs for
half the students coming out of all law schools. They are going without
jobs.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But again, market dynamics are playing a role.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We are beginning to see a natural cutback in enrollments,&quot; says
Diamond. &quot;I think the natural market forces take over.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The message gets back,&quot; adds Armstrong, &quot;and bright young
people in college will get that message and choose other careers. The laws
of the marketplace will take care of it, but for now, the numbers are out
of balance.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And for those who are young in the profession, that means they face a tough
employment atmosphere. But it doesn't mean they won't succeed.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Achievement has to do with you,&quot; Armstrong says. &quot;You can
come out of Pitt or Duquesne law and compete with the Harvard or Yale law
school and still achieve. But, you won't have the opportunity for the first
position that you used to have because there is such a huge supply of lawyers
coming out without a lot of jobs. The jobs will go to the top students coming
out of the top-rated schools. So a guy like me would probably not get a
job in a law firm at all today. I couldn't get a job in this law firm today.&quot;Says
Grigsby: &quot;The advice I have for them is that they should not be concerned
with the material things early in their careers. When they come out, they
should be optimistic and they should have courage. If they have to open
a little storefront with their name on it, then by all means go open it.
And they'll make a living. It might not be the best living. They may not
compete with the people on LA Law, but those things are secondary. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The important things that you acquire early in life are not the material
things - the car, the bank account or the clothes on their back. The things
that you acquire that are important are those areas of knowledge that will
help them represent their client at the least amount of cost to the client.
If they are lucky enough to catch on with a firm or an employer, they shouldn't
think of the firm as big brother. It's a team. It should be a team. Whether
they eventually want to be a partner in the firm is really of secondary
importance to what should be their primary concern: learning and contributing
as they go. If they do those things, the other things will fall in line.
It will fall in line like dominoes.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think the opportunities are still there if you are willing to work
hard and develop into a specialized practice,&quot; says Lieber. &quot;You
won't do that immediately. I didn't do that immediately. You have to be
able to see what types of practice will be available to you in the future.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Duquesne and Pitt can and do compete well with with law graduates
coming out of Harvard, Yale, Columbia or Penn,&quot; says Diamond. &quot;There's
an initial edge for the top schools that comes with tradition, reputation
and so forth. But I believe that after the young lawyer's first four or
five years, that edge is gone. Now, it comes down to performance.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
