    <TITLE>Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Supplement5.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H4Editor.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Economics 101 </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>It's Time to Give All Our Young People<BR>
Some Basic Economic Instruction</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</I></B> </CENTER>
<P><HR>I recently went to Italy, hitting most of the tourist traps including
the Colosseum in Rome. As amazing as the Colosseum was, it was what I saw
outside the Colosseum that made me stop and look a second time. Dozens of
independent street vendors had set up shop about 15 feet apart, all selling
plastic Arabian horses for the same price: $7.<BR>
<BR>
Now mind you, several friends had asked me to pick up some gold for them
in Italy; others wanted linen or silk ties. But nobody told me to bring
them back a plastic Arabian horse. And I can assure you that outside the
Colosseum, nobody was buying the Arabian horses. Business was dead.<BR>
<BR>
So from my viewpoint a few steps away, here's the setting: The market was
flooded with these Arabian horses, and there was virtually no demand. Obviously,
these street vendors lacked a grasp of basic economics. I shook my head
as I looked at them. <BR>
<BR>
Then I realized something: I've seen the same situation at home, just not
as obvious. Many young people here enter their adult life without knowing
how to balance a checkbook, let alone with an understanding of basic economic
principles such as supply and demand. What's worse is that many of them
end up working for your company or mine, sometimes costing us customers
in the process. Others, meanwhile, are trying to strike out on their own
with their own version of the plastic Arabian horse.<BR>
<BR>
It's time to change the atmosphere by beefing up the state's core educational
curriculum, namely by adding an economics requirement. <BR>
<BR>
Currently in Pennsylvania, students must master four years of English, three
years of math, science and social studies and two years of arts and humanities
to graduate from high school.<BR>
At least 30 other states already build economics into the core curriculum,
so Pennsylvania is a state trailing the pack. <BR>
<BR>
In Texas, for instance, each school district is required to offer English,
math, social studies and science, plus an enrichment curriculum that includes
economics, with an emphasis on the free enterprise system and its benefits.<BR>
<BR>
In California, the graduation requirements include three years of English,
two years of math, two years of science and three years of social studies,
including at least a one-semester course in economics.<BR>
<BR>
In Florida, the core requirements include four years of English, three years
of math, three years of science, one year each of world and American history
and a course in economics that includes an overview of the history, doctrines
and objectives of all major economic systems.<BR>
I could go on through the list of states, but I think you get the point.<BR>
<BR>
Granted, some Pennsylvania schools have taken the initiative, seizing on
the programs offered by the Pennsylvania Council on Economic Education and
Junior Achievement to bring economics into the curriculum. But many others
ignore the need for basic economic education, and that's why legislators
must act.<BR>
<BR>
All Pennsylvania students should study the free enterprise system and the
opportunities it presents. They should also learn about the global economy
and how it will influence their professional lives. They can then make educational
choices that will help their own economic position once they graduate from
college.<BR>
<BR>
We don't want them to end up selling plastic Arabian horses. Ideally, we
want them to be the wholesaler who sold all those Arabian horses to the
retailers on the street.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
