<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Editorial.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H3Publish.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.GuestEditorial.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> </CENTER>
<P><B><IMG SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="LEFT"><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Going for the Gold</FONT SIZE> <FONT size=+1></B>Tim Parks
Tries Reining in Six Regional <BR>
Economic Development Agencies<B></FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher <BR clear=all></I></B><HR>Pittsburghers
are hopelessly immersed in turf. Instead of basking in the pristine glory
of Kurt Angle's Olympic victory, Pittsburghers launched a frivolous debate
about his &quot;official&quot; residence. When Scott Township staked its
claim to the new Olympic champion, the ensuing media coverage distracted
everyone from Kurt's outstanding accomplishments.<BR>
<BR>
Kurt Angle's victory was the region's victory. His achievements are not
the exclusive domain of any particular neighborhood. Embroiled in a heated,
typically Pittsburgh discussion about turf, Pittsburgh lost sight of the
big picture. Kurt Angle went for the Gold and got it. <BR>
<BR>
If Pittsburghers can't celebrate together, they are unlikely to be able
to work together. Yet they must.<BR>
The Pittsburgh Regional Alliance (PRA), one of the Working Together Consortium's
express mandates, is charged with amalgamating the region's primary economic
development players. Creating the PRA was pivotal. Experts feel the region's
future economic development success hinges on a single point of entry for
enter-prises interested in establishing a presence here. This un-Pittsburgh
notion of cooperation runs counter to our pandemic insularity.<BR>
<BR>
Kurt Angle would not be surprised to learn that in true Pittsburgh style,
the PRA marries the efforts and goals of its six component organizations
but doesn't marry the organizations. Each maintains its autonomy. Ask any
organizational behaviorist: Organization charts sewn together with dotted
lines rather than welded together with solid lines regularly unravel.<BR>
<BR>
A courageous contrarian, Tim Parks, the newly anointed head of the PRA,
is willing to buck the odds. And Parks may well prove the organizational
behaviorists wrong: His personal relationships with the heads of the six
agencies and his impressive track record as the executive director of the
Pittsburgh High Technology Council afford him a unique opportunity to succeed
in spite of a flawed organizational hierarchy.<BR>
<BR>
Adding Parks to the PRA team already has already filled an egregious void
in the alliance's agenda. For the two-plus years that the PRA was on the
drawing boards, spawning entre-preneurial ventures was not in its purview.
Yes, the granddaddy of Pittsburgh economic agencies was going full-speed-ahead
sans the largest present-day contributor to job creation, the entrepreneur.<BR>
<BR>
Now let's hope the dotted lines of this organization chart hold the region
together tightly enough to compete against those regions less interested
in turf than in growing businesses.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
