</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H5Guest.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Home Cooking</FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>By Hiring Pittsburgh-Based Companies, <BR>
We Invest in our Region and our Future
</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Robert J. Dunn</I></B><HR></CENTER>
<P>Nobody ever got fired for hiring the big guy.&quot; This is a saying
we've all heard in one form or another. It illustrates a philosophy of risk-free
business that can become all too prevalent when our region loses sight of
its roots and the economic vitality that existed at the beginning of the
century.<BR>
<BR>
We have encountered this thinking at times with CEOs and CFOs who have been
provided with a choice between one of the large, well-known national consulting
firms and one of Pittsburgh's firms - smaller and     lesser-known, but
able to demonstrate comparable capabilities. The decision, all too frequently,
is made not in favor of the local firm, even when the Pittsburgh firm may
offer contractual guarantees for performance and service levels that save
thousands.<BR>
<BR>
While we encounter companies unwilling to &quot;Buy Pittsburgh,&quot; we
also encounter many who are willing to take a chance on local companies.
We remain encouraged with our efforts to sensitize managers to their risk-averse
business decisions. We have been thrilled when our efforts have led to more
open-minded action and, in some cases, a change of heart that favors one
of our region's companies. We just need to continue the fight.<BR>
<BR>
In the marketplace, it is known that risk-takers must contribute and forge
the dynamic relationships upon which economic vitality thrives. In Pittsburgh's
marketplace, corporate decision-makers need to provide opportunity to smaller
Pittsburgh companies, who can rebuild the economy of our region. Pittsburgh
corporations should use Pittsburgh-based accountants, Pittsburgh-based advertising
agencies, Pittsburgh-based architects, etc. Some do, but many do not. Nor
have many even looked toward Pittsburgh to assess the local capabilities
- even for project work that could plant and nurture seeds to develop our
region's future.<BR>
<BR>
In the technology industries, risk-averse companies will consider only the
Big Six professional services groups or other national technology firms,
while a perfunctory glance is given to the companies in their own backyard.
The reason given - &quot;Too risky.&quot;  If the company isn't a brand
name with deep financial resources, it's easier to say, &quot;I hired the
big guys. If they can't get it right, what can I do?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It hasn't always been that way.  At the turn of the century, Andrew Carnegie,
when asked about his decision to step away from the railroads and enter
the steel-making industry, said he happened to be in the right place at
the right time. His comment may appear modest, but his conviction was not,
and he forged the power of an industry's and region's growth. <BR>
 <BR>
At that time, giants such as Carnegie, Westinghouse, Heinz and others pulled
this region together. Pittsburgh eventually was recognized as one of the
world's largest corporate  headquarters. During this period, entrepreneurs
felt pretty good about the challenges ahead since companies were cooperating
and building something together. Each time a bid was   awarded to another
local company, it was like a blood transfusion between family members. Those
revenues were rechanneled back into this region whether it was through newconstruction,
the arts, a better quality of living for employees, or even through tax
dollars to support education or public works.<BR>
Today, much has changed, but much remains the same. The people of our region
must once again pull together and build together.<BR>
 <BR>
Whether you manage within health, manufacturing, financial or some other
industry, you are already finding or are about to learn that the effort
to upgrade, manage and sustain information technologies at competitive levels
will require outside assistance. Why not give one of the many high quality
Pittsburgh-based technology firms, and the Pittsburgh region, a real chance?<BR>
<BR>
We need to get to know each other, to build regional relationships and to
trust each other. Pittsburgh companies generate and recycle monies into
the region. It is a transfer of wealth that is reinvested at home. This
type of philosophy enables quality people to stay here and pursue careers
that are meaningful and productive. It also leverages new resources at Carnegie
Mellon, the University of Pittsburgh, and Duquesne University, to mention
a few, through training and technology.<BR>
<BR>
If we grow together within this region, we'll all become stronger. This
would be a renewed brand of thinking that will help to create a foundation
of industry from which to build a new and dynamic era of prosperity. <BR>
            <BR>
Robert J. Dunn is president of MCSI, a Pittsburgh consulting firm.<BR>
