<H4>Duquesne Looks at the Family Unit<BR>
</H4>
It's no coincidence that Duquesne University President John E. Murray Jr.
is also executive director of the university's new Family Institute, a repository
of information about the family and the social dilemmas resulting from the
disintegration of the traditional family unit.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It was my big, fat idea,&quot; Murray says with a smile. &quot;It's
a personal interest of mine, something I've looked at a good bit for the
past 10 or 15 years.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Indeed he has. Murray cites a variety of statistics, some of which raise
some eyebrows:<BR>
u Since the 1960s, out-of-wedlock births and violent crime have increased
at about the same rate: 500 percent.<BR>
<BR>
u Children who live apart from one parent (in comparison to a two-parent
household) are twice as likely to drop out of high school, twice as likely
to have a child before age 20 and one-and-a-half times as likely to be out
of work and out of school in their early 20s.<BR>
<BR>
u Children from single-parent families or step families are two to three
times more likely to have emotional or behavioral problems and end up in
psychotherapy three times as often.<BR>
u About 46 percent of families with children headed by single mothers live
below the poverty line, compared to 8 percent of those families with two
parents.<BR>
<BR>
Duquesne partnered with the Scaife Family Foundation to get the institute
up and running. The Scaife Foundation is providing funding totaling $538,000,
enough to see the institute through its first four years. Murray says other
groups have expressed interest in supporting the initiative. He expects
no problems in keeping the institute alive beyond the initial years.<BR>
<BR>
Murray says a variety of disciplines - from economists to sociologists -
have studied and commented on how the breakup of the family unit has led
society into the proverbial tank. Duquesne wants to bring together many
disciplines - including historians, political scientists, theologists, philosophers,
economists and lawyers - while gathering, coordinating and evaluating current
studies of the family unit and pursuing some original research. Eventually,
Duquesne will publish a textbook for use in colleges and universities and
offer distance learning programs. The school will also host an annual symposium
on the family and sponsor special forums to explore potential changes in
social policy regarding the family.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Fifteen years ago, we used to say, 'Children are resilient. They'll
get over it,' &quot; Murray says. &quot;We know now that's not the case.&quot;
<H4><BR>
ER's Strohl Takes Honors for Healthcare Coverage<BR>
</H4>
Executive Report's Lydia Strohl walked away with top honors at last month's
33rd annual Golden Quill awards, winning a Golden Quill for continuing coverage
of healthcare and the Ray Sprigle Memorial Award for excellence in print
reporting in the magazine/nondaily newspapers        category.<BR>
<BR>
Strohl, 34,  is Executive Report's executive life editor and handles our
monthly People Making News interview and Executive Diner review. She also
reports on healthcare trends in the monthly Healthbeat feature and has authored
extensive pieces on the changing healthcare market.<BR>
The Golden Quill judges, who this year were members of the Cleveland Press
Club, singled out Strohl with the Sprigle award, commending her for &quot;providing
useful information about a subject that is difficult to understand: the
move in healthcare to managed care.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The pieces for which Strohl was honored included the October 1995 cover
story about how employers cut health insurance costs by restricting employee
options. She followed that with another this past February that detailed
how the decision-making power in healthcare is swinging from the doctors
to the managed care providers.<BR>
<BR>
Finally, Strohl authored the two-part Users' Guide to Managed Care series
that appeared in the June and July issues. The series looked at managed
care from the customer's perspective, providing insight on how to pick a
primary care physician and obtain specialty care. Back copies of all the
issues are available at the ER office for $2.50 each.    Incidentally, Strohl
authored another healthcare piece for this month's  cover story package
on rivalries. She gives the reader an inside look at the showdown escalating
between two healthcare giants: the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center
and Allegheny General Hospital (see page 30). She also wrote a Healthbeat
piece that discusses the different philosophies between Blue Cross and HealthAmerica
when its comes to the use of primary care centers (see page 81).<BR>
<BR>
The Golden Quill awards annually recognize broadcast and print journalists
for excellence. This year's awards were held Sept. 5 at Woodson's.<BR>
<BR>
Executive Report had finalists in three other categories. Jane Black's piece
on business ethics that appeared in the April 1995 issue was a finalist
in the feature category. Pohla Smith's sports feature on Ladbroke at the
Meadows, which appeared in the April issue, was a finalist in the sports
category. Editor-in-Chief Jim Urban was a finalist in the columns category.
<H4><BR>
Taking You Along for the Ride</H4>
Jim O'Brien is a Pittsburgh guy.<BR>
<BR>
He was born in Hazelwood, attended Allderdice High School and the University
of Pittsburgh and later spent time as a sports    writer at the former Pittsburgh
Press before becoming sports information director at Pitt. Today, O'Brien
spends his time writing about Pittsburgh sports teams. His series of books
this decade now totals six with the release this fall of &quot;Dare to Dream,&quot;
a profile of players and coaches on the current Steelers team.<BR>
<BR>
O'Brien has also chronicled the Steelers' Super Bowl teams of the '70s,
the Penguins of past and present, and the summer of 1960 when the Pirates
won a world championship. He also wrote a book about Pirate Hall of Famer
Roberto Clemente. The factors that make O'Brien's efforts unique are two-fold
First, O'Brien not only writes and researches the books, he also lays out
the pages and designs the cover jacket, deals with the typesetter and printer,
handles marketing, sales and distribution and -most importantly - pays all
the expenses. The latest book will cost about $85,000 to produce.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I'd love to be John Grisham,&quot; O'Brien says. &quot;It's got to
be easier. I'll do some book signings around the holidays, arriving at the
store when it opens in the morning and staying there until it closes at
night. I don't think Grisham or Anne Rice have to do that, but I know I
have to.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Also unique is the fact that O'Brien keeps the whole production and distribution
process in Pittsburgh despite likely opportunities to cut expenses by taking
some functions outside the region. Cold Comp Typog-raphers, located on Penn
Avenue in downtown Pittsburgh, handles the typesetting. Geyer Printing in
Oakland prints the books. <BR>
<BR>
Some journalists bristle at O'Brien's books because the books are full of
first-person accounts of his own experiences, whether it be hanging out
at the old Schenley Hotel in Oakland or interacting with the late Art Rooney
during the Steelers' dynasty years. O'Brien says he interjects himself into
the books on purpose.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I like to take the reader along on the trip with me,&quot; O'Brien
says.<BR>
<BR>
Many readers have embraced O'Brien's style, causing the bookstores to be
more receptive than they were when O'Brien first became a publisher. Waldenbooks,
which refused to buy O'Brien's first book until he actually produced a physical
copy, placed an order for the latest book sight unseen. And O'Brien has
found some customers among several Pittsburgh employers - including Respironics
and National City Bank - who buy copies in bulk and distribute them to clients
or employees as gifts. The books are considered nominal gifts under the
Internal Revenue Code, which makes them deductible by   the employer as
a business expense while excluding them from the   recipient's income<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
