"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Bothering the Banks</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT size=+1>Two State Senators Want to Limit Bank Fees;<BR>
The Banks Say the Senators are Off</FONT><BR>
<I>By Jim Strader </I><HR></CENTER>
<P>It sometimes seems hardest to find an automated teller owned by your
bank when you need just a few dollars - stopping to pick up a pizza on the
way home from the office, or picking up the dry cleaning while running Saturday
errands.<BR>
 <BR>
It used to be that nearly any ATM would work, although your bank would hit
you with a small fee if you used another bank's machine. Now, you could
pay twice to get your hands on your money. Your bank still wants its fee,
of course, and some banks have taken to dunning you a second time - imposing
another charge for the privilege of using their machines.<BR>
<BR>
Two state senators from Allegheny County say this relatively new   practice
amounts to a different kind of bank robbery - with the banks doing the taking.
Democrats Albert Belan of West Mifflin and Leonard Bodack of Lawrenceville
have introduced legislation to ban the  surcharges on ATM transactions in
Pennsylvania, calling it a matter of consumer protection. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;If there was ever a demonstration of the need for beefed-up consumer
protection, this new ATM surcharge is it,&quot; Belan says.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There's just something fundamentally wrong with a system that allows
consumers to be double-charged for the privilege of withdrawing their own
hard-earned money,&quot; Bodack says.<BR>
<BR>
One bank assessing ATM surcharges is PNC Bank, the largest in the state
and headquartered in Pittsburgh. Belan and Bodack took dead aim at the hometown
bank, criticizing the institution for adding the 50-cent charge at a time
when PNC had just reported a 28 percent jump in quarterly earnings. The
senators also say PNC recovers the cost of the inter-bank transaction separately
from the ATM user's bank, which generally passes that cost along to the
customer as a fee.<BR>
PNC balked at the Belan-Bodack proposal.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There's no doubt that we think this is unwise legislation,&quot; says
Jonathan Williams, PNC vice president for media relations. &quot;We think
the idea of price controls, when it is understood for what it is, is abhorrent
to most Pennsylvanians.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The surcharge - which PNC calls an &quot;access fee&quot; - is not a hidden
cost to those who use the bank's ATMs. Williams says all machines are marked
clearly with a notice that customers of other banks will pay an additional
50 cents for use of the ATM. In addition, a similar message appears on the
screen during the transaction and includes an opportunity for the customer
to terminate the withdrawal without charge.<BR>
<BR>
To the bank, the issue is one that people can handle without the intervention
of the Legislature - or the Congress, where the issue has come up recently
as well. Earlier this year, the American Bankers Association urged a House
subcommittee to leave things as they are, without legislative intervention.<BR>
<BR>
Philip Hudson, an executive vice president of Utah's First Security Service
Corp., testified that the bankers' group feels customers find ATMs to be
convenient, that customers have many choices about how to bank and that
banks provide adequate information about fees.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Competition for customers' business will ensure that each consumer
will have access to the best product at the lowest possible price,&quot;
Hudson told the panel.<BR>
 <BR>
But the Pennsylvania senators see things differently, charging that the
move by PNC, Mellon Bank and some others amounts to &quot;price-gouging&quot;
and &quot;exploitation.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
PNC says the fees pay for the network of ATMs, which the bank now operates
in seven states, including   most of Pennsylvania. Recently, the bank expanded
its automated teller network beyond the traditional   branch locations to
high-traffic places such as convenience stores and grocery stores. <BR>
Williams cited an example from a visit to a convenience store to make his
point. He told of stopping at a downtown store for a pack of chewing gum
and finding it to be more expensive than at a drug store or supermarket.
Not wanting to pay the higher price, he put the pack down and bought the
gum at another location.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;People are capable of making these decisions every day in many, many
ways,&quot; Williams says. &quot;There is a value to the convenience that
an ATM provides&quot;.
