ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.People.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Uniform Madness</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>Teaching Kids to Value Themselves, Not Their Clothes<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>Ann Devlin - Columnist</I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>It all started in the toddler department. I was on a pretty modest
mission: finding a couple of colorful T-shirts for our 3-year-old daughter.
There were lots of possibilities, in all the right colors. But each time
I reached for a hanger, what I pulled out was something more than I planned
on - and definitely more than I wanted. <BR>
<BR>
Every single little shirt had a company name printed on the front, and sometimes
the sleeves too. We're not talking little logos or tags sewn discreetly
into seams. The company names were several inches taller than they probably
appear on annual reports. The obvious goal was to turn even the tender-aged
into walking, talking billboards.<BR>
<BR>
How productive.<BR>
<BR>
This at a time when law enforcement and educators alike are decrying the
impact that the commercial label craze is having on teenagers. We as a society
find ourselves horrified anew with each fresh report of a kid being beaten
- even killed - because another kid wanted their team logo jacket or their
athletic shoes. Yet clothing and shoe manufacturers continue to blithely
make money the old-fashioned way, promoting consumer envy. <BR>
<BR>
Giddy from profits, they can't stop there. They have to nurture seeds of
that envy in even the youngest. I imagine that across this country, there
are children just learning their ABCs, who look in the mirror, see the big
bold letters silk-screened or embroidered on their shirts and, believe their
names are spelled O-S-H-K-O-S-H. Betcha that as their parents cleared up
that confusion, they also had to do some explaining as to why the company
that made that shirt had to put its name on it. Imagine how logical that
reasoning sounded to the 2- and 3-year-olds who couldn't even read yet?
Ah, but the point, of course, is that as their parents offered explanation,
they offered justification as to why the little ones should be wearing that
name ... that company's clothes, with pride. For those manufacturers and
their retailers, mission accomplished.<BR>
<BR>
First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton charged during her speech to the Democratic
National Convention that we live in a culture that tells children to value
each other for the clothes they wear, not what values they have in their
hearts. Which brings us to a few other items. Now that we're back in the
school year, we hear from the President (yes, I know it's also an election
year), plus a number of principals across the country and countless concerned
parents A Call to Uniforms. This idea couldn't make more sense to me. And
I bring 12 years of experience in wearing plaids and browns and blues to
support my argument. Uniforms instantly eliminate all of the wardrobe rivalries
that are so readily distracting, especially to teenagers. They function,
in the best sense, as economic equalizers. Once again, what can and does
matter most is what is in their heads and in their hearts, instead of what
is on their backs or in their parents' bank accounts.<BR>
<BR>
Uniforms save money, too. Yet, we continue to hear loud objections from
angry parents and students who insist clothing should be a matter of personal
choice, not a dictate. They argue that uniforms strip young people of an
important opportunity for individual creative expression. Oh. Then let's
put them in uniforms, and make art mandatory. And along the way, someone
might think to mention that were it not for the application down through
time of the concept of &quot;individual creative expression&quot; in everything
from science to math to management to medicine, we'd still be &quot;Yabba,
Dabba, Dooo-ing&quot; it like the Flintstones.<BR>
<BR>
I would say, &quot;Let's all grow up here.&quot; But, fact of the matter
is, it's grown-ups who've bankrolled this kiddie consumer seduction. It's
grown-ups in clothing manufacturers' design studios, who are charged with
finding new ways to exploit children in the clothes they wear. And it's
grown-ups who have instructed, by their own words and buying decisions,
that clothes telegraph a visual shorthand in our commercialized culture
about who and what we are. Why is it surprising then, that dressing right
matters more to some than doing right?<BR>
<BR>
So are there a few grown-ups out there ready to do the right thing? Are
we ready to refuse to buy clothes that carry as their main decoration, a
logo? Are we prepared to write to the manufacturers and let them know why
they lost the sale? Are we ready to take clothes wars out of the classroom,
corridors and cafeterias of our nation's schools? And, finally, are we ready
to help kids get this consumer thing right, by explaining to them that the
strongest fibers by which they should judge and be judged, are the fibers
of their character. <BR>
<BR>
