<HEAD>
    <TITLE>People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H10People.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Diner.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>Maggie Hardy Magerko</FONT></I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Name: <I>Maggie Hardy Magerko</I><BR>
Occupation: President, Nemacolin Woodlands and 84 Lumber<BR>
Age: 30<BR>
Personal: Divides time between a Belle Vernon, Pa., farm and<BR>
Nemacolin with husband Peter Magerko and son P.J., 2<BR>
Education: Upper St. Clair high school, 1983<BR>
Last Vacation: A dude ranch in Colorodo<BR>
</B><HR>Maggie Hardy Magerko's card is two-sided. One side reads President,
Nemacolin Woodlands Resort, the other President and Chief Operating Officer,
84 Lumber. At 30, the heir to Joe Hardy's formidable empire is in full bloom,
presiding over a $120 million expansion of the exclusive Fayette County
resort and the refocusing of the traditional 84 Lumber agenda simultaneously.<BR>
Magerko, who got her training &quot;on the job,&quot; is forceful and confident.
And despite, or maybe because of, tremendous wealth (the Hardy fortune is
valued in excess of $350 million), she's quite frank. Being in touch with
the customer is her battle cry - and she's betting a fortune that she knows
what they need. Lydia Strohl talked to her at her office in Nemacolin Woodlands.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Executive Report:</B> How did you end up running the resort in your early
20s?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Maggie Hardy Magerko:</B> In 1987, when we gained possession of Nemacolin,
I was with 84 Lumber in executive training, in the stores. My dad purchased
this property, and we had no idea what we were going to do with it. All
we knew was that we had to clean it up. It was in disrepair. So we just
started painting it. I hand-painted the chain-link fence around the tennis
courts. My sister and brother-in-law were involved at the time, so I decided
to design a spa. I traveled the country and tried to pick what I thought
were the better qualities in the better spas, and designed and opened the
spa in 1989. <BR>
<BR>
Needless to say, my dad and my brother-in-law didn't really hit it off,
so my dad, I guess I was 21, 22, said, 'Here are the keys, go run it.' I
fell on my face quite a bit, but learned very quickly what we needed to
do was to fill the beds. That was main priority, to get the business in
and fill the beds. We've always been under major construction since 1987,
kind of figuring out what we're trying to be here. What we're trying to
be is a very luxurious, five-star establishment that's profitable. So that's
been my mission for the last nine years. It seems like two. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>Why did your family purchase it?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> Just days before the auction, this crazy attorney threw a brochure
on my dad's desk. We were looking for [a vacation home], something kind
of different. We had no intentions, honestly, of getting involved in this
business, it was the last thing on our minds.<BR>
<BR>
I loved to fish. So when my dad saw this brochure, he came up. It was three
days before the auction; both he and I did fall in love with the place.
I was going to buy a little parcel to go fishing on. I haven't been fishing
for nine years, either. <BR>
<BR>
Instead, we gained possession of the entire property. I don't want to say
it was a spontaneous move, but it kind of was. At that time in my dad's
life, I think, I don't want to say he was bored with 84 Lumber, but the
systems were pat, it was running, and he wanted a new challenge. When we
first bought the place, he had intentions of making this his estate. But,
you know, he likes to share with others. So rather than making it an estate,
we figured, let's make this into a nice resort. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER</B>: What have been the biggest challenges getting this business running?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> The lack of experience, and I guess you could say, putting trust
in people and getting burned, and having to still maintain trust in people.
That's been the hardest for me. Today I'm probably more involved with 84
Lumber than Nemacolin Woodlands. In 84, I have associates that have been
there for 30 years. In [the resort], it's very transient. They seem to like
to come and go. So that's been a challenge, to gain consistency through
the upper management and the staff in general, through the selection of
the right people. <BR>
<BR>
My goal is to really get this place on the map, so when I walk down any
street, somebody comes up to me and says, 'Wow! [That's] not just a great
facility, but boy, you really have it all together operationally with the
staff and service.' So that's been a challenge, because we're on a really
fast-track basis. My dad's 73 now, I want this to be somewhat complete before
he passes away.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Are your brothers and sisters involved now?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> None of the other brothers and sisters are involved. There's
a total now of six of us. My father had a baby girl last year, and she's
only a year old in September, which is a little different. I'm the second-to-youngest
now, I used to be the youngest. The next sister to me is 12 years older
than me. My mom was 42 when she had me, and they used to call me 'the bonus.'
<BR>
<BR>
My sister gained the lord of the manor. Seven years ago, my dad purchased
a lordship title over in London. Last year, he passed it to my sister, Robin
Hardy Freed, and she is now the Lord of the Manor.<BR>
<BR>
Way back when, it was like the mayor or the governor of the town. Now, it's
a ceremonial title. They have what's called a Court Leap, which is held
over in a little town called Henley-in-Arden, in November. They go over
different projects that are going to be happening in the town, fundraising.
<BR>
What we do with it, though, is hold a royal reception here Labor Day weekend.
They have a Brooklooker, like a modern-day DER; an ale-taster, who back
then would go around and taste all the ale; a butter-weigher, to make sure
that you have received your value, and a town crier who will go around and
announce any events that are happening that day. We bring those people over
here, on the royal reception day, and we reenact it. All of our staff who
would be serving that day, we put them in the garb, as I call it. It's a
wonderful excuse to have a party, is what it is. Actually, it's the Saturday
prior to Labor Day. Traditionally, we only had the Royal Reception as a
one-day event. Last year, we dedicated the Mystic Rock golf course, so we
made it an entire weekend. We're going to repeat that this year.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How do you divide your time between 84 Lumber and here, and what
are your responsibilities to each organization?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> It's completely different. They're two separate operations.
There are a lot of similarities, I guess: a business is a business is a
business, all trying to make a profit. 84 is very, I don't want to say it's
set, because in the last three years, I've been starting to make some major
changes. The systems are set, though, and I have very solid people there.
It's a very objective company, whereas Nemacolin is very subjective. Meaning,
if you walk into an 84 Lumber yard, you would look at a 2x4, and both you
and I would agree if it's a good piece of lumber, or it's a bad piece of
lumber. Up here at Nemacolin, it's very much service. Your opinion and my
opinion could be on different ends of the spectrum. That is the most challenging.
<BR>
<BR>
Also challenging is the culture. At 84 we're celebrating our 40th anniversary.
They understand the expectations. Here, we're constantly growing, and we're
constantly adding a new product. At 84, although we're going after a different
target audience now, it's basically the same. So here at Nemacolin, you're
constantly changing. That's the toughest. <BR>
<BR>
I'm very hands-on here at Nemacolin. I'll walk around and meet and greet
with the guests, talk one-on-one with the hourly associates, and do strategy
meetings with the board of directors. At 84, it's at a higher level, I guess
is the way to say it. With 400 locations, I do travel quite a bit. But I
deal through people more. I have a lot of confidence in people, I have to
in order to operate that place. <BR>
As far as dividing my time, it all depends on the agenda for the week. I
think in this Royal Reception weekend we'll spend over a million dollars,
so my priority leading up to Labor Day is going to be Nemacolin. <BR>
<BR>
At 84, I manage through agendas. Every Monday we have an operational meeting;
after that I have a board of directors' meeting. During the week I meet
one-on-one with each person in development. So that's kind of how I work.
Then I go out to visit the stores throughout the year. Sometimes I go out
and just spot-visit, unannounced, then we have town meetings. So when I
say it's not hands-on, I'm not just sitting in an office in an ivory tower.
But I'm not out there loading trucks, though I did do that. It's different,
I don't want to say administrative, because it's more than administrative.
Again, I have to develop people there. We do 100 percent promotion within.
We do not hire for the top executive from the outside. So development of
people is so crucial there. <BR>
<BR>
It is here at Nemacolin, too, but I need to bring people in from outside
to get the staff exposed. Some of them have never been down to Pittsburgh.
And when you talk five-star, they think the Holiday Inn. I have a little
more sophistication down at 84 with the type of people that I'm dealing
with. Geographically, I can't physically walk around 84 stores - I have
to manage through people. Whereas here, if I don't like how something is,
I can physically roll up my sleeves and change it and have immediate satisfaction.
There, it's tougher. If you want to make one little change, and say it's
$1,000, you have to multiply it by 400. So it's tough. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Would you say your agenda there and here are different?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> Yes. 84 is a bare-bones, high-profit company. Instant cash in
the bank. Here, it's more of a long-term type project, where we're trying
to get the service and the facility up to speed. We will be profitable this
year. That will come in time, but first we need to get the place established.
We need to get it set straight. Again, there, everybody's on an incentive.
I myself am on an incentive down at 84. It's very much performance driven.
Very basic. Here, it's a little fluffy.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> When you say this facility was in bad shape when you got it,
had it been out of service?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> Yes, it was out of service for three or four months, minimum.
When we got up here, the grass was at least four feet up to the front door.
Not to gross you out, but downstairs there was meat in the refrigerator
that had been unplugged, so there were maggots everywhere. It just was like
a house that no one lives in for three or four months, and it sat, and there
was no loving tender care here. So that's really what we did. If you step
back from the main inn, you can see everything with a copper roof is what
we've added. The 30-room original lodge was the only thing up here, with
an 18-hole golf course, which we've completely revamped. <BR>
<BR>
Al Rockwell had it way back in the '60s and '70s, and what he did was he
owned about a thousand acres, it was fenced in about eight feet high. He
would bring in exotic animals and let them loose and go hunting with his
cronies. It really wasn't open to the public at the time, it was for private
pleasure. He sold it to Cordelia Scaife. She didn't have it for very long,
I think about one to two years she had it. I believe it was only open a
couple of months. And then it went back to Kent Rockwell; he did have it
open to the Alcoas of the world, the Westinghouses of the world, but it
was more of a rustic, mountain, men's getaway. Now we're trying to make
it more contemporary and much more luxurious for families, an all-around
resort. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> The restaurant, the Golden Trout, had a name for itself.<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> Yes it did, it was remarkable. And more than even Nemacolin,
you heard of the Golden Trout, and we have kept that name. It has done very
well.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> It's kind of a remote place, how have you reached out in terms
of marketing?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> Actually, from our construction, we're getting attention. I
don't think anyone in their right mind would put over $100 million in renovation
in this day and time. That alone has gotten us recognition. We're on Route
40, which is the national highway. There are a lot of people that travel
this. But bar that, we have the Mystic Rock golf course that we opened up
last year. Pete Dye designed that course. That has gained national recognition.
We were voted one of the top 10 new courses by Golf Digest, Golf Magazine,
Tee Time, all the major publications. The spa has gotten national recognition
from Bazaar, Mademoiselle, all the big publications. It's a lot of word
of mouth, and satisfying the guests.<BR>
<BR>
We do have a marketing plan. Our target markets are Washington, Baltimore,
Columbus, Harrisburg, Philadelphia, Cleveland, of course Pittsburgh, West
Virginia, Maryland, and what's happening is just slowly it's creeping out
and creeping out. For example, we don't have an available room all this
month. We're really going gangbusters. The deficiency of the property, and
that's why we're building a new addition, is we're overbuilt. We have 138
rooms, and we have vast amenities: two 18-hole golf courses, the spa, tennis,
the conference facility, all the eateries, so we're overbuilt as far as
amenities compared to rooms. You make money in this business by putting
heads in beds, as they say. So we're adding 125 rooms, and that will be
opened up April 15, 1997. That will balance out the property.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Has there been a master plan for all this development?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> I wish I could give you more of a sophisticated answer, but
after you're in something, you have the sense, the instinct or feel. I can
walk by a guest and tell you if they're having a good stay, a great stay,
or a terrible stay, just by their body language. And you can kind of sense
what that guest wants almost without asking, what type of level they've
traveled. We used to travel quite a bit when I was younger, so we knew the
expectations of the type of client that we're going after. Typically all
those places have a pampering type of spa. Typically they have a designed
course, not like our little links course that Al Rockwell designed. We needed
an upscale, Pete Dye golf course, because eventually we would like to have
a PGA tournament up here. That's our goal. That's why we built it, for exposure,
for Nemacolin. We knew again, group business, that's where you get the volume
of people. So it was kind of a common sense business sense, how do we become
profitable, and how do we maintain an upscale, luxurious property? And how
do we mix that hand in hand? That was always kind of our foresight.<BR>
<BR>
The perception out there was, the perception still is, that we're private,
which we are not. We welcome anybody to come up here to use the spa as a
day guest, or to use all of the facilities as a day guest. You don't have
to spend the night, which a lot of people think they have to do. Also, the
perception is, we closed for one year for renovation at the old inn, so
the perception was, we're closed in the winter. Wrong perception. We're
open, so we added the ski slopes, and last year, occupancy just flew. Not
that everybody was skiing, but we broke down the barriers as far as we're
closed in the winter. But it's a wonderful ski area. We have three slopes,
one chair. It's a little area, but it's great for families. You aren't scared
to bring your little guys to learn how to ski because you won't have somebody
racing down and hitting them. So it's worked out quite well. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>How much did your father purchase the property for, originally?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> $3.2 million.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> And you've put $120 million into it?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> Yes, so that's like chump change, I guess you could say.<BR>
<BR>
At 84, there's an emotional attachment. Here, there's an umbilical cord
attached to me. Again, I've been beat up so much in a good way, I've learned
so much about people, and I've learned about business, and I've learned
how to make a profit up here at Nemacolin, so it's my baby. If anything
would ever happen, I'd go nuts. It's an emotional business. We are so self-contained.
We have our own water system up here. We have our own sewage system up here.
We have our own telephone system up here - it's a city within itself. It's
like we're the mayor here. It's fun.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> You said this month [August] you're filled to capacity - is this
the first month that's happened?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> It's the first month that we're 100 percent occupied, yes. So
it's awesome. We're really now just coming into our own. We've been under
such major construction since 1987 that it was really tough to put a strong,
strong marketing plan together, because you as a guest might not want to
come up here and hear pounding nails or step in mud. Now that's kind of
isolated. It doesn't really impact the guests coming up here today. They're
actually kind of fascinated with the building because it's a different type
of architecture.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> In Pittsburgh, a lot of restaurateurs and others in the hospitality
industry talk about how hard it is to find good people. Out here, that must
be exacerbated by your location - how do you go about staffing?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> I'm going to talk about a couple of different levels, because
they all have their own challenges. The thing I think that makes this property,
or any private property difficult is there's ego involved, there's emotion
involved. And if you get another guy who is also the leader, what happens
is, there's a conflict. So I kind of got off the general manager kick. I
don't think it'll ever work, because I'm too intimately involved. I don't
just sit on the board of directors and veto things. The guests stop me in
the hallway, and if their stay isn't going right, they feel very comfortable
in telling me so. And of course I take action. So that's always been a challenge.
Because a typical GM, if you will, thinks, 'I'm the expert, why did you
hire me?' Well, I guess we, meaning my dad and myself, have visions of this
place being the best of the best, and we want it done now - not tomorrow,
the next day, or next month - so sometimes maybe our expectations are up
here. To find that top person that meets it has been almost impossible,
quite frankly.<BR>
<BR>
I've structured it differently. I have a consultant, two of them, actually,
who could be here permanently. But because they have the terminology of
consultant, they have a very open communication with me, they are very honest
with me, whereas before, if something wasn't going right, I'd call from
when I was out on 84 trips, and they'd say everything was fine. I have a
gentleman in operations, and I have a gentleman who I call my financial
advisor, he's very heavily involved in the economic part. <BR>
<BR>
As far as the mid-level, we have a challenge where we're located. People
who have sophistication might have a difficult time living up here on the
mountain, there is not much to do. When we bring people in, that's been
a challenge. Especially a married couple, the man or the wife is working,
that's fine, but the one staying at home, what do they do? We're trying
to start promoting within, kind of like we do at 84, but using these people's
exposure to train the hourly level associates, and the mid-level managers,
to get them exposed to what's out there in the real world, the true traveler's
expectations, to quality service. We're using the high-profile people, knowing
they probably won't be here 10 years down the road. The people from around
this area, not typically from right here in Farmington but the Pittsburgh
area, they have roots, so they're adjusted to this type of living. <BR>
The hourly associates are, in my opinion, neat people. They're very genuine
people. They don't have the polish or maybe the sophistication, but they'll
pat you on the back and say 'Hi, are you enjoying your stay?' Which again,
you get both sides, either too forward or not formal enough. But they give
you a comfy, cozy feeling. We have a training program that's fantastic.
I have a gentleman from Marriott, and Marriott as you know is well-known
for their training. I have a whole training center in the condos. It starts
off from the first day of orientation, depending on what department they'll
be going into, it can range up to three days, then there's a 90-day probationary
period where they go through intensive training.<BR>
<BR>
We're up to about 550 associates on the payroll, and with the new addition
we'll easily climb up to over 600 to 700 people. Our sources are starting
to get limited. So we're working with different colleges now, we have internships,
we provide housing. We have to get a little innovative. We clean their uniform
for free. We used to make them pay for uniforms, now we give them for free.
The great thing is, because Nemacolin is now coming into its own, it's easier
to now captivate people to come up here. Because they want to be a part
of this neat adventure that we're going through. You're walking through
Pittsburgh, you mention Nemacolin, people don't think you have a disease,
they know it's a resort.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> When these beds are done, what's next?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> We're always going to have something. Everyone always says,
'When are you going to be done?' We're probably going to be breaking ground
very shortly on another ballroom. Now that we're adding 125 rooms, plus
138 rooms we have in inventory today, we can now accommodate association-type
groups. The current room can hold about 325 to 350 depending on what type
of entertainment and how it's set up. We need a room that can really accommodate
about 600 people.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>What percentage of your guests now are groups versus individuals?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> About 60 percent group business, 40 percent transient-leisure.
It's changed. I think for us that is about normal, and that's what it should
be. We have direct sales people, and they have their different target markets.
But what happens, and it's kind of neat, people come with a group, then
we find they come back with their families, which works out great. <BR>
<BR>
It's very hard, or much harder, I should say, to meet the expectations of
the leisure individuals because you never know what their agenda is for
the day. With the group, it's all preplanned, so you can anticipate their
needs.<BR>
<BR>
For the first time in hospitality history, we're putting in a system called
Spa-Soft. When you call to make your room reservation, you can make a spa
reservation, and we've expanded that so you can make dinner reservations,
tee times - any amenity you want to use or any service that we provide,
they'll schedule it on the phone in a matter of minutes. That will make
sure we can accommodate the guest, but will help us as far as staffing,
service and expectations. Say you're up at the golf shop and you're running
a little late for dinner, you'll be able to change your reservation right
there. It'll be very guest-friendly.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Do you see yourself going either one way or the other as far
as 84 and Nemacolin are concerned?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> I'm too goofy. I like to have about 50 balls in the air, and
really not know which one's going to hit first. So for me just to do a single
dimension, I'd be lousy. I don't like to really focus on one thing for very
long. I'm much better if I have problems everywhere and it's really screwed
up, that's when I'm at my best. When it's smooth, I'm terrible. I get bored.<BR>
<BR>
I really enjoy having them both. I think 84 has an opportunity to be even
better. The last three years we've changed our business. We were the typical
retail walk-in. Now I have over about 1,000 outside salespeople that go
out and service contractors. Before the business was geared towards you
and your husband coming in to buy whatever. Today I think it's about 35
walk-in and 65 to 70 percent contractor business. Three years ago it was
probably 30 percent contractor, so it's a major shift. We could have gone
either way with 84. <BR>
<BR>
We could have converted all our stores into the big box, if you will, like
a Home Depot, or Hechinger's, or we could go really with what we're built
for, and that is the contractor. That's really what my dad started with
84. By accident, he got the walk-in business. There needs to be real attention
paid, because I have some old-timers that have been around and maybe are
not believing in it, if you will. It's a challenge to turn them around.
<BR>
<BR>
ER: How involved is your dad with 84?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> He's not. Which is nice, and I mean that as a compliment for
him, because he trusts in me. He's involved in the site work, he's involved
in looking for new stores, in development. He always has been, actually.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Are any of your brothers and sisters involved in 84?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> No. I'm the heir apparent, if you will, for the family.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Did he always know that was going to happen, or is that just
by chance?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> No, I think it was trial and error. He could be a real SOB to
work for, really he can. He and I have a special relationship, whereas my
other brothers and sisters, they let him beat them down. I'll go fist to
fist with him, and then he backs off. He loves to see people react. When
he sees no reaction, then he'll just drive you down. It does not take much
for me to react, you know, zzzt! So we get along very well. We're both kind
of hyper. You should see us in the room together.<BR>
<BR>
I think with the sons - I have two brothers, my oldest brother is going
to turn 50 this year, and the next one will turn 49 - you get the ego in
the way. I look back at patterns with family-owned businesses, and when
there's two men, it's a competition. Rather than working together, it's
who's in control. I'll admit, we get into some pretty good fights, but stimulating
fights. I'll tell him to bug off, if you want me to do it, let me do it,
and he respects that. I don't think they ever felt comfortable saying bug
off. <BR>
<BR>
Also, when I came into my own a little bit, he was older. I think that has
a little bit to do with it - he had to think of a succession plan. I was
his last resort. I remember sitting at the table, and he said he was going
to give it up to charity. And I looked at him, and tears almost started
coming, because he'd worked too hard. Not saying that that wouldn't be a
good cause, but I wanted to see it continue, I didn't want to see someone
else receive it. It would have torn me up.<BR>
<BR>
So I said, give me a chance, see what I can do with it. And I'm not bragging,
honestly I'm not, but he won't, so I have to: the last three years, we've
had the best three years at 84 and Nemacolin. But especially 84. The sales
and the profits have just gone skyward. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Is your husband involved in the businesses at all?<BR>
<BR>
<B>MHM:</B> He's involved up here at Nemacolin, in the construction. He
was a state trooper, and I didn't care for that too much. It kind of scared
me, especially when I got pregnant. It was his decision, of course, with
a little push. I needed his help up here. I'm involved in the overseeing
of the construction and the design. I don't get involved in the day to day,
because I can't. So he handles that along with my dad. Which definitely
has some challenges.<BR>
<BR>
My husband will come home sometimes and say, 'I worked for Joe Hardy and
I sleep for Joe Hardy.' So that's kind of fun.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
