<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.People.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Get Me to the Church</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1> On Time? You Bet, Just Ahead of a Slew of Other Brew
Pubs Pouring Into the Region</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Lydia Strohl </I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>Finally, something good's come of the parish closings that swept
Pittsburgh a year and more ago. That local trend, coupled with a national
trend - local brew pubs - begot The Church Brew Works.<BR>
There's not a lot outside the Church, the former St. Johns the Baptist,
in Lawrenceville, to belie its transition: A small, tasteful wooden sign,
a few bushes of basil off the kitchen (formerly the rectory) and an enlarged
parking lot are the only clues.<BR>
 <BR>
Inside, however, it's hard to hide the building's reincarnation. Replac-ing
the altar in the newly painted azure sanctuary are four huge copper brewing
kettles. Their blatant takeover as the new heart and soul of the place bothers
some, others not at all. &quot;There's a long history of beer and the Catholic
church,&quot; says Sean Casey, owner. &quot;The local fathers come in and
visit.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The space has been totally redone, with some clever twists: The confessionals
now house waitress stations and bar supplies; the original medieval-style
lamps and heavy pews are reused; light shines in through jewel-tone stained
glass, and large aluminum air conditioning ducts are contemporary statuary.
But the space is airy and loud, even when not too crowded, and the unfortunately
chosen plastic-topped tables give the huge space a cafeteria feel.<BR>
<BR>
The beer, however, is good, and Tony Knipling, president of TRASH, the Three
Rivers Alliance of Serious Homebrewers, has high hopes for it. &quot;I have
good feelings about it - they had a deadline to meet to open, but I think
it will improve. The brew master (Bryan Pearson from Houston, Texas) is
real energetic and not happy yet, and that's positive.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Church has four house brews on tap: Celestial Gold, a German pilsner;
Pius Monk Dunkel, a dark German lager; Pipe Organ Pale Ale, an English style
bitter, and Bell Tower Brown Ale, an American style brown ale. They're available
in a sampler for those who want to try them all, or just want to play quarters.
I liked the Bell Tower best, for its velvety deep taste. Knipling agreed:
&quot;It's the truest to style.&quot; A special wheat beer, Hefe Weizen,
brewed with German yeast, is now being poured as well: it's lovely and full,
with a hint of honey.<BR>
<BR>
In the kitchen, chef Erik Cantine, formerly of Max Planks, has put together
an eclectic menu. On the bar side of the aisle, sandwiches and what the
pub hopes will be its signature wood-fired pizzas are available. It does
not disappoint: We tried the exotic mushroom pizza, a white pizza with an
olive oil and dill base,  lightly cheesed and littered with mushrooms. The
dough's the star: chewy and dense, puffed with beautiful crusty bubbles.
The chargrilled salmon BLT was also tasty, a thick fillet grilled yet moist
in the middle, on a crusty combi-corn bread. They forgot to bring my broccoli
and jicama slaw, but get points for originality. Soups were long on taste
but odd in texture: that day's seven-onion soup was a little thick, and
the smoky black bean a little runny. Also good was a special sandwich, 
jerk chicken on a bun with sauteed veggies. The fries still wear their peels.<BR>
<BR>
Across the aisle from the bar is the restaurant, featuring a much more upscale
menu. Though the lunch menu features many of more casual bar items, the
dinner menu is smaller and more formal - almost at odds with the loud and
formica surroundings. (Sorry, I can't get past the tables.) We tried the
asparagus and goat cheese strudel with roasted duck, moist with sherried
wild mushroom sauce and savory with dried cranberries - it was the biggest
wow of the night. The &quot;untraditional&quot;  pierogie that day was a
spinach pierogie filled with eggplant portobella and feta. Yum.<BR>
<BR>
Not much about the menu is traditional. Bread is a light foccacia dusted
with the wheaty sweet pellets of recycled hops. Entrees are served with
a house salad, baby greens and an eclectic choice of dressings (I recommend
the ale vinaigrette). For dinner, we tried the buffalo strip steak (yep,
the kind which formerly had horns), a chargrilled salmon and the midwestern
pork chop - unfortunately, all grilled dry that night. The accompaniements
were fantastic, however - the buffalo basted in a hearty sauce of brown
ale and portobello, the chop with a coriander fig and apple chutney. Beer
and its raw materials are used liberally throughout the menu, to great advantage.<BR>
We also tried the Santa Fe chicken: sauteed moist and spicy in an achiote
marinade, and served with an interesting and tasty roasted yucca and corn
mash. A pan-seared breast of chicken, with a dijon peppercorn crust and
a quinoa pilaf, was also a little on the dry side: but I loved the quinoa
pilaf, rice dotted with the hearty grain of the Maya. The vegan pasta with
smoked tofu was overpowering with soy sauce. Desserts - we tried a pecan
pie sprinked with barley, and a cappucino mousse pie styled like tiramisu,
of which they'd regrettably sold out - were unusually lush, and the coffee
passable.<BR>
<BR>
All in all, the Church is worth a pilgrimage. It's uniqueness will please
those wanting something new on the eye and the tummy: the few kinks are
those of a management eager to please.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
The Church Brew Works<BR>
3525 Liberty Avenue<BR>
Pittsburgh, Pa. 15201<BR>
688-8200<BR>
<BR>
Hours: <BR>
Tues. - Sun.: 11:30 a.m. - midnight<BR>
Fri. - Sat.: Pub is open until 1 a.m. but no food is served after midnight<BR>
<BR>
Light Fare: $1.75 - $9.95 <BR>
Dinner Entrees: $12.95 - $16.95<BR>
