<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Small Business Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Diner.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Law.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Small Business Downturns<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>They're Part of the Economic Cycle, not Just Past<BR>
 History; Planning Can Diffuse Their Negative Impact<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Henry Lipput</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>When Pittsburgh's steel mills began closing in the 1980s, the resulting
economic downturn in the region affected many other businesses. At Universal
Welding, a machining and welding repair shop serving heavy industries such
as steel and coal, sales dropped from $3 million to $1 million.<BR>
&quot;Our basic market was the Pittsburgh area,&quot; says Tom Woods, the
company's president. <BR>
 <BR>
In response, Universal Welding created short- and long-term plans to get
the company back on track. They also focused marketing efforts. <BR>
 <BR>
&quot;We went after the mini-mills, selling the same products that we sold
to the integrated mills,&quot; says Woods. &quot;We just stayed focused.&quot;
<BR>
 <BR>
Universal Welding's experience is as timely now as it was 10 years ago.
A recent survey of small businesses found that 30 percent of them expect
the economy to decline this year.  <BR>
Preparing companies for this eventuality is the job of the Pennsylvania
Small Business Development Centers. The federal and state funded program
has offices at universities and colleges throughout Pennsylvania.<BR>
<BR>
Jim Kunkel, of the SBDC's St. Vincent College branch, believes companies
need to plan ahead so as not to be caught in a downturn. <BR>
 <BR>
&quot;What happens all too often is that  small business owners are so involved
with day-to-day operations that they simply don't have the time for formal
business planning,&quot; he says. &quot;But you have to find time. In a
competitive environment like ours, things tend to change pretty rapidly.
 If you don't have a clear vision, a clear focus of where you want to be,
any kind of a downturn can escalate into a major difficulty.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
According to Kunkel, businesses also need to preserve liquidity during a
downturn. &quot;Lenders typically factor the increased risk caused by poor
economic conditions into their decision making,&quot; he says. &quot;If
you don't have a good feel for the pulse of your business and its cash needs,
a source of capital could dry up overnight.&quot; <BR>
 <BR>
Kunkel says that companies must see a problem on the horizon and react quickly,
before it becomes a major stumbling block.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;People tend to get a bunker mentality when the economy's taken a downturn,&quot;
says Ann Dugan, director of the SBDC at the University of Pittsburgh. &quot;They
tend to spend less or to be more frugal with the dollars that they do spend.
I always take a look at the current product offering and say, 'OK, how can
we get to those price points that maybe are a little bit lower than we're
offering now and still be part of the market?' &quot;<BR>
<BR>
During a downturn, Dugan advises, companies should look at every expense:
&quot;I think it's time to really scrutinize your budget and to take a look
at each expenditure and say, 'Is this really necessary?' &quot; One way
is to consider subcontracting out services that are now done in-house. But
Dugan says there are ways to grow business during a downturn.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The easiest thing to do is to sell more to existing customers,&quot;
she says.  &quot;That's the first rule. The second rule is to look for new
customers. What part of the market haven't you been servicing? While a lot
of your competitors have dried up their advertising and marketing support
- and they're in the bunker mentality - there's an opportunity there for
a savvy business person to really take advantage of that kind of market.
And I would highly encourage that the last area that they want to dry up
in is marketing and advertising,&quot; Dugan says. &quot;That's the first
thing that people do in a downturn, and it's the worst strategy they can
have.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Dugan suggests that a company that finds itself in a downturn without having
prepared for it should begin discussing new terms with suppliers and creditors,
&quot;asking [them] to carry you a little bit longer.&quot; <BR>
 <BR>
Dugan also recommends renegotiating terms with the bank early. &quot;When
you're six or seven months into a seven-month streak of bad time, it's not
a good time to ask your bank for a longer amortization of a loan so that
your monthly payment goes down. Banks become more difficult to work with,
and you're in a much weaker negotiating position.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Companies troubleshooting poten-tial problems in this manner can avert disaster
and - just maybe - even benefit from the increased attention and focus.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If you can fight it out, go back to basics and maybe cut some of the
company cars and those kinds of things, you can weather the storm,&quot;
says  Woods. &quot;Certainly you become a better company for it. We appreciate
every order and take care of every customer we can get our hands on. You
learn not to take anybody for granted.&quot;                <BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> 
<ADDRESS>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <A HREF="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments
or suggestions?</A><BR>
&copy; Copyright 1995-2005: Executive Report, Inc.</ADDRESS>
</BODY>
