<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Business Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrTitleBusinessLaw.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Sports.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Veiled Racism </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Employers Who Tolerate it in the Work Place<BR>
Leave Themselves Open for a Lawsuit<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Jim Urban</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>At first glance, phrases like &quot;one of them,&quot; &quot;another
one&quot; and &quot;poor people&quot; don't carry negative connotations.
But from the perspective of Carol Aman and Jeanette Johnson, those phrases
- combined with other offending actions by their fellow employees - amounted
to a collective workplace nightmare.<BR>
<BR>
Aman and Johnson are African-American women who worked for a New Jersey
furniture rental firm. White employees often used the phrases mentioned
above when talking about Aman, Johnson and other black employees. The fellow
employees also falsely accused Aman of favoritism and dereliction of duty
and, on several occasions, physically snatched documents from Aman's hands
and stole time cards that she needed to perform her job.<BR>
 <BR>
Aman and Johnson finally sued Cort Furniture Rental Corp. under federal
Title VII, which requires employers to prevent racist views from affecting
the work environment. The women think the words were evidence of the inherently
racist environment in which they had to work. A federal appeals court agreed
earlier this year, overturning a trial judge's decision to dismiss the case.<BR>
<BR>
The appellate court ruling points out to employers the importance of keeping
racism out of the workplace. Those who don't eradicate racism can have it
turn around and bite them in the form of a lawsuit, as well as         
 low employee morale and lessened productivity.<BR>
<BR>
Most notably, the courts will not tolerate veiled racism, the U.S. Third
Circuit Court of Appeals said in the strongly worded opinion.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Discrimination continues to pollute the social and economic mainstream
of American life, and is often simply masked in more subtle forms,&quot;
Circuit Court Judge Timothy Lewis wrote for the appellate court. &quot;It
has become easier to coat various forms of discrimination with the appearance
of propriety, or to ascribe some other less odious intention to what is
in reality discriminatory behavior. In other words, while discriminatory
conduct persists, violators have learned not to leave the proverbial 'smoking
gun' behind.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;But regardless of the form that discrimination takes, the impermissible
impact remains the same, and the law's prohibition remains unchanged,&quot;
Lewis wrote.<BR>
<BR>
Attorney William L. Doepken of Pittsburgh's Doepken Keevican &amp; Weiss
says the case is unique in that there were no overt racist actions, such
as use of an obvious racial epithet toward the women.<BR>
&quot;But you look at the overall situation,&quot; Doepken says. &quot;When
you add in the overall ambiance of the workplace, it moved it to a different
level. I am not a particularly liberal person, but I agree with this decision.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Attorney James B. Brown of Pittsburgh's Cohen &amp; Grigsby says the decision
comes at a time when the use of &quot;code words&quot; - the court's term
- has become more common among inflammatory radio talk show hosts and some
politicians. Brown says employees hear others use the words and think it
is fine for them to do the same. But in the workplace, it's not OK. It can
be trouble.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The Third Circuit is sending a pretty clear message,&quot; says Brown,
who counsels employers on Title VII matters. &quot;You need to have your
supervisors aware of what's going on in the workplace. It's incumbent upon
the employer to be proactive if the employer suspects that there is a racially
hostile work environment.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The racially hostile environment situation is very similar to hostile work
environment claims stemming from sexual harassment. Once the employer has
reason to suspect a problem, it must investigate and communicate to all
employees that the behavior - whether it be racism or sexual harassment
- will not be tolerated. If the conduct continues, the employer must take
further steps, up to dismissal of the offender.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You can't allow that kind of atmosphere,&quot; Doepken says. &quot;Cort
should have recognized what they had.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
From the victim's perspective, the Third Circuit stated in a 1995 case that
the following proof is necessary to prove a racially hostile work environment
claim:
<UL>
  <LI>The victim must show that he or she suffered intentional discrimination
because of race.
  <LI>The discrimination must have been pervasive and regular.
  <LI>The discrimination must have detrimentally affected the victim.
  <LI>The discrimination would detrimentally affect a reasonable person
of the same race in that position.
  <LI>The offender was an employee or contractor of the employer.
</UL>
Of course, one racist comment does not make a hostile work environment.
The frequency of the discriminatory conduct, its severity, whether it is
physically threatening or humiliating and whether it unreasonably interferes
with an employee's work performance also plays into the mix.<BR>
Ideally, most employers won't reach that point because they took preventive
steps ahead of time. For one, Brown says, employers should be proactive
in fostering a harmonious workplace atmosphere by stressing the strengths
of cultural diversity.<BR>
<BR>
He also recommends that employers identify code words and clearly communicate
that their use is prohibited in the workplace. <BR>
<BR>
Most importantly, enforce the policy and train supervisors to recognize
a racially hostile work environment and eradicate it.<BR>
<BR>
Says Brown: &quot;If people complain about remarks that are made, and the
employer deals with the matter immediately, there will be no problem.&quot;<BR>
<H3>Racially Hostile Workplace</H3>
<UL>
  <LI>Victim suffers intentional discrimination due to race.
  <LI>Discrimination is regular and pervasive.
  <LI>Discrimination affects victim.
  <LI>Such discrimination would affect a reasonable person.
  <LI>Employer is responsible for the offender.
</UL>
