"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Special Agents</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Sports Agents Gain Notoriety During Negotiations,<BR>
But Their Jobs Get Even Tougher<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Bill Modoono</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>They may be the least sympathetic figures in all of sports. Their
names almost never appear in print except during times of crisis: player
holdouts, free-agent bidding wars, superstar defections. No wonder sports
fans see sports agents as agents of gloom.<BR>
<BR>
To the average fan, the nicest thing that can be said about sports agents
is that they are necessary evils. Sports is too big a business to exist
without them.<BR>
<BR>
So it might come as something of a surprise to learn that one local sports
agent considers it part of his role to instruct his clients in how to improve
their speed and how to achieve a sense of fulfillment in ways &quot;other
than the bank account.&quot;<BR>
 <BR>
Or, that a second local agent describes himself as a &quot;central clearinghouse&quot;
for a range of services that include financial planning, media relations
and book publishing. Moreover, he considers it essential not to be &quot;jealous&quot;
of anyone who can perform any of those functions better than he can.<BR>
The overwhelming image of the sports agent is as the hardnosed negotiator,
getting the most for his player, regardless of its impact on the team. And
while no agent will stay in business unless he can perform well for his
client - i.e., get him the best possible deal - contract negotiations are
just part of the agent's overall efforts.<BR>
<BR>
Ralph Cindrich, a sports agent based in Carnegie, says contract negotiating
is &quot;the least intensive thing I do, time-wise.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Cindrich, 46, who ranked sixth in a Sports Illustrated listing of the biggest
National Football League agents, spends more time on legal matters for his
clients, including dealing with a wide range of personal problems off the
field. <BR>
<BR>
This is not surprising, given that, as Cindrich says, his clients are &quot;young
and virile and have active lives outside of football.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
One of Cindrich's clients, quarterback Jeff Blake of Cincinnati, is a rising
star in a glamorous position, which could mean that Cindrich's work on his
behalf will be far removed from the playing field. Blake, who Cindrich terms
&quot;highly marketable,&quot; could earn in excess of six figures in outside
endorsements, which will likely be handled by a national marketing firm.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You have to network and know the parties that can do best for your
client,&quot; says Cindrich. If that means &quot;losing&quot; some control
over part of his endeavors, so be it, says Cindrich. <BR>
<BR>
He sees representing a client as &quot;a team effort&quot; and jealousy
has no part in it.<BR>
<BR>
Cindrich's efforts on behalf of former Pitt star Mark May are a good example
of how the system can work. Cindrich's local ties helped get May a broadcast
job with WTAE-AM. That experience, in turn, put May in line for his current
national network role with TNT. For that, Cindrich had to connect May with
an agency that deals with the major networks. <BR>
<BR>
Gusty Sunseri, 38, an Oakmont-based agent whose clients include Pro Bowl
players Sean Gilbert of the Washington Redskins and Curtis Martin of the
New England Patriots, says he has performed a number of functions for his
clients including babysitting a snake.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You do whatever's necessary,&quot; says Sunseri. &quot;That's very
much a part of the job.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Sunseri also likes to help his clients prepare for the National Football
League draft by connecting them with Buddy Morris, a conditioning coach
at Pitt. Working with Morris improved the 40-yard dash times of both Gilbert
and Martin, Sunseri says, thereby increasing their value to the NFL. <BR>
 <BR>
Though Sunseri does not make investments for his players, he does recommend
financial advisors and considers it his function to &quot;oversee the process.
I get them in touch with the right people.&quot;<BR>
Sunseri's work on behalf of Gilbert included helping him put together a
Christian video featuring a number of NFL stars. He thinks that kind of
thing makes Gilbert a pro athlete who &quot;transcends what athletes are
supposed to be.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Sunseri's idea of his &quot;ultimate purpose&quot; no doubt transcends what
the average sports fan considers to be the function of agents. Sunseri thinks
the most important thing he does is serve as a role model for his clients.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Part of the process is to show them ways to be fulfilled other than
the bank account. I want to be an example for them.&quot;	 <BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
