<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Sports.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H17Education.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size =+2>Classroom Convenience</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+1>If You Can't Make it to the Classroom,<BR>
Schools Will Bring the Classroom to You<BR>
</FONT></I></B><BR>
<I>By Gretchen McKay</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>When Audrey Quinlan decided to return to college last year to pursue
her master's degree in elementary education, the full-time educator had
several objectives.<BR>
<BR>
Not only did the institution need to have a good academic reputation and
affordable tuition - it had to be convenient to both work and home.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I work during the day and didn't want a long drive at night,&quot;
explains Quinlan, a teacher and part-time principal at Queen of Angel Regional
Catholic schools in North Huntingdon.<BR>
<BR>
Her solution? She enrolled in a graduate program at the IUP Monroeville
Center, a satellite campus of Indiana University of Pennsylvania that is
just a 25-minute drive from her home in North Huntingdon.<BR>
<BR>
Quinlan is just one of a growing number of college students in the Pittsburgh
area choosing suburban satellite locations over the college's traditional
main and branch campuses. IUP's Monroeville center, less than a year old,
already enrolls more than 150 students.<BR>
<BR>
Suburban campuses offer many advantages for the adult pupil: smaller class
sizes that allow for greater interaction between students and instructors,
a location close to work or home and more manageable, familiar settings.<BR>
<BR>
IUP, with its main campus in Indiana and branches in Punx-sutawney and Kittanning,
has offered graduate programs at various Pittsburgh locations for over a
decade. But as enrollment climbed over the years, those facilities that
were rented by the hour couldn't meet the needs of IUP's students, says
continuing education dean Edward Nardi.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;The Monroeville center allows us to be there, with our regular staff,
six days a week,&quot; notes Nardi, &quot;with all    the services of our
regular campuses.&quot;  Not to mention ample - and free - parking.<BR>
The disadvantages, maintains Nardi, are negligible, if they exist at all.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;These people are working adults and as such, have different priorities,&quot;
he says, most notably a desire for     convenience.<BR>
<BR>
Tony Nicolazzo, who earned his executive MBA from the IUP satellite last
year and now works for T.D.I. Managed Care Services, agrees.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I knew they were using main-campus professors, so I was assured of
IUP's quality,&quot; he says. As for the more social aspects associated
with college, &quot;I had four years' worth as an undergrad.&quot;<BR>
At the Monroeville center, opened this past January, students can earn a
master's degree in elementary education, adult and community education,
criminology, and industrial and labor relations. There's also the executive
MBA program for working business professionals.<BR>
<BR>
IUP also offers courses at alternative sites on the undergraduate level.
Students in the allied health programs take classes at West Penn and Allegheny
General hospitals. Those seeking Pennsylvania Act 120 instruction (which
sets training standards for municipal policemen) can take police academy
courses at one of IUP's several satellite criminal justice centers, including
ones in Butler and at California University.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, IUP is in its second year of a collaborative program with Community
College of Allegheny County, where students can earn a bachelor's degree
in elementary education with an emphasis in the urban environment at CCAC's
north campus.<BR>
<BR>
IUP, of course, is not alone in offering courses at off-campus sites.<BR>
<BR>
The University of Pittsburgh,too, offers courses at a Monroeville location
 - the Expo Mart - as well as in the South Hills at Mt. Lebanon High School.<BR>
<BR>
Both organized in the early 1970s as a way to enable the adult student to
return to higher education, these locations now serve between 250 and 300
students each year. <BR>
 <BR>
&quot;If you're an older student who has never been to college, sometimes
a large campus can be intimidating,&quot; says Robert Comfort, associate
dean of the College of General Studies at Pitt. &quot;These locations provide
a way for them to start in a smaller, more familiar setting, with smaller
classes.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Comfort concedes the variety of courses offered at the two locations can't
compete with that available at Pitt's main campus in Oakland, and students
must eventually return to one of Pitt's four regional campuses to complete
their degree. But he insists that's not a problem.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Students in a suburban school like this stop in and out, depending
on what's going on in their lives,&quot; Comfort says. &quot;These campuses
were never designed for someone to complete their degree there.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In the North Hills, La Roche College allows students to work toward a B.S.
in management, accounting and computer analysis at the Newport Business
Institute in Lower Burrell. Also new this year is the opportunity to earn
a B.S. in nursing or certification in gerontology at the Meadville Medical
Center and the Horizon Hospital System/Sandy Lake; a B.S. in psychology
is planned for early fall 1997.<BR>
 <BR>
The school started offering those options because, &quot;We find with the
adult learner, distance is a factor,&quot; says Patricia O'Donoghue, La
Roche's vice president for academic affairs. &quot;It's more a matter of
access than anything else.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The college's satellite campuses, she says, are typically established &quot;out
of respect for the multiple demands of adult students' lives.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Alternate locations, in fact, have been part of La Roche's history for the
past 20 years. The school offered courses for servicemen at the federal
building downtown in the late '70s.<BR>
<BR>
Though she concedes some satellite students may not feel a part of     
the larger La Roche community, O'Donoghue argues &quot;adults are too busy
working&quot; to notice or care about the lack of social or cultural diversity.<BR>
<BR>
Point Park College in downtown Pittsburgh recently expanded its accelerated
&quot;Saturday Fast&quot; program to classrooms at Beaver County Com-munity
College and the Cranberry Center of Butler County Community College.<BR>
<BR>
The downtown location isn't convenient for all students, notes Carol Loncar,
dean of enrollment. Bringing the program to sites in Butler and Beaver counties
- both rapidly growing areas - makes the program more accessible and convenient
for a greater number of students.<BR>
<BR>
Students at Robert Morris College work toward their degrees at the main
campus in Moon Township, or opt for its sister campus in downtown Pittsburgh,
where the school originally set up shop in 1921. Nearly every course is
offered at both locations.<BR>
<BR>
And then there's the Community College of Allegheny County, the 18th largest
multi-campus community college in the U.S. It offers over 200 academic programs
at more than 400 sites, including its four main branches and eight off-site
regional campuses as well as at area high schools and technical centers.
                                                 <BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
