<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>HEALTH BEAT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Education.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H15Health.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Feature.1.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>Primary Care<BR>
</FONT></I><FONT size =+1>If You Build It, Will They Come?<BR>
Blue Cross is Finding Out Right Now<BR>
</B></FONT><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>On a humid summer afternoon, the dust swirls off the dirt piles on
a newly developed McKnight Road site, soiling the cars and cloying the air
already hot from the newly laid asphalt parking lot. Inside, however, through
the smooth automatic doors of the freshly built building, it is cool and
blue. High panels of bleached maple reach up into the sunlit atrium. Modern,
mission-style teak furniture welcomes the visitor, still numb from battling
traffic on the overcrowded mall road. There is a reverent, pristine sort
of hush about the place.<BR>
<BR>
Welcome to Blue Cross' new primary care center, McCandless. It houses groups
of primary care physicians and specialists, not to mention a shining new,
fully stocked Thrift Drug store (which even carries coloring books, just
in case you forgot yours).<BR>
 <BR>
There's a health information center, with a classroom outfitted with a kitchen
for nutrition-oriented classes. Though not yet complete, the center will
eventually have on-site laboratory and imaging services, as well as play
host to rotating groups of specialists through a special agreement with
 the University of Pittsburgh Medical Center. <BR>
<BR>
The McCandless site is one of eight primary care centers being built by
Blue Cross - six from scratch and two refurbished sites - as part of a $300
million &quot;retooling&quot; the region's pre-eminent healthcare insurer
is undergoing to compete in a marketplace increasingly dominated by managed
care.<BR>
<BR>
No one much questioned that healthcare, with its skyrocketing costs and
astounding inefficiencies, needed retooling. What is curious, however, is
that Blue Cross' response,  in an industry where overcapacity is the current
curse and efficiency the mission, has been &quot;build.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our premise was that as a health plan we had to interact with the
 healthcare  providers,&quot; says Gus Georgiadis, executive vice president
of primary care delivery systems for Blue Cross of Western Pennsylvania.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;The one-year contract arrangements had to end,&quot; Georgiadis says.
&quot;The entire approach has been to work with physicians and ensure they
have clinical autonomy. We provide all the assets and manage the business
through one office. The concept of a medical mall entity, whereby consumers
have access to one-stop      shopping, is a hot concept across the country.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Others, however, beg to differ.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;One-stop shopping doesn't seem to be what the market is selecting,&quot;
   says Dan Lebish, vice president at HealthAmerica. <BR>
<BR>
He should know. <BR>
 <BR>
HealthAmerica's original HMO product required HealthAmerica subscribers
to choose care from staff physicians in medical centers in Moon, Cranberry,
Wexford, Green Tree, Upper St. Clair, Oakland, Monroeville and Penn Hills.
But in the last five years, HealthAmerica products have increasingly opened
up physician choice, as the company contracts with physicians throughout
the region.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We're losing money on our medical offices - we've invested too much
in fixed assets. We're trying to develop a separate identity for our physician
groups that practice in medical offices, and open them to accept other payors.
In market after market, managed care companies are getting out of that sort
of business,&quot; says Lebish.<BR>
<BR>
The Blue Cross centers are close geographically to HealthAmerica's - Blue
Cross is opening centers in Moon, Wexford, Green Tree, Robinson, Monroeville,
McCandless, West Mifflin and Squirrel Hill - but Blue Cross says it has
a different philosophy.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;What went wrong with Health-America was, one, they employed physicians.
That's not the right course to pursue because their focus is different than
when they continue to run their own practice,&quot; says Georgiadis.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Second, we're working with physicians who already have established
presence in the community, not adding or duplicating existing capacity.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Three, today, medicine is much like a cottage industry where there
is little coordination of care. Just as we know business brings people together
to solve issues, in medicine the by-product will be a high quality of care
and a reduction in the cost of care over time,&quot; says Georgiadis.<BR>
<BR>
The physicians in the Blue Cross Primary Care Centers have sold       their
assets to Blue Cross and are     guaranteed a certain profit in a multiyear
arrangement. <BR>
<BR>
Blue Cross has partnered with 250 physicians throughout the region. Half
are in these asset purchase arrangements, while the other half continue
to own their own practices.<BR>
Some experts see Blue Cross' strategy as short-sighted.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The smart money is not buying assets,&quot; says Paul Mango, a consultant
with McKinsey &amp; Co., &quot;but Blue Cross wants to leverage the hospitals'
behavior, and even controlling 1 to 2 percent change in market share is
big. That's why, if there's 2,500 or 3,000 physicians in the market, Blue
Cross worries about controlling 250.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Blue Cross is setting up a provider network for fear if they didn't
have the primary care physicians they would be cut out of the market entirely,&quot;
agrees Dr. Sean McLinden, executive director of the Health Research Institute
at Duquesne University. &quot;In Crawford County, where there's a strong
medical society and only one medical center and a lot of local employers,
they were able to cut the managed care companies out of business.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Regardless of the underlying intent of Blue Cross' bricks and mortar program,
they will no doubt experience some of the same problems that led not only
HealthAmerica, but larger, national players, to rethink their investments
in bricks and mortar. According to Lebish, there is an inherent conflict
being both payor and provider of healthcare .<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It is a challenge to manage these two types of businesses,&quot; says
Lebish. &quot;Sometimes the goals and objectives don't match 100 percent.&quot;<BR>
