ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Feature.2.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Rivalries</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+><BR>
</FONT SIZE></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Carving up the Regional Healthcare Market<BR>
<BR>
UPMC vs. Allegheny General Hospital<BR>
<BR>
By Lydia Strohl<BR>
<BR>
</B>With the Healthcare Environment Changing at a Lightning-Quick Pace,
Allegheny General Hospital and the Pitt Medical Center are Moving Fast in
an Attempt to Insure Their Strength for Years to Come<BR>
<BR>
Last spring, a young man in his 20s was injured playing touch football near
Sharon, Pa. He was rushed to Sharon Regional Hospital's emergency room,
where it was discovered he had an internal head injury. <BR>
<BR>
In the past, he immediately would have been flown by helicopter to one of
Pittsburgh's large, tertiary care hospitals. Instead, Sharon's ER doctors
transmitted brain scan images via computer directly to the office of Dr.
Julian Bailes, one of Allegheny General Hospital's top neurologists. Bailes
determined that no surgical treatment was necessary, meaning that the patient
could be treated successfully at Sharon.<BR>
<BR>
Over the next two weeks, the physicians talked regularly, sharing information
electronically. The patient convalesced in the community hospital, minimizing
cost to both his health and to the healthcare system.<BR>
<BR>
That's the human side of the hospital affiliations that seem to be in the
news daily. But on the administrative side, there are stories few want to
hear: of consolidation and downsizing.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There are too many physicians, too many hospitals, too many catscanners,
too many administrators,&quot; says Jeffrey Romoff, president of the University
of Pittsburgh Medical Center. <BR>
&quot;Were there too many steelworkers? Of course not. There just weren't
enough steel sales. But, in fact, what you had was an industry that grew
in an expanded economy, then market forces changed, and everything had to
be ratcheted down. That's exactly what happened in healthcare.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
What's odd, though, is that this &quot;ratcheting down&quot; resembles the
video game Pac-Man: a frantic gobbling up of hospitals, physicians and other
health services. UPMC, Allegheny General Hospital, St. Francis Health System,
West Penn Hospital, Mercy, even Blue Cross of Western Pennsyl-vania, are
all scrambling around with their checkbooks out. (For more on Blue Cross,
see HealthBeat, page 81).<BR>
<BR>
The dust has by no means settled, but to date UPMC - with its Tri-State
Health System - and Allegheny General Hospital - aligned with Pyramid Health
- have emerged as very competitive forerunners.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The American capitalistic way is that when there is not enough revenue
to go around, you compete heavily to sell your product in a reduced market.
And in order to do that, you have to spend money on sales forces, on product
development, on research - on all the very things there are too many of,&quot;
says Romoff. &quot;It's a matter of survival.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The specter that all hospitals are trying to survive is managed care, which
controls costs by delivering care in the most appropriate, lowest cost setting.
And that's not the hospital.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In the old days, the hospital bed was the revenue center,&quot; says
Jim Fritz, president of Pyramid Health, an integrated delivery system set
up by five regional hospitals and their physicians. &quot;In our day, it
is a cost center, and we're looking at how to decrease days and consolidate
services.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The hospitals know this well.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;To the extent that we are successful at Pyramid, we will be doing
more things in doctors' offices, in outpatient settings and in the community
hospitals, which are in essence less expensive than a tertiary care hospital,&quot;
says Anthony M. Sanzo, president and CEO of Allegheny General Hospital.
&quot;If we are successful, we will have enough customers that all of our
facilities and our doctors will remain busy and productive. Chuck O'Brien
[of West Penn] or Jeff Romoff or Sister Joanne Marie Pindiorio [of Mercy
Hospital], they'd say the same thing. Unfortunately, we all can't be right,
and still have a 60 percent contraction [of the market], but that's certainly
our attitude.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Is this a change in hospital philosophy, in which the name of the game is
filling beds? Not really. &quot;Many hospitals perceive that this is a game
of musical chairs,&quot; says Martin Gaynor, professor at Carnegie Mellon
University's Heinz School of Public Policy. &quot;They don't want to be
left standing when the music stops. If they have lots of capacity, it's
hard to be left out.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Two Networks To Date</B> <BR>
<BR>
Thus far, UPMC and AGH have been the most public in the race, announcing
the formation of networks, buying up and affiliating with hospitals throughout
the region as well as primary care practices. They're also buying up and/or
marketing the image of existing top-notch researchers and clinicians, to
create an aura of quality and spin off research when possible into for-profit
ventures. They're investing in sophisticated information technology to streamline
operations between providers and, they are hopeful, payors. And they continue
to squeeze as much redundancy out of their own operations as possible. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;UPMC is one of the top 10 academic medical centers in the world, and
how can you preserve academic and clinical commitment in a dramatically
changing economic healthcare climate?&quot; asks Romoff. &quot;For the first
time, the healthcare marketplace has been unleashed to operate with conventional
market forces from which it was insulated in prior years, due to the nature
of reimbursement. Now it's functioning like many large industries function.
There is a history here of aggressive leadership. But I have not invented
the rules of the game.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
When UPMC and its affiliates put seven helicopters into service, Romoff
responded to critics charging him with duplication in an already costly
sector. &quot;If we already have three helicopters at AGH, is this a waste
of resources? In principal yes, if you take the social good model and assess
the needs, there should be one delivery system, rather than two competing
- one with seven, one with three, soon to be armed we've got to take them
out.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
UPMC, with $1.5 billion in assets and a $1.2 billion 1996 operating budget,
includes Presbyterian, Montefiore and Eye and Ear hospitals and Western
Psychiatric Institute and Clinic. These hospitals have 1,220 licensed beds
and 10,000 full-time equivalent positions. UPMC also receives $200 million
in research funding from outside sources. The former Aliquippa Hospital,
now UPMC/Beaver Valley, and the former South Side Hospital, now UPMC/South
Side, add another 408 beds and 1,235 employees.<BR>
<BR>
UPMC also has affiliated with numerous other hospitals through a variety
of agreements and joint ventures (see sidebar). Most recently, UPMC announced
merger agreements with Shadyside, St. Margaret and Washington hospitals,
and Romoff says seven other hospitals are in &quot;merger conversations.&quot;
UPMC also is an exclusive partner with Blue Cross in Medicare HMO Security
Blue, having put up over $12 million in financing for a 20 percent stake.
UPMC's size has some, including Romoff, calling it an &quot;800 pound gorilla.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;With the mergers upcoming, our assets will be in excess of $2 billion,&quot;
says Romoff, who will not state a total budget for UPMC's re-engineering.
&quot;I know there were reports that there is a kitty of $300 million, but
there isn't. UPMC has substantial reserves, but each decision has to justify
itself.&quot;<BR>
Along with the hospital network, UPMC is creating an integrated delivery
system called Tri-State Health System. Tri-State hospitals have 3,599 licensed
beds and 2,501 doctors, 482 of those in primary care. Tri-State has no contracts
with insurers as yet, but hopes to soon.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Eventually, UPMC and Tri-State are going to be synonymous, 25 to 30
hospitals will wind up being involved,&quot; says John Paul, UPMC executive
vice president. &quot;Oakland has to branch out - healthcare services have
to be geographically accessible.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But the 800 pound gorilla has some physicians at affiliation targets - especially
specialists - quaking at the thought of a UPMC takeover. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The physicians here are concerned about competition,&quot; says Dr.
Bruce Block, medical director of family health at Shadyside Hospital. &quot;If
'UPMC's Best Cancer Care' opens a booth in the lobby, then those here will
find it hard to compete. They've heard the UPMC culture has poor morale,
is not a good place for work or for patients. Estimates are that there are
a third to one-half too many doctors. They fear they won't have a livelihood.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Some will leave, like many did when UPMC bought Montefiore - ironically,
many Shadyside physicians are refugees from that situation.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We've seen clear interest from physicians over there,&quot; says Jim
Collins, senior vice president at nearby West Penn Hospital, which at press
time announced its intent to join with Mercy Health System to form an integrated
delivery system. &quot;Some have a wait and see attitude, but a number are
uncomfortable,&quot; Collins says.<BR>
<BR>
Says UPMC's Paul: &quot;We hope that rather than stealing cases we are peripheralizing
and enhancing what is already available in that organization.&quot; But
he and others admit there will be winners and losers.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There's been positive reaction overall as the change they anticipated
did not occur the way they thought,&quot; says UPMC/South Side CEO George
Korbakes, also recently named president of UPMC/Beaver Valley. UPMC/South
Side is currently applying to convert 30 to 35 of 225 licensed beds to sub-acute
nursing beds, given the area's elderly population. Transitioning acute care
beds to less costly categories, like long term care, is how hospitals can
deal with overcapacity. Even that can rankle, however.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;But there has been and is a group that is going to think of the glass
as being half empty instead of half full,&quot; says Korbakes. &quot;Physicians
had those concerns prior to the acquisition, and some still do - but it
hasn't happened.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Perception or reality? Some will win, some will lose. Many have no choice.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We can't survive without affiliating with someone, and we knew that
a year ago, but no one was interested,&quot; says Dr. Richard Collins, an
orthopedic surgeon who is also on the board of Braddock Hospital, where
90 percent of patients are on Medicaid or Medicare. Now, the board is talking
to UPMC and St. Francis Medical Center. &quot;As a physician, I was worried,
but now I don't feel threatened by the merger. [UPMC has] explained why
it's not in their best interest to alienate the physicians, who control
the patients. But you get the sense that if you're not their friend, then
you're their enemy.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Collins notes nearby McKeesport Hospital's affiliation with UPMC. &quot;They
could be a real competitor. So in considering St. Francis we need to know
if they are strong enough to stand up to UPMC and survive. They've both
told us all the right things: They want to provide care to a poor community.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's tough to know what they want. I get the sense they're feeling
like I did as a kid playing monopoly, buying up all I could then figuring
out what to do with it later.&quot;<BR>
Speaking of Monopoly, the state attorney general's office is looking closely
at the consolidating healthcare market.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We're currently looking at the UPMC/Shadyside announcement - prior
to that, there's not been a high enough concentration in an area to raise
competitive concern,&quot; says Carl Hisero of the attorney general's office.
His boss, state Attorney General Tom Corbett, admits, however, they don't
have the staff in place to adequately monitor the fast-changing arena.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The AGH Agenda<BR>
</B><BR>
Across the Allegheny River, administrators at AGH aren't worried about monopolies
- around here, at least. Up until now, their western Pennsylvania strategy
has been one of collaboration, not acquisition. AGH, Sewickley, Allegheny
Valley, St. Clair, Forbes Health System and their medical staffs all have
equal stake in Pyramid Health, a network of 2,326 beds and 1,100 doctors.
<BR>
Independently, AGH has been acquiring a network of primary care physicians
- they have 150 to date, with a target of 350 throughout the region. And
AGH currently has a joint venture with Blue Cross known as Gateway, a 95,000-member
Medicaid HMO. Interestingly, this challenge to Pitt's dominance could have
been avoided.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The leadership of this organization understood that for it to fulfill
its mission the hospital needed to be an affiliate of a major medical school,&quot;
says Sanzo. When approaches to Pitt were rebuffed, they looked elsewhere.
That quest led to Philadelphia, where AGH's parent - Allegheny Health, Education
and Research Foundation - has merged the Medical College of Pennsylvania
and Hahnemann Medical School into Allegheny University of the Health Sciences,
which also includes schools of nursing, public health and health professions.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It sent a message to the academic medical community that we were serious.
That stronger entity enabled Allegheny to recruit far more effectively in
Philadelphia, and we've grown immensely,&quot; says Sanzo. They've wooed
top researchers, including Dr. Suzanne Ildstad from Pitt. <BR>
<BR>
AHERF, a $1.7 billion corporation (AGH is $470 million) owns or manages
a network of 4,000 beds, nearly 26,000 employees and 450 primary care physicians,
including the six hospitals of the Graduate Health System in Philadelphia,
which AHERF has a management contract with as a first step towards future
consolidation. In 1997, AHERF will receive $70 million from outside funders
for research. What started as a mission to reinforce AGH became far more,
including, says Sanzo, an education in managed care. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;All the things we're experiencing here [with managed care], Philadelphia
has gone through. So long before we started to develop a primary care base
in Pittsburgh, we did it in Philadelphia. And we had to develop a network
of hospitals - there we did it differently, we jumped right into mergers.&quot;<BR>
In Pittsburgh, AGH has 755 licensed beds and 3789 employees.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The difference between our approach and what appears to be the Pitt
approach is we're not walking into the community and looking for absolute
control,&quot; says Sanzo. But he does not deny that AHERF will discuss
mergers with hospitals in this region. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We are in discussions with the Forbes system, and it is very likely
we will be in discussions with other organizations as well. We have absolutely
no interest in the acquisition of hospitals,&quot; says Sanzo. &quot;As
we talk to organizations like Forbes we're trying to create a structure
that is least disruptive - the board structure will rely heavily on the
existing board. The medical staff will also remain intact, and to the extent
it can, management will remain intact. What we'd like to do is recognize
that there are operational differences and preserve the best of both worlds.
If we are successful, Forbes will merge into AHERF and be a sister to AGH.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
What that would mean to Pyramid, in which both Forbes and AGH are equal
partners, remains to be seen. Jim Fritz, Pyramid CEO, says in the event
of acquisition, Pyramid stock is returned to the corporation; he is investigating
how that would work. Pyramid has signed risk-sharing contracts with both
HealthAmerica and US Healthcare and is in discussions with Blue Cross. AGH
also wants to put specialists in Blue Cross' primary care centers, which
currently is an arrangement the Blues have with UPMC exclusively.&quot;That's
a risk. That might upset existing providers in the North Hills, and Blue
Cross is smarter than that,&quot;says Sanzo. &quot;We wouldn't go in with
the approach 'You will work with us or we'll put you out of business.' &quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Read Between The Lines- By Cynthia Bent</B><BR>
<BR>
It's a great thing for a city to have two papers,&quot; says Samuel Kennedy,
chairman of the newspaper department at Syracuse University's Newhouse School.
&quot;You have a multiplicity of voices. But it's a thing of the past. You
can count on two hands the number of cities that have two. A lot of people
are probably going to be watching what happens in Pittsburgh.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Kennedy's talking about what already is an escalating rivalry in the region
- a newspaper war between the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette and the Tribune-Review.<BR>
<BR>
The two newspapers target each other in advertising and trade barbs in print.
For instance, any reference in the Post-Gazette to the Tribune-Review is
invariably followed by the words &quot;of Greensburg,&quot; which labels
the Tribune as an outsider despite the fact that it maintains a large operation
at Station Square and smaller offices in Monroeville, the South Hills and
the North Hills.<BR>
The Tribune? It regularly takes the gloves off in its Whispers column, a
political/business gossip column in its Sunday edition. Late last year,
for instance, the Tribune told in Whispers of a Post-Gazette reporter arrested
for indecent exposure in South Park.<BR>
<BR>
In other newspaper markets, the competition enters the advertising side,
too. The recently released book &quot;The Chain Gang&quot; describes how
publishing giant Gannett Co. gives advertisers discounts if they pull their
advertising from Gannett competitors.<BR>
<BR>
Pittsburgh became a one-paper town when The Pittsburgh Press closed following
the drawn out strike by Teamsters delivery drivers in 1992. Since then,
the Post-Gazette - which purchased the Press and closed it - has been top
dog in town.<BR>
<BR>
Sounds like all should have been easy-going for the Post-Gazette. But the
daily is finding a couple of thorns in its side - namely a slow drop (3.2
percent last year) in circulation.<BR>
<BR>
The Tribune currently defies the nationwide trend of dailies losing readership.
Its circulation has jumped 65 percent over the last five years, and continues
to increase at a rate of 10,000 readers annually, most in Allegheny County.
This is in large part because of an infusion of tender loving cash on the
part of its owner, millionaire Richard Mellon Scaife. On Sept. 10, the Tribune
broke ground on a new $43 million ultra-modern full-color production plant
in Marshall Township.<BR>
<BR>
Scaife, a conservative Republican, has always wanted a larger presence in
the Pittsburgh market. But his generous cash offer for the former Press
was rebuffed by owner Scripps-Howard, which sold instead to the Block family,
owners of the liberal Post-Gazette.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;As it became apparent we were not going to be chosen to [purchase
the Press], that is when we decided we would continue to do something in
Pittsburgh,&quot; says Edward Harrell, president of the Tribune-Review Publish-ing
Co. &quot;It was a philosophical decision made by Mr. Scaife because he
has over and over said that any market that doesn't have a choice in their
news source is an impoverished market.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;With two newspapers,&quot; says Syracuse's Kennedy, &quot;you get
two accounts of news events, different views in editorials and columns -
all great for the marketplace of ideas.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Kennedy also believes the presence of competition drives the quality of
journalism up, especially in hard news, the lifeblood of a paper.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It helped at papers where I worked to have someone else going to meetings
and talking to sources, because we knew they were breathing down our necks.
What happens with one paper is that it becomes less aggressive and less
committed to hard news because it's harder to do, takes more time and money,&quot;
Kennedy says.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It certainly was a commitment financially to a growth pattern that
means spending an awful lot of money over the next 10 to 15 years,&quot;
agrees Harrell. &quot;It was certainly not a profit-making decision. Scaife
believed that with the one newspaper operating, particularly the Post-Gazette,
that there wouldn't be a diverse opinion.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In the joint operating agreement [under which the Post-Gazette and
Press formerly published], the PG was the smaller of the two newspapers.
So Pittsburghers had already voted. They just didn't get what they voted
for. Now they're voting for the Tribune-Review.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Post-Gazette doesn't quite see things that way.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We don't think of Pittsburgh as a two-paper town,&quot; says PG vice
president and general manager Robert Higdon. &quot;There are lots of papers
in the area. We're fatigued with people trying to stir something up between
the Post-Gazette and the Tribune-Review, which is, frankly, a Greensburg
paper.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
There's that Greensburg reference again.<BR>
<BR>
Right now, at almost 74,000 daily (130,000 Sundays) the Tribune-Review is
only a third the size of the Post-Gazette, whose circulation hovers around
240,000 (440,000 Sundays). But the TR continues to grow consistently.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In five years we will be a major player in Pittsburgh that cannot
be ignored. We think that in about 10 years, we will exceed the size of
the former Post-Gazette - we expect to be somewhere in the neighborhood
of 150,000 at that point - by continuing to market and improve the paper,
and to offer more local information to Pittsburgh,&quot; says Harrell.<BR>
<BR>
The prevailing opinion from leaders at the Post-Gazette is that 10,000 readers
a year doesn't scare them. Harrell thinks that's a mistake.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Look at the facts. Most major chain stores and retailers believe they
have to have 55 to 60 percent coverage of a market. No matter how you stretch
it, you can only get 42 percent with the Post-Gazette. Most [advertisers]
realize the Post-Gazette is an inadequate buy, and they have to buy something
else in order to get the coverage they need. Buying us puts them up in the
52, 53 percentile range. A couple of years from now, [our circulation] will
be even better, and we'll be a must-buy add-on.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Post-Gazette, laissez-faire attitude or not, isn't standing still. It
is adding full-color capacity by 1997. It added a new food section on Sept.
12. It added two zoned editions - an East Neighborhood page and a separate
North Hills edition - which it says have sold out advertising space. <BR>
Both papers are on the move. Given their different political leanings, the
historical friction and the resources behind each paper, it might not be
long before there's some serious news to report about their relationship.<BR>
<BR>
A little competition never hurt anybody, especially a newspaper.<BR>
<B><BR>
'They Care About Regions' <BR>
<BR>
The Pittsburgh Region Extends Well Beyond Allegheny County;<BR>
Here's Why We Must Rid Southwestern Pennsylvania of Parochial Attitudes
and Market it as One Region With Plenty to Offer<BR>
<BR>
- By Jim Urban</B><BR>
<BR>
Larry Larese once got invited to a breakfast program during which one of
the region's economic development agencies was prepared to unveil its plan
to grow the regional economy. Larese, who heads economic development efforts
in booming Westmore-land County, knew neither he nor any of his staffers
had been included in the host agency's planning process. So why should he
expect Westmoreland County to be included in the final plan? It wasn't.<BR>
Needless to say, Larese blew off the breakfast.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We've had problems with some economic development agencies that think
the region stops at the Allegheny County line,&quot; Larese says. &quot;On
the other hand, there have been those who realize the region extends beyond
Allegheny County.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It's those that think regionally, Larese and others say, who are approaching
the process of economic development the way it should be approached.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Nobody cares about cities or counties anymore. They care about regions,&quot;
says Duquesne University President John E. Murray Jr., who last year headed
the Committee to Prepare Allegheny County for the 21st Century, a blue-chip
panel that studied the way Allegheny County functions. One of the COMPAC
21 panel's suggestions addressed the concept of regionalism: The panel recommended
that Allegheny County develop and promote policies that allow the counties
of southwestern Pennsylvania to work together as a region.<BR>
<BR>
First and foremost - the reasoning goes - let's attract prospects to the
region. Once the prospects are here, then there's nothing wrong with a little
friendly competition between the various counties.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Let's view this from the customer's perspective,&quot; says Michael
Krajovic, executive director of the Fay-Penn Economic Development Council,
a group that works for economic development in Fayette County.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We are here to help the company make the best decision possible. If
that means Fayette County, that's good. If it's Westmoreland or the city
of Pittsburgh, that's good, too.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We kept them in the region.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The first step is getting all the counties to buy into the regional effort.
Unfortunately, the atmosphere at times has been closer to factionalism than
regionalism, and some relationships have been downright bitter. Critics
in outlying counties point out, for example, that the infrastructure needs
in some outlying areas have been given short shrift. And there are gripes
that the point people in regional economic development have at times tried
to push projects into Allegheny County even though a more suitable site
sits in one of the surrounding counties.<BR>
<BR>
The result: outlying counties do their own thing. Westmoreland, for instance,
increased its marketing budget by about 150 percent this year and is aggressively
pushing the county both regionally and nationally. One billboard promoting
Westmoreland County sits on Route 51 just outside of the Liberty Tubes in
Pittsburgh, a location that angered some economic development people in
Allegheny County. <BR>
<BR>
Enter the peacemaker by default: Tim Parks, head of the new Pittsburgh Regional
Alliance. His main job is to promote the region's interests, but first he
must sell the idea of regionalism to the counties that comprise it.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We will grow if we increase the total volume of interest in the region,&quot;
says Parks, former head of the Pittsburgh High Technology Council. &quot;This
is the Pittsburgh region, with as much emphasis on region as there is on
Pittsburgh. We have to develop that. The Pittsburgh Regional Alliance needs
to be a mechanism of genuine agreement between the counties that feel they
are part of this effort. We need genuine participation.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
So far, it appears Parks is making some headway. Larese, in particular,
was impressed by the fact that Parks personally visited him shortly after
Parks assumed his role as head of the regional alliance. That's a sharp
contrast to how Westmoreland has been treated in some past instances.<BR>
&quot;If they can structure a good marketing program, we are certainly willing
to participate,&quot; Larese says. &quot;We have products to market. If
we can get leads through a marketing program, we are willing and able to
participate.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;[Regional marketing] needs to occur,&quot; adds Fay-Penn's Krajovic.
&quot;This is a global economy with regional markets. The world sees Uniontown
and Greensburg as being a part of the Pittsburgh region. Pittsburgh is how
we are seen by the rest of the world.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And Pittsburgh actually gets something in return for the use of its name.
Viewed as a region, Pittsburgh now includes the ski slopes, white-water
rafting and cave-exploring of the Laurel Highlands, a region that - according
to one study - offers more to do than the better-known Poconos to the east.
That's a far cry from the traditional image - still prevalent nationally
- that Pittsburgh is a dirty steel town.<BR>
<BR>
But regionalism doesn't stop with marketing. Murray's COMPAC 21 panel took
it a step further, calling for a nonaggression pact between the various
counties. In other words, counties shouldn't be stealing companies from
each other. The COMPAC 21 panel cited greater Milwaukee, where Milwaukee
County and three neighbors signed a business relocation pact. Under the
pact, any county receiving an inquiry for relocation assistance from a company
located in a neighboring county will inform the county in which the business
is located. In addition, all the counties agree to not aggressively seek
businesses already located within Wisconsin and to abstain from direct mail
marketing, telemarketing or cold call visits to firms within Wisconsin.<BR>
<BR>
Ideally, if one county can't accommodate a growing business within its boundaries,
one of the neighboring counties can. It's already happened here. Westmoreland
lured power conversion equipment manufacturer Robicon from Plum Borough
to a site near Alcoa's Technical Center in Upper Burrell Township. That's
better than having Robicon and its 400 jobs move to Ohio, a state that is
constantly contacting businesses here about relocation. But that's the only
time when businesses should move from one county to a neighboring county.<BR>
<BR>
As Parks says, &quot;Internal shuffling is not healthy.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Another possibility is a regional property tax-base sharing program among
the counties of southwestern Pennsylvania. Murray says a good tax-base sharing
program spreads the wealth throughout the region and pushes development
to the most sensible location. Since all communities share the wealth, they
do not have to compete against each other. One such plan exists in Minneapolis,
although its critics say it is too complex to be implemented. Any movement
here would have to be simple and clear, Murray says.<BR>
<BR>
<B>There's Only So Much Money<BR>
Large Arts Organizations vs. Small Arts Organizations<BR>
<BR>
The Dollars Don't Flow Like They Used to, so the Smaller Arts Organizations
Battle for FinancialSupport; The Ones That Don't Carve Out a Niche Struggle
to Survive<BR>
<BR>
By Jim Urban</B><BR>
<BR>
Jane Alexander, chair of the National Endowment for the Arts, paints a bleak
picture when it comes to her drastically reduced budget. Congress cut the
1996 NEA budget nearly 40 percent - from $162.4 million to $99.5 million.
And don't look for a windfall in the 1997 budget, she adds.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;As a consequence,&quot; says Alex-ander, &quot;we have to reduce our
funding for the arts in every area. We simply will not be able to do it
all, and there will be many arts organizations that will go without and
go under.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In a place like Pittsburgh - where arts have become a critical part of the
region's identity and economy - that's not good news. And it only gets worse.<BR>
<BR>
Despite the wishes of Congress, corporate America probably will not be able
to pick up the slack. While giving to all nonprofits increased 5.8 percent
nationally between 1993 and 1994 - the most recent years for which statistics
are available - there was a steady decline in the proportion of corporate
contributions to the arts, according to the NEA. In 1991, about 12 percent
went to culture. By 1994, that dropped to 9.5 percent. It will likely suffer
more as corporations are also asked to pick up the slack for government
cuts in social services.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In these next few years,&quot; says Alexander, &quot;it's just going
to be tougher to ask the private sector to support every worthwhile societal
cause that suffers from downsizing government.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
So who wins and who loses in the arts community? Should the small and medium-sized
arts organizations fade or die so the larger arts groups can maintain their
level of quality? Absolutely not, say insiders in the arts community. The
smaller groups round out the region's cultural offerings and add diversity
to the mix. They believe that's what makes Pittsburgh's cultural environment
so rich. <BR>
<BR>
So then does quality among the larger groups suffer at the expense of saving
some of the smaller organizations from extinction? No again, since the larger
draws are the &quot;anchor tenants,&quot; so to speak, around which the
smaller groups can gather.<BR>
<BR>
Ideally, both the large and the small must coexist, those in the art community
assert. And in the end, that will mean cooperation instead of competition.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's extremely important that we have a mixed and varied tapestry
in our community,&quot; says Carol Brown, executive director of the Pittsburgh
Cultural Trust. &quot;We need institutions like the City Theater and the
Dance Alloy. We must strike a balance.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The NEA's Alexander agrees. She thinks the proper support system in any
arts community is built like a tripod. One leg is comprised of supportive
legislators, and another is comprised of a supportive business community.
The third is a network of arts organizations that come together to strategize
for mutual survival and growth.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;[This is] where large institutions recognize the need to nurture the
small and emerging groups, where support systems of volunteers and citizens
give freely of their services, and where there is a recognition that if
one group is suffering, the disease may spread to another,&quot; Alexander
says. <BR>
The problem in Pittsburgh is that it's tough for larger groups to nurture
the smaller groups when the larger groups are trying to solve their own
problems, caused mostly by the region's stagnant population base and economy.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You have growing costs, yet your ability to generate additional sales
through contributions and ticket sales appears to be flat,&quot; says Stephen
Libman, executive director of the Pittsburgh Ballet Theater, one of the
big players. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;How do you maintain your artistic excellence through that atmosphere?&quot;
Libman asks. &quot;It's become more difficult each year primarily because
needs always outweigh the financial resources. Some major corporate heavyweights
aren't around anymore. Some that are still here decrease giving locally
because they have organizations all over the world and are spreading their
endowment dollars all over the world.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The smaller groups, meanwhile, try to solve the same problems: growing costs,
flat sales. Only their circumstances, in some cases, are more dire and their
resources greatly diminished.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It is more difficult for smaller organizations to raise funds,&quot;
says the Cultural Trust's Brown. &quot;They have less staff, they have less
people in development - if they have anyone at all.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Some small groups grow into larger groups, some don't make it. I have
great sympathy for the needs of the smaller organizations.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The smaller arts groups that are thriving do so by carving out a niche or
becoming very creative with their approach to potential funders. In today's
philanthropic circles, some funders expect something in return.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You have to become more creative, even if you are creative already,&quot;
says Pauline Cooper, executive director of the Aliquippa Alliance for Unity
and Development, a group that sponsors an annual contemporary art show along
with art education in the small Beaver County community. <BR>
This year's show, which ended in early September, featured about 130 artists,
up from 12 in the show's first year, 1994. Funders for the show and the
education programs include the Heinz Foundation, the Richard King Mellon
Foundation and the Grable Foundation, among other sources.<BR>
&quot;It's very important to have a plan,&quot; Cooper says. &quot;Think
of what you want to do and then balance that with the funder's interest.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Smaller groups also build support around strong boards of directors. And
many now accept grants under the condition that the money will be used for
education or to target specific groups like the elderly or underprivileged
youth. The Pittsburgh Public Theater, for instance, has seen a 450 percent
increase in the number of student tickets sold because of special efforts
it made at the urging of some of its funders.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You have to redouble your efforts and try to create a better and better
case for your existence,&quot; says Stephen Klein, managing director of
the Public, which saw record ticket sales last year, its 21st season.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Whether [arts groups] are large or small,&quot; Klein says, &quot;if
any of these things are diminished it would affect the general atmosphere
for all groups.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;You don't have a great civilization without great arts. You don't
have a great community without arts. That's one of the reasons that Pittsburgh
is considered a great city.&quot;<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
