<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Feature.1.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Supplement1.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+><B>Turning Trash Into Cash<BR>
</B></FONT SIZE><BR>
<I>By Cynthia Bent</I><BR>
<HR><B>A Handful of Companies in the Region Make<BR>
Money Selling Products Made With Recyclables;<BR>
Here's the Problem: Many Find Out That it's<BR>
Difficult to Procure the Recyclables They Need<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>Dateline Namibia, Africa.<BR>
<BR>
Workers in the northern part of the country pick up litter on the roadsides,
collecting over 35,000 empty bottles. The local Ovambo tribespeople, facing
a wood shortage, turn this trash into a windfall.<BR>
 <BR>
Instead of building houses out of wood, they stack the bottles on their
sides, cement them together like bricks, and presto - a wall.<BR>
<BR>
That kind of ingenuity works on this side of the Atlantic, too. Think of
the further uses for recycled newspaper, for instance - animal bedding,
mulch, insulation, more newspapers, packaging, fibers for industrial applications
and more. Recycled plastics can be used for many of the same applications
that virgin plastics can, for comparable prices. All steel produced in the
United States has at least some recycled steel in it, sometimes 100 percent.<BR>
<BR>
Pennsylvania's Act 101 mandates that at least 25 percent of the municipal
waste stream be recycled, and contains other provisions to create infant
markets for recycled materials. There are some in the Pittsburgh area who
think making something out of trash is a golden opportunity - and that western
Pennsylvania could be the place to do it. But products made from recycled
material aren't widely used. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I get calls often from people who want to develop business plans using
recyclables. They see the opportunities out there,&quot; says John Stephen
of the Group for Recycling in Pennsylvania. Stephen says recycling has matured
so much that his group shifted its mission from the traditional message
- pushing people to recycle cans and paper - to creating networks and promoting
entrepreneurial activity. The group tries to create markets for the plastic
bottles and newspapers at the community's disposal, so to speak.<BR>
<BR>
It's only a question of helping them connect with the right resources. In
some cases, the resources aren't that hard to find.<BR>
<BR>
In Pittsburgh, for instance, the Ben Franklin Technology Center awards challenge
grants for research and development to companies interested in profiting
from recycling. Much of the money comes from a state fund committed to growing
the recycling industry. Ben Franklin has given a hand to a number of such
companies, and plans to play a big part in proving that with some patience,
imagination and attention to building networks, the use of recycled materials
as manufacturing sources will be part of our  economic future.<BR>
<BR>
A handful of recycling businesses in the area agree with that statement.
Their products are diverse - from rubber backpacks to plastic lumber   
 to compost - but their problems      and successes are similar. Most  notably,
they have difficulty procuring recyclables.<BR>
 <BR>
In the first of a two-part series, ER looks at the rewards of going recycled
and the aggravations that dog businesses who used recycled waste as raw
material. Next month: how western Pennsylvania might build recycling networks
and profit in the long run.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Early Birds<BR>
</B><BR>
Carla Castagnero is busy proving every day that recycling is a growth industry.
The company she founded, Pittsburgh-based Agrecycle, takes trash that's
seldom considered recyclable - grass cuttings, tree limbs, autumn's leaf
piles and the like - and turns it into black gold - a soil medium or additive,
compost, rich in nutrients.<BR>
<BR>
Compost comes at roughly $20 per cubic yard. Landscapers snatch it up by
the truckload. The governor's office thinks highly of it, too. Agrecycle
was awarded the 1995 Governor's Waste Minimization Award for creating a
sustainable market for a recycled product. It was the smallest company ever
to win.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Sixty percent of the waste stream is organic,&quot; says Castagnero.
&quot;Organic waste is the major source of methane in landfills.&quot; But
she doesn't believe it has to be that way.<BR>
 <BR>
Agrecycle takes in golf course waste, cuttings from landscapers and florists,
and yard waste from municipalities and homeowners - for 60 percent of what
it costs to dump at a landfill. The process of composting then takes months.
During that time a very high-tech monitoring and curing process takes place
as the material is shredded, piled and allowed to reach 150 degrees as it
rots. Oxygen levels are monitored. The material is sprayed and turned over
repeatedly.<BR>
 <BR>
The demand is there from landscapers - both professional and amateur - because
compost changes the soil structure, suppresses diseases, returns water to
the soil, boosts aeration and is a major erosion preventer.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's not like your backyard compost heap - this is a much higher quality,
scientifically controlled process. It's very clean stuff,&quot; says Castagnero.
Compost users are so happy, she says, that Agrecycle has a 100 percent return
buy of compost record - everyone who has ever bought it, comes back. One
customer is the Pittsburgh Zoo, whose steep front hillside received a skin
of compost to anchor the landscaping. Currently, demand outstrips supply.
And expansion is in the works.<BR>
 <BR>
Castagnero says composting is still an infant industry, with lots of room
to grow. Agrecycle is the only composting facility in the western Pennsylvania
area, and if plans work out, will soon be the only one in central Pennsylva-nia,
too. But the composting business isn't all a bed of roses.<BR>
<BR>
Composting is very capital-intensive, with its big earth-moving machinery,
appetite for land and labor requirements. On the upside, composting is a
perfect use for brownfield sites - old industrial land whose pollution levels
make it inhospitable for other uses. Composting's main requirement is large
lots of remilled asphalt.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;People have the perception that leaves have no use,&quot; says Castagnero
of the uphill battle for exposure. &quot;People also don't recognize that
it's illegal to dump yard waste in landfills now, ever since Act 101. And
if you were to put it in the landfill, it's gone forever, and for 40 percent
more money.&quot; It's also illegal in many places to burn yard waste. But
most people don't know that. Getting the word out to get raw material in
is their biggest challenge, she says. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The [Department of Environ-mental Protection] is excited about the
business,&quot; says Castagnero, and the state is willing to lend a hand.
Municipalities soon will be able to qualify for recycling grant money by
participating, to aid in their collection costs. Agrecycle hopes to form
public-private partnerships with municipalities in the next year, to form
one more link in the supply chain they've been building steadily.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Another Entrepreneur<BR>
</B><BR>
Littlearth began in 1993 as a business project in a University of Pittsburgh
entrepreneurship class. Founders Ava DeMarco and Rob Brandegee merged her
design skills with his business acumen to create a line of carry-alls, belts
and accessories made from recycled inner tubes. Littlearth sells a belt,
for instance, equipped with the fastener from an automobile seat belt and
decorated with used bottle caps. The bags that look like leather are actually
made of inner tube rubber.<BR>
<BR>
The pair's first craft show resulted in $25,000 worth of orders, Brandegee's
dropping out of Pitt to  run the business and a rapid move to a Homewood
warehouse. This year, Littlearth is projected to do around     $4 million
in sales.<BR>
<BR>
Littlearth faces the same problem as many businesses that use recycled materials
- it can't find them. The availability of old traffic signs and license
plates that it fastens to carry-all bags is very sporadic, for instance.
They were forced to change to manufacturer substandard tires or &quot;blemishes&quot;
when demand outstripped supply of postconsumer tires from repair shops.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I might call a state's transportation department looking for 20 tons
of old road signs, and the guy'll say, 'Well, we'll have some in a couple
of months, but we're not sure how many,' &quot; says  Brandegee. <BR>
Littlearth also now uses new seatbelts instead of going to the dump and
cutting them out of old cars. It simply became infeasible to recover the
1,000 belts a day they now ship. But everything they sell still has at least
some recycled content, difficult as it is to find. The bottle caps, for
example, are still straight from the bars of Pittsburgh. Last year, Littlearth
recycled over two million bottle caps.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's very important to not only be a socially conscious business,
but a viable business at the same time,&quot; says Brandegee. That takes
a constant commitment to setting up networks, so if one vendor has no plates
one month, there is another to turn to. &quot;It takes work to build up
a network, but it can be done.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's a big issue; it's tempting because it's a lot easier to buy new
materials. But that's not what we're about.&quot; Brandegee emphasizes that
the commitment to recycling is worth the effort because of the cach&eacute;
their reputation has with their customers.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's not about this year; it's not about five years from now; it's
20, 30 years from now.&quot; Brandegee believes ignoring recycling because
it's difficult now is shortsighted, and that if efforts are made to set
up an infrastructure everyone will profit.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think that people are really making an effort to bring it into the
21st century, it's just going to take a while,&quot; says Brandegee.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Fencing in Profits<BR>
</B><BR>
Aeolian Enterprises in Latrobe has the same challenge - to find consistent,
quality sources of material for their product. Aeolian makes plastic lumber
from post-consumer polyethylene - the plastic from, for example, milk jugs,
soda bottles or shampoo.<BR>
 <BR>
The lumber is used for fencing, deck material and other specialized purposes.
It's light, costs out comparably with wood, doesn't have to be painted and
doesn't rot. And it doesn't splinter in the highly worn areas of benches.<BR>
<BR>
Unlike Agrecycle, Aeolian hasn't had much of a problem finding nationwide
markets. Aeolian's sales have doubled or tripled in each of the past five
years. PVC fencing has been standard in the industry for some time, and
     it's not a large leap for buyers to       consider recycled plastic
- if it's a clean, consistent color.<BR>
<BR>
Aeolian's other challenge, on top of finding a clean source, has been to
increase the adaptability of their plastic for other uses by adding to its
tensile strength. They've been innovators in this endeavor, too. Through
research partly sponsored by the Ben Franklin Technology Center, Aeolian
found a way to add used newspaper fibers in various methods to improve the
strength and rigidity of products.<BR>
<BR>
This research is opening the doors to a spate of additional projects, including
using recycled rubber to increase tackiness in the surface of decking, and
filling the hollow centers with a paper-based foaming agent to prevent bacteria
from infiltrating the centers, making the lumber attractive to food service
builders.<BR>
<BR>
Aeolian's first source of plastic was ground-up milk bottles. Problems with
different colors or caps creeping into the mix, however, spurred a search
for a different source. Aeolian now buys repelletized post-consumer plastic
from one of the largest mills in the country.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;When we started, we knew there wasn't much of an infrastructure out
there for recycled materials,&quot;  says president William McClintic. &quot;We
thought one would develop - we thought we'd be a part of creating a demand
for plastics. But still no one local can meet this demand.&quot; It's not
that there aren't enough milk jugs out there, he says, but that there aren't
enough companies processing quality product.<BR>
 <BR>
The plastic industry is subject to wild swings of the market - like    
   the other industries mentioned above, it's a young business, without
much infrastructure. <BR>
<BR>
But, say all three CEOs, it's important to realize that the problem isn't
that there's not enough waste. Given time and attention, all three CEOs
believe the markets for plastic, rubber, newsprint and other recycled materials
will solidify, and the supply should be cheaper than new raw materials.
<BR>
<BR>
Closing the loop, reusing trash instead of burying it makes sense for everyone,
they say. But can the supply ever catch up with the demand? <BR>
<BR>
       <BR>
<B>Next month:</B> Supplying these new businesses is an unfulfilled market
niche, but is currently hampered by the growing pains of the region's curbside
recycling programs.                            <BR>
<BR>
