<A HREF="../zine/1096.Feature.2.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Supplement2.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Long Overdue ... But Finally Taking Off</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1></B><BR>
<B></FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Vince Gagetta</I></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Pittsburgh International Airport Sorely Lacks Air Cargo Facilities,<BR>
But the County is Finally Taking Steps to Remedy the Situation;<BR>
Can We Stave Off Competition from Columbus, Cleveland and Youngstown?</B><BR>
<BR>
Gary Bishop is tired of seeing all those loaded trucks driving past his
airport headed to and from places like Columbus, Ohio. He knows that many
of those trucks are filled with things either made in the Pittsburgh area
and destined for far-off domestic and foreign markets, or made elsewhere
and being shipped here. <BR>
<BR>
And he knows that a lot of those trucks are being loaded and unloaded at
facilities like the old Rickenbacker Airport in Columbus, a former Air National
Guard installation that was converted about five years ago into an air cargo
center. <BR>
<BR>
He also knows that Youngstown, Ohio, much closer to Pittsburgh than Columbus,
is gearing up to turn the Youngstown-Warren Regional Airport into an international
air-cargo center - a project that has caught the eye of President Clinton,
who has recommended that $47 million in federal dollars be spent on the
facility.<BR>
<BR>
It doesn't stop there. Bishop knows that management of Cleveland Hopkins
International Airport has undertaken a five-month long study to help determine
air cargo demand throughout its region and identify opportunities to expand
its air-freight business.<BR>
<BR>
That's why Bishop, who as Allegheny County's aviation director is head of
Pittsburgh International Airport, was so pleased last August when the county
committed to something both the airport and the Pittsburgh area desperately
need: more and better facilities to handle air cargo. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Columbus already is taking a share of Pittsburgh's air cargo market
because it has the facilities to handle [cargo] better than we do,&quot;
Bishop said. &quot;With improved facilities here and increased cargo-handling
capacity, we look to retake that business.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
There is more than a fair amount of business at stake. A study conducted
two years ago showed that Pittsburgh ranks 17th in the country for total
air freight volume, both inbound and outbound. But much more flies into
the area than flies out. The number of shipments flown in earns Pittsburgh
a No. 10 ranking among U.S. cities, whereas the amount of air cargo being
flown out of the airport here puts us way down the list - in 46th place.<BR>
<BR>
It's not that manufacturers and distributors in this market don't use airlines
or freight forwarders to ship their goods. Every year, studies show, more
than $8 billion worth of goods produced or assembled in the area or distributed
by area companies are moved by air freight. But only a small percentage
of it is flown out of Pittsburgh International. The remainder is shipped,
mostly by truck, to better equipped air cargo centers in Columbus and Cleveland.
Some goes even further, to centers in Philadelphia and New York City. Harrisburg
even gets a share of this market's goods.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;A study done in 1993 shows that 80 percent of the international cargo
from this region leaves here on a truck, not inside a plane,&quot; Bishop
says. &quot;Some people around here find that to be a depressing statistic.
I don't. I find it nauseating.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Bishop's personal feelings aside, Pittsburgh International's ability - or,
as it turns out, inability - to handle air cargo is critical to the airport's
future as a vital economic asset.<BR>
<BR>
Air cargo traditionally has gotten little respect in Pittsburgh, and it
shows. A 1994 study for the county by a Denver consultant called air cargo
&quot;a secondary priority to passenger aircraft and passenger air service.&quot;
There are only two buildings at Pittsburgh International used for air cargo.
So it is little wonder that air cargo traffic here has been increasing by
about 3 or 4 percent a year, whereas nationally air cargo traffic has been
growing at between 5 and 7 percent a year - and is headed higher.<BR>
<BR>
Bishop says air cargo growth nationally is forecast to be well into double
digits in the next five years. National airport passenger traffic growth
is anticipated to be much more modest over that period, from the mid- to
low-single digits, he said.<BR>
<BR>
That's why county officials are so eager to become more serious contenders
for airfreight business. To do so, Bishop says, requires not merely upgrading
the airport's cargo handling facilities but &quot;an explosion, because
air cargo capacity has been so severely underdeveloped here. We have a history-making
opportunity to correct a serious situation. It's a real prime expansion
opportunity.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The aviation director was referring, of course, to plans the county commissioners
approved in August to tear down the old Greater Pittsburgh Airport terminal
and develop the 178-acre site as a business center. Plans for the proposed
Airside Business Park include air cargo buildings and facilities and a fixed
base facility for corporate jets, air charters and other general aircraft
usages. Also planned for the site are buildings for offices, light manufacturing
and warehouses.<BR>
<BR>
Both Bishop and Allegheny County Economic Development Director Allan Wampler
pressed the county commissioners hard for the project. Wampler has been
especially vocal about razing the abandoned terminal, once the pride of
Pittsburgh, that had been allowed to deteriorate into an embarrassing eyesore.<BR>
<BR>
Wampler and others realize that the terminal is not suited to several of
the uses suggested for it: air museum, shopping mall, office building. The
building was in such poor condition - the roof leaked, its windows were
broken, and scavengers had stripped it of anything and everything of slightest
value - to be structurally worthless. The land the terminal sat on and that
surrounded it had become more valuable than the building itself. As far
as Wampler was concerned, tearing down the terminal and turning the site
from an economic liability into a valuable asset was one of his and his
department's top priorities. And he told that to anyone who would listen.<BR>
<BR>
Gary Bishop was more than just a casual listener to Wampler's message. Bishop
pointed out that there was at least one thing about the site that suggested,
even dictated, its eventual conversion into something closely related to
air travel and air freight: 70 acres of reinforced concrete ramps between
18 and 36 inches thick and strong enough to support the weight of airplanes.<BR>
<BR>
Wampler agrees. &quot;The more you walked around the site, the more you
could see that it's not an office building, a shopping mall or a warehouse,
it's an airport,&quot; he says.<BR>
<BR>
And so it shall remain, which is good news to Pittsburgh area companies
that long have complained about Pitts-burgh International's relatively meager
capabilities for handling air cargo, particularly outbound shipments. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The question for our members never has been shall we enhance the airport's
ability to handle air cargo, but how can we do it,&quot; says Joseph Dornbrock,
executive director of the Airport Area Chamber of Commerce. &quot;The expansion
certainly will benefit many of our member companies, but it has regional
ramifications. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Economic development must continue to be a priority for this region
so we can enhance regional competitiveness. Improving the region's air cargo
capabilities is only one facet of the effort to enhance regional competitiveness,
but it is a vitally important one.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Expanding and improving Pittsburgh International's air cargo-handling capabilities
will improve the airport's bottom line, enhance regional competitiveness
and assist economic development efforts. The announcement of plans for the
Airside Business Park certainly was greeted with enthusiasm by the Pittsburgh
business community.<BR>
<BR>
But just expanding and improving facilities is no guarantee that those businesses
which now take their goods to, say, Columbus or Cleveland for air shipment
will suddenly switch that business to Pittsburgh International. Other serious
problems besides capacity impact the airport's attraction as a cargo-handling
facility. One such problem is highway access.<BR>
<BR>
A spokesman for Sony, which manufactures big-screen television sets near
New Stanton, said that once the need for additional air cargo capacity at
Pittsburgh International is clearly demonstrated, &quot;the county has to
start planning to develop the infrastructure that will make access to the
airport more convenient.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
That observation was repeated often by area company officials who say getting
to the airport is no fun at all. And it is not a condition that will change
just because the Airside Business Park becomes operational, they add. So,
many of those trucks that Gary Bishop hates to see driving by his airport
may well continue to do so - unless highway access improves. <BR>
<BR>
The aviation director points out that the opening of the so-called Airport
Parkway has caused a dramatic drop in traffic on Business Route 60, which
was the main road to the old airport and the one that will serve the Airside
Business Park. That will give traffic headed to the park an easier shot,
he said.<BR>
<BR>
But just getting to Business Route 60 is itself a challenge for many companies.
The most direct route for companies located in the northeastern and southeastern
suburbs is through or close to downtown via the Parkway East or Route 28.<BR>
<BR>
And companies north of town along the Interstate 79 corridor, the area of
most dynamic business development and growth recently, have a particular
problem getting there. I-79 traffic bound for the airport from those northern
suburbs has no direct access to the most direct airport area route: the
Parkway West. And traffic leaving the airport area traveling the Parkway
West cannot get on to I-79 North where the interstate intersects the Parkway.
All traffic north of the intersection must travel between I-79 and the Parkway
via mostly narrow, winding and congested Route 60, the Steubenville Pike.<BR>
<BR>
That makes no sense, Gary Bishop agrees, but it is a cruel fact of life
that has existed for years. And it is a fact that the Allegheny County commissioners
finally are planning to confront. Bishop said the commissioners are petitioning
the state to construct a &quot;normal&quot; interchange where I-79 passes
over the Parkway to allow access for all that traffic to and from the north.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is critical,&quot; Bishop says. &quot;The area served by I-79
from that intersection north to Erie carries enough traffic to justify making
the change. And from the airport's perspective, there is so much actual
and potential air cargo business in that area that we would certainly welcome
whatever can be done to get that business to us more quickly and more conveniently.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
If the change is not made soon, companies in the I-79 corridor might find
it easier to switch than fight the traffic. This would be especially true
if the conversion of Youngstown-Warren Regional Airport into an international
air cargo center proceeds as planned. Access to the Youngstown area for
those companies via the Pennsylvania Turnpike is relatively painless and
will become more so when the roadway's Route 19 interchange in Cranberry
is reconfigured to provide a direct link to I-79.<BR>
<BR>
It will take several years before all the new cargo-handling facilities
and improvements envisioned for Pittsburgh International can become fully
operational. That will give the Columbus airport more opportunities to attract
- some say &quot;steal&quot; - air freight business from Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
It also will give the Youngstown facility a leg up on Pittsburgh because
planning there appears to be further along. The Federal Aviation Administration
already has awarded a $590,000 grant to the Youngstown airport to study
lengthening its runway to accommodate major airline cargo operations, according
to published reports. That grant enabled the airport to begin other studies,
scheduled to be completed this month, that are the final steps before federal
construction money can be applied for.<BR>
<BR>
The Youngstown airport's location near the Ohio-Pennsylvania border makes
it an attractive alternative to Pittsburgh International for companies north
of Pittsburgh that ship and receive goods by air. The commissioners and
economic development officials of several Pennsylvania counties near Youngstown
are supporting efforts to complete the international air cargo center in
Youngstown.<BR>
<BR>
And recently, it has been reported, three business leaders from northwestern
Pennsylvania have taken seats on the committee planning Youngstown's airport
expansion. <BR>
<BR>
Building this capability in Pittsburgh will take years - if area leaders
can pull together to do it at all. Until then, those trucks will just keep
driving by.<BR>
<P><CENTER><B>Cleveland Backs Off Air Cargo; Youngstown Becomes Aggressive</B></CENTER>
<P>It looks like Pittsburgh International Airport will have some competition
as it beefs up its air-cargo handling capabilities.<BR>
<BR>
Economic development leaders in eastern Ohio are pushing for an air-cargo
center of their own at Youngstown-Warren Regional Airport, only a few miles
over the Pennsylvania line. That's about a one-hour ride from Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
Supporters of the Youngstown project include the Federal Aviation Administration
and President Clinton, who gave the proposal a big boost in July when he
recommended that $47 million in federal funds go toward the establishment
of a cargo airpark. The money will be spent on land acquisition, runway
extension and other aviation improvements.<BR>
  <BR>
The Clinton administration is requesting the money in the next budget.<BR>
<BR>
A few months prior to Clinton's commitment, the FAA awarded a $590,000 grant
to the Youngstown airport to conduct studies on lengthening the runway to
accommodate major airline-cargo operations. Those studies are currently
underway.<BR>
<BR>
Getting a larger share of air cargo means   more revenue for an airport.
Air cargo operators pay landing fees but don't require expensive passenger
terminals. That's why Ohio officials feel the medium-sized Youngstown facility
is a good fit.  And it sure doesn't hurt that it will also be smack in the
middle of the economically ravaged Youngstown area, hit hard by the collapse
of the steel industry.<BR>
<BR>
Most of the major airport cargo hubs are    established in the Midwest.
The region is ideal     for cargo carriers because it is about equidistant
from Europe and the Far East and is within 500 miles of half of the nation's
population and      industrial activity. <BR>
 <BR>
Already, Lufthansa, a German airline with   other U.S. hubs, has expressed
interest in locating  a Midwest cargo hub in Youngstown, officials   there
say.<BR>
  <BR>
Facilities that locate in the airpark will be under a foreign trade zone.
With that designation, products stored there and equipment used to manufacture
goods there would not be taxed.  <BR>
Further north, there are indications that Cleveland Hopkins International
Airport won't jump into the cargo business. Right now, Hopkins handles a
minimal amount of cargo.<BR>
<BR>
For one, Hopkins' longest runway is 8,999 feet, too short for a loaded Boeing
747 - the aircraft of choice for long-range air cargo delivery - to safely
take off or land. Ohio officials also want to push the cargo business into
the Youngstown facility. <BR>
 <BR>
Before deregulation of the airline industry in 1978, cargo was primarily
flown by the major passenger airlines. After deregulation, cargo-only airlines
emerged and grew; they now ship about half of the nation's air cargo. <BR>
