"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Technology Takes Over at Law Firms </FONT></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Law Firms Looking for an Edge Have Invested in Technology That
Makes ThemMore Time-Efficient and Cost-Effective; It Also Helps Generate
New Business<BR>
<BR>
By Chris Swaney<BR>
</B><HR>Gone are the dark hallways littered with boxes of legal documents.
Gone too are the closed office doors, where lawyers huddled to escape the
clacking of secretaries typing. The new space is brighter and more open.
All documents are carefully coded and stored in a central depository. Computer
terminals have replaced yellow pads for many lawyers, and secretarial clusters
are spread out, so noise is less of a problem.<BR>
<BR>
Like the corporate clients they represent, major law firms are discovering
they must keep pace with the technological advances changing the face of
American business.<BR>
<BR>
Although, perhaps three-quarters of the nation's law firms use computers
for word-processing, Jones Day Reavis &amp; Pogue goes well beyond that.
One data base, for example, stores profiles and specialties of its lawyers
worldwide, so a Jones Day lawyer can call on lawyers in any of the huge
firm's U.S. and foreign branches for help.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The big issue about technology is how we make use of it to improve
productivity,'' said Irvin A. Leonard, a Jones Day lawyer specializing in
sports.<BR>
<BR>
At Jones Day, there's also a mock courtroom with video cameras that can
shoot three angles and play back on a split screen. The technology enables
lawyers to rehearse before heading into a real courtroom.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, there's a computerized guide to tell a lawyer, for example,
what motions to file in a particular situation.<BR>
<BR>
And the firm keeps computerized testimony and other data about expert witnesses.
All of this helps reduce research time and allows lawyers to assess quickly
the strength of expert witnesses. <BR>
With the expanded computer capability, Leonard says the firm also offers
other cost savings to clients with their in-house legal staffs. <BR>
<BR>
For instance, Jones Day and many of its major clients can tap into each
other's data bases by phone lines, eliminating duplication and research.<BR>
 <BR>
But because most law firms can't afford to go out and buy each new generation
of new technology, some Pittsburgh firms are looking at how to hook up with
information technology networks. <BR>
&quot;The networked firm can do business anywhere, anytime,'' says Lewis
Davis Jr., a Buchanan Ingersoll lawyer specializing in corporate finance.
&quot;We close deals across the country with our computer system.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Increasingly, law firms are using wide-area networks to engage in electronic
commerce with customers. The Internet, a worldwide network of computers
linked by phone lines, has emerged as a means for low-cost business networking.
And law firms also are seeing a flurry of activity on the Net's World Wide
Web, an engaging way to post information and electronic advertising that
reaches a potential     25 million &quot;Internauts.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
At the heart of every network is an acre of coding that is software - the
stuff that makes the bytes run on time. As law firm computing evolves from
the mainframe/centric to the client/ server model, the software running
it has to become an extremely clever jack-of-all-trades, operating on ma-
chines from a variety of vendors and processing everything from huge data
files to optically scanned images to video presentations.<BR>
<BR>
And while some Pittsburgh lawyers still feel they are Web crawling rather
than Web surfing, the transition to computers for tasks beyond word-processing
has been smooth.<BR>
Carole Katz, a Reed Smith Shaw &amp; McClay attorney, says her conversion
to computers has made the job more flexible.  Katz, who specializes in labor
and employment issues, has three sons ranging in age from 2 to 9. &quot;I'm
not a techie, but it's helpful to be able to check my e-mail from home.''<BR>
A recent study by the American Bar Association says computer         technology
alone will help trim   administrative time on cases by 10 percent to 20
percent.<BR>
<BR>
Dave Christopher of Reed Smith says the firm has spent $5 million to  $7
million to upgrade its computer banks. &quot;Our goal is to have a PC on
    all desk tops by the end of the year,'' says Christopher. The law firm
employs 900.<BR>
<BR>
A stone's throw away at Meyer Unkovic and Scott, Dennis Unkovic says his
firm is preparing to beef up its computer status. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;This very significant financial commitment for the purchase of the
best technology available will enable us to provide the quality of service
our clients expect in the next century,'' Unkovic says. <BR>
Unkovic and other Pittsburgh lawyers are betting that high-tech offices
will enhance efficiency and help lure top law school graduates to the city's
firms.<BR>
<BR>
Traditionally, Pittsburgh has been a tough sell to new recruits, especially
in competing against New York or Los Angeles, according to a survey by the
Justice Research and Statistics Association in Washington, D.C. <BR>
<BR>
The same survey also reported that about 10 percent of Pittsburgh lawyers
still do not feel comfortable using a word processor.<BR>
<BR>
David Armstrong, 65, is one of them. Armstrong, a managing partner at Dickie
McCamey &amp; Chilcote, says he is old enough to slide by. &quot;I still
use the Dictaphone and legal pad.'' <BR>
<BR>
Armstrong reminds us that there is nobody more filled with anxiety than
a lawyer who has been told that he should start writing with a word processor.
He keeps putting it off or uses it as a giant desk paperweight. <BR>
<BR>
But Armstrong also is quick to point out that there's nobody more evangelistic
than a lawyer who has made the leap. Like all evangelists, he has been given
the good news, which is that a personal computer can store hundreds of common
paragraphs used in wills and other legal documents that can be called up
on a monitor as needed when drafting a fresh document. Previously, most
lawyers clipped and pasted together pieces of old documents, then made additions
in longhand. The draft would then be sent to the word-processing department
and ultimately edited. In the meantime, most lawyers say they had lost their
initial thought.<BR>
<BR>
So, most Pittsburgh lawyers still believe they have found a high-tech guardian
angel in the personal computer. <BR>
<BR>
And no matter how much they must tweak the new computer navi- gator, nobody
wants to revive the   typewriter. <BR>
<P><CENTER><B>Adding Technology: Should a Firm Move Quickly or Proceed With
Caution?   </B></CENTER>
<P>For millions of PC owners, there is only one network that really matters,
and that's the Internet. The vast collection of interconnected computers
is the fastest growing network around: More than 25 million business professionals
will have access to the Internet by the end of the year. Dennis Unkovic
will soon be one of them.<BR>
<BR>
Unkovic's firm, Meyer Unkovic and Scott, will plunge into cyberspace by
Nov. 1. &quot;We're not just dipping our big toe into it, we're diving right
in head first,'' says Unkovic. <BR>
<BR>
A handful of other Pittsburgh firms have been on the Internet for a while,
using it to service clients and market the firm. From Cohen &amp; Grigsby's
home page, for example, browsers can read firm bios or pull off articles
written by firm attorneys on a variety of legal topics. Firm attorneys also
utilize e-mail to communicate with clients.<BR>
<BR>
Another Pittsburgh firm &shyp; Kirkpatrick &amp; Lockhart &shyp; used technology
to sharpen a client's case in recent environmental litigation. One courtroom
presentation included an animated fly-over of the site that was the subject
of the litigation. In the same trial, Kirkpatrick &amp; Lockhart attorneys
stored about 1.5 million documents on computer CDs.<BR>
<BR>
Firms that harness technology can use it as a selling point, says Kirkpatrick
&amp; Lockhart partner David Cohen, the firm's technology guru. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;When you go into a potential client, you can concretely show them
you will save them money and deliver better service to them,&quot; Cohen
says. &quot;It really gives you a leg up on the competition.<BR>
&quot;One of our goals is to remain on the same systems as our clients because
we are increasingly working with them on a collaborative basis. We very
often exchange documents. A lot of faxes or phone calls have been replaced
by e-mails,&quot; Cohen says.<BR>
<BR>
Often for law firms, the first step toward harnessing technology involves
replacing the existing computer system. That's where Meyer Unkovic and Scott
started.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We decided to dump our primary barrister system and install a network
for our 100 employees,'' says Patty Hess, office manager at Meyer Unkovic
and Scott.<BR>
<BR>
Hess says the conversion involves going totally with PCs. For Unkovic, the
best thing about this high-tech conversion is that it's the first step to
electronic commerce, which means carrying out all sorts of transactions
between companies and consumers across the network. <BR>
<BR>
Keeping up with the flood of information has made it imperative for most
law firms to embrace information technology, according to Stephen Franco
of the Yankee Group.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We just felt it was time to make a change,'' says Unkovic. &quot;We
also were getting requests from clients who wanted to contact us via e-mail.''<BR>
<BR>
In addition to a new computer system, Hess says the law firm also will have
a bank of laptops available for lawyers who do a lot of traveling. During
the summer, for example, Unkovic was in Japan helping Pittsburgh Mayor Tom
Murphy drum up export business for the region.  &quot;The laptop gives you
the ability to take your work and resources right with you,'' Unkovic says.<BR>
 <BR>
Ken Judson, a partner at Meyer Unkovic and Scott, says computers allow for
real time communication.<BR>
 <BR>
The new virtual law firm also gives lawyers the luxury of computerized testimony
and other data about expert witnesses. All of this helps reduce research
time and allows lawyers to assess quickly the strengths of expert witnesses.<BR>
 <BR>
For instance, Jones Day Reavis &amp; Pogue has combined two computerized
systems to allow lawyers to call up on their computer screens not only the
status of a case but also such details as which lawyers and paralegals worked
on the case and how much the firm has spent in research and expenses. Lawyers
used to get 70 cents out of every dollar earned, but now get about 40 cents
out of a dollar, after inflation is factored in, according to the U.S. Department
of Labor's report on white collar workers.<BR>
<BR>
Still, there are some skeptics out there. Some industry watchers say law
firms have moved too quickly to embrace this new technology and then have
problems keeping up. <BR>
The best Web sites offer key information about a firm, such as where and
how the services can be used.<BR>
<BR>
Small law firms have several choices for networks. Depending on the applications,
users should think about using the following systems to troubleshoot problems
on networks. The most popular programs are Windows for Workgroups, Novell
Netware, Windows 95 or Windows NT. <BR>
<P><CENTER><B>Caught in the Net: For Many Firms, It's a Multidimensional
Marketing Tool</B></CENTER>
<P>The web site for Pittsburgh law firm Tucker Erensberg opens with the
basics: the firm's address, telephone and e-mail address, with links to
attorney bios and information about the law firm's four offices. Interested
prospects can e-mail the firm with the click of a button.<BR>
<BR>
Another Pittsburgh firm - Reed Smith Shaw &amp; McClay - dressed its web
site up a bit, incorporating the firm logo and providing a link to a welcome
message from the managing partner. There's also links to Reed Smith's firm
publications.<BR>
<BR>
These are just two of a handful of Pittsburgh law firms that are using the
Internet for a variety of practical purposes. The firms on the cutting edge
use the Internet to communicate within the office and with clients, to conduct
legal and nonlegal research and to locate experts in sometimes obscure fields.<BR>
<BR>
In the end, the client spends less in legal fees because of the firm's computer
efficiency.  <BR>
As for home pages, they have unique marketing uses of their own. For instance,
one Boston firm has a button on its page that - when pressed - sends a firm
brochure via e-mail to the prospect. Other firms are posting forms that
enable them to collect data from potential prospects.<BR>
<BR>
Here's some other home page uses:
<UL>
  <LI>Promote the firm's speakers bureau
  <LI>Promote the firm's e-mail mailing list
  <LI>Provide links to clients' home pages
  <LI>Spotlight favorable news coverage of the firm
</UL>
<BR>
Some firms are also using the web sites to recruit prospective attorneys.
Here are some Pittsburgh <BR>
firms and their web addresses:
<UL>
  <LI>Aderson Frank &amp; Steiner: http://www.adersonfrankandsteiner.com
  <LI>Buchanan Ingersoll: http://www.bipc.com
  <LI>Cohen &amp; Grigsby: http//www.cohenlaw.com
  <LI>Doepken Keevican &amp; Weiss: 	http://www.dkwlaw.com 
  <LI>Houston Harbaugh: http://hhpc@nauticom.net
  <LI>Kirkpatrick &amp; Lockhart: http://www.kl.com
  <LI>Reed Smith Shaw &amp; McClay: http://www.rssm.com
  <LI>Thorpe Reed &amp; Armstrong: http://trinfo@pgn.net               
                       
</UL>
