<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Supplement2.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Supplement4.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Walking and Talking Like Banks<BR>
</FONT>
By Rebecca Fenoglietta</B></CENTER>
<P><HR><BR>
<B>Credit Unions of Today Offer a Variety of Services<BR>
To Aggressively Court Consumers; But a Recent Court<BR>
Decision May Throw a Bone Into Some Credit Unions' Growth Plans</B><BR>
<BR>
When Frank Schwertz first joined his company's credit union, it was a simple
place to collect interest on the savings from his paycheck. More than 30
years later, Schwertz has his choice of credit union services: mortgages,
pre-approved credit lines, debit cards, financial advisors and more.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;I started to work for Mohawk Airlines in 1964,&quot; says Schwertz,
a USAir inspector. &quot;Back then, we were given a credit union application
along with our other orientation information. The credit union was extended
as a courtesy, part of the new employee package. I joined because it was
a simple way of automatically putting away savings.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Today, Schwertz takes advantage of the majority of the services offered
by the USAir Federal Credit Union. In fact, he does the vast majority of
his &quot;banking&quot; through the credit union, not a bank. <BR>
&quot;I like the familiarity,&quot; he says. &quot;With a bank you may know
one or two of the tellers, but the credit union is run by your coworkers.
It's all employees, working together. You feel more comfortable when you
know the members have the same stake you do.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
One thing's for sure: Today's credit unions are not your father's institutions.
They are likely to offer more and more services previously available only
at banks, and some accumulate assets well into the millions. While many,
especially credit union members, applaud these changes, credit unions also
have their share of critics.<BR>
 <BR>
These critics point out that while credit unions are experiencing substantial
growth, they continue to be treated as nonprofits, enjoying exemption from
federal taxes, as well as from the Community Reinvestment Act that requires
banks to put money back into the communities they serve. <BR>
The critics also question whether expanding a union's common bond - the
requirement that members have some connection to each other - makes credit
unions even less deserving of nonprofit tax exemptions.<BR>
<BR>
If it walks like a bank, talks like a bank, it should be treated as a bank,
goes the argument. But the credit unions are quick to point out: credit
unions aren't banks. And that distinction gives them an advantage with some
consumers.<BR>
<BR>
A recent study by the American Bankers' Association found that banks have
an image problem. Less than half of the respondents, 44 percent, strongly
agreed that banking is an honorable profession. A mere 29 percent strongly
agreed that banks are flexible in meeting your financial needs, and only
31 percent strongly agreed that bankers care about their communities.<BR>
<BR>
Molly Hevia, vice president of marketing for USAir Federal Credit Union,
says that trust and familiarity are exactly what makes a credit union different
from a bank.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Credit union members have more control than do bank customers,&quot;
she says. &quot;Members elect their board, who are co-employees. Employees
see their board members every day, and can talk with them. The board member
can then take an employee's concern right back to the board. That doesn't
happen at the bank.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
A credit union is different because it is truly &quot;democracy in action,&quot;
 Hevia says. Members are owners who each have an equal vote in board and
committee elections. There are no stockholders looking for profits. All
members are the beneficiaries who profit equally. At USAir, the union is
governed by a voluntary board of directors made up of USAir employees. A
five-member supervisory committee also is volunteer. They regularly audit
teller lines, cash flow and loans.<BR>
<BR>
Because of that difference, credit unions should retain their tax-exempt
status as well as community investment exemptions, she says. Currently,
federally chartered credit unions pay only real and personal property taxes.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Congress passed [the Com-munity Reinvestment Act] in 1977 because
banks were ignoring the needs of their communities,&quot; she says. &quot;It's
not a problem with credit unions because the needs of the community have
always been the first priority. We've always complied.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And while the USAir credit union serves 77,000 members throughout the country,
and has $397 million in assets, Hevia says that the basic mission remains
unchanged.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Credit unions don't stop behaving like cooperatives when they grow
in size. We are still nonprofit no matter what our assets are. Our members
still have equal votes. We still are run by volunteers. Our members are
the owners. In return, they get lower loan rates and higher savings rates.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>More Regulation?<BR>
</B><BR>
University of Pittsburgh law professor Edward Symons, who specializes in
banking law, is skeptical of allowing nonprofit status for large credit
unions.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;When a credit union's motivation is relationship-driven, it's distinct
from a customer-based institution. But when [a large credit union] becomes
client-based in its relationship, the focus changes from being interested
in a common group with a single, common tie, such as employees.<BR>
&quot;Similar institutions should be treated similarly. All financial institutions
should be taxed the same unless there's a clear and convincing policy reason
for different taxation and regulation,&quot; Symons says.<BR>
<BR>
Regionally, banking officials are reluctant to enter the debate. <BR>
<BR>
Jonathan Williams, PNC Bank spokesperson, says that his bank's only issue
regarding credit unions is their tax-exempt status. &quot;We've always had
good relations with credit unions, and we've even worked to create credit
unions in some communities,&quot; he says.<BR>
<BR>
Matthew Giles, senior vice president at Mellon Bank, chooses instead to
focus on what banks can provide above and beyond credit unions. He points
to Mellon's new financial centers where customers can get all normal branch
services, including opening new accounts and getting loans, plus video bankers
- an opportunity to talk to experts like investment counselors via two-way
video.<BR>
Giles says Mellon has identified several customer concerns. &quot;We've
found that customers want convenience, service, information and choices.
[Mellon addressed that with] extended hours, our  supermarket bank offices
at Giant Eagle and our customer        service area in our branches, where
customers can do many non-cash transactions.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Giles also identifies personal computer banking and its new online services
as things that give Mellon the edge over any credit union.<BR>
<BR>
With assets totaling $43 billion, Giles says Mellon is not overly  concerned
with credit unions eating too much of a market share. &quot;We look at all
of the competition. There's   a whole host now. Every bank and  non-bank
is looking at how to service customers.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There are differences no matter how large a credit union becomes.
No credit union offers the same kind of convenience and services that we
do.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Growth Unions<BR>
</B><BR>
One way that a credit union becomes larger is by expanding its common bond.
In other words, it opens up its membership to those outside the immediate
company or group, depending on the type of credit union. Lately, credit
unions have been taking heat for such expansions. This summer, a federal
appeals court in Washington held that the Federal Credit Union Act's language
limiting memberships to groups with a common bond of occupation or well-defined
geographical area disallowed AT&amp;T Family Federal Credit Union from extending
membership to various unaffiliated, small businesses in North Carolina and
Virginia. The American Bankers Association and several North Carolina banks
had sued the National Credit Union Association, or NCUA, the credit union's
regulating body, for allowing AT&amp;T to offer credit union membership
to these additional businesses.<BR>
<BR>
In agreeing with the bankers, the court concluded that all members of a
federal credit union must share a common bond. Multiple occupational groups
(often called select employee groups) within a single credit union do not
share that common bond.<BR>
<BR>
     Symons, the Pitt law professor, agrees with the AT&amp;T decision but
says it is a narrow decision. Nevertheless, he says that the effect of the
decision could call into question a variety of credit union charters whose
membership includes multiple common bonds.<BR>
<BR>
Not necessarily, say others. According to Hevia, USAir Federal Credit Union
received an advisement from the NCUA concerning this case, warning that
additional groups added to that credit union may have to be divested. USAir
has approximately 14 small companies to which it has extended membership.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Because we're anticipating an appeal, we're going to go forward [and
allow more select employee groups to join]. What this decision, as it stands,
will do is prohibit small companies from having their own credit union.
This is exactly what the banks want. We feel the government won't allow
it to happen,&quot; says Hevia.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There are 12,000 credit unions with more than 70 million members.
Most of them are small. All told, assets total about $320 billion. Citicorp
and Bank of America hold more than one-and-a-half times that amount. We're
just a speck. It's tough to understand why banks are [so antagonistic].&quot;<BR>
Jack Elliott, an attorney with Pittsburgh's Cohen &amp; Grigsby who specializes
in corporate and banking law, sees problems with the AT&amp;T case. Elliott,
who represents several credit unions, cites the fact that the original Credit
Union Act was written some 60 years ago. <BR>
<BR>
Applying 60-year-old language to credit unions of today does not make sense,
he says.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's not clear that [limiting select employee groups] is the right
approach in a majority of cases,&quot; Elliott says. &quot;In the case of
large credit unions, the lines are blurred. For example, the Navy has a
credit union with approximately $1 billion in assets. That may not be along
the lines of the original goal of credit unions. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;But locally, credit unions are a small select group, with a mission
to return value back to its members, not to make profits.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Looking Long Term</B><BR>
<BR>
Elliott says that the AT&amp;T case is so new that its effect is difficult
to forecast. Nevertheless, he believes that credit unions should have access
to select employee groups. &quot;The ability for credit unions to expand
is important to allow them to remain solvent. If they're not allowed to
expand, they won't survive.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Individual credit unions facing expansion decisions will have to 
think carefully. They could have     to disengage later, depending on  how
the AT&amp;T decision is  implemented.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Finally, Elliott says that most of   the local credit unions are smaller
than the AT&amp;T union, and don't    pose a significant threat to financial
 institutions.<BR>
<BR>
In Point Breeze, for example, members of a food co-op operate a small credit
union in the back room of the store.<BR>
 <BR>
The East End Food Cooperative Federal Credit Union, almost three years old,
is comprised of about 210 members, all culled from the coop's approximately
3,000    members. With total assets at  $61,000, the union offers savings
    and some loans. Soon, they plan to offer certificates of deposit.<BR>
<BR>
There are no regular business hours because of insufficient manpower, explains
president Tom Pendaleon. <BR>
<BR>
Like USAir, the credit union is managed by an all-volunteer board   of directors
as well as volunteer    committees. And while expanding membership outside
of the common bond is often debated, it has thus far not happened.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Because we're all volunteers, we like the pace we have now. It gives
us a chance to learn. We would like to expand membership, but from within
the co-op. In that way, we could stand to grow a little.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Pendaleon says that despite the small amount of services, the co-op credit
union does have real advantages. &quot;It's convenient to be able to bank
when you shop,&quot; he says.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Additionally, we're much closer to the street. We're prudent [when
approving loans], but we're close enough to the community to have a relationship
with our depositors, and that factors into a member's decision to join.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
And, in the end analysis, that closeness and familiarity becomes a very
important part of a credit union's appeal, be it big or little. <BR>
<BR>
Even for USAir's Schwertz, who is one of 77,000 members. <BR>
<BR>
Looking back, he remembers when the credit union was located in an old abandoned
hangar. Back then, the credit union paid back yearly interest bonuses; dividends
akin to what bank stockholders receive. Today, those bonuses are gone; replaced,
he says, by an increase in services and other physical expansions.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The bonuses are gone, but they're putting new buildings up. Maybe
we have moved away from the original mission, but in return we get more
services. If you're in the credit union for pure savings, you're not going
to be as happy as someone using it for all of the services. It's a trade-off.&quot;<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
