<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/1096.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/1096.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/1096.Supplement5.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Taking Minutes and Wasting Hours<BR>
</FONT>By Catherine Dressler</B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>With Corporate America Pushing for  Maximum Efficiency, Why are
Meetings <BR>
We Sit Through So Painfully Inefficient?<BR>
Here's Advice on Running Meetings</B><BR>
<BR>
We begin with a simple quiz. Your boss has called a staff meeting. Given
the choice, you would rather:<BR>
A. Drink plenty of coffee, down a few No-Doz and find a comfortable chair.
After all, to resist is futile.<BR>
B. Schedule a preventative root canal.<BR>
C. Volunteer for a tax audit. <BR>
D. Submit to the exquisite torture of a band of rebels equipped with gallon-buckets
of honey and mounds of giant red ants. <BR>
<BR>
If you were actually contemplating B, C or even D, don't despair. You're
not alone.<BR>
<BR>
Despite widespread efforts to cut costs and save time in the workplace,
business meetings are still universally regarded as incredibly inefficient.
In the age of so-called competitiveness, it seems many of us are meeting
more than ever and getting little done. <BR>
<BR>
Enter Sharon Lippincott, a Monroeville consultant and author dedicated to
ending the meeting madness. She estimates the average manager in Pittsburgh
spends about 15 hours a week in meetings 50 weeks a year. That's about 18
weeks of work time spent in meetings. In a survey reported in Industry Week,
managers estimated about one third of the time they spend in meetings is
wasted. If that's true, Pittsburgh managers could be wasting about six weeks
a year in meetings - six weeks that could be used getting work done, or
at least enjoying a vacation.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;They'd probably rather be in the Bahamas. They'd be having a better
time if they were,&quot; Lippincott says. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Anatomy Of A Meeting</B><BR>
<BR>
Lippincott estimates a meeting of eight midlevel workers who earn $40,000
a year could cost $320 an hour, including salaries and benefits. That's
nearly $6 a minute. Many upper-level executives spend 60 to 70 percent of
their time in meetings, according to Mitchell Nash, a partner of Interaction
Associates Inc., a training and consulting firm based in Cambridge, Mass.
&quot;A company could be wasting thousands or hundreds of thousands of dollars,&quot;
he says.<BR>
 <BR>
Nash says the most common complaints about meetings include:
<UL>
  <LI>The purpose of the meeting is unclear.
  <LI>The meeting participants are unprepared.
  <LI>The conversation veers off track.
</UL>
Meeting participants don't discuss issues. They dominate the conversation,
argue, or take no part at all. <BR>
An executive at the Software Engineering Institute in Pittsburgh might have
put it best when he described meetings in an anonymous survey as &quot;a
place where you keep the minutes and lose the hours.'' Then there was the
sign in a conference room at the Valley News Dispatch in Tarentum saying,
&quot;Are you lonesome? Working on your own? Hate making decisions? Hold
a meeting!&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Improving Your Meetings<BR>
</B><BR>
If all this talk is getting as depressing as, well, the last meeting you
went to, take heart.  You can improve your meetings, especially if you get
your colleagues to work with you. Look at meetings as a process that begins
when you decide to include others in a decision or action. That process
ends only when those decisions are made or the actions are taken.<BR>
 <BR>
Decide, first of all, whether to call a meeting at all. Define your objectives
as specifically as possible and consider whether a meeting is the best way
to achieve them, Lippincott advises. You might decide E-mail, phone calls
or reports will get the job done faster than a meeting. <BR>
 <BR>
In her book, &quot;Meetings: Do's, Don'ts and Donuts,'' Lippincott lists
these good reasons for calling a meeting:
<UL>
  <LI>To convey information to a group.
  <LI>To solicit information.
  <LI>To answer questions.
  <LI>To sell something.
  <LI>To brainstorm.
</UL>
What about the bad reasons to call a meeting?
<UL>
  <LI>The meetings are always held at a certain time.
  <LI>The matters to be addressed have always been addressed in meetings.
  <LI>To look important and in control.
  <LI>To get out of the office for a while.
  <LI>To look busy.
  <LI>If you do decide to hold a meeting, put some thought into the location.
</UL>
<BR>
Quick, routine meetings might be most convenient at your office. Computers
can link participants at different sites for a &quot;virtual meeting.&quot;
If you need privacy or want to avoid distractions, you might want to consider
gathering outside the office.<BR>
<BR>
 &quot;As long as you stay in the office, you're going to keep getting those
phone calls, and people are going to have to keep finishing something,&quot;
Lippincott says.<BR>
<BR>
A local hotel might fit the bill (see the sidebar list of meeting places
on pages  61-62). A resort can provide a nice treat with recreational facilities
for time off. The world-class Mystic Rock golf course has boosted the draw
of Nemacolin Woodlands, a spa resort in Farmington, about an 80-mile drive
from Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
The resort is building a new ballroom for large meetings and a 124-room
addition modeled after the Paris Ritz. &quot;A lot of people say we're remote,''
says Maggie Hardy Magerko, president of the resort (for more on her, see
People Making News on page 10). &quot;I think that works to their advantage.
You have a captive audience. They can get more done in a short period of
time.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Regardless of where you meet, make sure your schedule breaks so that the
participants stay refreshed. Some people like to schedule games or exercises
to break the tension. One meeting planner passed out Play-Doh. Don't hesitate
to provide donuts or another light snack to make the meeting a little more
enjoyable. But don't plan full meals during meetings. It's too hard to concentrate
and talk with a full mouth.<BR>
<BR>
Make sure you invite the right people to your meeting. If you are solving
problems, include people knowledgeable about the process and the technology
in question. Some meetings, particularly larger ones or those involving
different levels of management, run best with a facilitator, an outside
party whose only role is to focus on keeping the meeting flowing.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Getting Started<BR>
</B><BR>
Whether or not you use a facilitator, these guidelines from Lippincott will
help keep your meetings on track.
<UL>
  <LI>State in one or two sentences exactly what you would like your meeting
to accomplish. A powerful purpose statement finishes the sentence, &quot;We
are holding this meeting to ...&quot; For an ongoing project, you may need
to schedule a meeting to formulate a mission or purpose statement. The time
invested in this will pay off with concrete results. 
  <LI>Distribute an agenda at least a couple days in advance. Include the
meeting participants, time, date and place as well as a list of the meeting's
objectives. Let the participants know what they are expected to contribute.
Passing the agenda out early gives them a chance to prepare and provides
direction during the meeting. 
  <LI>Start on time. Making this a habit will encourage others to be punctual.
If you plan to begin a meeting first thing in the morning, though, you may
need to schedule a few minutes after the designated start of the day to
give people time to get settled, pour a cup of coffee and recuperate from
the pressures of the morning commute.
  <LI>Set ground rules to maintain focus, respect and order during the meeting.
For a one-time meeting, the leader might submit the rules at the start of
the gathering. For longer projects, the group should set the rules together
and use them as guidelines that can change over time. You might limit the
amount of time or number of times each person can speak about an issue.
New group members should be given copies of the ground rules.    
  <LI>Take responsibility for the outcome of the meeting. Help keep the
discussion on track and see conflict not as a threat but as a way to find
the best solution.
  <LI>Schedule time on the agenda for a strong close. End the meeting by
evaluating what was accomplished and planning the next meeting.
</UL>
If your meeting is not working, try other tools, including brainstorming
techniques or computer software that helps you create the agenda. The latest
electronic gadgets can help. For example, large computer monitors now act
as high-tech chalkboards. <BR>
<BR>
You can hear one success story at the Software Engineering Institute, the
federally funded research and development center at Carnegie Mellon University.
The center began working to improve its meetings in 1992, when it enlisted
Xerox Corp. to help 300 employees with a variety of management problems.
Pete Malpass, a project leader at the institute, teaches new employees techniques
including conflict resolution and how to offer constructive criticism. The
training for new workers has been cut from seven to five-and-a-half hours.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We practice on ourselves what we preach to others,'' Malpass says.<BR>
<BR>
Meeting agendas are considered so vital that employees can walk out of meetings
that convene without one. Every meeting has a leader, a facilitator, a timekeeper
and a note-taker. &quot;We were terrible at meetings when I got here,&quot;
Malpass says. &quot;This is delightful.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Like Malpass, you can dig your way out of the meeting abyss. Don't expect
deep, lasting change to come easily. You and your colleagues will have to
make a commitment. But the payoff could be more time for meaningful work
or - better yet - a longer vacation.                                   
          <BR>
