<B><FONT size=+2>The Annual JA Hall of Fame Inductees<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<HR><B>A Message From the Chairman<BR>
By William Dietrich<BR>
Chairman, 1996 Southwest Pennsylvania Business Hall of Fame</B></CENTER>
<P>Dear Junior Achievement Supporter:<BR>
<BR>
The business history of southwestern Pennsyl-vania is replete with enterprising
spirit. Over the years, imagination and initiative sparked this area's leaders
to undertake bold, new ventures. Business founders such as Andrew Carnegie,
H.J. Heinz, Andrew Mellon and George Westinghouse laid         the foundation
and established the precedent   for success.<BR>
<BR>
In keeping with the spirit of this community, Junior Achievement has been
inspiring local students &shyp; the future of America &shyp; to learn the
value of free enterprise, understand business and economics and become the
leaders of tomorrow.<BR>
<BR>
I am honored to serve Junior Achievement as the chairman of the 9th annual
Business Hall of Fame program. This event will recognize the following individuals
this year for their outstanding accomplishments in our business community:
C. Frederick Fetterolf, Gerald McGinnis, Quentin McKenna, William Block
Sr. and Robert Mehrabian. We also honor Dr. John E. Murray Jr. with the
Achievement Award for his life-long continuing efforts to encourage our
future leaders. The work of these gentlemen exemplifies the best of free
enterprise.<BR>
<BR>
Success is fueled by hard work, dedication and vision. The five laureates
for this year's Business Hall of Fame have limitless vision that enables
them to convert ideas into enterprises. They made great contributions to
their communities through outstanding business, social, cultural and civic
leadership.<BR>
<BR>
Please join with me on Nov. 18, 1996, at 6 p.m. at the Westin William Penn
ballroom as we honor the great leaders of our time and celebrate the promise
of tomorrow's business leaders, i.e., today's Junior Achievers.<BR>
<P><CENTER><B>JA Works: <BR>
Here's How<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>In this day and age, athletes, musicians, actors and other celebrities
can no longer be held up as models of success and good citizenship. The
negative publicity surrounding such pop culture icons as Michael Jackson,
Pete Rose, Mike Tyson and of course, O.J. Simpson, has caused the country
to question the people whom we hold up to our children as &quot;successful.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Sometimes the best examples of perseverance, dedication, commitment and
ultimately success, however we define it, can be found in the people we
know. Our parents, peers and mentors can offer us a wealth of knowledge,
experience, guidance and a pattern on which to shape our behavior.<BR>
By going into the classroom and working with students one-on-one, JA volunteers
have the opportunity to provide students with a positive and accessible
role model. The simplest commitment to a group of students can provide them
with a lasting and positive impression.<BR>
<BR>
A great way students can meet with adults who are positive role models is
through Junior Achievement programs. More students than ever will get the
opportunity to interact with Junior Achievement volunteers this school year.
Each volunteer can benefit the life of each student.<BR>
The K-6 program allows young students in kindergarten through sixth grade
to learn about their roles in the economy of the family, community, city
and country. Volunteers from the business community visit the classroom
to bring students a practical understanding of how free enterprise works
in the community and the value of an education.<BR>
<BR>
Through hands-on activities, students in the K-6 program learn fundamental
business principles and how they can become contributing members of society.
These programs lay the foundation for continued learning and success in
high school and beyond.<BR>
<BR>
Another JA program, ESIS, allows seventh-grade students to see first-hand
how staying in school makes sense. Through the Success board game, students
learn the long-term benefits of getting their high school diploma. Students
also see what the world holds for a high school dropout. They scan the classifieds
trying to find a job they would be qualified for as a dropout. <BR>
<BR>
Junior Achievement's goal according to S. Lee Strayer, president of Junior
Achievement of Southwest Pennsyl-vania, &quot;is to provide a complete kindergarten
through 12th grade curriculum in the coming years. The only way that can
be accomplished is through business and community leaders going into the
classroom.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Junior Achievement's programs also represent a vital steppingstone from
a student's secondary education to college or directly to the work force.<BR>
<BR>
The U.S. position in the world economy depends directly on our nation's
ability to prepare tomorrow's workforce. Business leaders recognize this
challenge as they continually search for workers with new and more sophisticated
skills. <BR>
<BR>
Junior Achievement knows from experience that a key to success is to bring
business and community leaders directly into the classroom. Young students
in search of positive role models find such volunteers important sources
of inspiration. At the same time, the Junior Achievement classroom volunteers
transform textbook theory into real-life experiences that greatly aid the
learning process. <BR>
<BR>
As our children are confronted with challenges at an increasingly young
age, it is critical that this type of classroom involvement now begins in
kindergarten. With the belief that it is never too early to start preparing
our nation's youth for their futures, Junior Achievement programs begin
in kindergarten and continue through 12th grade. The goal is to help children
learn the parallel between success in school and success in the workplace.
When our children learn this, it is far easier for them to continue their
education through graduation and become contributing members of society.
<BR>
Students learn about their roles as individuals, consumers and workers in
environments that extend from their homes to an international marketplace.
A variety of activities are included to help each student develop decision-making
and workforce-readiness skills.<BR>
 <BR>
For further information on how you can get involved with the next generation
of business leaders, call Junior Achievement at 1-800-522-6957.  <BR>
