<P><CENTER><B>The 1996 Laureates<BR>
</B></CENTER>
<P>William Block Sr.<BR>
<BR>
William Block Sr., chairman of PG Publishing Co., has been a key figure
in Pittsburgh's newspaper industry since before World War II. Block entered
the newspaper business in 1937, a year after graduating from Yale University.
<BR>
 <BR>
His father, Paul Block Sr., who bought the Pittsburgh newspaper in 1927,
died in 1941. Bill Block and his brother, Paul Jr., became co-publishers
of the Pittsburgh Post-Gazette and the Blade of Toledo, Ohio.<BR>
 <BR>
In 1989, he stepped aside as publisher and became chairman of PG Publishing
Co., with his son, William Block Jr., and nephew, John Robinson Block, becoming
co-publishers of the newspapers.  <BR>
The Post-Gazette published under a joint operating agreement with The Pittsburgh
Press until the eight-month strike began in May 1992. PG Pub- lishing Co.
reached agreement with the E.W. Scripps Co. in October to buy the assets
of The Press and negotiated contracts with its unions enabling the PG to
resume publishing in January 1993. <BR>
 <BR>
Block has served on the boards of directors of many local organizations
and has assisted many civic causes, among them the Better Bus-iness Bureau,
the Historical Society of Western Pennsylvania, the Allegheny Conference
on Com-munity Development, the Community Chest of Alle-gheny County and
the Pitts-burgh Symphony Society. <BR>
 <BR>
The Squirrel Hill resident has been married since 1944 to Maxine Block.
They have four children and eight grandchildren.  <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Gerald E. McGinnis<BR>
<BR>
As chairman of Respironics Inc., Gerald E. McGinnis guides the strategic
direction of a rapidly growing international enterprise with annual sales
approaching $100 million. McGinnis founded the company in 1976 and served
as president and chief executive officer until his election to the chairman's
position in November 1994. Under his direction, Respironics consistently
appeared on annual lists of outstanding companies established by such national
publications as Forbes and Business Week and was cited for outstanding product
and service quality in three of the past four years by a national association
of pulmonary care organizations.<BR>
<BR>
   Prior to establishing Respironics, Mr. McGinnis served for five years
as president and chief executive officer of Lanz Medical Products Corp.
- a business he also founded. Already recognized as a creative engineer,
McGinnis' management capabilities were soundly demonstrated during the Lanz
years. The company concluded operations in 1975 when its primary product
was sold to a large corporation. Concurrent with his tenure at Lanz, McGinnis
served on the Critical Care Department staff of Pittsburgh's Pres-  byterian
University Hospital. <BR>
<BR>
McGinnis holds a bachelor's degree in mechanical engineering from the University
of Illinois and a master's degree in the same discipline from the University
of Pittsburgh. He began his engineering career in 1958 at the research and
development center of Westinghouse Electric Corp. During his 11 years at
Westinghouse, McGinnis participated in a variety of health-related projects.
His work there was headed by a six-year assignment as manager of the Bio-Engineering
Department, a company unit engaged in projects to develop artificial heart
and heart-assist devices. From 1969 to 1971, McGinnis headed the Surgical
Research Department at Allegheny General Hospital in Pittsburgh. <BR>
The Respironics chief executive serves as a director of numerous organizations
and institutions. In addition to his own company, his board memberships
include Vascor Inc.; Point Park College; Pittsburgh High Technology Council;
Health Industry Manufacturers Association; Pennsylvania Council on Economic
Education; United Way of Westmoreland County; Junior Achievement of Southwest
Pennsylvania; Healthcare Technology Institute Pittsburgh; Biomedical Corporation;
Economics Amer-ica; Pittsburgh World Affairs Council; The Pittsburgh Symphony
Society and the CEO Club.<BR>
<BR>
McGinnis has authored or co-authored a number of scientific papers and a
chapter of a book on airway cars. He holds more than 15 registered U.S.
patents and contributed directly to the development of the design distinctions
which differentiate Respironics products.<BR>
<BR>
Quentin McKenna<BR>
<BR>
Former Kennamental CEO Quentin C. McKenna has served as Kennametal's chairman
of the board since 1986. He was president and CEO from 1979 to 1991.<BR>
<BR>
A native of Claremont, Calif., McKenna holds a bachelor's degree from Pomona
College and a master of engineering degree from Stanford University.   He
completed doctoral course work at the University of Southern California
and at UCLA.<BR>
<BR>
McKenna served in various management positions at Hughes Aircraft Co. before
joining Kennametal and holds three patents in missile guidance. In 1983,
he was named recipient of the prestigious Eli Whitney Memorial Award by
the Society of Manufacturing Engineers in light of his accomplishments as
an engineer, inventor and industrialist furthering production technologies.
He has been a member of the Executive Committee of the Manufacturers' Alliance
for Productivity and Innovation since 1980.<BR>
<BR>
McKenna has served on various boards including the the Pittsburgh Branch
of the Federal Reserve Board, Pittsburgh National Bank and St. Vincent College.
From 1991 to 1995 he served as an Adjunct Professor at Carnegie Mellon University.
Presently, he is on the board of Interlake Corp., the Carnegie Science Center
and the World Affairs Council. He and his wife also jointly own the Hyeholde
Restaurant in Moon Township.<BR>
<BR>
C. Frederick Fetterolf<BR>
<BR>
C. Fred Fetterolf, former president and chief operating officer of Alcoa,
was born in Franklin, Pa., July 18, 1928. <BR>
<BR>
Fetterolf joined Alcoa in 1952 as a sales trainee in Pittsburgh after receiving
a bachelor's degree in chemistry at Grove City College. He started with
the basics, but later handled a variety of positions as he worked his way
up.<BR>
 <BR>
Fetterolf became a chemical and general salesman in Cincinnati, Ohio, in
1953 and later served in sales assignments in Louisville, Kentucky and San
Francisco.<BR>
<BR>
Fetterolf returned to Pittsburgh in 1965 when he was promoted to industry
assistant - flexible packaging. Later, he was named division sales manager
- flexible packaging, a position he held until 1969, when he moved to Los
Angeles as assistant district sales manager. <BR>
<BR>
He became district sales manager in Philadelphia in 1971, returned to Pittsburgh
as industry manager - defense in 1974, and became general manager - marketing
in 1975.<BR>
 <BR>
Fetterolf was elected a vice president in June 1977 and named vice president
- Alcoa smelting process project in February 1979. He became vice president
- operations, primary products in August 1979, and vice president - science
and technology in February 1981.<BR>
 <BR>
He was made executive vice president - mill products in July 1981 and elected
a director and president in February 1983. He took the office of president
in April 1983 and was appointed chief operating officer in April 1985.<BR>
 <BR>
    Fetterolf is a director of a number of corporations and serves on various
civic and educational organizations. <BR>
<BR>
He also has been honored by his alma mater as a recipient of the Grove City
College Alumni Achievement Award.  <BR>
<P><CENTER><B>Achievement Award:</B> </CENTER>
<P><B>John E. Murray Jr.</B><BR>
<BR>
For 21 years, Junior Achievement of Southwest Pennsylvania has presented
its annual Achievement Award to a local chief executive. These executives
are honored for their personal accomplishments and those of their companies
- people and institutions which have done the most for the free enterprise
system. The award has traditionally been presented at Junior Achievement's
annual meeting; 10 years ago, however, a new tradition began with the presentation
of the award at the annual Business Hall of Fame Dinner. This year's dinner
continues the tradition with the event scheduled for Nov. 18 at the Westin
William Penn.<BR>
<BR>
This year's winner, John E. Murray Jr. was selected president of Duquesne
University in 1988, the first lay president in the school's then 111-year
history.<BR>
<BR>
Murray brings to Duquesne a tradition of service to the Pittsburgh community
and the legal profession. He earned his undergraduate degree at LaSalle
University in 1955. He received his J.D. from Catholic University of America
in 1958 and his S.J.D. from the University of Wisconsin in 1959.<BR>
<BR>
As president of Duquesne, Murray instituted a $6 million plan to increase
faculty and staff salaries to be competitive with similar institutions nationally
and increased awards and scholarships by 120 percent. Under his tenure,
the university received more than $2 million in grants for library endowment
and raised nearly $74 million, nearly tripling the university's Spirit of
the 90s Capital Campaign goal of $25 million. In 1992-93, Duquesne achieved
the highest enrollment in its history and entrance criteria rose.<BR>
<BR>
Duquesne was ranked by U.S. News and World Report as one of the top 10 Catholic
universities in the nation.  Barron's Guide to Colleges has listed Duquesne
as one of the best 300 college buys in the country and USA Today ranked
Duquesne's campus as the safest in Pennsylvania and one of the safest in
the country.<BR>
<BR>
Under Murray's leadership, the A.J. Palumbo Center was named one of the
top 10 grossing arenas in the nation by Performance Magazine after less
than one year of operation and is now ranked sixth in the nation.  Murray
also saw Duquesne's A.J. Palumbo School of Business Administration join
only 20 percent of universities in the nation to receive reaccreditation
by the Accreditation Council of the American Assembly of Collegiate Schools
of Business.<BR>
 <BR>
Murray has nearly completed plans to reconstruct and refurbish campus facilities,
including beautifying Academic Walk with a fountain, OmniStone and English
gardens.<BR>
  <BR>
Murray was named ARC Allegheny Volunteer of the Year for 1994. In addition
to being recognized with the 1993 Catholic Charities Distinguished Service
Award, Murray was selected Man of the Year by Vectors/Pittsburgh in 1993,
after having been chosen Man of the Year in Education in 1988.  He was also
the 1988 St. Thomas More Award recipient.<BR>
<BR>
In 1991 he was honored as the Person of Vision by the Pittsburgh Blind Assoc-iation.
In 1992, Murray also received the President's Award from the Continuing
Education Association of Pennsylvania. He was also Alumnus of the Year for
the Catholic University of America and received an honorary degree from
La Salle Uni-   versity in 1995.<BR>
<BR>
Murray served as University Distinguished Service Professor of Law at the
University of Pittsburgh; professor of law and dean of the school of law
at Villanova University; professor, associate dean and dean of the University
of Pittsburgh School of Law; and professor of law and dean of the school
of law at Duquesne. <BR>
<BR>
Murray recently headed the  Committee to Prepare Allegheny County for the
21st Century, or ComPAC21, the Resource Equity/Adequacy Panel of the Allegheny
Policy Council and is general chair of the 1996 United Way of Allegheny
County campaign.<BR>
<BR>
A respected author of 12 books and a legal scholar, Murray served an unprecedented
11 years as editor of the prestigious Journal of Legal Education and has
written numerous treatises and classroom books. His articles have also been
published in the law reviews of Cornell University, Fordham University,
the University of Pittsburgh, Villanova, and William and Mary College of
Law.<BR>
<BR>
JA's mission is to inspire and educate young people to value free enterprise.
The 1995 Achievement Award winner and his predecessors are symbols of this
mission. Past recipients of this award  include:<BR>
<BR>
1995 John Connelly, Gateway Clipper Fleet<BR>
1994 Robert Bozzone, Allegheny Ludlum Corp.<BR>
1993 Gerald E. McGinnis, Respironics Inc.<BR>
1992 John G. Rangos Sr., Chambers Development Co.<BR>
1991 Thomas A. McConomy, Calgon Carbon Corp.<BR>
1990 Dr. Richard M. Cyert, Carnegie Mellon University<BR>
1989 Thomas H. O'Brien, PNC Bank Corp.<BR>
1988 Richard P. Simmons, Allegheny Ludlum Corp.<BR>
1987 Vincent A. Sarni, PPG Industries Inc.<BR>
1986 Douglas D. Danforth, Westinghouse Electric Corp.<BR>
1985 Dr. Charles L. Sewall, Robert Morris College<BR>
1984 Ernest U. Buckman, Oliver Realty<BR>
1983 James H. Higgins, Mellon Bank<BR>
1982 David M. Roderick, USX Corp.<BR>
1981 G.J. Tankersley, Consolidated Natural Gas Co.<BR>
1980 Jerry McAfee, Gulf Oil Corp.<BR>
1979 Robert E. Kirby, Westinghouse Electric Corp.<BR>
1978 Fletcher L. Byrom, Koppers Co. Inc.<BR>
1977 Robert Dickey III, Dravo Corp.<BR>
1976 Edgar B. Speer, U.S. Steel<BR>
1975 John D. Harper, Alcoa<BR>
1974 Willard F. Rockwell Jr., Rockwell International   <BR>
