"3"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H4Editor.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH=
"363" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" 
HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Clinton vs. Dole </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>You can't Believe Everything Clinton Says;<BR>
Here are Some Examples</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</I></B> </CENTER>
<P><HR>President Clinton tells you this as he heads toward a second term
in office:<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I'd like the American people to know that I have worked very hard
to be on their side and to move this country forward, and we're better off
than we were four years ago,&quot; the president said near the end of the
first debate between he and Republican nominee Bob Dole last month. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;But the most important thing,&quot; the president continued, &quot;is
my plan for the 21st century is a better plan.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Says who?<BR>
<BR>
 In reality, the president's promises of a targeted tax cut and commitments
to education and welfare reform are as vague as the accomplishments he now
touts in this election month. Nevertheless, the polls show Clinton with
a comfortable lead as the campaign comes to a close.<BR>
<BR>
For the sake of accuracy, here's a look at some of the president's rhetoric:<BR>
<BR>
Clinton says we have the smallest government in 30 years. Indeed, the president
has trimmed nearly 250,000 federal jobs since taking office, and the total
federal work force is now smaller than during the Kennedy administration.
However, two-thirds of those cuts have come from the Defense Department
because of the end of the Cold War. <BR>
<BR>
Repeat after me: &quot;Thank You Ronald Reagan.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The non-defense federal work force - commonly known as bureaucrats - has
shrunk some under Clinton's &quot;reinventing government'' plan. Nevertheless,
it is still about 40 percent larger than when John F. Kennedy was president.
<BR>
<BR>
The misinformation doesn't stop there. In fact, Clinton manipulates facts
like an expert.<BR>
<BR>
For instance, the president also says he is tough on drugs despite    numbers
that show drug use among young people steadily increasing. Clinton has taken
credit for appointing a former general this year as the nation's drug czar.
What he forgot to tell was that in 1993, Clinton        slashed the size
of the drug czar's   office by about four-fifths as part of    his effort
to reduce White House staff by 25 percent. <BR>
<BR>
There's more.<BR>
<BR>
Clinton takes credit for putting 100,000 police officers on the streets.
Granted, Congress in the 1994 crime bill authorized 100,000 new officers
by the year 2000. <BR>
<BR>
But Congress thus far has allocated money for just 44,000 officers, and
only about 20,000 of those are actually on the streets, the Justice Department
said last month.<BR>
<BR>
In the same breath, Clinton  attacks congressional Republicans, accusing
them of trying to cut Medicare by  $270 billion. The president instills
fear in the country's older population.<BR>
 <BR>
In fact, Republicans never proposed reducing Medicare spending. Both Republicans
and Clinton have called for restraining the future growth of Medicare -
the GOP by $270 billion over seven years, the president by $124 billion
over the  same period.<BR>
 <BR>
Under the GOP plan, Medicare spending still would have risen by 7 percent
a year, according to the Congressional Budget Office.<BR>
<BR>
It's likely Clinton will have locked up his second term by the time most
of you read this piece. But the president ended that first debate in October
by putting the ball in our court.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I like Sen. Dole,&quot; Clinton said. &quot;You can probably tell
we like each other. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We just see the world in different ways, and you folks out there are
going to have to choose who you think is right.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
I've made my choice. <BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
