<P><B><IMG SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="LEFT" WIDTH=
"93" HEIGHT="122" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>Unconventional Center</FONT SIZE> <FONT size=+1></B>Renovating
The David Lawrence Convention Center<BR>
Is a Worthy Cause for Pittsburgh<B></FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher <BR clear=all></I></B><HR>In the
raging debate over the allocation of diminishing public dollars, those capital
investments with the capacity to attract resources to the region should
receive priority. An expanded convention center's express purpose is to
fuel the influx of people to this area. New people bring new money. Therefore,
the convention center should be a priority investment.<BR>
<BR>
The proposed $262 million expansion and renovation of the David L. Lawrence
Convention Center is by any measure a prudent expenditure. The convention
center's reported 5 percent annual growth rate last year is not sufficient
to capture Pittsburgh's fair share of the lucrative convention market. <BR>
The physical constraints of the relatively outmoded center mean Pittsburgh
is no longer competitive as a major convention market. <BR>
<BR>
By definition, convention centers bring in dollars to a region - dollars
that otherwise would not be there. This expands the total local economy
by putting more dollars into play. Alternatively, other potential public
investments like the proposed new baseball stadium do not. <BR>
<BR>
Regional assets increase the     velocity of money within the existing local
economic system. But public facilities like convention centers expand the
overall economy.<BR>
<BR>
A convention center is the gateway to the region it serves. Over 530,000
people attended events at the David Lawrence Convention Center last year.
Our sterile and (some would argue) hostile environment at the current convention
center hardly reflects a sophisticated and energetic community. Instead
of creating a welcoming atmosphere, our convention center is tired and haggard,
showing definite signs of wear. Its harsh personality is the antithesis
of Pittsburgh. As proposed, the convention center renovation would capture
the charm of Pittsburgh's underutilized rivers. Sprawling toward the cultural
district, the expanded convention center would lure visitors to the city's
vast array of cultural amenities.<BR>
<BR>
Chaired by Federated Investors President J. Christopher Donahue, the Convention
Facilities Needs Assess-ment Task Force projects a 4 percent return on government's
proposed investment in the facility. These projections do not adequately
account for the multiplier effect of introducing totally new money to an
economic system. The renovation will increase the proverbial pie. Given
the region's lackluster economic performance in recent years, I'm entirely
supportive of capital investments that introduce incremental monies to the
region and entice visitors to return.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Un&quot;-conventional attitudes normally do not prevail in Pittsburgh.
Let's hope that &quot;un&quot;-convention center attitudes do not germinate
here either!<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
