<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0"
ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H5Guest.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40" 
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>No Contest</FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>From Management's Perspective<BR>
The Clear Choice for President is Bob Dole </FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By John E. Lyncheski</I></B><HR></CENTER>
<P>We are nearing the end of corporate America's quadrennial debate on which
presidential candidate will be better or worse for management. If we evaluate
the candidates merely in terms of their impact on the ability of companies
to manage their work forces, it's Dole in a landslide.<BR>
<BR>
Let's start by looking at the numbers - not the polls, but the funding.
 Businesses have made major contributions to both campaigns and will have
an important voice in either administration. But organized labor has put
all its eggs in Clinton's basket.<BR>
<BR>
With $35 million dedicated to Clinton's re-election, labor would likely
have clout in a second Clinton term. Organized labor now represents approximately
17 percent of the workforce, compared to a peak of more than 30 percent
in the 1950s. Despite this decline in relative numbers, organized labor
would continue to have a major say in the Clinton administration. Clinton's
labor secretary, Robert Reich, has stated on many occasions that he considers
himself labor's advocate.<BR>
<BR>
If re-elected, Clinton's appointees to the National Labor Relations Board,
the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission and other government agencies
will tend to be in an adversarial relationship with management. By decision,
rule and policy, the Clinton NLRB has already leaned heavily towards organized
labor. President Clinton appoints the chair, a majority of the board and,
perhaps most significantly, the general counsel, who acts as chief prosecutor
in the enforcement of National Labor Relations Act.<BR>
<BR>
Labor's influence will also lead Clinton to name federal judges more likely
to support outlandishly large verdicts in employee lawsuits against employers.
Courts are still ruling on many aspects of the major employment-related
legislation passed in the late '80s and early '90s. <BR>
<BR>
The judges appointed by Clinton are more likely to make an expansive, plaintiff-oriented
reading of the fine points of employment law, saddling management with greater
liabilities, promoting litigation and raising the cost of litigation even
when the employer wins. Conservative judges appointed by Dole will take
a more even-handed approach.<BR>
<BR>
The long-term impact of Clinton's judicial appointments could be devastating
to management. Federal judges are appointed for life and often sit for 20
years or longer. The judges named over the next four years will be making
decisions well into the 21st century.<BR>
<BR>
But the fact that labor has pitched its tent in the Clinton camp is not
the only reason that Dole is better for management. Dole is more likely
to support pro-management legislation: 
<UL>
  <LI>Clinton supports and Dole opposes a bill that would end a company's
right to use replacement workers when its employees engage in an economic
strike. For companies that must continue operating during a strike, the
use of replacement workers is essential. Ending that right would dramatically
shift the balance of power in labor relations towards unions.
  <LI>Dole remains in favor of the TEAM Act, which would enable management
to empower the approximately 85 percent of the workforce not unionized to
help improve the work place for management and themselves. Clinton vetoed
the act earlier this year.
</UL>
<BR>
Dole has made shrinking taxes and government the focal point of his economic
program, while Clinton's stand on such issues as education, welfare, transportation
and environmental regulations makes him the '90s equivalent of a &quot;big-government&quot;
Democrat.<BR>
<BR>
Reducing government is more than just a way to reduce taxes: There has been
a movement to reduce government by privatizing its services. Privatization
typically leads to less costly and higher quality services. It also creates
opportunities for the businesses that assume the government services to
thrive and create jobs. A Dole administration is more likely to support
privatization.<BR>
 <BR>
To be sure, Clinton has many ties to the business community. He supports
several positions that help companies more effectively compete internationally,
develop a workforce with the skills needed by today's businesses and encourage
the development and deployment of emerging technologies.<BR>
<BR>
But for the most part, Dole holds these positions, too. Dole owes no debt
to organized labor, he has demonstrated his ability to work with Congress
to pass pro-management legislation and he is committed to lower taxes and
less government. He should get the nod from management.                
           <BR>
John E. Lyncheski is head of the Labor and Employment Law Group at Pittsburgh's
Cohen &amp; Grigsby.  The opinions expressed above are Mr.Lyncheski's personal
views and are not necessarily those of Cohen &amp; Grigsby.<BR>
