<B><FONT SIZE=+2></FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT SIZE></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>
<H4>CMU's Mehrabian Among JA Honorees on Nov. 18<BR>
</H4>
Last month's special section on the Junior Achievement Business Hall of
Fame profiled this year's laureates, minus one: Carnegie Mellon University
President Robert Mehrabian.<BR>
<BR>
Mehrabian - along with William Block Sr., C. Fred Fetterolf, Gerald E. McGinnis,
Quentin McKenna and John E. Murray Jr. - is being honored Nov. 18 at 6 p.m.
at the Westin William Penn in Pittsburgh.<BR>
<BR>
JA annually recognizes individuals for their outstanding accomplishments
in the business community.<BR>
<BR>
During Mehrabian's six-year tenure, Carnegie Mellon has strengthened its
position as one of the premier research universities in the world.  Mehrabian
also led a campus building program of grand scope, including construction
of a $47 million University Center. <BR>
<BR>
Mehrabian announced in March that he will retire in 1997. He is remaining
as president until the university completes an orderly transition to a new
chief executive.  Mehrabian, who has no immediate professional plans, said
he would return to California to be with his family.<BR>
<BR>
Mehrabian serves on the boards    of directors of Allegheny Teledyne Inc.,
DQE and Duquesne Light Co., Mellon Bank Corp. and PPG Industries Inc.  He
also serves on the Science and Technology Council of ALCOA. <BR>
<BR>
Examples of his civic and cultural activities include: membership on the
executive committees of the Council on Competitive-ness and the Allegheny
Conference on Community Development, the board of WQED, the Regional Industrial
Development Corporation of Southwest-ern Pennsylvania and Penn's Southwest
Association.<BR>
<BR>
Mehrabian chaired the Forging a New Freedom Campaign, a cooperative effort
among business and community institutions to make Pittsburgh the most accessible
city in the nation to people with disabilities. <BR>
<BR>
He also chaired committees that produced reports titled &quot;Toward a Shared
Economic Vision for Pittsburgh and Southwestern Pennsylvania&quot; and &quot;The
Greater Pittsburgh Region: Working Together to Compete Globally.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The reports served as the economic revitalization blueprint for the region,
outlining initiatives now being implemented by a broad-based coalition of
civic and industry leaders in southwestern Pennsylvania.<BR>
 <BR>
Mehrabian also led the development of Pittsburgh's first riverfront technology
park, a 48-acre site that is home to a new 90,000-square-foot building for
Carnegie Mellon's (applied) Research Institute.<BR>
<BR>
Mehrabian is an internationally recognized materials scientists. He has
authored 139 technical papers and has edited six books. He holds eight U.S.
and more than 40 foreign patents. His awards include election to the National
Academy of Engineering in 1984. He is a Fellow and Distinguished Life Member
of the American Society of Metals International (ASM) and recipient of The
Henry Marion Howe Medal of ASM. <BR>
<BR>
He is also a fellow of and received the Leadership Award of The Minerals,
Metals and Materials Society (TMS) and the 1994 James F. Compton Humanitarian
Award.<BR>
<BR>
Mehrabian, born in 1941, is of Armenian descent. He was educated at Phillips
Exeter Academy, and received his bachelor's and doctor of science degrees
in the field of materials from Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT)
in 1964 and 1968, respectively.<BR>
<BR>
After his graduation, he remained at MIT and held the successive positions
of research associate, assistant and associate professor. In 1975, he moved
to the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, where he was both a 
professor of metallurgy and professor of mechanical engineering.<BR>
<BR>
He served in the U.S. Department of Commerce from 1979 to 1983 when he was
first chief of metallurgy and later director of the Center for Materials
Science at the National Institute of Standards and Technology. While at
NIST, he initiated a number of innovative government/industry programs that
became models for such cooperative efforts.<BR>
<BR>
Mehrabian joined the University of California at Santa Barbara as dean of
engineering in 1983. <BR>
During his tenure, the college initiated seven multidisciplinary research
centers, established a new materials department, recruited 65 new faculty
and was ranked the No. 1 up-and-coming college of engineering by U.S. News
and World Report magazine in 1990. <BR>
<BR>
While at Santa Barbara, he helped start Superconductor Technologies, Inc.,
(STI) which is now traded on NASDAQ.                                   
       <BR>
