<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0"
ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H14EyeonH.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Razor Thin</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT size=+1>Open Seats in This Election May Determine Whether<BR>
the Republicans Maintain a Majority in Harrisburgh</FONT><BR>
<I>By Jim Strader </I><HR></CENTER>
<P>Two years ago, Pennsylvania voters gave the business community a boost
by picking a governor with a pro-business platform and voting in lawmakers
to help Tom Ridge carry it out.<BR>
<BR>
But the Republican takeover - with Ridge as governor and a GOP majority
in the Senate and House - faces a challenge even though Ridge still has
two years to serve and is not up for re-election this month. Though the
Senate seems safely in Republican hands, a razor-thin, one-vote GOP margin
in the House could be in jeopardy. After all, a Democratic majority in the
House was elected in 1994; Republicans gained control only after a Democratic
representative from northeastern Pennsylvania switched parties several days
after the voters sent him back to Harrisburg.<BR>
<BR>
Democrats have made no secret of their desire to regain the majority they
held for a dozen years in the House - and the control of the speaker's gavel
that comes with it. A major thrust of the fall Democratic campaign has been
to take advantage of President Clinton's early lead over Republican Bob
Dole and try to carry other Democratic candidates on the ticket along on
Clinton's coattails. In addition to the statewide offices of attorney general,
auditor general and treasurer, half the Senate and the entire House is up
for election.<BR>
<BR>
While Democrats have seemed very confident of their chances - from the presidential
race on down - Penn-sylvania business leaders have had other ideas. Their
goal has been to try to help business-friendly lawmakers - for the most
part, the Republicans - hold on to control in Harrisburg. And they like
their chances.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think coattails, as it relates to legislative races, is overrated,&quot;
says Jim Lee, director of the political action committee of the Pennsylvania
Chamber of Business and Industry. &quot;Our sense is most incumbents will
probably be re-elected despite Clinton's strong favorable ratings in Pennsylvania.<BR>
 So what we're trying to do is communicate to business people that it's
important that they be supportive of those members of the House and Senate,
especially as it relates to their support of business.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
After the election two years ago, state business leaders seized the opportunity
to push for changes they wanted accomplished by the new GOP regime in Harrisburg.
Working through such groups as the Chamber Political Action Committee, 
the major lobbying group for business in the capital, they had success on
several fronts.<BR>
<BR>
Leading the changes were a reduction in business taxes, more friendly environmental
regulation and lower costs for workers' compensation, all of which help
Pennsylvania better compete with other states.<BR>
<BR>
Lee says the Chamber Political Action Committee takes some of the credit
for bringing about the changes in workers' compensation and attributes its
success to grassroots organizing of support among lawmakers. Some legislators
have been paid back by the Chamber Political Action Com-mittee during the
campaign.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Many members are certainly getting pounded by organized labor and
the trial lawyers for that vote,&quot; Lee says. &quot;It's important for
business to come to the aid of those members at the grassroots level.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Given his belief that most incumbents are likely to be re-elected, Lee says
the Chamber Political Action Committee has concentrated its efforts at maintaining
GOP control of the House on open seats - including districts in Pittsburgh's
South Hills and Clarion and Butler counties. <BR>
<BR>
The work isn't easy. Democrats hold a large edge - nearly 400,000 voters
- over Republicans in registration across the state. Of course, that advantage
did not prevent the results of 1994, and, on a smaller scale, heavily-Democratic
Allegheny County also elected a Republican majority to the county board
of commissioners for the first time in decades.<BR>
<BR>
The Chamber Political Action Committee puts out press releases on behalf
of candidates and writes &quot;advocacy letters&quot; to chambers of commerce
in a candidate's district. The political committee also works to get voters
out, puts together fund-raising events, writes letters to the editors of
newspapers and does some polling.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;What we're trying to do, from a legislative standpoint, is to use
the same grassroots effort that we did with getting passage of workers'
comp,&quot; Lee says. &quot;We're not a big-money PAC. [But] we do feel
our name carries some weight.&quot; 
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> </CENTER>
<ADDRESS>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <A HREF="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments
or suggestions?</A><BR>
