<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Ann Devlin</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.People.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Customer Caring</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>I Found it at Disney World and at Wendy's;<BR>
Let's Hope I Find it Other Places, Too<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>Ann Devlin - Columnist</I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>Sometimes, to get to the point, you have to do some traveling. So
put on your Mouse Ears, you're headed down to Disney World, where I sit
writing this column.<BR>
<BR>
Maybe your company has customer service - or maybe you are a customer wondering
whatever happened to service. Well, in the Land of Mickey, they've refined
the concept to the point where it might more aptly be called &quot;Customer
Caring.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
My husband Bill, daughter Mara and I were outside the Convention Center
here, waiting for a bus to take us to one of the parks. Three busses pulled
up over the span of about five minutes, but all were bound for different
destinations. So was the next one that rolled into view. It stopped, the
doors swung open, and Joe the driver called out to ask us where we were
headed. <BR>
<BR>
We told him, and he essentially told us we couldn't get there from here,
at least not by bus. We had to go back up to the Convention Center, down
to the Boardwalk and wait for a launch. We stood up and started to pack
up when Joe added, &quot;So, climb on board.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
We did a double-take.<BR>
<BR>
Now Joe's job title and salary are far from Michael Eisner's, but on that
day and that moment, Joe took ownership of our situation. He perceived a
problem, investigated, provided a solution and then even blushed when we
expressed our gratitude.<BR>
<BR>
Acting solely on his own initiative, he recognized an opportunity to demonstrate
&quot;Customer Caring.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Next stop: Wendy's at Edgewood Town Center. I want to tell you about what
happened to me here just before we left for Orlando. I stopped to try out
their new Veggie Pita. I hadn't been to Wendy's for a while and had to get
reoriented to the changes they'd made in the drive-thru lanes.<BR>
<BR>
First, a big new menu board with an electronic display listing each item
as it was ordered, along with the price and finally the total. No more shouting
and squawking back and forth to make sure the order was right or to double-check
what was owed. Nice improvement. I pulled up to the window, paid, and received
my change. All the while I was watching a Wendy's employee prune and groom
a rhododendron planted between the pay-up and the pick-up windows. She was
actually misting the leaves and wiping each one of them off. As I rolled
past to get my lunch, another worker thanked me for the order while handing
me the bag, then went on to wish me a terrific weekend - all while actually
making eye contact. <BR>
<BR>
Customer Caring. <BR>
<BR>
And now, our final destination: The Strip. Up at the far end of Liberty
Avenue sits a brand spanking new garage called &quot;My Mechanic.&quot;
Ken Hagg got tired of all the rip-offs he witnessed while working in and
then managing car repair shops.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;My Mechanic&quot; is Ken's revenge. Here, you can get a first or a
second opinion on what is wrong with your car. They'll diagnose the problem,
give you a full print-out running down all the necessary parts and repairs
and even give you a companion list of estimated costs. What they won't do
is repairs. What they will do is keep whoever does do them, honest.<BR>
<BR>
Here is an owner who is literally making &quot;Customer Caring&quot; his
entire business. And to drive home the point all the more, Ken took great
pride in showing off his waiting area. It not only is decorated as warmly
as many family rooms in Pittsburgh, but even has well-stocked toy cabinets.
<BR>
<BR>
Customer Caring.<BR>
<BR>
I write these three examples for you because I believe Customer Caring should
be celebrated in these times when so many companies can barely find their
way past the bottom line to improve what is commonly known as customer service.
What I am stewing over is what to do about businesses and companies that
make big money while demonstrating absolutely no sense of Customer Caring.<BR>
<BR>
These are the firms that gleefully announce by the month new and ingenious
fees to charge for their services. The stores that by virtue of their location
have a virtual monopoly on a neighborhood's business, and yet evidence no
commitment to be a good neighbor in improving the inside or the outside
of their stores. The corporations that have demanded such absurd levels
of productivity from their employees, that a worker on the phone can't even
offer a &quot;thank you&quot; or a &quot;goodbye&quot; or any other kind
human communication because time management experts have written pleasantries
out of the script.<BR>
<BR>
They seem to view the notion of Customer Caring as quaint, inefficient,
unaffordable, expendable. <BR>
Let's run that by executives at Disney. 1995 earnings: $1.7 billion. <BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> 
<ADDRESS>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <A HREF="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments
or suggestions?</A><BR>
