<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT=
"Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H10People.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Diner.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>Cliff Shannon</FONT></I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Name: <I>Cliff Shannon</I><BR>
Occupation: President, SMC Business Councils<BR>
Age: 44<BR>
Personal: Lives in Squirrel Hill with wife Sheila Schrieber<BR>
and children Cynthia, 6, and Stephen, 4<BR>
Education: B.A., 1973, Dickinson College<BR>
Last Book Read: Charlie and the Chocolote Factory, by Roald Dahl<BR>
Last Vacation: Disney World, November 1994<BR>
</B><HR>SMC Business Councils, so long billed as &quot;The Voice of Smaller
Business,&quot; came to be known through the voice of Leo McDonough, who
served the organization for 29 years and grew it to over 4,800 members.
 This summer, he turned over the reins to Cliff Shannon, a newly returned
Pittsburgh native who's spent much of his career in Washington, D.C. When
 Shannon and his wife Sheila, an attorney, decided to return to Pittsburgh
last year, he made a list of three jobs he thought he'd like to have - and
this was one of them. Having served with Senator John Heinz and Senator
Kay Hutchison of Texas, as well as being a lobbyist for chambers of commerce,
there's no doubt that Shannon's politically qualified to take over in the
advocacy department. Here, the question then becomes, How do you replace
a legend? &quot;You don't,&quot; says Shannon, &quot;you just succeed one.&quot;
Lydia Strohl talked to Shannon about his vision for SMC in the organization's
Braddock Avenue office.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Executive Report:</B> What's been your career track to date?<BR>
<BR>
<B>Cliff Shannon:</B> I'm a native of southwestern Pennsylvania, I went
to college in Pennsylvania and got involved in politics pretty soon after
I graduated. I worked for Senator Heinz from 1976 to 1991 when he died,
but for about a two-year period I hiked off to Harrisburg to work for the
Thornburgh administration. I was Senator Heinz' chief of staff from 1984
to 1991. After Senator Heinz died, I was a lobbyist for Chambers Development
Corporation of Pittsburgh, then went to work for Senator Kay Hutchison of
Texas when she was elected in 1993, as her chief of staff.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What are the salient issues you bring from those experiences?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> Government relations is not the meat and potatoes of what SMC
does, but for its members, government relations is episodically very important.
The experience that I have and the people and things that I know should
be very useful in pursuing that facet of SMC's agenda.<BR>
<BR>
In addition, my role is to manage the group of enterprises that is SMC's
daily work, and in my work for Senators Heinz and Hutchison I managed a
varied set of efforts and 50 to 70 people with varying specialties. I think
what appealed to the board as much as my political experience was that I
had a track record of making the trains run on time, not just in one office,
but in a group of offices that were spread out from Texas to Philadelphia,
with all the things associated with that, from making the budget to hiring
and firing.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>Talk a little bit about the organization that you're inheriting.<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> SMC has grown explosively in the last half dozen years. In any
kind of growth at that pace there are some growing pains, but the work that
I'm inheriting from Leo [McDonough] is going exceedingly well, and there's
every reason for us to continue. And by exceedingly well I mean not just
growth, but continuing to provide value-added services that make membership
a plus item for them. People aren't joining SMC and paying their dues because
they like having the plaque on the wall. They can point to tangible things
that offset the cost of membership. Then there are intangible things: government
relations, human resources and some of the other services we provide that
make it a good mix for them.<BR>
<BR>
Group healthcare is for most of our members the most important service.
We have an insurance company for-profit subsidiary, and through that we
can offer any type of insurance, workers' compensation and life and disability.
We may expand the range of products that are available this year - one of
the obvious places is the high-deductible health insurance policies that
accompany the new medical savings account programs. We're going to run a
seminar on medical savings accounts for our members on November 8. We could
conceivably go into auto insurance.<BR>
<BR>
Our second most widely subscribed benefit is telephone service; we're growing
rapidly with two or three plans and 1,300 or 1,400 subscribers. We're embarking
on a package service discount plan that we think will attract literally
millions of dollars of our members' freight business because of the rates
we're able to offer. We do education and training programs, from our new
family business series that talks about issues of succession, among other
things, to the special seminars on telecom, workers' comp, energy de-reg
and so on. And we're collaborating with the World Trade Center on an export
series, so we keep busy.<BR>
<BR>
Members have a laundry list: They can get discounts on almost anything you
can think of. One of the most popular is credit reports, which businesses
use to make sure they're going to get paid.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What was the key to the explosive growth?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS: </B>Group health insurance was the catalyst for it. We were very
aggressive in getting to the businesses that needed that product and we
have a pretty good name identification among small business people. SMC
has been throughout southwestern Pennsylvania for a long time. And that's
why we're doing well in Harrisburg - because we've got a good product and
provide a range of services that your typical chamber of commerce doesn't.<BR>
<BR>
We don't provide group health insurance to all our members - one reason
is because they can now go direct to Blue Cross and get an experience-rated
individual group. That's changed our relationship with some of our older
members - they're looking to us for other services, and that's fine.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>What's the alternative?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> In many cases they were doing without health insurance, they
were purchasing a product we would judge as inferior to the Blue Cross mainstays,
or they were paying an arm and a leg to Blue Cross as an individual. Those
were the choices, and although those are not still the only choices, for
most small businesses the best alternative remains joining a group plan.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> How's managed care changing your insurance products?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> It's not changing the insurance agency's work. How it's changing
our members and their employees' healthcare security is another question,
and the answer to that question is going to determine a lot of future decisions.
One thing is certain - for an increasing number of small businesses, price
is no longer the only issue. The quality of care and reliability of services
they get through coverage are emerging as equal issues.<BR>
<BR>
The difficulty for an organization like ours and for the people that subscribe
to our group health plan is the ability to take the key person out of the
workplace for a half a day or a full day to explore a complicated issue.
If you take the leader of a group of five, the other four may not have a
very productive day. We'll run some programs, put it in the magazine, the
newsletter, send out a special mailing, hire airplanes, but your ability
to get to everybody still has bounds. But short of having enough individuals
that you can send people around to the work site, you can't do it. We have
12 member reps that have hands-on contact - but that's 5,000 members, it
takes a long time to slough through it.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Geographically, is western Pennsylvania your strongest market?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> Absolutely. Of 5,000 members, we're 300 in Harrisburg and 65
in Philadelphia.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Is there an opportunity to gain as much ground in central and
eastern Pennsylvania? <BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> It took a lot of time to gain that ground [in southwestern Pennsyl-vania].
I believe that the opportunity to grow rapidly in the southwest was a function
of the franchise, the familiarity. Because we don't have that same franchise
in central Pennsylvania, and don't have one at all in eastern Pennsylvania,
it's slower. With the general resistance to Pittsburgh in Philly, it's a
question how far we can go there. People in Pittsburgh have some idea that
there's some kind of competition, whether it's sports, tax burden, something.
But Philadelphia is an East Coast city. To them we're a Midwest city, somewhere
out there in the fields of golden wheat. There's a very big difference there.
So for us as a Pittsburgh-based company to say we want to go do business
in Harrisburg, State College, Lancaster, great. But Philadelphia, it's a
different story. We've got one person there and a couple of sales people
and we'll see what happens. Frankly, I don't know if it will work.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> What's the importance of growing the membership?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> The political influence that one can wield is a function of your
geographic scope. If you have a member from Lock Haven who can call on a
Lock Haven rep, the grassroots touch is better than anything you can get
a paid gun to do in Washington. It's not the same as if the businessman
down the street from him, who may be his lifelong baseball-playing friend,
calls on him and says &quot;My business is at stake here.&quot; That matters.
That is the best reason for us to get bigger in geographic terms. The public
policy aspect is the most important.<BR>
<BR>
But the services are our bread and butter. People won't join a group like
ours for government affairs. They are interested in the issues and upset
if they get the wrong result. But they need to see something in their everyday
workplace that is made better, whether it's credit reports, discounts on
lawyers, whatever. They may only use it once, but if they get $1,000 worth
of legal time for $275, that justifies the membership for them. <BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Coming back to Pennsylvania and looking at the issues for small
business here, have the issues changed?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> I think there has been a shift for small business. It's been
an improvement, but we have a long way to go. Whether you take tax code
provisions, state tax code, workers' comp reform, unemployment compensation
reform - there's a list of things that have improved that I think are indicative
of the growing importance of small business.<BR>
<BR>
In Texas, they are preoccupied with growing business. What seems to be most
important is built around the notion of growth. Pennsylvania is not that
way. Decisions are bound up in other things, like quality of life. No one
from Texas would ever say it this way, but the way I see it they believe
in growth and the rest will take care of itself. Here, what kind of job
it will be, what will it pay, what will it do to the air and the water,
what kind of business will it bring in, what kind of tax will it pay - all
these things are put into the cauldron. And that scares some businesses
away, and slows down local entrepreneurialism. We have much more regulation
here, whether it's ump-de-ump little municipalities and the county and the
state. In Texas, they tend to just let the state take care of it.<BR>
Is that good or bad? It depends. If you think quality of life ought to be
up at the top of the list there's an amount of regulation you're willing
to tolerate. If you think growth is paramount, the amount of regulation
you'll tolerate is considerably less.<BR>
<BR>
My theory is that for the small business community, if you can     rationalize
the regulatory superstructure, moderate taxes and keep them constant and
walk away from it, you'd never hear another peep from them about what government
could do for them, forever. The programs through SBA, Harrisburg and this
and that are helping a small band of business,       but the broad community
would best be served by rationalizing regulations and taxes. Disappear SBA,
it could all just go away - and this is heresy - if the small business people
could just know they won't get regulated out of business.<BR>
<BR>
There's been some progress. I think in Harrisburg and Washington they've
been ripping some pages out of the existing regulations. They have been
trying to pay more attention to small business concerns. Congress has put
some laws on the books that say you must, as part of your regulatory drafting,
include an analysis of what this means to small business. Congress has set
themselves up to be able to veto regulations if they don't like them for
small business effects or otherwise, and it's small business driven, I really
believe. There's still a long way to go.<BR>
 <BR>
<B>ER:</B> How will this fall's election affect the picture?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> If we have a Republican Congress, the big game in town next year
will be tax reform. There will be tax reform in the 105th Congress. If we
have a Republican Congress, reform will center around &quot;Can't we make
this system simpler and a whole lot less expensive?&quot; If we have a Democratic
Congress, you may still have tax reform, but I don't think of the same variety.
You'll get some tinkering, but I don't think you'll see any massive fooling
around with the system.<BR>
But there's still a tax bill, so you have to pay attention to that. But
[with the Democrats], the Clean Air Act, pre-authorization, that's obviously
very important to this region, and I believe the 105th Congress will address
it. OSHA reform, Superfund reform, although Congress can reauthorize the
Superfund tax over and over if it wants to, the underlying program is past
due for reauthorization, and that's a big effort. Health reform, if it's
a Democratic Congress, we'll see health reform, no doubt.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> Where does SMC fit into the structure of economic development
agencies in the area and how will the PRA affect that?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> I think the point is, with the Pittsburgh Regional Alliance,
that no one's quite sure, aside from perhaps the people that are at the
heart of it, what the landscape will look like in a few years. The goal
of streamlining local and regional development and attraction efforts is
great, long overdue and will pay dividends. But when it's going to occur
and what agency will do what  it's pretty hard to figure out how we fit
in that mix, except that we will collaborate and cooperate constructively.
Somewhere in that mix, we have some resources to bring to the table, even
if it's just matching up businesses.<BR>
<BR>
To date, collaboration has been spotty. What a regional alliance holds out
is some rational, ongoing basis for involvement. If you ask me what we do
each year I could write a list - I think a better way is to have three things
we do each year over and over. It would make more sense, would be easier
for me budgeting. For the people in the PRA it makes it easier to know they
can count on it, rather than what happens now, and that's that someone gets
an idea and then runs around to find someone to pay for it. Tim [Parks]
has got a tall order in front of him, but the upside potential is worthwhile.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER:</B> This region gets a pretty bad rap when it comes to small business.
What's the reality?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> We have demographic problems that are difficult. We have had
only incremental growth and that's a difficult proposition if you want to
compare us to some go-go place, as the Post-Gazette series did. Our labor
costs are higher. We have some things that are not good competitively, if
you think that what small business people do is look at Seattle and Boston
and Tampa. I don't think that's what people do in the main. Small businesses
tend to be home-grown, so some of those &quot;disadvantages&quot; become
less important. The fact that we have slow growth and relatively unappetizing
demographics is a real problem, no matter what the impulse for the small
business community, because their ability to make a go of the business is
affected by the pace of growth and the older population. <BR>
<BR>
That said, I think the fact that our local universities have been turning
out people with increasing willingness to stay around here and make a go
of it is a good sign. Some of the people that are hanging around are doing
what common sense says, which is growing up businesses that serve that older
population. It may not be the Wall Street Journal's favorite kind of small
business growth, but nursing care, acute care outside of the hospital which
will have the salutary effect of reducing healthcare costs, helps everybody.
<BR>
<BR>
I think there's some light at the end of the tunnel there. We've lost everything
we're going to lose in manufacturing, and the core that remains is lean,
very competitive, making products that are unique, or better than everyone
else. The labor costs are offset, I think, by the skilled workforce, a motivated
workforce.<BR>
<BR>
As for the pace of growth, Pittsburghers might want a little more growth,
but I don't think they want to grow like some of these other places do.
The good news and the bad news about Pittsburgh is that it doesn't change
much. It's the good news because it's the reason I came back, it's the reason
a lot of people stay here. The bad  news is it doesn't support people making
millions of dollars here. Someone like that might be better off somewhere
else. We have plenty of successful entrepreneurs here, it's just not go-go.
It's not like Pittsburgh explodes out by 20 percent each year with new office
complexes - that's not what this place is about. <BR>
<BR>
And it's good, we don't have the traffic and crime and pollution that the
go-go cities have that make the quality of life less desirable. We'd like
to be more prosperous, but I don't think we want to be as prosperous as
San Antonio if it comes at the price of having the quality of life deteriorate.<BR>
<BR>
<B>ER: </B>How will you have to change your mindset to assume this position?<BR>
<BR>
<B>CS:</B> I have to be more out front. There was one star of the show when
   I worked for elected officials and I   wasn't it. I'm not the star of
the show here,  but in order for the organization to have an effective public
voice I have to do more of that. Some people get a big charge out of it,
but I thought long ago that apart from the business aspect, the only person
that cared whether my picture was in the paper was my mother. And maybe
my wife and daughter.	                               <BR>
