BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Jump In</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>The Food's a Little Bit of Heaven, But the<BR>
Atmosphere Can be a Little Bit Like Hell</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Lydia Strohl </I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>Before visiting Jump - Robin Fernandez and company's new restaurant
located in their downtown &quot;social gallery&quot; Heaven - I pondered
the name.<BR>
<BR>
After a couple of visits, I've narrowed the meaning of Jump to: <BR>
<BR>
A. What every fiber of your being does for an hour after leaving Heaven,
which literally pulsates with music. <BR>
B. What you do in the 20-minute wait for the ladies' room. <BR>
C. The only way to dance on the packed dance floor.<BR>
D. What you do when the food comes, because it's wonderful. <BR>
<BR>
In fact it's &quot;E. All of the Above.&quot; So despite the fact that for
me, a trip to Heaven on a crowded Friday night was a little hellish, I say
go ahead and Jump.<BR>
<BR>
Another example of the savvy group's trend-spotting ability, Jump's menu
is diverse, less formal than Siena, more upscale than Rosebud, with international
overtones, fresh ingredients and overall consistency in bringing innovative
menu items to fruition.<BR>
<BR>
Heaven, in the former disco on Sixth Street, is beautiful. Fulfilling all
current trends under one roof, there's a velvet-clad champagne bar, a mod
martini bar, a dark-paneled cigar bar and a pool and microbrew bar. The
main bar and dance floor, complete with disco ball, dominate the space.
It's difficult to escape the dance tunes and light show, even in the restaurant.<BR>
<BR>
 Jump, which is on the second floor, has its own bar and two small dining
rooms, sparely but richly decorated. Cool high-backed steel chairs and architectural
accents make the space contemporary chic. <BR>
<BR>
And the food was really good. We started with a grilled baby squid in a
punchy lime marinade and served with  fresh salsa. The shrimp bisque was
divine: creamy, with chunks of shrimp. Raw is another trend, it seems: We
tried carpaccio, which was tender but bland without the accompanying capers.
We also had the Ahi tuna loin, seared rare and served Japanese- style with
soy sauce, wasabi (green horseradish) and gari (pickled ginger). Phyllo
envelopes stuffed with baby goat cheese, fresh berries and tarragon were
lushly tender, but too sweet for a starter. Maryland-style crabcakes were
moist, full of celery and accompanied by an interesting swirl of saffron,
chile paste and habanero pepper sauces (it's the green one that's hot).
 The winner in the appetizer queue was a delightfully subtle dish of fresh
scallops, escargot and shittake mushrooms in puff pastry, topped with a
creamy sauce of roasted shallot cabernet and goat cheese. <BR>
<BR>
The appetizers, paired with a salad,  make a fine light dinner. The salad
selection is varied: We tried the field greens salad, a delicious blend
of fresh unusual greens, topped, but not smothered, with a tart basalmic
vinaigrette. The oriental vegetable salad was a little stronger, with a
dressing of sesame seed vinaigrette coating the medley of greens, oyster
mushrooms, red peppers and crunchy toasted vermicelli noodles. Both were
liberal portions, enough for two.<BR>
<BR>
The entrees, too, show a range of influences. There is a lean toward Oriental:
Sea scallops, shittake mushroms and vegetables in a garlic-ginger black
bean sauce topped nutty Japanese Soba noodles in a beautifully combined
sweet and tangy dish. Lobster ravioli are big, hand-hewn hunks of homemade
pasta around rich lumps of lobster, only lightly seasoned and topped frugally
with a madiera cream sauce that allowed all components of the dish to star.
The chicken fusilli, however, was drowned in a bland romano cream sauce
and went un-touched. Ahi tuna perfectly seared over hardwood coals, yet
raw in the middle, was paired with refreshing salsa. <BR>
<BR>
Food aside, the details are also great - bread, baked fresh at Siena each
day, is grainy and crusty and warm. The wine list is small but complete,
though on the high side. And the service is friendly and kind - ask for
Lisa, a small, impish woman with dreadlocks, whom one dining companion dubbed
the best waitress ever. On the minus side, the cushioned benches are ergonomically
incorrect, too tall for the tables - which get small if you're doing the
appetizer buffet thing. <BR>
<BR>
Then there's the rest of the joint. On a Friday, it was noisy and loud,
difficult to talk to anyone except the people on either side of me. And
I had to leave the table for 20 minutes to stand in line for the limited
nightclub facilities. On a Tuesday, it was like a morgue, with less than
a dozen people scattered throughout the six areas. Easier on the ears and
the elbows, but a little bit disappointing if you go out to people-watch.
And who doesn't.<BR>
<BR>
Jump<BR>
107 Sixth Street, Downtown<BR>
338-2720<BR>
<BR>
Hours: <BR>
Tues. - Sat.: 4 p.m. - 11 p.m., full menu; appetizers and desserts until
2 a.m. <BR>
Sun: 9 p.m. - 11 p.m. full menu; appetizers and desserts until 2 a.m.<BR>
Mondays: Closed<BR>
<BR>
Appetizers and Salads: $3.95-$10.95 <BR>
Entrees: $9.95 - $18.95<BR>
