<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Sports Business </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Diner.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT=
"Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrTitleSportsBusiness.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363"
HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" 
HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Premium Seats</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>With More Upscale Seats, Teams Increase Ticket Revenue<BR>
Without Increasing the Total Number of Seats<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Bill Modoono</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>The relationship between professional sports team owners and the
seats located in the venues in which their teams play used to be a simple
one. Bluntly stated, when it came to seats, owners wanted as many as possible,
and filled with paying customers as often as possible.<BR>
<BR>
Nothing is so simple in sports these days, which could explain why Pittsburgh
is being made to feel inadequate in terms of its pro sports facilities.
And why Three Rivers Stadium and the Civic Arena, both well-maintained big-time
facilities in ideal      locations, are being criticized by the very teams
that have prospered while playing there for decades.<BR>
<BR>
The Pirates, Steelers and Penguins have all made serious requests in the
past year for new and/or renovated facilities to be &quot;competitive&quot;:
a '90s sports buzzword that some see as a synonym for greed. In the case
of the Pirates, a new stadium - to be located adjacent to Three Rivers -
is considered so vital to the team's long-term future here that new owner
Kevin McClatchy will be allowed to move the team if the funding is not in
place for it within three years. <BR>
<BR>
What might seem odd to some is that the stadium designed to save the Pirates
would be one with the smallest seating capacity in the National League -
roughly 36,000 seats. If the Pirates do move out, the Steelers have renovation
plans for Three Rivers, but, again, increased capacity is not the main objective.
Capacity would likely only increase from 59,600 to 65,000, which might not
even satisfy all those loyal fans on waiting lists for Steeler season tickets.
<BR>
<BR>
What will increase is the number of &quot;premium seats,&quot; a concept
pretty much foreign to Pittsburgh sports at present. The Pirates introduced
a modified version of the plan with its addition of seats closer to home
plate this year. The fans who sat there paid more to be closer to the field,
but got added amenities such as wait service. <BR>
<BR>
Joe Gordon, marketing director for the Steelers, describes club seating
as &quot;a superior type of seating with a premium price.&quot; If Three
Rivers were reconfigured, Gordon says, the Steelers could add about 10,000
club seats. Club seats would differ from luxury boxes - the desired stadium
asset of the '70s and '80s - in that the fans tend to be closer to the field
and out in the open. But club members would get amenities such as reserved
parking, wait service and access to a private lounge area.<BR>
<BR>
Of the three Pittsburgh pro teams, the Penguins are most insistent     
about wanting to add premium seating. Owner Howard Baldwin created the Igloo
Development Corp. in September to examine ways to improve and/or replace
the 35-year-old Civic Arena. And again, capacity is not the issue.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If we get a new building, it will have a larger capacity,&quot; says
Chuck Greenberg, an attorney with Pittsburgh's Cohen &amp; Grigsby who is
president of the Igloo Development Corp. &quot;But capacity is not the primary
factor in wanting a new place. Variety and location of the seating is more
important.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Greenberg believes that the Civic Arena is in an ideal location, has a strong
historic link to the Penguins and has many other &quot;attractive characteristics.&quot;
What it does not have is the 100,000 square feet of retail space for an
attached urban mall that the new MCI Arena being built in Washington will
have. Nor does the Civic Arena have wide aisles or ease of access within
the building. Greenberg contends only the loyalty of Penguins fans has kept
them from grumbling about the crowded conditions in the bathrooms and concession
stands between periods of hockey ames.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;To compete, we have to make    the building generate more revenue
and be more fan-friendly,&quot; Greenberg says. &quot;We want to make a
trip to the arena the most enjoyable experience possible.&quot;<BR>
Greenberg says Allegheny County should see a new arena as a regional asset
that will serve more than just the Penguins. <BR>
<BR>
Likewise, the Steelers have proposed lavish plans that would include North
Shore development along with the new club seats. A new Pirates stadium would
be part of that development, too. Whether taxpayers see these efforts as
contributing to the overall good is open to debate. <BR>
<BR>
There's no debate on this point: New seating plans can increase revenue
for all three teams without significant increases in attendance.       
                <BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
