<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Small Business Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Sports.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT=
"Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT=
"40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Law.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Let Sonny Sweep Up<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>By Putting Your Children to Work,<BR>
You Help Them Mature, Plus Get a Tax Break<BR>
<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Henry Lipput</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Let's say you're the owner of a small grocery store or filling  
station. You have a 14-year-old son    and are thinking of hiring him to
introduce him to the business world and give him a sense of responsibility
and financial independence. It sounds ideal for the kid, but, to be blunt,
what's in it for you? <BR>
<BR>
Well, actually, if handled correctly, there are a number of perfectly legal
tax breaks that both you and your child can take advantage of, including
payroll tax benefits with no requirement to withhold Social Security, Medicare
or federal unemployment tax. So you can actually pass some wealth to the
child, whose tax rate is more favorable. At the same time, the child learns
what it is like to work and collect a pay check.<BR>
<BR>
The downside? Don't try to pull one over on the tax man. The Internal Revenue
Service in some cases will look closely to see that the child is actually
doing some work and is not being overcompensated.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The first thing that's key in employing a child is that the compensation
has to be reasonable for the duties that the child is performing,&quot;
says Emanuel Dinatale of the Pittsburgh accounting firm Alpern, Rosenthal
and Co. &quot;In other words,  you would not want to have a child at 13
being paid as an executive or something of that nature when what they're
really doing is rendering no service or the service that they're rendering
is not worth what you're paying them. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;What we see a lot is the children doing things like stuffing envelopes
and emptying wastebaskets, cleaning up, things of that nature, which is
fairly manual labor and yet they can certainly earn minimum wage or something
that is reasonable for the service that they're rendering.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Assuming we get over that hurdle,&quot; says Dinatale, &quot;then
the parent would have a deduction for wages paid. So they would reduce their
business income, and now the child receives income. The benefit to the family
overall is that first of all, a child, when they receive this income - which
is considered earned income - they are allowed to deduct up to $3,900 [$4,000
in 1996] as a standard deduction.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But just make sure the children are doing some work.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The big problem is, what job are you going to give them?&quot; says
law professor Mark Yochum, who teaches taxation, among other courses, at
Duquesne Law School. &quot;There has to be a bona fide occupation. You just
cannot hire them and say you have hired them. I would say the No. 1 litigated
issue in tax cases in the world is unreasonable compensation. The IRS will
disallow the deduction, they may in fact litigate the issue of whether the
kid's an employee at all. But the deduction in theory is limited only to
reasonable wages. You can't pay him $10,000 a month to deliver groceries.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
A child employed by a parent could set up an IRA account, which defers taxation
until the money is withdrawn from the IRA. But if the child's only income
is from the parent's business, it may not be such a good idea. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;If the [first] $4,000 isn't taxable,&quot; says Gennaro DiBello, a
tax manager with Schneider Downs in Pittsburgh, &quot;then I guess why would
we want to do the $2,000 IRA?  From an investment side, yes, it makes sense.
From a retirement side it makes sense. However, from an income tax side
there doesn't appear to be a benefit there.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Adds Yochum: &quot;The kid would be treated like anybody else with an IRA,
and you wonder whether you want to put money away and have it tied up. That
may not be advantageous. You want to make sure that the kid has some income
that is subject to tax so that he can take advantage of the standard deduction
that he is entitled to.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
There are situations in which a child has, in addition to [his or her] earnings,
other earnings from interest and dividends that are going to put the child
into a tax bracket. &quot;Then they would want to utilize the IRA to move
their income down and be able to save not only the income tax [but] get
the [IRA's tax] deferral,&quot; Dinatale says.<BR>
<BR>
In the end, the tax break may not be that significant for the small business
owner. But that doesn't mean there's no reason to put the child to work.
It just may be more a matter of sense than dollars. &quot;The moral aspect
of work is the positive aspect of this,&quot; says Duquesne's Yochum of
the idea of hiring one's child. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;In terms of a tax [break], there isn't one of any significance unless
you can find a real job that the kid can do. But for the garden variety
guy that has a very, very small business, and not a lot of accumulated wealth,
I really don't see this as a big deal.&quot;<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> 
