<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Business Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrTitleBusinessLaw.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"
WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" 
HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Severance Agreements</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>They Can Shield You From Liability Later,<BR>
But Only if They're Handled Properly<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Jim Urban</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>When package delivery giant United Parcel Service started cutting
jobs, management offered severance packages through which employees could
resign &quot;for personal reasons&quot; and receive some compensation under
the condition that they release UPS of employment discrimination claims
stemming from the terminations. <BR>
<BR>
Two Hispanic employees signed the severance agreements, then turned around
and filed a racial discrimination lawsuit anyway. Recently, a federal appeals
court said the employees could proceed, overturning a lower court's dismissal
of the case.<BR>
<BR>
Why didn't the severance agreements shield UPS from potential liability?
The Eleventh Circuit Court of Appeals said UPS may not have given the men
sufficient opportunity to have the severance offer reviewed by an attorney.
The men claim UPS gave them only 24 hours to accept the severance offer
and would not permit them to take a copy of it home. UPS denies those charges.
Nevertheless, the facts are something the jury should hash out, the appeals
court said in reinstating the lawsuit.<BR>
<BR>
The UPS case is an example of the problems that arise when employers misstep
as they attempt to insulate themselves from liability by having terminated
employees sign waivers.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We are often called in after the horse has left the barn, so to speak,&quot;
says Joseph Perry, an attorney with Pittsburgh's Springer Bush &amp; Perry.
&quot;Once it is done - if it is not done right - you face a lawsuit, and
the big bucks can come into play.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Courts generally will look at a combination of factors in determining whether
an employee knowingly and voluntarily agreed to a severance package. The
factors include:
<UL>
  <LI>The plaintiff's education and busi-	ness experience; 
  <LI>The amount of time the plaintiff had to consider the agreement before
signing it; 
  <LI>The plaintiff's opportunity to consult with an attorney; 
  <LI>The employer's encouragement or 	discouragement of consultation with
an attorney; and 
  <LI>Whether the employer gave some-thing of value for the waiver. 
</UL>
 <BR>
Severance agreements amount to contracts, which means each party must get
something in return for what they give up. The employer is obviously getting
something: in this case, a waiver of the employee's legal rights. But what
do the employees get? A common mistake employers make is offering something
to which the employee is already entitled: already-earned salary, for example.<BR>
<BR>
On the other hand, some examples of adequate compensation - known in legal
circles as consideration - include outplacement services, continued healthcare
coverage or a lump sum of money that is not already owed to the employee.
The employer should spell out in the agreement what it is giving in return
for the waiver. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The key ingredient,&quot; says Perry, &quot;is that there must be
valid consideration. It must be clearly stated. The language must be succinct.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
More and more, employers - to avoid the kind of mistakes UPS made - go as
far as having attorneys handle the severance offer.<BR>
<BR>
The employer says 'This is over,' then I'll talk to the employee for 15
minutes and explain what the employer is proposing in the severance offer
- both the upside and downside,&quot; says William Doepken of Pittsburgh's
Doepken Keevican &amp; Weiss. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is done in a very open, honest manner. I just say 'It's up to
you, if you want to reserve these rights, you can. Go talk to your attorney.
Here's what we are willing to give you in exchange for giving up these rights.'&quot;<BR>
<BR>
For some terminations, federal law dictates how much time an employee should
have to review a severance offer. In terminations of employees age 40 or
over, the employee must have 21 days to review a severance offer under the
Older Workers' Benefit Protection Act. And if a waiver of an age claim is
sought from a group or class of employees being terminated, each individual
must be given at least 45 days to consider the proposal.<BR>
<BR>
 <B>What Does Severance Cost?<BR>
</B><BR>
Employers deciding whether to offer severance in return for a waiver must
balance the cost against what they are getting in return. If handled properly,
a severance agreement could prevent a lawsuit, bad publicity and legal expenses
that run into six figures. Nowadays, some insurance carriers refuse to cover
employers involved in discrimination litigation.<BR>
<BR>
Basic severance starts with straight monetary compensation, with some companies
offering to extend healthcare coverage. Outplacement of upper management
personnel usually costs about 15 percent of that person's former salary.
It can be expensive, but it gets the person thinking about his or her future
as opposed to dwelling on the past.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's been proven that one's propensity to litigate is reduced because
their direction and attention is focused forward,&quot; says Tom Sullivan,
a vice president in Pittsburgh with the outplacement firm Right Associates.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> 
