"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Law.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT=
"Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H15Health.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Education.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2></I>There's a Charm<BR>
<I></FONT></I><FONT size =+1>West Penn and Mercy Affiliate: They Say the<BR>
Physicians Will Be the Center of their System<BR>
</B></FONT><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>We told you it was changing fast. Just as we went to press last month
with the story of the contention between the region's top two emerging delivery
systems, the Western Pennsylvania Healthcare System and the Pittsburgh Mercy
Health System announced formation of a third.<BR>
<BR>
Officials from the two companies behind Community Health Partners, as the
new integrated delivery system (IDS) is called, say it's different than
 the other networks emerged to date.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's like having four people watching a train wreck, watching this
market evolve,&quot; says Bernard H. Crowley, vice president of managed
care at Mercy. &quot;At least three of them will see it differently. That's
where we are. We see the world differently than [AGH] or UPMC, and what
we're putting out there has a different twist.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
According to Jim Collins, vice president of managed care at West Penn, they
looked at the networks in the market and decided to beat 'em, rather than
join 'em. &quot;We wanted to be cost effective and community oriented,&quot;
says Collins, who says the system will be functional by January of 1997.
<BR>
&quot;And we have a fundamental belief that physicians should be at the
center. Doctors will be 50 percent of the board of directors and have an
opportunity to own the network.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The physician, ultimately, has ac-countability for healthcare,&quot;
says Crowley, with 23 years in managed care, most in southern California,
where he ran a Blue Cross HMO. &quot;We want to build relations with physicians,
and the physician's economic status. The physician will be able to shop,
so the hospital has to become competitive at the bottom of the equation.
If you align the incentives and let economics work, the market will shake
out.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Prime Medical Group, a 50-member multispecialty group of physicians with
one of the region's largest patient bases, already has joined Community
Health Partners.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We saw an opportunity to be at the heart of the network in terms of
governance and ownership, and we didn't see with the other two arrangements
in town where we would really be involved in the decision-making,&quot;
says Dr. Lee McCormick, medical director of Prime Medical Group. &quot;There
is clear agreement that the board will be 50/50 physicians and hospitals,
so any decision has to be agreed on by a majority of both parties.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Although the physician organizations of the five hospitals participating
in the Pyramid Health System are also part of its board, McCormick believes
the concept is different: &quot;I'm not sure that when there is an academic
medical center involved that governance truly can be 50/50. That's what
concerned us about the other two networks. The academic medical center has
to fill beds to support teaching and research programs, and that creates
a problem for primary care physicians, who are relegated to a lesser level
in the whole scheme of things.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Like Pyramid, the IDS which AGH is a part of, and Tri-State, the UPMC driven
network, Community Health Partners will be contracting on a higher risk
basis with insurers. The network will accept a lump sum for each subscriber
that chooses their network, and will count on their ability to manage that
patient's care cost effectively to maximize profit. It's called global capitation,
and out of this amount comes any testing, doctor, hospital or other costs
incurred. <BR>
<BR>
Currently, Community Health Partners has 150 primary care physicians, and
Crowley says they're looking for a base of 300 to 400 primary care physicians,
plus a cadre of supporting specialists and hospitals throughout eight counties
of western Pennsylvania. Physicians must make exclusive commitments to the
network. Both Crowley and Collins declined to give figures on the investment
required tocapitalize the network, saying that the business plan is still
in development.<BR>
<BR>
Once the structures are in place, Crowley expects that both economics and
quality will dictate that Community Health Partners physicians exclusively
will use their hospital network, which they want to expand beyond the four
hospitals currently in the West Penn and Mercy systems.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Why would we give services to someone who's not part of our network?&quot;
reasons Crowley. &quot;Allegheny General is not going to help us build market
share. If [the doctor] wants to choose AGH, maybe he should be choosing
Pyramid.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
McCormick insists, however, that the hospitals will have to mind their bottom
line, or physicians will go elsewhere - no matter what the partnering arrangement.
&quot;We probably will use them as long as they maintain their cost effectiveness,&quot;
says McCormick. &quot;But they understand they have to maintain that.&quot;
                                    <HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91"
HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91"
HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH=
"83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> 
