<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0"
ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H17Education.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT=
"40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Feature.1.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size =+2>Wired</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+1>C</I>lassroom, Dorm Room, Dining Room; Not Just for
Nerds<BR>
Anymore, Campus Computers Become Pervasive<BR>
<I></FONT></I></B><BR>
<I>By Gretchen McKay</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Fifteen years ago, the most high-tech machine a kid could take to
college was his electric typewriter.<BR>
Today, that same student is most likely lugging a personal computer to school
along with the stereo and coffeepot. And he doesn't have to dig through
the depths of the campus library to do research; a world of information
is now available right in the dorm room. <BR>
<BR>
At his computerized fingertips are dozens of databases and library card
catalogs (including the Library of Congress) as well as abstracts from thousands
of general-interest and trade periodicals, courtesy of the Internet.<BR>
<BR>
As the 21st century approaches, computing has never been more critical.
In fact, a 1995 survey by the American Association of State Colleges and
Universities discovered that more than half of those institutions polled
had computers in the classroom while nearly a quarter boasted electronic
links to individual dorm rooms.<BR>
<BR>
Probably no Pittsburgh institution is more aggressive when it comes to computing
technology than Carnegie Mellon University, which launched one of the world's
first large-scale, high-speed campus networks more than 10 years ago.<BR>
 <BR>
Today, the fiber optic &quot;Andrew&quot; network connects CMU's 10,000
students, faculty and staff through public clusters and workstations scattered
across campus. In fact, every building at the university is wired for network
access, allowing those with personal computers to simply plug into the Internet
and World Wide Web.<BR>
<BR>
Andrew also makes possible an extensive electronic mail and bulletin board
system, which enables students and faculty to communicate on-line; remote
printing capabilities allow students to print out hard copies of documents
at several campus locations.<BR>
<BR>
Computing is so important at CMU, a world leader in computer technology,
that for the past decade all first-year students have been required to take
the Computing Skills Workshop, a series of  introductory computing competency
courses.<BR>
<BR>
Why the push to get students wired?<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Without a doubt, the ability to handle technology - and use it wisely
- is an advantage in the job market,&quot; explains Don Hale, vice president
for university relations. <BR>
Technology is so pervasive at CMU, Hale adds, that computers are a &quot;tool
in every discipline&quot; and     department.<BR>
<BR>
And not just for research: Along with word processing, students use computers
to complete lab experiments, check a class syllabus or download lecture
notes, even to hold an out-of-class group discussion.<BR>
<BR>
Students can even create their own university-based World Wide Web home
page to &quot;chat&quot; or share information with others (including their
resumes). <BR>
<BR>
Computing is also an important feature at the Graduate School of Industrial
Administration, where students can access the university network from remote
locations, saving time and travel costs. The program now features the school's
&quot;Flex Mode&quot; program for out-of-state executive students, via a
new $100,000 teleconferencing system.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The business school has always been a leader in computer technology,&quot;
says Dean Douglas Dunn, Ph.D. &quot;With this program, we continue to be
on the cutting edge.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Students at Duquesne University can also expect to make extensive use of
information technology during their studies. The campus library has been
completely on-line since 1994, and the university makes available 29 public
computer labs with a total of 500 computers (though officials estimate nearly
two-thirds of all students own their own PCs).<BR>
<BR>
Though Duquesne doesn't require computer courses per se, &quot;Most faculty
expect that students have basic computing skills as well as access to the
Internet,&quot; says Cynthia Golden, director of educational technology.<BR>
<BR>
A majority of colleges require    students to demonstrate computer proficiency.<BR>
<BR>
Electronic mail, for example, is an integral part of the college experience.
Not only do professors make materials available to students via the Web,
the university employs special &quot;computer conferencing&quot; software
that allows small groups of students to hold discussions out of the classroom
with an instructor. In addition, some courses in the Saturday college are
offered exclusively on-line, and &quot;students are clamoring for more,&quot;
Golden says.<BR>
<BR>
As at CMU, all dorm rooms are wired for the college network, allowing students
instant access to the campus and other libraries. Technical support is provided
by &quot;resident hall consultants&quot; who have attended special training
programs.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There pretty much isn't anything related to computing and networking
that Duquesne students can't do,&quot; says Golden.<BR>
<BR>
For instance, when a comet recently crashed into Saturn, students had computer
images of the collision as fast as any researchers in the world.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Today's grad needs to be able to think and problem solve and use the
tools of experts in their field,&quot; Golden maintains. &quot;And those
tools typically involve computing.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Of course, you don't have to be a large university with vast resources to
be big on campus telecommunications.<BR>
<BR>
Students are granted unlimited computer use at Robert Morris College, which
has required its students to demonstrate computer proficiency in such software
applications as spreadsheets and data bases since 1983.<BR>
<BR>
The Moon campus residence halls are all wired with fiber optic high-speed
access lines, and both campuses have four mediated classrooms with flagship-level
machines. The college also maintains eight remote lines, each with 40 connections,
for off-campus students to access the network.<BR>
Both students and faculty extensively use e-mail, allowing a &quot;dynamic
exchange of data,&quot; according to Frederick Kohun, Ph.D., head of   
     the computer and information systems department. Lotus Notes, for instance,
allows small groups of students to exchange information and coordinate projects,
with an instructor commenting on the side.<BR>
<BR>
Chatham College, too, is wired for the 21st century, with a high-speed data
network that uses 16.1 miles of cable with a fiber optic backbone.<BR>
 <BR>
The Jennie system, established in 1995, allows Chatham students to check
the library's card catalog or use e-mail in their homework assignments without
stepping out of their dorm rooms.<BR>
&quot;We like to say we have a   computer connection for every pillow,&quot;
says Anne Steele, vice president of    academic affairs.<BR>
<BR>
Jennie also allows students to access, research and download everything
from entire books to Ph.D. dissertations through innumerable data bases,
as well as access hundreds of on-line library card catalogs.<BR>
<BR>
Though it is not currently on-line, Point Park College, through a partnership
with the Carnegie Library of Pittsburgh, will soon offer its students the
latest in computing through the Library Center on Wood Street.<BR>
<BR>
When completed next year, the collaboration will allow the small college
to connect to the information superhighway amid 19th century architecture.<BR>
<BR>
And tiny Westminster College in New Wilmington, Pa. has gained a reputation
for its state-of-the-art system, which rivals CMU's. In addition to free
Internet access and e-mail services from dorm rooms, the college's 1,500
students enjoy four computer labs with 125 general access computers, as
well as six specialized labs with another 50 computers. And 10 &quot;smart&quot;
classrooms boast the latest in computer and audio-visual technology.<BR>
<BR>
 &quot;Any way you can display and manipulate data electronically, you can
do it in our classrooms,&quot; says John Deegan Jr., vice president for
academic affairs and dean of the college.<BR>
<BR>
What's more, next year's curriculum (which requires all students to demonstrate
computer proficiency by the time they graduate) has been revised to &quot;embed&quot;
that technology into all four years of study.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;From day one, each of our courses will include computer technology
as an integral component,&quot; says Deegan,  something he claims will distinguish
Westminster from any other educational institution. &quot;Computing will
be part of the learning experience.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Students, for example, will have to surf the Internet to research an English
paper or master spreadsheets for a quantitative reasoning course.<BR>
<BR>
Computing technology, Deegan explains, is essential to competitiveness in
the 21st century.<BR>
&quot;It's hard to imagine how our future professionals can enter the workplace
without these skills and opportunities,&quot; he says.<BR>
