"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>What We Make<BR>
How Pay Measures Up in Pittsburgh</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+><BR>
</FONT SIZE><I>By Catherine Dressler</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Pittsburgh Mayor Tom Murphy makes $78,856 a year. Penguins star Mario
Lemieux makes several million. How much money do you make? Whatever your
answer, you probably wish it were more. It seems most of us are squeezing
to pay the bills, whether we work one job or two, wear a three-piece suit
or a uniform. Good jobs can be hard to come by, especially in Pittsburgh's
tight labor market. Long gone are the days when so many families got by
just fine on one paycheck from the steel mill down the street. <BR>
<BR>
Just how are we doing now? Which  jobs pay the most in Pittsburgh, and which
ones pay the least? Where are the  good jobs? <BR>
<BR>
Some of the answers are no surprise. Doctors and lawyers come out on top.
Housekeepers and burger-flippers are near the bottom of the paycheck food
chain. But salaries aside, all of us have something in common: the ever-
changing economy. Whether we work the same job for years or move around,
many of us must constantly reinvent ourselves professionally to stay afloat.
<BR>
  <BR>
In 1994, the average annual wage in Allegheny County was $28,642, according
to the state. That was nearly $2,000 above the Pennsylvania average. Base
salaries for Pittsburgh professionals fall about 2 percent short of the
national average, according to David A. Hofrichster, vice president and
managing director of the Hay Group human resources consulting firm. <BR>
 <BR>
&quot;There's a good, strong, conservative aspect to Pittsburgh,&quot; he
says. &quot;Having gone through all the downsizing, I think people are a
little more cautious about adding to their fixed costs.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Total compensation for Pittsburgh professionals is in line with the national
average when bonuses and other incentives are taken into consideration,
according to Hofrichster.<BR>
<BR>
A U.S. Bureau of Labor Statistics study shows that workers in the Pittsburgh
area (including Allegheny, Fayette, Washington and Westmore-land counties)
made 3 to 4 percent less than the national average in four occupational
groups in 1994. Those groups were professional, administrative, clerical
and maintenance. Janitorial workers here made 1 percent less than the national
average.  But employees in protective services, such as police officers
and firefighters, made 6 percent above the average, and technical employees,
such as computer operators and drafters, made 1 percent more. Pay in Philadelphia
and four metropolitan areas in Ohio was generally higher in the categories
surveyed. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Lawyers on Top<BR>
</B><BR>
A 1995 state survey of wages spanning 169 occupations in southwestern Pennsylvania
(excluding healthcare), showed lawyers' average annual salaries tops among
experienced white-collar workers: $84,680. But think twice before signing
up for law school.<BR>
<BR>
Pittsburgh is second only to Washington, D.C., in the number of lawyers
per capita: one in every 180 citizens, according to James I. Smith III,
executive director of The Allegheny County Bar Association. Smith refers
to the mid-1980s as the &quot;glory days,&quot; when the best and brightest
law graduates commanded starting salaries of $60,000 to $65,000 from the
big firms. In the downsized '90s, those firms are making fewer new hires
and paying graduates at least $10,000 less.<BR>
The state survey found lawyers just starting out made an average of $33,545.
But some law graduates start much lower, say $20,000; others make  $15 an
hour as law clerks. The bar association counsels graduates to consider using
their law degrees in less-crowded fields. Smith advises graduates to take
what they can get in the beginning.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There are 400 entry-level lawyers coming up behind them every year,&quot;
he says. <BR>
<BR>
Financial planners made the second-highest average pay, $73,371 a year,
according to the state survey. Charles E. Stone, a certified financial planner,
agrees the field is lucrative for those with the right credentials and attitude.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There is unlimited potential in terms of income,&quot; says Stone,
who became a financial planner about five years ago after six years as a
stock broker. He works with the Advisors Group Inc., a member of The Acacia
Group.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There are no big salaries paid,&quot; Stone says. &quot;This is a
fee or commission business.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That means to make the big bucks, financial planners have to market themselves
and build a strong client base. Says Stone, &quot;It's not a field for someone
who just goes out to make a buck. It's a trust-based business.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Among experienced white-collar workers,  the state salary survey ranked
export-import managers third, at $64,175 a year; education administrators
fourth, at $59,366; and traffic engineers fifth, at $58,163. Plant engineers
made the best pay among entry-level workers,with an average of $44,613.
 <BR>
The heart may be in the home, but the money isn't. Live-in housekeepers
made an average $14,840 a year, the least of the white-collar jobs surveyed.
Bank tellers came in second-worst, at $16,317 a year; followed by general
office clerks, $16,390; data entry keyers, $16,966; and accounting clerks,
$18,204.<BR>
<BR>
<B>The Trade Jobs<BR>
</B><BR>
Among blue-collar jobs, welders and flamecutters came out on top, with average
hourly pay of $22.20 for experienced workers. But living by welding alone
is harder than it used to be.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I'm no millionaire,&quot; says Richard Zillweger, owner of Anderson
Welding Co. in Etna. The kind of manual welding that Zillweger does in his
shop is becoming less common as more sophisticated machinery enables less
specialized workers to do the job. Some gas stations, for instance, have
welding equipment.<BR>
 <BR>
The survey ranked plumbers, pipe-fitters, sheet metal workers, tinsmiths
and millwrights next. Those trade jobs all pay more than $20 an hour on
average. Not surprisingly, waiters and waitresses get the thinnest paychecks,
with an average hourly pay of $3.18. But that figure excludes the tips that
should make up most of their income.<BR>
<BR>
Bartenders came in second-worst, at $5.15 an hour, but they, too, get tips.
Fast food pay is also low: Cooks      average $5.28 an hour, according to
the survey, while cashiers get $5.52. Personal home aides do a little better,
but not much, at $5.65 an hour. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The Painful Shift<BR>
</B><BR>
Pittsburgh's job landscape is the key to really understanding the pay picture.
As defined by the state Department of Labor and Industry, Pittsburgh's labor
market comprises the six counties of Allegheny, Beaver, Butler, Fayette,
Washington and Westmoreland. The labor force stands at 1.14 million, including
1.1 million employed and more than 55,000 jobless. The area's unemployment
rate for 1995 was 5.9 percent, the same as the state's but higher than the
U.S. rate of 5.6 percent. <BR>
Pittsburgh, like the rest of the state and most of the nation, is shifting
from a goods-producing to service-based economy.  Eighty-three percent of
the jobs in the Pittsburgh area are now service-related, encompassing fields
such as transportation, utilities, trade, finance, health, education, social
services and government. The large manufacturing layoffs that characterized
the decline of steelmaking in the 1980s are rare now, but growth in manufacturing
is stagnant. Only 17 percent of the jobs in the Pittsburgh area are in goods
production, including mining, construction and manufacturing.<BR>
<BR>
For some people, especially the less educated and skilled, the shift has
translated into lower-paying jobs that provide no benefits. &quot;With the
decline of the steel industry, many people had to accept what was available
and they did,&quot; says Roberta Wilson, a state labor market analyst. &quot;If
they wanted to stay here and work, they had to step down a notch or two.&quot;
Gone are the days when a high school diploma could land you a good job for
life with benefits. &quot;The job market of the '90s and the next century
is for the educated and the skilled,&quot; Wilson says.<BR>
<BR>
In the last several years, the number of jobs in Pittsburgh has grown very
slowly, less than half the pace of the national average. In 1995, growth
averaged 1.1 percent, translating into 11,900 new jobs. &quot;We've had
remarkably steady, but clearly unremarkable growth in jobs year after year,&quot;
says PNC Bank economist Stuart Hoffman. <BR>
<BR>
It's hard to say how many &quot;good&quot; jobs were created, the kind that
come with at least some benefits and enough pay to live comfortably and
set aside a little for retirement and the kids' college fund. It's hard
even to say how many of the jobs already in existence fall into that category,
because most statistics and studies don't gather much information about
pay scales. Employers and workers are reluctant to disclose exact pay figures.
Few subjects are considered as private in our culture as our salaries. &quot;We
have very little information on pay scales,&quot; Hoffman says. &quot;We
just don't know that much.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Technical Skills = Money</B><BR>
<BR>
Michael Zang is optimistic about his chances of landing a good job when
he graduates in December with an electrical engineering degree from the
University of Pittsburgh. Zang, 23, has worked two and a half years in what
began as an educational-cooperative program with Respironics Inc., a medical
device manufacturer based in Murrysville. With that kind of experience under
his belt, he's confident he'll be able to command at least $30,000 a year
to start. &quot;I think I'll be able to stay in Pittsburgh,&quot; he says.
&quot;There are a lot of small growing companies here.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Local recruiters and employment agencies say demand is strong and pay  solid
for workers with technical skills in the computing, information systems
and engineering fields. For example, electrical engineers just out of school
average $30,000 to $35,000 a year, according to Doug McAuley, a recruiter
with Suber and Meeks Technical Search and Placement. The same engineer with
five years' experience could get $55,000 to $60,000. The area's growing
software industry also provides good jobs, for those with the right resume.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is a very high-end industry for people with very particular skills,&quot;
says Steve Rushen, an economist at the University of Pittsburgh's Center
for Social and Urban Research. <BR>
 <BR>
Recruiters say the problem is less a dearth of good jobs than a lack of
workers with the skills to fill them. &quot;The people who are having to
settle for less perhaps haven't kept their skills up,&quot; says Steve Martin,
district manager for the Kelly Services employment agency in Pittsburgh.
A secretary without computer software skills may have a hard time landing
or keeping a job, but demand is strong for executive secretaries who are
knowledgeable about software, according to Martin. They  can command $9
to $15 an hour.<BR>
<BR>
Though scarce, manufacturing jobs in the Pittsburgh area pay better than
the national average. Production workers in the region made an average of
$14.55 an hour in June, according to a survey by the U.S. Department of
Labor. That's nearly $2.50 more than the national average of $12.10 an hour.
And it's quite a bit higher than the hourly average of $10.89 in states
like North Carolina, where the absence of unions helps keep salaries down.
  <BR>
<BR>
<B>Lucrative Healthcare</B><BR>
<BR>
A 1994 report by the University of Pittsburgh found growth in higher-paying
jobs in the fields of healthcare, engineering, management, trade, banking
and air transportation.<BR>
The healthcare field is taking a hit in the shift to managed care, though.
About 1,600 jobs were lost in 1995 due to restructuring. But the health
field still employs about one in nine workers in the Pittsburgh area, about
116,000 jobs.<BR>
<BR>
Healthcare also provides some of the best pay in the Pittsburgh area. A
1994 state survey comparing average salaries in 120 health-related occupations
in the region found experienced plastic and reconstructive surgeons made
the most, $242,000 a year. Those just starting out in this field didn't
do badly, either, at an average of $175,625. Radiologists were not far behind,
at $239,296, followed by urologists at $201,000. Ophthalmologists, surgeons,
cardiologists, obstetricians, orthodontists, otolaryngologists and pathologists
earned an average of $162,000 to $199,000 a year. <BR>
<BR>
But the picture is very different for  some technicians, assistants and
aides. The lowest-paying job of the 120 surveyed was veterinary technician,
which pays an average $14,294. Chiropractic assistants were next, at $14,325,
followed by dental assistants, optometric assistants and nurse's aides,
all of whom made less than $16,200. <BR>
<BR>
Other healthcare workers do much better: In 40 of the 102 occupations compared,
salaries for medical workers in southwestern Pennsylvania exceeded the statewide
average. Plastic and reconstructive surgeons had the largest difference,
exceeding the state average by nearly $53,500. Despite hospital  downsizing,
and sometimes because of it, good jobs can still be found.  <BR>
&quot;Although we've had so many mergers and acquisitions on the hospital
side, there's still a lot of growth,&quot; says  Joni Lampl-Seiavitch, vice
president of Management Recruiters of Pittsburgh-North, which helps fill
positions in the medical field. <BR>
<BR>
The demand for medical assistants, for instance, is very strong, according
to Florine Stevenson, a medical assistant at the St. Francis Central Hospital
satellite office in Brookline. &quot;Not only can you work in a hospital,
but you can work in a doctor's office, laboratory, any healthcare setting,&quot;
she says. Stevenson raised her seven children as she worked for 31 years
in the medical field, first as a nursing aid in a sterilizing unit at Presbyterian
Hospital. The hourly pay for medical assistants with experience and good
training ranges from $15 to $20, Stevenson says. Starting pay is closer
to $7 to $10 an hour.  <BR>
<BR>
Others are finding new niches in the world of managed care. For example,
registered nurses laid off by hospitals are marketing their practical knowledge
and moving to medical device manufacturers, insurance companies and HMOs.
&quot;They know the other side of it,&quot; says Lampl-Seiavitch. Many nurses
making the change have not had to take cuts in the salaries they got at
hospitals, which typically ranged from $40,000 to $50,000.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Nurses became desirable for information-technology companies and insurance,&quot;
Lampl-Seiavitch says.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Performance-Based Pay<BR>
</B><BR>
If it seems like you're making enough to stay just ahead of inflation, you're
typical. Salary increases averaged 3.9 percent in 1996, according to a survey
by the consulting firm Hewitt Associates. &quot;Like it or not, flat-base
salary increases are here to stay,&quot; says Ken Abosch, Hewitt's compensation
group leader. But the picture isn't all bleak because more companies are
handing out incentive bonuses in the form of special recognition awards,
performance awards and cash profit-sharing. Some of the payments are tied
to the company's performance overall while others focus on the worker or
a particular unit. Most of these bonuses are annual, but some cover periods
over a few years.  &quot;It's more results- and outcome-oriented than ever
before,&quot; says Hofrichster, from the Hay Group consulting firm. <BR>
<BR>
That means annual performance reviews are more important than ever. With
the emphasis on results, many companies are making performance appraisals
more comprehensive. Some companies are involving not only bosses, but peers,
subordinates and customers in the review process. &quot;The old days of
just pleasing your boss and counting on a pay raise are over,&quot; Hofrichster
says. Companies are more likely to give poor or mediocre performers no raises
so they can give more to the star performers. On average, 10 to 15 percent
of workers get no annual raise, Hofrichster says. That's a departure from
the past, when everybody got at least a token increase.  <BR>
The sometimes-harsh realities of work today are prompting some to take a
hard look at salaries and ask, &quot;Is it really worth it?&quot; Patricia
DiVecchio founded Life-Work International several years ago in Pittsburgh
to help people find the work they truly want to be doing. &quot;I think
people are looking at salary as one among many things,&quot; DiVecchio says.
&quot;They're more willing to sacrifice salary for work that they love.
They're willing to scale down and shift a bit. Most people say their job
is about making a living, but is it really about making a living or making
a dying?&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Zang, the Pitt electrical-engineering student, says salary will not be top
priority when he evaluates job possibilities. &quot;I would look at other
things first, the opportunities, benefits, the work environment,&quot; he
says. &quot;For me, happiness doesn't come with making 'X' amount of money.&quot;
In the uncertain, tough world of work today, that might be the most healthy
perspective.          <BR>
<BR>
