<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Feature </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Feature.1.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0"
ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H1Features.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Supplement1.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+><B>Cash From Trash<BR>
</B></FONT SIZE><BR>
<I>By Cynthia Bent</I><BR>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>When John puts his newspapers out to be recycled, where do they go? It
depends. A city truck might come along and take them to a processor. Or
he might have to drop them off at a bin himself. From there, the processor
can bale and sell them to any one of a number of places &shyp; a de-inking
mill that will make more newsprint or other low-grade paper out of it, a
farmer who will use it for animal bedding, or maybe to  a plant that turns
it into blown-cellulose insulation.<BR>
<BR>
Or maybe, if the price of paper is low, the processor will dump John's newspaper
straight into a landfill.<BR>
<BR>
Recycling's growing pains in the city of Pittsburgh are a good snapshot
of what's been going on regionally, and in fact, nationwide. Prins, the
city's former recyclables processor, made headlines when, unable to get
enough money for the material on the open market, it was caught dumping
the city's recyclables into a local landfill. <BR>
<BR>
Understandably, the city canned Prins, renegotiating the contract with a
new processor, Browning-Ferris Industries. But current market prices for
glass, plastic and metals aren't very favorable: Now, instead of receiving
$42.50 a ton for its bottles and cans, the city pays BFI $53 a ton to take
them off its hands &shyp; at least for a year, the term of the new contract.
Considering that landfilling trash costs just $16 per ton, is recycling
worth the hassle?<BR>
<BR>
Area recycling started in 1989. At that time, a mere one percent of the
waste stream got recycled. Now, countywide, it's more like 12 or 13 percent
and growing. And it's also law. Pennsylvania's Act 101 mandates that municipalities
of over 5,000 people strive to recycle 25 percent of their trash.<BR>
Recycling sometimes has been a cheaper alternative to landfilling municipal
waste here and sometimes, as presently, not. Volatile markets cause difficulties
in getting money out of recycled goods, and the long distance to some processing
mills makes things more difficult. A prime example &shyp; a shortage of
newsprint here in the U.S. combined with a short-term surge in demand overseas
caused the price of newsprint to skyrocket last year. Then came a glut in
supply as everyone jumped into the market, and this year, prices have fallen
again.<BR>
<BR>
As a result, the price processors get for old newspapers has shot skyward
and then plummeted in the space of one year. To complicate matters, newspapers
from western Pennsylvania have a ways to go to the nearest de-inking plant
to be recycled. Some paper is shipped as far as Canada and Mexico. Municipalities
that last year depended on hefty revenues from old newspapers can't even
pay to get rid of them.<BR>
<BR>
But it is possible, those in the industry maintain, to run a successful
recycling program. Their definition of a successful program: One that uses
recycling as an integrated part of overall waste management programs, not
as the be-all, end-all solution to garbage, and not one that mandates a
clear profit all the time from its recycling. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We have to get over the idea of recycling as a cash cow,&quot; says
Don Berman, former Allegheny County recycling coordinator. &quot;People
in the industry know it fluctuates with supply and demand. As a part of
the overall waste management scheme, properly meshed, recycling can be a
good strategy.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Trash It<BR>
<BR>
Some people say it's not worth the bother.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Bulk municipal solid waste is just not an environmental problem here
now,&quot; says Chris Hendrickson, professor of engineering and director
of the Green Design Initiative at Carnegie Mellon University. &quot;There's
plenty of landfill space, it's inexpensive, and modern landfills are very
safe.&quot; His team at CMU has done extensive studies to show that recycling
in some situations not only costs more, but also is more environmentally
damaging, through extra fuel consumption, pollution, and wasting of resources
that could be directed elsewhere. &quot;We're more interested in separating
toxins from the waste stream. We're advocating battery collection, for example.&quot;
Hendrickson also believes a greater emphasis should be placed on designing
products and packaging to generate less waste in the first place.<BR>
<BR>
The recycling industry &shyp; and the public &shyp; objects strenuously
to this attitude. Proponents try to show that recycling generates resource
conservation, jobs, economic development and energy conservation, as well
as conserving the environment.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;It's more than just a shame to throw these things away,&quot; says
Mark Lichtenstein, president of the National Recycling Coalition Inc. &quot;Recycling
is a multi-million dollar business. We've got to look at this stuff not
as trash, but as commodities.&quot; He cites statistics that attribute over
100,000 jobs in the northeastern U.S. to recycling, in processing and manufacturing.
<BR>
<BR>
And recycling is in public demand. &quot;We like to say recycling is more
popular than democracy,&quot; says Lichtenstein, citing statistics that
say recycling programs across the country have an average 70-80 percent
participation rate.<BR>
<BR>
Recycling can, say its backers,   support itself, and more, if properly
managed &shyp; managed like a business, with an eye on the fact that recyclables
are commodities, and the market for them is cyclical, like any other. And,
they say, recycling is the only service a city can provide that has the
potential to earn revenues back.<BR>
<BR>
A snapshot glimpse of the steel industry shows what can happen when the
infrastructure for recycling is laid. Steel recycling is more than a bonus
&shyp; it's integral to the process, and it's big business. All steel made
in this country consists of some, and sometimes all, recycled steel. The
networks of its distribution have been developed over more than a century,
going back to scrap dealers traveling door to door looking for old pots
and pans. Now, the industry's recycling rate is 68 percent. There are, obviously,
technological differences between recycling metal and plastic or paper,
but still, the story can provide useful perspective. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We've had more than 100 years to develop this infrastructure. We need
to look at the long term as other industries develop technologies to integrate
use of recycled content,&quot; says William Heenan, president of the Steel
Recycling Institute. He predicts with commitment, plastic and paper industries
will use as much recycled material in manufacturing as the steel industry
does.<BR>
<BR>
Trash Savvy<BR>
<BR>
There are a couple of key elements to the recycling chain. First, a municipality
can get the most bang for its bottles by providing a clean, consistent stream
of material, working together with processors.<BR>
&quot;You've got to know what you're doing, be in it for the long term and
establish good partnerships with your processor,&quot; says Jim Guyaski
of BFI. &quot;You can't overreact to down markets and panic. If you build
into your relationship a system to share the risks and the profits, you're
going to be successful. But it takes trust.&quot; He'd like to see a contract
with the city with an indexing system worked in, so that if prices for commodities
were up, both would share the profits, and the losses.<BR>
&quot;If all the risks fall onto the processors, we have to make sure we're
covered,&quot; he says, which drives up the costs for the city on any contract.
&quot;But until there's trust that everyone's working together, that's not
going to happen.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Quality sells,&quot; says Vince Tarentino, marketing development coordinator
with the state's recycling department. &quot;As you demonstrate over time
that you can provide uncontaminated materials, that's not forgotten by the
mills when markets are down.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If you bring in a good clean load,&quot; agrees Jim Guyaski of BFI,
&quot;it's a winner for everyone. The key thing we're weak on in this area
is that people have to know what the processor can accept. Like, not all
containers are recyclable.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Soda bottles, for instance, are often made of two types of plastic, one
recyclable, one not, and have to be weeded out by hand at BFI. Motor oil
bottles may have the recycling symbol on the bottom, but unless they're
properly rinsed out, they're too contaminated to sell, so BFI has to pick
them out too.<BR>
<BR>
In September, Pittsburgh kicked off a new public-education program, Wastebusters,
to take on the challenge of involving residents in recycling. Youth will
be a key focus of the $100,000 campaign, with programs aimed at the classroom
and at recruiting school-age volunteers to canvass and spread recycling
gospel.<BR>
<BR>
Tarentino and others also advise smaller municipalities to band together
and deal as a unit with processors to gain clout. Right now, most of the
smaller communities around western Pennsylvania try to go it alone, and
they just don't generate enough trash to make themselves attractive. Negotiating
one big, long-term contract makes life easier for the processors than trying
to hammer out a dozen small ones. The bigger the haul promised to processors
and mills, the better.<BR>
<BR>
One band of municipalities in the South Hills learned this first-hand. Back
in the mid-80s a few boroughs - Baldwin, Brentwood and Whitehall - got together
on a waste collection contract and found they were able to get a better
deal as a unit than alone. The strategy worked just as well when recycling
came along in 1989. Since then, Jefferson, Castle Shannon and Pleasant Hills
jumped on the bandwagon, and the deals got even sweeter.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;To the best of my knowledge,&quot; says Edmund Reddy, secretary/manager
for Whitehall borough, &quot;we're the largest collection in western Pennsylvania.
It's worked out great for us.&quot; To get a better deal, says Reddy, the
state needs to lend a hand by creating markets for the material they generate.<BR>
&quot;You need end users. The state should push a de-inking plant, so hauling
newspaper isn't so expensive. We need to ensure markets, and that's not
our responsibility on the local level.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Don Berman echoes Reddy's wish for a de-inking plant, and so does BFI's
Guyeski. Others suggest the state commit to driving markets by buying recycled.
In the end, they all say, you have to spend a buck to make a buck. Working
to attract manufacturers, and nurturing industries with new technology is
the next step in developing a recycling infrastructure. That will mean jobs
for the area, a market for the material, and success for recycling.<BR>
<BR>
The state does have incubation projects. Administered by the Ben Franklin
Technology Center in Pittsburgh, the Environmental Technology Research and
Development Fund awards challenge grants to Pennsylvania companies like
Aeolian Enterprises, a Latrobe company that uses plastic from milk jugs
to make lumber.<BR>
<BR>
The state also works in other ways to attract industries. Tarentino's job
is market development. The advantage, he says, would be low cost raw materials
for the region &shyp; a distinct economic advantage.<BR>
&quot;In general,&quot; he says, &quot;there is an opportunity for recycling
to work in western Pennsylvania based on the fact that there's over 2 million
people generating waste, and that Pittsburgh has a great location, being
within an hour of 60 percent of the U.S population.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But he hands much of the responsibility back to the municipalities, saying
he doesn't see a lot of strategic long-term planning or commitment to ride
out market highs and lows. <BR>
<BR>
The city is working on its own long-range plans. Pilot programs for collecting
from bins, instead of tying bottles and cans in blue bags, were launched
in September. Fourteen new dual-compartment trucks are due in the city,
to keep separate mixed plastics and cans from newspapers, making it possible
to take the two streams to different processors.<BR>
<BR>
One step closer: Collection of newsprint stopped in June after the Prins
debaucle, but the city recently signed a one-year contract with Pittsburgh
Recycling Services, which will pay $5 a ton for old newspapers.<BR>
<BR>
There are success stories. Most of the empty Iron City (and other ) bottles
in the city end up at MONAC, a granulator in South Hills, which sells most
of its glass to Glenshaw glass, which sells most of its bottles to Pittsburgh
Brewing Company ... so every time Pittsburghers heft an I.C. Light, chances
are, they're buying recycled &shyp; the final step in the recycling circle.
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
