<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Feature.2.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0"
ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><IMG SRC=
"../hci/H1Features.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="363" HEIGHT="40"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Supplement2.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>The Sky's The Limit</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1></B><BR>
<B></FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Vince Gagetta</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>It's a &quot;Field of Dreams.&quot; That's how the managing partner
of a large and growing downtown law firm that is bursting at the seams and
eagerly searching for a large block of office space in the Golden Triangle
describes the Pittsburgh office market. &quot;And if they build it,&quot;
he adds, &quot;we will come.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The &quot;it&quot; he refers to is not a new baseball park but new Class
A downtown office space. And when he says &quot;we will come,&quot; he really
means &quot;we will move.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
&quot;And so would a lot of other law firms, financial services companies
and similar operations who want and need to be downtown,&quot; he continues.
&quot;What so many firms like ours are looking for are big blocks of contiguous
space where we can consolidate our operations. And we can't find any that
suit our needs.&quot;<BR>
	<BR>
The Golden Triangle is a &quot;Field of Dreams&quot; for just about everyone
involved. Users of large blocks of office space are dreaming about more
space becoming available to give them more mobility and flexibility. Building
owners are dreaming of a significant increase in lease rates that for several
years have been sluggishly low. So have developers who say they need to
see rental rates in Class A central business district buildings approach
something close to $30 (current average: approximately $21.50) before they
think seriously of building new office space.<BR>
<BR>
Everyone would like to see those dreams come true in 1997. But none of them
are holding their breath.<BR>
<BR>
Pittsburgh, especially the Golden Triangle, has been a remarkably stable
commercial real estate market for several years and is likely to remain
so, unless there is a dramatic change in available Class A office space.
Despite a stubbornly sluggish local economy, corporate displacements and
downsizing, and what some see as a marked deterioration of downtown retail
properties, rental and occupancy rates for both office and retail space
have remained virtually constant.<BR>
<BR>
The question on everyone's mind is: Could there be a significant change
in the status quo in 1997? And the answer from realtors, developers, building
managers, tenants and other interested observers of the real estate scene
is: Not likely. <BR>
<BR>
William E. Burroughs, president of Scott &amp; McCune Co., a downtown commercial
realtor, for example, is looking for rental rates to rise only &quot;very
gently in the next two years.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
George H. Kingsley III, executive vice president and district manager for
Grubb &amp; Ellis, downtown, says we &quot;may see some shifting in the
market in 1997,&quot; but he expects the Class A market to remain tight
and Class A rates to increase only slightly in the new year.<BR>
<BR>
Peter Sukernek, general manager of the Hanna Commercial Real Estate Services
unit of Howard Hanna Co., is looking for continuing strong development activity,
but he expects stability to be the watchword again in 1997. <BR>
<BR>
The latest available report on commercial real estate in Pittsburgh by the
Galbreath Co. states that &quot;Pittsburgh continues to enjoy a stable market
and will experience moderate increases in occupancy, rental rates and absorption
throughout the remainder of the year.&quot; The year referred to is 1996
but all things in the report point to 1997 offering more of the same.<BR>
<BR>
Another sentence could be added to all of these statements, beginning with
the word &quot;unless&quot; - as in unless the Pittsburgh Cultural Trust
secures a major tenant for its proposed new office tower on Penn Avenue
near Seventh Street and begins construction plans (as may already have happened
by the time you read this); or unless Federated Investors decides to build
its own signature building downtown if, of course, it decides not to commit
to being the Trust's major tenant (which also may already have been decided).<BR>
<BR>
It's not that there aren't blocks of vacant office space in the central
business district, some of them in such tony Class A addresses as the USX
Tower, Mellon Bank Center and One Oxford Centre, some in less elegant but
still very respectable Gateway Center, and still others in up-and-coming
buildings like the former Gimbels department store. But they generally are
not the large, sprawling, contiguous blocks that tenants like the law firm
mentioned earlier are lusting after. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's next to impossible to satisfy anyone looking for 150,000 square
feet or more downtown,&quot; claims Jeffrey B. Ackerman, president of Brokerage
Services for CB Commercial/Arnheim &amp; Neely. &quot;That's why people
are looking for new construction.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
As well they might. There hasn't been an office building erected in the
Golden Triangle in the long lean years since the last building boomlet,
which saw the construction of CNG Tower (1987) and Fifth Avenue Place (1988).<BR>
<BR>
The next new downtown office building most likely will be the Cultural Trust's
16-story office tower on Penn Avenue. Plans call for the tower to be flanked
by a new building to house the Pittsburgh Public Theater and a 10-story
parking garage with spaces for 686 cars. Because of the city's financial
involvement in the project, the tower can defy conventional wisdom which
dictates that one should not build an office building here for lease to
outside tenants unless and until rental rates rise to the $30 level. But
the first shovel won't be pushed into the dirt until someone commits either
to being the building's only tenant or to leasing a substantial chunk of
the building's 400,000 square feet of space.<BR>
<BR>
Almost everyone assumes that the &quot;someone&quot; will be Federated Investors,
the giant mutual funds management firm currently the sole occupant of Federated
Investors Tower near the David L. Lawrence Convention Center. Federated,
which also rents space in at least two other central business district buildings
under leases that will expire in the next 30 months, wants to consolidate
its financial services operations, which are growing at a rate that is nothing
short of phenomenal.<BR>
But Federated spokesman J.T. Tuskan says his company's decision on new office
space has been complicated by factors other than rental rates and space
availability. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Not only are we involved in negotiations with the Cultural Trust to
come up with a reasonable square footage rate, we also are waiting to see
what action (City Controller) Tom Flaherty will take on the business privilege
tax,&quot; Tuskan said in late September. &quot;The two issues, a favorable
lease rate and the business privilege tax exemption, go hand in hand. But
we can't make a long-term commitment to taking new space in the city until
the business privilege tax issue is resolved.&quot;<BR>
Flaherty filed suit to overturn an exemption from the city's business privilege
tax for financial services companies that was granted by the state legislature
and has the strong support of Mayor Tom Murphy.<BR>
<BR>
Federated wants to stay downtown but does not need to. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;We can operate the type of business we're talking about in Green Tree
or Cranberry or out near the airport,&quot; Tuskan pointed out. <BR>
<BR>
He needs not add that it would be a real blow to downtown should the company
decide to relocate out of the city. Federated, which started out in 1976
with 80 employees managing $800 million has grown to be a $90 billion company.
By the end of 1996, Tuskan says, mergers and acquisitions in the works will
make Federated a $105-billion business employing 2,000 people - 1,800 of
them downtown.<BR>
<BR>
Speculation about when the Cultural Trust's tower will be built and who
will occupy it has taken some of the limelight away from a significant development
downtown that already is under way and promises to have a major impact on
business in the Golden Triangle: the new downtown Lazarus store at Fifth
Avenue and Wood Street. Site work for the new store began last August and
the store is scheduled to open in late 1998.<BR>
<BR>
Arnheim &amp; Neely's Ackerman says the Lazarus store is the first new department
store to be built in a major American city in 10 years, the most recent
being in Washington, D.C. And he thinks the new store already has begun
to affect the Fifth Avenue retail market, which has grown a little shabby
in spots over the years. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Retailers already are lining up    to get spots near the Lazarus store,&quot;
   he says. &quot;Downtown retail is coming back strong.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That's a point all the realtors interviewed for this article agreed on.
Grubb &amp; Ellis' Kingsley calls the new Lazarus store &quot;a real stabilizing
factor in what continues to be a very competitive market.&quot; And Galbreath's
commercial real estate report points out that Lazarus also is renovating
its suburban stores in an effort to solidify its position in this market.<BR>
 <BR>
Burroughs of Scott &amp; McCune says the Lazarus project also impacts office
occupancy in the central business district: &quot;The demolition of the
buildings at Fifth and Wood for the new store eliminates a lot of marginal
office space that has been underused or vacant for a long time.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
That is the only way the Lazarus downtown project will affect office occupancy
rates. One of the original proposals for the project included the construction
of an office tower above the four-story store and underground parking garage
at some later date. That is not going to happen, says Steve Leeper of the
city's Office of Economic Development. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The story was that we were considering reinforcing the garage foundation
so it would support an office tower, should it be decided at some future
time to build one,&quot; he says. &quot;But that was only a preliminary
consideration and the story got blown way       out of proportion. We have
no plans to add an office tower to the project, so the garage is not being
reinforced to support one.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Class A office developments downtown get most of the attention, but things
are happening in some of the smaller, older buildings that merit mentioning.
Burroughs of Scott &amp; McCune looks for developments along Fourth Avenue
in the old Bank Center and nearby buildings to cause some excitement in
1997.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The move of the downtown and business branches of the Carnegie Library
to the Bank Center building and the opening up of space in the Commonwealth
and Union Bank buildings because of National City's move to Riverfront Center
will focus some attention on the Fourth Avenue area,&quot; he says. &quot;Those
older but well- maintained buildings are very attractive to smaller tenants
looking for quality space at a reasonable rate.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Downtown's smaller, older buildings &quot;are the backbone of this market,&quot;
Burroughs believes.<BR>
Steady as she goes may be the forecast for CBD real estate activities in
1997, but things in the city outside the Golden Triangle - the so-called
fringe market - and in the suburbs are proceeding at a much more lively
pace. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The fringe market has outperformed the central business district,&quot;
points out Kingsley of Grubb &amp; Ellis. &quot;Things are beginning to
move on the North Side, and look at Station Square. A big factor in Station
Square's success is the subway, which provides easy access from downtown.&quot;<BR>
Jeffrey Ackerman calls the conversion of the Allegheny Center retail mall
on the North Side to 100 percent office space, most of it already leased,
&quot;a major success story.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
As for new office construction in the fringe market, the Rubinoff Co. has
received approval from the Urban Redevelopment Authority of Pittsburgh to
build another office building on Washington's Landing, the 42-acre island
in the Allegheny River under the 31st Street Bridge that used to be called
Herrs Island. The 30,000-square-foot office and flex space building will
be the fourth such building Rubinoff has built or is building on the island,
where a 90-unit townhouse development also is being completed.<BR>
<BR>
If the fringe market is hot, the suburban market is hotter - and has  been
for several years, especially the Parkway West corridor. There is a lot
 of movement in the corridor, but  quality vacant office space does not
stay vacant long.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The suburban market generally is very strong,&quot; observes Hanna
Commercial's Sukernek. &quot;Continued activity in high-tech development
certainly helps to drive this market, especially in the western corridor
and the northern suburbs.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The northern suburbs, particularly Cranberry Township, have risen to rival
the Parkway West corridor as a development hot spot. How hot is it? It is
probably the only place in the market where anyone would even think of building
an office building on speculation. Not one but three buildings with a total
of 90,000 square feet of office space are going up in Cranberry, and the
proposed rental rates are not far below those being charged for Class A
rates in the Golden Triangle, according to Ackerman of Arnheim &amp; Neely.<BR>
<BR>
Kossman Development Co. hopes to begin construction on two new office buildings
in its Steuben Plaza development on Route 60 near I-79    in Robinson Township
in 1997. But construction of the twin towers,      each 130,000 square feet,
will not  begin until &quot;we get a firm, long-      term commitment from
a major      tenant,&quot; says Tony Dunn, president      of Kossman Development's
Kossman Realty Co. unit.<BR>
<BR>
Elsewhere in the suburbs, construction already is under way on the Pointe
in North Fayette, a $23 million project near Robinson Towne Center, and
the $22 million Rostraver Square development in Westmoreland County, among
many others at all points of the compass.  <BR>
<BR>
