<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Supplement1.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH=
"363" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" 
HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>The Action Behind the Action </FONT></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>What's Driving the Wave of Mergers and Acquisitions in the Banking
Industry?<BR>
For Starters: Less Regulation and the Banks' Desire for Market Stability<BR>
</B><BR>
<HR>If you've grown attached to the name on your local bank branch, brace
yourself. It's no secret that bankers have fallen in love with the idea
of merging, and they're getting together at an unprecedented scale.<BR>
<BR>
Early this fall, PNC Bank Corp. completed conversion of all Midlantic Bank
offices and consumer products to PNC. During the past eight months, Midlantic
and PNC Bank have integrated their products, staffs, back-office operations
and branch networks.<BR>
 <BR>
The Midlantic deal carried a price tag of $2.84 billion, but it wasn't the
biggest area bank buyout. That honor fell to First Union's $5.4 billion
takeover of First Fidelity last June.<BR>
<BR>
The forces driving these deals are more than banking whimsy.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The competitive nature of the industry is changing,'' says attorney
Henry S. Pool of Pittsburgh's Tucker Arensberg, a law firm that counsels
numerous banks in the region.<BR>
<BR>
Simply put, most of the services you used to go to the bank for, you can
now get elsewhere. And to counter that competition, some banks think they
need to be: 
<UL>
  <LI>Much larger, so they can afford expensive, but more efficient technology;
and
  <LI>Freed from regulatory shackles, so they'll have an even chance against
Wall Street and other challengers.
</UL>
Some banks are getting together just because the federal government finally
is allowing it, Pool says. A new federal banking law is clearing away barriers
to interstate banking, so banks are merging to take advantage of opportunities
they spot in other states. <BR>
<BR>
Analysts also say banks are eager to branch across state lines to protect
themselves against severe local recessions, such as the one New Jersey suffered
within the past decade, crippling Midlantic and First Fidelity for a time.
With branches in many regions, the operations in a prosperous area could
offset those in a depressed one.<BR>
<BR>
Some Northeastern banks only recently have repaired the damage   they suffered
in that recession, and some aren't sure what to do for             an encore,
analysts say. They're          vulnerable to another regional downturn,
and their markets no longer       are growing. Deposits in the Pittsburgh
area, for instance, have fallen from about $75 billion in the early '90s
to $69 billion now. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Bigger Is Better<BR>
</B><BR>
In today's banking parlance, mergers are what work. Just ask Thomas W. Golonski,
president of National City Bank of Pennsylvania, formed in August 1995 when
Cleveland-based National City Corp. acquired Integra Financial Corp., a
$15 billion in assets bank holding company.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Banks need economies of scale to fight competition,'' says Golonski,
who was once president at Integra. &quot;We were ready to take the next
step and the merger let us do that.''<BR>
<BR>
Under the terms of the merger, Integra shareholders received two shares
of National City common stock for each share of Integra common stock in
a tax-free exchange. The merger will be accounted for as a pooling of interests.
Based on the recent market price of National City stock, the transaction
had a value of $62.75 per share, for a total of $2.1 billion, or 1.96 times
book value. <BR>
<BR>
The combined company now has assets of $50 billion, deposits of $35 billion
and stockholders' equity of $4 billion.  But the merger is not an indication
that the market will no longer be important to the larger company.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We think our strengths remain in our strong local client base,'' Golonski
says. And in September, Golonski and others unveiled the new 158,000-square-foot
headquarters for National City Bank of Pennsylvania at the corner of Fort
Pitt Boulevard and Stanwix Street. Golonski says the building will be the
headquarters for retail banking, commercial banking, credit, trust, legal,
marketing, finance, human resources and National City Brokerage.<BR>
<BR>
A new branch is scheduled to open in its lobby in the next several months.
National City Bank of Pennsylvania, with 263 branches in 23 western Pennsylvania
counties, is the largest bank within the National City Corp.<BR>
<BR>
If anything, the new entity seems geared to bring more strength to serve
these clients. &quot;Our technology budget, for example, at National City
is $50 million,'' Golonski says. &quot;And we are excited about our new
private client group.'' Through that new venue, Golonski says financial
planning and personal trust business will be handled.<BR>
<BR>
Industry analysts say the National City deal was a match made in heaven
because Integra was at a point where it had to grow to stay competitive.
And much of that growth is expected to be generated by these new areas of
banking service, like National City Investments - a full brokerage house
where customers can buy stocks and bonds.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Will Mergers Slow?<BR>
</B><BR>
A recent Dun and Bradstreet report predicts that by the year 2000, super-regional
banks will dwindle from the current 65 to about 13, and the number of commercial
banks will slump from 13,000 to about 8,000. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The surge to merge will continue,'' Pool says. <BR>
<BR>
Merging helps banks eliminate branches and jobs, to better make operations
fit a shrinking business. When PNC said it was buying Midlantic, it also
announced that 63 redundant branches would be shut and jobs would be eliminated.
Meridian Bancorp said it would close 24 branches and get rid of 1,107 jobs.
CoreStates Financial eliminated 2,800 jobs and 37 branches in March 1995.
<BR>
<BR>
They're not alone. In a 1996 Right Associates survey of 269 U.S. banks and
financial institutions, almost seven of ten companies responded that they
have downsized in the past 19 months. Six of ten reported that they plan
to in the coming 18 months.<BR>
<BR>
Why the cinch? For years now, American consumers have been turning from
bank deposits to investing in mutual funds. Rather than borrow from banks,
they're getting personal loans from credit card companies and home loans
from mortgage brokers.<BR>
<BR>
American businesses also are abandoning banks. In the past, &quot;only the
very biggest'' companies sold bonds or stocks on Wall Street, but now technology
enables thousands to do so, according to research from the Federal Reserve
Bank of New York. <BR>
<BR>
Instead of turning over paper documents to bankers for lengthy analysis,
companies can now ship their financial statements to Wall Street computers,
where analysts can organize and analyze them quickly and less expensively.
<BR>
<BR>
The Reserve Bank study found that only small and midsize companies are still
bank-dependent, too small for securities firms to bother with. Any firm
with real heft can go straight to Wall Street and probably get better rates
than it would from a bank.<BR>
<BR>
Bankers and analysts say one of the reasons PNC was so eager to buy Midlantic,
and First Union to buy First Fidelity, was that the two acquired banks were
strong in New Jersey, a state  flush with midsize companies. With Wall Street
posing no threat to that lending niche - at least for the time being - banks
have their profitable way with those borrowers.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We now operate on a unified basis from New Jersey to Kentucky and
are at the forefront of banks operating with a common set of products and
systems,'' says Thomas H. O'Brien, chairman and chief executive officer
of PNC Bank Corp. <BR>
<BR>
Garry J. Scheuring, vice chairman of PNC Bank Corp. and former chief executive
officer of Midlantic, says customers have access to a broader array of PNC
Bank products and expanded delivery systems.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Fending Off Wall Street</B><BR>
<BR>
Wall Street also poaches consumer business. Mortgage brokers and credit
card companies bundle their loans and resell them in the securities markets.<BR>
  <BR>
It's a mass-production version of banking, and it's possible only with advanced
computers to channel the loan payments from the borrower, through Wall Street,
and into the hands of many investors, a Dun and Bradstreet report says.<BR>
<BR>
One big buyer of those securities is the mutual fund business, which undercuts
bank lending and also makes it tougher for banks to get deposits. <BR>
<BR>
Without expensive branches and tellers, a mutual fund often can offer a
better return than a bank. So it was no surprise that bank deposits had
fallen from 23.7 percent of household financial assets in 1980 to just 17.9
percent in 1992, according to Federal Reserve data. Meanwhile, mutual funds
had grown from 1.8 percent of those assets in 1980 to 8.4 percent in 1992.<BR>
 <BR>
That was an impetus for the Mellon and Dreyfus merger in 1994. Merging with
the Dreyfus mutual fund company helped Mellon become the nation's second-largest
investment management firm, with assets under management totaling approximately
$200 billion. The value of the transaction, $1.8 billion, was accounted
for as a pooling of interests. Dreyfus shareholders received 0.88017 shares
of Mellon Corp. common stock for each of the approximately 36.6 million
Dreyfus shares outstanding.<BR>
<BR>
The merger, together with Mellon's 1993 acquisition of The Boston Co., made
Mellon a diversified financial services company with a bank at its core.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Services = Customers<BR>
</B><BR>
Banks don't expect customers to put up with busier tellers and longer lines.
They're looking for new technologies that will make banking quicker and
easier: ATMs, banking by phone and banking by personal computer.<BR>
 <BR>
In September, Industry.Net and PNC Bank established a strategic alliance
to provide multiple payment and financing options for business to complete
electronic transactions in Industry.Net's Online Marketplace. The payment
system will provide companies with multiple payment options, including credit
cards, purchasing cards and electronic funds transfers.<BR>
<BR>
By itself, replacing expensive people with expensive machines won't solve
the bank's efficiency problems, analysts say. The key to making technology
pay is to keep it busy all the time, and that requires customers and more
customers. <BR>
<BR>
But the Pittsburgh area is not growing, so banks can find customers only
by merging, or by growing       their services to attract customers from
elsewhere. <BR>
<BR>
One area of growth is credit cards. Last year, banks mailed out 2.7 billion
preapproved credit card solicitations - roughly 17 offers to every American
aged 18 to 64. That averages about $130,000 of available credit per household.
Consumers have leaped to make use of it, according to a study by a Tarrytown,
N.Y., research firm. <BR>
<BR>
It is moves like this one that will in the future define a new culture for
successful banks. And the banks that do survive will have to prove themselves
nimbler and more flexible with their services, and more responsive to  
  consumer needs.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif" BORDER=
