<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Supplement2.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH=
"363" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Supplement4.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" 
HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Pile it on Now, Reap Rewards Later<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Christopher Lawton</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Cynthia Wang came a long way - literally - to study for dual masters
degrees in industrial administration and computational finance at Carnegie
Mellon University. Born and raised in China, she studied biomedical engineering
there until her father had an opportunity to start a software company in
the United States. Wang finished her degree at the University of California
at Santa Barbara, then quickly began her pursuit of the dual masters degrees
at CMU.<BR>
<BR>
She expects the dual degrees       will take her a long way, too - in  
    big business. <BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Early on,&quot; Wang says, &quot;I learned that I was very interested
in math and computers and wanted to continue my education to prepare myself
for a career in either consulting or high finance. The MSIA/MSCF dual degree
program will prepare me for the highly technical work environment of Wall
Street as well as the quantitative environment of a consultant specializing
as a financial analyst for business and fixed-income planning.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
That sounds like a plan, and Wang is not alone. More and more students at
the graduate level are pursuing dual degrees with the expectation that more
doors will open for them along their career path once they are finished.
And the schools, which are recognizing the trend, are offering an ever-increasing
variety of dual degrees. Penn State, for instance, is combining business
education in its new five-year, dual degree program in which students can
earn a Ph.D. in pharmacology while they also earn their MBA. Students conduct
their Ph.D research during the day at Penn State's Milton S. Hershey Medical
Center in Hershey. They take their MBA classes at night and on weekends
at Penn State's Harrisburg campus.<BR>
<BR>
The program is geared toward people who plan to work for small to mid-sized
biotechnology firms. When they finish the program, they have management
skills in addition to scientific expertise. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;[Scientists] find themselves managing labs rather than working in
them,&quot; says Mel Billingsley, professor of pharmacology in the college
of medicine at the Hershey Medical Center. &quot;As soon as they step away
from that design bench, they are immersed in very different kinds of activities
- scheduling, managing personnel, budgeting and coordinating programs.&quot;
<BR>
<BR>
Many in the private sector believe their scientifically trained staff often
lack the essential business skills of management, financial, strategic planning
and teamwork. The Penn State program addresses that.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Any way you look at it, a dual degree makes you more versatile, better
educated and more valuable to an employer,&quot; says Eugene Miller,   
         the author of Barron's Business Guide to Graduate Business Schools
and           a holder of two graduate degrees     himself - in chemical
engineering and journalism.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Young and Old<BR>
</B><BR>
Students in dual degree programs range from the young, inexperienced, newly
graduated undergraduate student to the older, more experienced business
professional going back to get credentials in another field.<BR>
 <BR>
Rich Milesky, who is currently pursuing his MBA and law degree at Duquesne,
is an example of the former. Most of his law classes take place during the
fall and winter, with MBA classes taking time away from his summers.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;I attended right after finishing my undergraduate work because I already
felt that I was used to the environment of school,&quot; says Milesky, who
hopes to work in either the legal department of a major corporation or use
his MBA to transition into upper management in a large corporation.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Either way I'll be open to more opportunities and I'll be better networked
by obtaining two graduate degrees rather than one,&quot; says Milesky.<BR>
<BR>
His classmate, Jeff Myers, takes the same courses but is in a different
situation. Like many working professionals, he pursues the often expensive
degrees while working, putting in long hours of study and lots of hard work.
<BR>
<BR>
Myers works for the supermarket chain Giant Eagle, where he's responsible
for real estate acquisition. Just over two years ago, Myers decided to strengthen
his knowledge of his work, which led to his pursuit of the MBA/JD at Duquesne.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The MBA program will enable me to shore up my current background in
real estate acquisitions while the law degree places me on equal footing
when dealing with attorneys on topics like contract negotiations and leasing
issues,&quot; says Myers.  <BR>
<BR>
Myers' days start early at the office and end late at school, but he says
there is also an upside to the fact that he's a working professional.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Although it's difficult to work full-time and also attend graduate
school, I'm able to bring more to my class because I have practical business
experience. And senior management at Giant Eagle supports me in obtaining
my degrees by being much more flexible with my schedule at work.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>Not For Everyone<BR>
</B><BR>
The dual graduate degrees work for someone like Cynthia Wang because she
has an idea of how she will make those degrees work for her later. Those
who don't have a plan are taking a risk, educators say. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Individuals who are interested in obtaining a dual degree must be
practical in their reasoning,&quot; says Robert Nachtmann, director of master's
programs for the University of Pittsburgh. &quot;Not only must students
be focused in their thinking, but also they must be willing to look at and
interpret what the market will demand of them.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Michael Weber, provost and academic vice president at Duquesne, agrees.
&quot;Because of the time and financial commitment involved in obtaining
a dual degree, students must have a vision of where they want to be in five
to eight years,&quot; says Weber. <BR>
<BR>
In recent years, the four branches of the military have also shown an increased
interest in dual degrees. Currently at CMU's Graduate School of Industrial
Administration, at least 25 students pursuing dual degrees come from or
currently serve in the military. These students seek the    technical and
managerial deepening   of a dual degree program, school    officials say.<BR>
<BR>
In many cases this is the reason that the best student is one who has practical
work experience and lessons from life to bring into the classroom. Lawyers
pursue master's degrees    with a concentration in managed healthcare; doctors
get MBAs so     they can manage their own practice under managed care; and
accountants study law. <BR>
<BR>
According to Pitt's Nachtmann, &quot;It's not foolproof, but a second degree
protects a student by making them a better risk. It implies that the student
is ambitious, perserverant and a self-starter.&quot;  <BR>
<BR>
<B>Undergraduates Too</B><BR>
<BR>
Dual degrees often don't begin for students at the graduate level. At most
colleges and universities, students are encouraged to pursue dual degrees
or at the very least, dual majors. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our goal at the University of Pittsburgh is to advise undergraduate
students at the earliest possible opportunity about the scope of dual degree
and double majors available to them for consideration,&quot; says Fred Kolac,
director of advising at the college of arts and sciences at Pitt. &quot;Our
advising staff tries to stress to the student that it would be better for
them to wait until graduate study to undertake a dual degree.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Kolac says a double major achieves the same results at the undergraduate
level as does a dual degree, but with less years spent in the classroom.
<BR>
<BR>
&quot;If a student makes the decision early enough in their academic career,
usually by the end of their freshman year, they can finish a double major
in four years. However, that same double major earned as a dual degree can
  take a student five years, with very     little additionally gained for
future employment.&quot;<BR>
 <BR>
Statistics for double majors on the undergraduate level and dual degrees
at the graduate level continue to show an upward spiral of interest from
students and corporate recruiters alike. <BR>
&quot;In the last three to four years, 20 percent of the students who graduate
from the school of arts and sciences do so with a double major,&quot; says
Kolac.<BR>
<BR>
Additionally, statistics are increasing on the graduate side of the equation
as more students continue to select dual degree programs. But the director
of masters programs at Pitt, Nachtmann, offers a word of caution.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Even though enrollment and interest is higher among students who like
the idea of a dual degree, it's not  for everyone. It requires a student
to have developed and processed quantitative mental abilities as well as
a      willingness to sacrifice time and money in the process of earning
a higher degree toward future employment in the marketplace.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
<B>A Sampling of Dual Graduate Degrees Offered in the Region</B><BR>
<BR>
There are several universities in western Pennsylvania that offer dual degree
programs. Here is a sampling of some of the programs:<BR>
<BR>
Duquesne University
<UL>
  <LI>MBA and Law 
  <LI>MBA and Masters, Management Information Systems
  <LI>MBA and Masters, Health Management
  <LI>MBA and Masters, Pharmacy
  <LI>MBA and Masters, Liberal Studies
  <LI>MBA and Masters, Nursing
  <LI>MBA and Masters, Science &amp; Environmental Management
</UL>
<BR>
Information: 396-6000.<BR>
<BR>
University of Pittsburgh
<UL>
  <LI>MBA and Masters, International Business
  <LI>MBA and Masters, Public and International Affairs
  <LI>MBA and Masters, Area Studies
  <LI>MBA and Masters, Management of Information Systems
  <LI>MBA and Law 
  <LI>Masters, Public Health and Ph.D. in Social Work
  <LI>Masters, Public Health and Law
  <LI>Masters, Health Promotion &amp; Education
</UL>
 	<BR>
Information: 648-1700 (MBA) or 624-3002 (PH) <BR>
<BR>
Carnegie Mellon University
<UL>
  <LI>Masters, Industrial Administration and Masters, Computational  Finance
  <LI>Masters, Industrial Administration and Masters, Business and Software
Engineering
  <LI>Masters, Industrial Administration and Masters, Civil Engineering
and Management
  <LI>Masters, Industrial Administration and Masters, Environmental Engineering
and Management
  <LI>Masters, Industrial Administration and Masters, Information Networking
  <LI>Masters, Industrial Administration and Law (Joint program with theUniversity
of Pittsburgh Law School)
  <LI>Masters, Industrial Administration and Masters, Collective Private
and Public Management and Policy
</UL>
(Some programs are earned jointly with other schools <BR>
within the Carnegie Mellon University system.)<BR>
<BR>
Information: 268-2272.<BR>
