<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Supplement</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="113" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44"
NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="91" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><A HREF="1196.Contents.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Contents" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="83" HEIGHT="44" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="1196.Supplement3.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="67" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG=
"3"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH=
"363" HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"><A HREF="1196.Editorial.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN="BOTTOM" WIDTH="39" 
HEIGHT="40" NATURALSIZEFLAG="3"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Doing It Right<BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<HR></CENTER>
<P>This Year's Regional Honorees in the Arthur Andersen<BR>
Enterprise Awards for Best Business Practices Show <BR>
How They Share Knowledge, Foster Innovation, <BR>
Satisfy Customers and Motivate and Retain Employees<BR>
<HR>American International<BR>
GAI Consultants<BR>
Guardian Protection Services<BR>
Management Science Associates<BR>
Metabolic Care Center<BR>
<BR>
Michael Baker Corp.<BR>
Send Me No Flowers<BR>
Solid State Measurements<BR>
St. Barnabas <BR>
Thermal Industries<BR>
<BR>
When you purchase custom replacement vinyl windows from Murrysville-based
Thermal Industries, the relationship doesn't end once the installation is
complete. First, there's the completion certification form that the homeowner
must sign to express satisfaction. Got a problem? First it's solved, then
it's logged and analyzed to preclude a recurrence.<BR>
<BR>
And the customer focus doesn't stop there, which is one reason why Thermal
is on the list of regional winners in the 1996 Enterprise Awards for Best
Business Practices, a program sponsored by Arthur Andersen's Enterprise
Group, Duquesne University's A.J. Palumbo School of Business, PNC Bank and
Johnson &amp; Higgins.<BR>
<BR>
Thermal won for its customer satisfaction strategies. Other regional winners
include GAI Consultants for sharing knowledge within its organization and
Michael Baker Corp. for fostering innovation. Another local business, Send
Me No Flowers, won the Small Business Enterprise Award. Six other companies
were finalists, and all 10 are now eligible for Arthur Andersen's national
awards program. They also will be recognized Nov. 14 at a Pittsburgh symposium
featuring the best business practices among the area's businesses.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;By recognizing these companies, we help them share the wealth of business
practice knowledge they have developed,&quot; says Arthur Andersen partner
Joseph Morando.<BR>
<BR>
All entrants submitted multipage responses to the entrance application.
Space constraints prevent Executive Report from going into detail about
each company's practices, but what follows is a brief synopsis of each of
them.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Satisfying Customers</B><BR>
<BR>
The process of customer satisfaction includes multifaceted, long-term and
systematic programs that help a company meet or exceed the customer's expectations.<BR>
<BR>
There's a difference between paying lip service to quality and actually
giving customers what they want, when they want it.<BR>
<BR>
Company leaders must be active, regularly visiting with key customers and
spending time and effort communicating the customer-based focus to employees.
Beyond that, senior management must also monitor customer satisfaction performance.
It's a simple question: Are the customers satisfied?<BR>
And it leads to another question: Are you giving the customers what they
want? In business, it's called understanding the market. Companies that
have   mastered this principle listen to the customers at   multiple levels
to gain both strategic and tactical understanding of their needs, passing
that information back to the company's research and development department.<BR>
<BR>
Some companies spread the customer satisfaction focus throughout the workplace
by pinning financial incentives to customer satisfaction numbers or awarding
employees for going beyond the call of duty.<BR>
<BR>
Thermal windows are custom-made, so every window being made has already
been sold to a customer, whether that is the homeowner, or the remodeling
contractor who personally contacts the homeowner. Staff members in the 20
Thermal branch offices talk daily with remodeling contractors and homeowners,
then pass information to the corporate service, engineering and marketing
departments. Formal surveys are kept to a minimum, since they can often
present a distorted level of satisfaction or dissatisfaction. Nevertheless,
the company constantly keeps a finger on market feedback, funneling information
back for possible product modifications and new product development.<BR>
<BR>
For instance, when the market wanted the look of a wood window and the durability
of a vinyl window, Thermal came out with a hybrid true wood inside/vinyl
outside window. Thermal is responsive to market demand, but does not lose
sight of customer satisfaction. <BR>
<BR>
In many instances, the remodeling contractors offer Thermal financing to
customers as a sales enhancement, and about 1,500 to 2,000 homeowners annually
elect to pay via the revolving credit plan. But Thermal has turned this,
too, into a customer satisfaction tool. Thermal conducts a telephone audit
of all credit plan buyers once installation is complete. If Thermal finds
anything short of total satisfaction, it withholds payment to the remodeling
contractor until the problem is remedied. The customer has the further remedy
of withholding payments to Thermal, which means Thermal is charged back
by the financing company.<BR>
<BR>
Incidentally, Thermal was charged back only once in three years. Even then,
the customer was eventually satisfied and resumed making payments.<BR>
<BR>
The other finalists in the customer satisfaction category were American
International Removals Inc. and Solid State Measurements Inc.<BR>
 <BR>
American International is a moving company based in the airport corridor
specializing exclusively in the international shipment of household goods
for families relocating overseas. Upon completion of each move, an American
International representative phones the family and asks questions designed
to generate crucial feedback about the move process. Account managers also
visit corporate accounts periodically to review services and brainstorm
possible improvements. <BR>
<BR>
The other finalist in the customer satisfaction category, Solid State Measurements,
manufactures semiconductor processing instrumentation. SSM keeps in touch
with customers by conducting numerous seminars and training courses throughout
the year. Management also travels extensively to meet with and solicit feedback
from customers. Since the company is relatively small, top management can
easily interact with every employee in the company regarding customer satisfaction.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Fostering Innovation<BR>
</B><BR>
The process of fostering innovation includes practices that companies employ
to empower individuals and teams to generate ideas and transform those ideas
into products, services or process improvements that eventually are implemented.
Innovation has two basic phases:
<UL>
  <LI>Inventing new products, services or processes that provide value to
the customers; and
  <LI>Commercializing: bringing to market the new products, services and
processes.
</UL>
The drive to be an innovative company must come from the top. Without committed
leadership,     a company isn't likely to devote the financial resources
to the process of fostering innovation, nor will it create an environment
in which employees are encouraged to take risks with new ideas.<BR>
Beyond leadership, there must be an organizational structure that funnels
and commercializes  those ideas  consistent with the company's vision and
strategies. And then there's human resources' role in creating a climate
that promotes and rewards creativity, risk-taking and decision-making.<BR>
<BR>
The judges found all those characteristics at Michael Baker Corp. Take Baker's
push to make Geographic Information System services a core competency. GIS
is the application of computer graphics technology to spatial analysis of
mapping data. It sounds more complicated than it is. An example: Baker used
GIS to reduce the results of about 14,000 soil samples onto computerized
maps that illustrated environmental contamination at the site of a former
chemical company near Erie. Today, the state constantly updates the data,
and Baker's GIS illustrations provide a constant up-to-date picture of the
site's remediation.<BR>
<BR>
Baker is a diversified provider of engineering, construction and operations
and maintenance services. The corporation is divided into five market-focused
business units that serve the buildings, civil, transportation, energy and
environmental segments. Its exposure to computers first came in the '50s.
The push to take GIS companywide as a core competency came in the '90s.<BR>
<BR>
Company leadership supported the push with funding and operations support,
putting together a core competency committee that included representatives
from the five Baker business units. Each member led a subcommittee that
helped champion GIS within their respective unit. The company speeded up
implementation by empowering employees to act, in some cases, without executive
approval. <BR>
<BR>
The process works. Since the creation of the GIS Core Competency Committee,
Baker's active GIS contracts have more than doubled, from 35 to 76. Recent
customers include the U.S. Department of Defense, a major oil company and
a steel company.<BR>
<BR>
The other finalists in the innovation category included Metabolic Care Center
and Management Science Associates Inc.<BR>
<BR>
Metabolic Care Center is a medical practice located in Greenville that uses
several cutting-edge methods of patient treatment. When a new product or
service is developed, an employee gives a detailed description of its impact
on other employee functions, patient flow, market need and financial impact.
From there, the product or service is taken into a three-month trial, from
which it can progress to permanent development. One example is a smoking
cessation program.<BR>
<BR>
Management Science Associates Inc. develops technology and analytic systems
for the information industry. MSA sees innovation as short-term risk taking,
but long-term risk-avoidance. It expects to continually update systems and
capabilities. Business solutions are never stagnant. Employees are encouraged
to generate ideas and are drilled with the reasoning that if only one of
ten ideas pans out, that's success.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Sharing Knowledge<BR>
</B><BR>
The process of sharing knowledge includes practices that companies employ
to ensure efficient access to information while stimulating the sharing
of ideas across all employees. Generally, such a process requires significant
expenditure to update and acquire new information technology and unrelenting
efforts to change the workplace culture from one of information hoarding
to one of knowledge-sharing.<BR>
<BR>
Successful companies today leverage their intellectual assets - their employees
- allowing them to use and exploit information together. Some knowledge-sharing
tools are simple, such as newsletters or companywide memos. Others aren't
so basic. Some companies draft resource maps that identify all the resources
within the company or develop expert lists that identify people with expertise
both inside and outside the company. What matters is how often and how broadly
they are used, and how effectively they work in the knowledge-sharing process.<BR>
<BR>
GAI Consultants provides civil and environmental engineering services to
clients in a variety of industries. The company was started in 1958 by a
group of young engineering students from Carnegie Mellon University. Today,
it employs over 400 and has offices in Pennsylvania and four other states,
but still works a personal touch into the process of sharing knowledge.<BR>
<BR>
Senior officers, for instance, know all employees by their first names and
act as mentors. So do the group managers and client managers. When  necessary,
mentors have been formally assigned to individuals.<BR>
<BR>
GAI also recently adopted Total Quality Management, a program specifically
designed to     create and share knowledge. And GAI employs a     full-time
librarian to assist individuals in finding      relevant project information
or history, technical journals, current news and information on relevant
regulations.<BR>
<BR>
The other nominee in this category is Metabolic Care Center, which set up
and modified a weight management program based upon input from employees
who deal with the patients. Initial ideas are discussed in a staff meeting
for early refinement, then the idea is tried on an experimental basis for
three months.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Motivating Employees<BR>
</B><BR>
The process of motivating and retaining employees encompasses practices
that encourage and keep employees performing at their potential. Highly
motivated employees are more apt to provide creative solutions to problems,
work harder, be more productive and have lower absentee and turnover rates.<BR>
<BR>
The process starts with company leadership, which communicates through words
and actions the value the company places on its employees. Job structure
is important, too. The best companies recognize that the diversity of workforce
demographics requires greater flexibility in structuring jobs. That may
mean allowing two part-time workers to share one full-time job or allowing
an employee to work from home.<BR>
<BR>
Performance feedback also is critical, helping employees to understand exactly
what is expected of them and offering the opportunity to share their concerns.
And there's always compensation: The best companies ensure that their compensation
levels are externally competitive and internally equitable.<BR>
<BR>
Of late, more and more employers empower their employees, soliciting their
input on how to cut costs or speed up processes. Studies show a direct,
positive link between involvement and commitment, which can in turn increase
motivation.<BR>
<BR>
The best employers also continually train employees in the company's core
competencies, strengthening the company's competitive position while helping
the employees reach performance goals and move their careers along.<BR>
<BR>
While the regional judges did not pick a winner in this category, two employers
were designated as finalists in the category.<BR>
<BR>
Gibsonia-based St. Barnabas Health System gives all departments the responsibility
of establishing goals that will motivate, train and retain employees. It
also pays close attention to compensation, polling competitors and reviewing
its own wage scales quarterly to ensure the wages are equitable. Employees
who wish to further their education in areas that can be utilized within
the corporate structure are reimbursed 100 percent. St. Barnabas also rewards
employees (with airline tickets to Florida) who create and prove ways to
save the health system money.<BR>
<BR>
The other finalist, Guardian Protection Systems, motivates employees two
ways, the most basic of which is financial reward based upon performance.
As sales goals are achieved, compensation increases. If the sales people
generate their own leads that end in sales, their bonus increases. The other
motivation involves personal recognition of high achievers by bestowing
upon them monthly and annual awards. Guardian also publishes rankings of
the various sales people.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Small Business Winner: Customer Satisfaction is a Science at Send Me
No Flowers<BR>
</B><BR>
To Robbin Steif, the customer is always right.<BR>
<BR>
Take the time a client hired her company, Pittsburgh-based Send Me No Flowers,
to deliver a gift basket to one of the client's business associates. The
only problem was that the business associate who was to receive the gift
basket had a partner who was getting nothing. And by the time the client
who placed the original order with Steif had remembered the other business
partner, the original gift basket was on its way.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;No problem,&quot; said Steif.<BR>
<BR>
She immediately sent a second basket to the same office for the partner.
The delivery person told the office manager that Send Me No Flowers had
mistakenly placed the second basket on the wrong truck.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The customer didn't have to look bad,&quot; Steif says today. &quot;We
were the ones that looked bad. And meanwhile, the office manager roundly
criticized our delivery person. It wasn't even our fault, but we took the
blame.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The commitment to customer satisfaction is why Send Me No Flowers is the
Small Business <BR>
Award recipient in the Arthur Andersen Enterprise Awards for Best Business
Practices. The judges liked Steif's obsession with satisfying customers
at all costs.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There is such a strong customer service ethic here,&quot; says Steif.
<BR>
<BR>
People work so hard to please the customer. It starts with me and it filters
down through the organization. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's really not hard. I started this business myself. When people
come and tell me something was wrong, it's as though they are slapping me
across the face.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
So Send Me No Flowers goes to great pains to make sure the customer is satisfied.
All first-time customers are educated as to exactly what will be delivered.
That way, there's no disappointment because the gift is not what they expected.<BR>
<BR>
They also get a call to check their level of satisfaction once the order
is delivered. Some say the recipient loved it. Others say they never heard
anything from the recipient. In that case, Steif's staff goes back to work,
calling the recipient under the guise that the driver was new and his deliveries
are being audited.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Just to make sure, we play the sleuth,&quot; Steif says. &quot;If
the delivery was OK, we'll call the sender back and tell them 'This is what
they said they received.'&quot;
<P><CENTER><HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
