<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Editor's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Supplement4.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H4Editor.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Bad Deals </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Even the best Deals Can Go Awry;<BR>
Here's Hoping We Don't Add to the list</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Jim Urban - Editor-in-Chief</I></B> </CENTER>
<P><HR>Some might say that Michael Carlow, who will be sentenced this month
for stealing about $31 million from PNC Bank, has set himself up to be a
two-time winner in Executive Report's annual Best Deals awards. We honored
his purchase of Pittsburgh Food &amp; Beverage in 1992 for Best Regional
Impact. He's the odds-on favorite to win next year in the category Best
Plea Bargain. <BR>
<BR>
It was Carlow who during the spring negotiated a deal with federal prosecutors
that will keep Carlow's father out of prison in exchange for Carlow's guilty
plea to charges of bank fraud, conspiracy, embezzlement and wire fraud.<BR>
 <BR>
Carlow will likely spend at least six and a half years in prison, according
to federal prosecutors.<BR>
Executive Report, along with Price Waterhouse, annually honors deals and
the people behind deals that have economically benefited western Pennsylvania.
A blue-chip panel of judges annually convenes to offer insight on various
nominees. You probably read about this year's winners - including American
Video Glass Co., the Pittsburgh Pirates and the Sen. John Heinz Pittsburgh
Regional History Center - in last month's issue.<BR>
<BR>
I jest, obviously, when I talk of Carlow getting an award for the disposition
of the criminal charges against him. But I'm hardly laughing when I look
at past deals gone awry. A few have been outright flops. In 1991, for instance,
we honored City Pride Bakery in the Most Innovative category. It suffered
through a cash crunch and was taken over by Carlow, who eventually closed
it down within 17 months of its opening. And the other Carlow fiasco  speaks
for itself.<BR>
<BR>
Some other deals just haven't panned out like the judges originally hoped.
In 1991, for instance, we honored WorldClass Processing as the Best Start-Up.
It still employs about 60 people in Ambridge, but lofty plans for a minimill
that would have employed about 400 have fallen through.<BR>
<BR>
Some also might say that Pittsburgh International Airport - the Best Regional
Impact winner in 1991 - hasn't panned out like we thought. For one, it sorely
lacks cargo handling capabilities, limiting its influence on the region's
economic growth.<BR>
<BR>
That brings me to another look at this year's winners. I hope the Pirates
will get their new stadium, securing the future of the team in the city.
I hope attendance at the Heinz History Center surpasses expectations. I
expect American Video Glass - a joint venture including Sony and Corning
- to prosper.<BR>
<BR>
One of the other winners this year was the Working Together Consortium,
honored in a new category labeled the &quot;Spirit of Pittsburgh.&quot;
Indeed, the consortium's work deserves praise. It has benchmarked our region
against others and set a strategy to create 100,000 new jobs by the year
2000, a lofty goal.<BR>
<BR>
I hope the consortium reaches that goal, but wonder if it will. At the consortium's
Competitiveness Summit in April, we heard various talks about what was going
to happen. The consortium was preparing to do this, getting ready to do
that. What had it actually done? A lot of planning, but what the region
needs is action.<BR>
<BR>
I remember, as a college intern years ago, writing my monthly rundown of
my tasks ... I was preparing to do this and was getting ready for that.<BR>
<BR>
My supervisor replied: &quot;Did you actually do anything?&quot;<BR>
<BR>
So here's a friendly reminder to the Working Together Consortium: Plans
sound good. Results will sound better.<BR>
<BR>
I wouldn't want the consortium forever linked in my Best Deals memories
to Michael Carlow. <BR>
