<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Publisher's Note </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Editorial.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H3Publish.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.GuestEditorial.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> </CENTER>
<P><B><IMG SRC="../pictures/publisher.gif" BORDER="0"
ALIGN="LEFT"><BR>
<BR>
<FONT SIZE=+2>World Class<BR>
In the Global Economy,<BR>
Good Is Not Good Enough</FONT SIZE> <FONT size=+1></FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Linda A. Dickerson - Publisher <BR clear=all></I></B><HR>Last month,
four friends took separate jaunts to Italy. Some went for business, others
for pleasure.<BR>
Although one can draw many useful conclusions from these individuals' observations
about the latest developments in Europe, the most provocative insight to
me was the noticeable change in their pizza preferences upon their return.
An aficionado of Pittsburgh pizza, I immediately sensed my friends' more
discretionary palate.<BR>
<BR>
The pizza that my friends and I ordered together a thousand times before
no longer sufficed. To me, Pittsburgh pizza remained adequate.  I've never
visited Italy. However, to these European travelers, without exception,
the pizza that they enjoyed here before was no longer appealing.  Their
culinary standards rose because they were exposed to world-class standards
in pizza production.<BR>
<BR>
As Americans become more mobile, crossing the boundaries between nations
rather than cities when they travel, they irrevocably enhance their expectation
levels. Good is no longer good enough to someone who's experienced the best.
Vive la difference.<BR>
<BR>
Because of this city's inherent insularity, Pittsburgh-based businesses
frequently fail to recognize world-class standards, much less meet them.
 Many Pittsburgh business leaders erroneously believe that they've effectively
buffered themselves against global competition.<BR>
<BR>
And fragmentation pervades the Pittsburgh culture. The celebrated efforts
of the Working Together Consortium, the region's action agenda for cooperative
economic development, attempt to fuse disparate revitalization initiatives.
Pittsburghers work hard. No doubt about it. That's the legacy of a city
with steel pulsating through its veins. But hard work without the synergies
available through cooperation will not suffice.  Disjointed diligence characterizes
much ofwhat we do here, obviating the potential benefit of our hard work.
The Working Apart Consortium would be a better title for Pittsburgh's efforts
to date.  At least our hard work prevented us from having to call  these
efforts the Falling Apart Consortium.<BR>
<BR>
Regions that cooperate to enhance their own collective competitiveness will
prosper in tomorrow's     environment.  Those regions which collectively
amass the resources    necessary to be world class will be able to compete.<BR>
<BR>
 Those which don't won't.<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
