<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Guest Editorial </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Publisher.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H5Guest.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Downsizing</FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>When You Use it to Get Rid of Problem Employees,</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>You are Asking for All Kinds of Trouble</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Judith E. Yankovic</I></B><HR></CENTER>
<P>As corporate America strives to increase profitability by minimizing
expenses, workforce downsizings have become commonplace. The first question
to be resolved involves the selection of employees to be terminated. While
&quot;poor performers&quot; and problem employees are the most logical choices,
a road full of land mines could be created, particularly if the performance
and problems were previously unaddressed. <BR>
 <BR>
We may assume that employees are getting accustomed to downsizing; however,
these types of terminations produce shock waves in the organization. In
many situations, the corporate culture and employee attitudes toward the
company are changed significantly. Nevertheless, the intensity of the employee
backlash can be mitigated by perceptions of fairness and legality.<BR>
<BR>
Often, the most scrutinized issue in a staff reduction is the selection
process for terminations. Were the &quot;right&quot; employees selected?<BR>
<BR>
The &quot;right&quot; employees in the employer's mind are frequently the
&quot;poor performers.&quot; Management may view this situation as presenting
an opportunity to unload &quot;dead wood,&quot; to rid the company of employees
with &quot;bad attitudes,&quot; or to terminate individuals who should have
been fired previously. <BR>
<BR>
While this approach may produce the desired &quot;survivors,&quot; it can
create legal liability and damage employer-employee relationships. <BR>
<BR>
In Pennsylvania, people are employed &quot;at will,&quot; which means that
either the employer or the employee can terminate the relationship at any
time for any reason or for no reason, unless federal or state laws are violated.<BR>
<BR>
Currently, there are a multitude of such laws, mandates and court decisions
that protect individuals from discrimination based upon race, sex, age,
religion, national origin, pregnancy and disability. Many individuals are
part of a protected class in at least one of these areas. <BR>
 <BR>
When a termination appears to deviate from logical sequencing or lacks proper
documentation and concern for &quot;due process,&quot; a charge of discrimination
might be filed and supported. Such charges, and the surrounding publicity,
can weaken an already tenuous internal and external public relations image,
divert management time and exact monetary penalties that are sometimes substantial.<BR>
Internally, the shock, grief and fear produced by sudden and widespread
terminations set the stage for more fear and distrust fueled by rumors and
misunderstandings. Unanswered questions regarding the selection of one employee
instead of another will heighten and prolong the recovery period, shaking
employee confidence and hurting productivity. <BR>
<BR>
I am not advocating keeping poor performers or the individuals who will
not conform to company rules and values. What I am saying is:  Don't muddy
the waters in a downsizing by co-mingling the two processes. Deal with poor
performers and rule violators at the time the undesired behaviors occur,
terminating the employee for cause if and when it becomes necessary. <BR>
<BR>
Employees know and recognize peers who are not playing as full team members.
These individuals will receive only superficial sympathy if they are treated
fairly and given adequate counseling and warning. Employers who carefully
document all performance issues and schedule counseling sessions to explain
needed improvements and the consequences of continued unchanged negative
behavior will show other employees that they too will be treated equitably
if misunderstandings develop.<BR>
<BR>
What is the best way to make downsizing selections? Try to divorce personality
and other intangibles from the process, basing your decisions on nonsubjective
considerations such as the elimination of part or all of a less critical
department or work unit, or even an entire function. Terminate individuals
with similar responsibilities on a last-in, first-out basis. Remaining employees
will be less sympathetic to newer employees. <BR>
<BR>
Terminations are never without pain. Management must accept the fact that
the corporate culture will be affected by a staff reduction. Once the initial
shock waves subside, the company can expect to be judged on the perception
of how the process was handled and whether individuals were treated fairly.
By making the right selection decisions you can strengthen this perception
and leave your company with a dedicated workforce.  <BR>
            <BR>
Judith E. Yankovic is president of The EQUUS Group Inc., a human resources
consulting company in Allegheny County.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
