<DOCNO>WT10-B33-359</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA061-000343-B037-265</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
http://www.execreport.com:80/zine/0896.Chronicles.html 192.204.56.67 19970115120323 text/html 10037
HTTP/1.0 200 Document follows
Date: Wed, 15 Jan 1997 12:08:31 GMT
Server: NCSA/1.4.1
Content-type: text/html
Last-modified: Mon, 07 Oct 1996 16:50:20 GMT
Content-length: 9861
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Chronicles </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.GuestEditorial.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H8Chronicles.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></FONT SIZE></B><BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+1></FONT SIZE></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>
<H4>An Old 'Horse' Chugs Along ... While a New One Is on the Way</H4>
&quot;Our special is a buck a horse,&quot; says Terry King, bartender at
the Brew House in Latrobe, Westmoreland County, speaking with his best western
 Pennsylvania accent.<BR>
<BR>
  Translation: That's $1 for a 12 oz. Rolling Rock long-neck bottle.<BR>
<BR>
 &quot;On those nights, they line up four deep at the bar,&quot; King says.
&quot;We have some microbrews, too, nothing too fancy. They don't do too
well out here.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
At trendy Planet Hollywood in New York, the horse goes for $3.75 a bottle.
It's about halfway up the scale there, say the bartenders. It's popular
with people who want &quot;something different,&quot; and with foreigners.<BR>
<BR>
Rolling Rock, the little beer that could, has been made in Westmoreland
County since 1939. Traditionally the everyday beer of choice for working-
class Pennsylvanians statewide, &quot;Rock&quot; (as it's known in Latrobe)
has grown a second personality - the &quot;specialty beer,&quot; enjoyed
by yuppies in   upscale bars and restaurants across the country.<BR>
<BR>
Latrobe Brewing Co. originally was owned by the Tito family, who started
the brewery along the Loyalhanna Creek shortly after the end of Prohibition.
The mainstay of the brewery, Rolling Rock had its golden years during the
heyday of small, local American breweries, from the 1940s through the 1960s.<BR>
<BR>
Then the 1970s brought the age of industry consolidation, and Latrobe Brewing
struggled to remain competitive. By the mid-1980s, several huge concerns
- including Anheuser Busch and Miller - owned well over three-quarters of
the American beer market.<BR>
<BR>
Tiny family breweries around the country folded up shop in the face of ultra-cheap
Bud and Miller Lite. The Tito family sold Latrobe Brewing to Sundor, an
investment group, in 1985, and Sundor passed the brewery on to the American
arm of Canadian giant Labatt. The Titos still figure in western Pennsylvania
beer, owning a distributorship in Latrobe. And Rolling Rock has taken on
a national presence because of its catchy name and unique, green long-neck
with the label painted on it.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Latrobe Brewing is an incredibly efficient, well-oiled machine. It's
a beautiful brewery,&quot; says Brad Hittle, director of marketing for Rolling
Rock.  &quot;Labatt saw a diamond in the rough - Rolling Rock has a special
image, with its painted label bottle. The brewery is an asset, and it's
a good beer. Labatt also saw that specialty beers would be the wave of the
future.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Rolling Rock, says Hittle, is about 10 to 12 percent of Labatt USA's total
volume. Labatt USA is in turn owned by John Labatt Limited of Canada, which
in 1995 entered into partnership with Interbrew S.A. of Belgium and Cerveceria
Cuahtemoc Moctezuma of Mexico, creating the fourth-largest brewing group
in the world. Through it all, tiny Rolling Rock and Latrobe Brewing have
not only maintained their integrity as a beer but have prospered. Last year,
in fact, saw the first time 1 million barrels of Rolling Rock were shipped
in one year's time. The &quot;horse&quot; has attracted quite a following.<BR>
<BR>
Labatt's strategy has been to not rock the Rock's boat. The brewery has
remained mostly unchanged; it's only the targeting and distribution that
needed the push. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;They just needed some tender loving marketing,&quot; says Hittle,
and that is exactly the resource Labatt knew how to muster.<BR>
<BR>
Maintaining what Hittle calls the &quot;charm and ease&quot; reputation
of Rolling Rock is the key to continued growth.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In the core markets of Pennsylvania, Ohio and New Jersey, the beer
still has an older audience. We call them our 'True Green' users. It's difficult
to upscale a beverage, but it's worked a little, especially in Pittsburgh,&quot;
he says.<BR>
<BR>
Outside of these core markets, Rolling Rock's audience is largely younger
(21 to 34), educated (67 percent with college education) and more affluent
(singles averaging $26,000 per year) than the mega-brews. And these have
been very important markets, indeed. Last year saw 20 to 30 percent growth
in the western and central United States.<BR>
<BR>
Not that there haven't been some stumbles along the way. Latrobe no longer
brews Rolling Rock Bock, a heavier, darker version of Rock. Hittle says
the beer never took off, not because of quality problems, but because of
inexperience at marketing and distribution.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;Their expectations were too high,&quot; says Hittle, &quot;but it
was a learning experience.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Latrobe Brewing Co. hopes to put that learning to work later this fall with
a new brew. Brewery insiders are tight-lipped, other than saying their plan
is to target the booming microbrew market, which, according to Hittle, is
here to stay.   <BR>
<H4>A Growing Business<BR>
</H4>
If, as the television ad tells us, our yard is our own little piece of the
planet, then Sherry Kyne is a pretty powerful influence in western Pennsylvania.
She's the owner of Eisler Nurseries, the firm that designs the planetary
habitats of Mellons, Scaifes and Heinz. The design for the grounds of the
new Fore Systems campus in Marshall Township, a contract just shy of $1
million, is under Kyne's (probably green) thumb as well.<BR>
<BR>
Kyne inherited the business from her grandfather, John M. Eisler, who founded
the nursery in 1926. Kyne, who grew up in eastern Pennsylvania, helped her
grandfather out in the summer at the nursery when she was young, but had
no intention of becoming a horticulturist. In fact, she graduated from college
with a degree in computer science and business management and was working
in Virginia as a systems analyst when her grandfather asked her to come
help him with the business.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;My grandfather was a one-man show,&quot; says Kyne. &quot;He had a
hard time letting go, but he was aging and not able to keep up. The business
needed fresh blood.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Four months after she returned, Eisler died, leaving the business to   
 her grandmother. Kyne stayed on, eventually inheriting the business in
full in 1987.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;People think it's a piece of      cake, that it's simple when you
inherit a business,&quot; says Kyne. &quot;But this business had a $12,000
value when he passed away.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Though a tremendous success from the '40s through the '60s, Eisler's failing
health and refusal to change had caused Eisler Nurseries to seriously falter
during the 1970s and '80s. Kyne had her work cut out for her. Though she
says the business hasn't been valued lately, she admits it's grown tremendously.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The first year we broke even,&quot; says Kyne. &quot;It had lost $500,000
in the three years previously.&quot; <BR>
Negative image was one large problem to overcome.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We had become overpriced, and that was tough to get over,&quot; says
Kyne. &quot;My grandfather raised prices when he was losing money.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Kyne rebuilt the nursery's garden center, affiliating with ServiStar as
one of their home and gardenshop places. And she updated equipment, as well.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Before, they did everything by hand,&quot; says Kyne. &quot;My first
purchase was a tree spade, a $100,000 machine. But it can dig a large tree
in a half an hour, which was a days-long process before.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Kyne also returned to school, taking advantage of a winter horticulture
program Penn State offered in the months the landscaping business was not
as busy. She met some people who were graduating that year, including Peter
Kyne, who became her husband and now runs the nursery; Eric French, who
now runs the landscaping business; and his wife Melissa Lim-French, who
is Eisler's estimator and buyer.<BR>
<BR>
With this team, and Don Webb to run the retail business, Eisler Nurseries
has been able to re-establish itself in the marketplace.<BR>
<BR>
 Kyne has updated the family business for the '90s, and not only the product
but the business is flourishing to prove it.                           
               <BR>
<BR>
