<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Chronicles.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Commit to our Children</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>Let's Give Them the Skills to<BR>
Master Technology That Will Shape Their Futures</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>Ann Devlin - Columnist</I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>OK, maybe you can explain it. <BR>
<BR>
Just how is it that in this countdown to the 21st century, when we all know
how critical computers and technology are now and will be in the economic
future of this region and its workers, we are graduating students from our
colleges and universities, not to mention high schools, who are computer
illiterate?<BR>
 <BR>
I have talked with students who don't see this as a problem. I have talked
with parents who are almost proud that they have resisted the introduction
of a computer into their home. I have watched school board members pander
to the perennially angry taxpayers in their district by showing absolutely
no vision, no leadership, no determination to make computer access and literacy
a mandatory budget priority.<BR>
<BR>
We are happy to insist children are our future. We seem just as happy to
resist equipping them for theirs.<BR>
<BR>
The obvious consequence: the creation of a society divided into information
haves and have-nots. It's an excruciating irony, for computers and the Internet
offer the ultimate democratization of information and communication.<BR>
<BR>
There are two initiatives in Allegheny County that actually do dare to challenge
our technological inertia. County Controller Frank Lucchino wondered if
it would be possible to electronically link all of the county's libraries.
The experts said yes. The mission is being accomplished even as I write
this. Ultimately, you will be able to go to one library and access resources
from all the libraries. <BR>
The second project is called County Knowledge Connections. It has already
introduced dedicated technology centers into several county public housing
projects. Residents are offered basic computer instruction, as well as guidance
in accessing library resources that once would have been inaccessible. <BR>
<BR>
These are terrific success stories. As evidence of our progress though,
they are painfully incremental.<BR>
<BR>
Toni Carbo worries about this. You may know her as Dean Carbo, professor
and head of the School of Information Sciences at the University of Pittsburgh.
What you may not know is that she is helping the leaders of the world figure
out where to go on the information superhighway. Formally put, she is the
co-chair of the U.S. National Committee for the International Federation
for Information and Documentation, and she currently chairs its Global Information
Infrastructures and Superhighways Task Force, along with its Information
Policy Committee. Representing the United States, she pulled up a chair
with the G-7 Round Table of Business Leaders as they struggled to advance
a vision of how technology and the information it delivers can change the
world.<BR>
<BR>
This is big. But at our lunch table, Dean Carbo reduces the issues to two.
First, the information haves and have-nots. She says that the have-not category
spans from the people who have technology at their fingertips but don't
know how to use it to the folks who have only a ghost of a chance of ever
buying a home computer. In our country right now, one third of the inner
city poor don't even have phones. Second, is the matter of what Carbo calls
not computer literacy, but mediacy, &quot;the ability to explore information
space and find, discover, organize, manage, observe, integrate, interact
with and create information.&quot; <BR>
 <BR>
So where to begin?  Before kindergarten, Carbo insists.  But to make   
that happen, the dean says work must be done with parents, caregivers and
day care centers. And then there is the  matter of teachers. The dean ruefully
acknowledges the &quot;Doorstop Phenomenon.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Apparently, the haphazard introduction of computers into ill-prepared schools
about a decade ago resulted in poor integration of technology into the curriculum.
To this day, the only value remaining is their weighty effectiveness as
doorstops. That's bad, but here's worse:  Carbo says, &quot;There are problems
with teachers and college professors feeling threatened.&quot; <BR>
 <BR>
For them, the dean suggests a newly minted maxim about an educator's place
in this technological revolution: &quot;It's no longer the sage on the stage
... but rather the guide on the side.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
But helping educators arrive at that place, Carbo says, will also cost money.<BR>
<BR>
It all comes down to this: We are all on the same page here. World leaders,
college professors, kindergarten teachers, school directors and parents
share the responsibility that comes with this revolution. We must subdue
both our anxieties and, if necessary, our egos, summon our collective will
and make a commitment to give our children the skills to master the technology
that will shape their lives.<BR>
    <BR>
The low-tech term for this, I believe, is &quot;doing right by our  children.&quot;
                                                <BR>
<BR>
