<HEAD>
    <TITLE>EYE ON HARRISBURGH</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Devlin.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H14EyeonH.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Diner.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Get the Message</B></FONT><BR>
<FONT size=+1>The State Is Trying to Promote Itself Nationally<BR>
With a Business-to-Business Ad Campaign</FONT><BR>
<I>By Jim Strader </I><HR></CENTER>
<P>Flipping through recent issues of some of your other  favorite business
magazines, you might have come across ads pitching Pennsylvania as a good
place to do business.<BR>
<BR>
Tom Ridge looks out from one ad. The governor's stern, shadowed face issues
a pledge to raise the stakes in competition with other states by further
lowering business taxes and workers' compensation rates. Another full-page
layout shows a bird's-eye view of the Earth, touting Lockheed Martin's decision
to locate a manufacturing center for its communications satellite business
in suburban Philadelphia.<BR>
<BR>
These advertisements, appearing in Fortune, Business Week and Inc., as well
as trade and special-market publications, are designed to reach people who
can create jobs - and encourage them to do it in Pennsylvania.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This is a business-to-business campaign,&quot; says John Verbanek
of Pittsburgh-based Ketchum, which has the state contract for the program.
&quot;We're not selling a consumer product. We're selling - frankly - between
businesses.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
State government is a business, with customers and a need to produce results,
says state Commerce Secretary Thomas B. Hagen. Finding new businesses to
set up operations in the state and keeping the ones that are here is a part
of that thinking and figures in the ad campaign, he says.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Economic development is a business-to-business marketing effort that
targets a select group of people,&quot; Hagen says. &quot;These advertisements
have been designated to get our point across dramatically and directly.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In developing the campaign, Verbanek and others at Ketchum keyed into the
reputation the state had with business people around the country. In surveys
and studies, the overriding theme was that Pennsylvania lacked a business-friendly
image and was seen as &quot;Tax-sylvania with a that's-your-problem attitude,&quot;
Verbanek says.<BR>
<BR>
The ad featuring Ridge stressed the changes brought about in his first year
in office, including a reduction in the corporate net income tax. The Lockheed
ad uses another approach - having companies sell the state by explaining
their business experiences in Pennsylvania. Yet another set of advertisements
following the same pattern is coming.<BR>
<BR>
Other aspects of this &quot;image-building&quot; campaign, as Verbanek describes
it, include a state presence at trade shows, telemarketing and good-old
public relations. Also, the state took out  a 19-page advertising supplement
in Fortune at the end of last year and has a partnership with home-shopping
retailer QVC to promote Pennsylvania products and locations on television.<BR>
<BR>
The state government also has a presence in cyberspace - an Internet &quot;home
page&quot; presenting information about Pennsylvania, including items of
interest to businesses.<BR>
<BR>
The state is centering its efforts to generate interest in the mid-Atlantic
region because Pennsylvania most often competes for jobs and businesses
with neighboring states. The target audience for the magazine ads is  14
million business decision-makers in that region.<BR>
<BR>
The Commerce Department also is running a broader tourism campaign through
a contract with Poppe Tyson, another Pittsburgh firm. The media's headlines
about that campaign focused on the new tourism slogan - &quot;Memories Last
a Lifetime,&quot; replacing &quot;America Starts Here&quot; - but not many
articles discussed a deeper goal the state associates with increased tourism.
Pleasure and business are linked, commerce officials believe, and Ridge
ties the two together when he says &quot;Today's tourist is tomorrow's investor.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Making that conversion, turning a tourist or a magazine reader into a member
of Pennsylvania's business community, starts with a basic connection with
the state. Making sure that information is out there and available can be
that first important step, the governor says.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Pennsylvania will reap substantial rewards by ensuring that interested
employers of all sizes are aware that the commonwealth has the welcome mat
out for job creators,&quot; Ridge says. &quot;As   the world economy becomes
more   and more competitive, so must Pennsylvania. ... Now, we're telling
the world about it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Like any sales pitch, what counts   is who buys.<BR>
<BR>
