<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Executive Diner </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.EyeOnHarrisburg.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H9ExDiner.gif" BORDER=
"0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.People.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2>Cafe Azure</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size = +1>Around the World<BR>
Never Tasted So Good</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I>By Lydia Strohl </I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR>Many people dream of owning a restaurant, and Christine Olson, a
housewife for 10 years, was one of them. But the realities of this particular
industry, in which many restaurants fail in the first year, are daunting.<BR>
<BR>
The perfect solution arose in the form of Bill Corcoran, then manager of
Cafe Azure on Craig Street. Combining her dream and capital with Corcoran's
expertise (he'd been with the restaurant since its inception in 1981), they
took over the cafe. After a total revamp in menu, philosophy and aesthetics,
it reopened in early 1995.<BR>
<BR>
Fronted by a shaded patio on bustling Craig Street, the restaurant is appealing
on the inside as well. Elegant neutral tones set off a modern decor. But
what's really contemporary is the cuisine; in fact, that's how they bill
it. The interesting menu is two-fold, one side changing seasonally, the
other every three weeks.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We don't hold to any particular cuisine,&quot; says Olson. &quot;You
might find food from Italy or France, or meatloaf. We follow trends, but
we also want to anticipate.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
On this menu, innovative combinations of exotic ingredients and  spices
in traditional dishes are the trademark of  chef Amy Henry-Perciner, a 
Culinary Institute of America graduate. A Pittsburgh native, she spent time
in England and Turkey after a stint at the Occidental Restau-rant in Washington,
D.C.<BR>
 <BR>
For starters, the summer menu offers country pat&eacute; with a chipolte
sun-dried cherry chutney, a rich, meaty pat&eacute; set off by the savory/hot
chutney. The sweet potato tartlette with sauteed shrimp, leeks and chili
peppers boasted a tender, crisp crust and a tangy filling, topped with the
incredible brainstorm of smooth mac-adamia nuts. Gazpacho was re-freshingly
chilled and spicy with cumin. A salad of arugula, mustard greens and swiss
chard with oven-dried tomatoes, black olives and blue cheese was beautiful,
but the garlic dijon dressing was too heavy and lacked zip.<BR>
<BR>
Entree offerings such as tamari and molasses grilled sirloin strip steak
with sauteed leeks and exotic mushrooms show the kitchen's creativity. We
tried grilled tuna with an apulia-style tomato compote and white balsamic
sauce. (If the terms confuse you, worry not, the attentive waiters know
their stuff.) It was a huge steak, ordinary but for the beautiful compote,
which added a Mediterranean flair. The pan-seared cornmeal-crusted golden
trout with a citrus sage compound butter was delectable, the sauce thick
with strips of lemon and lime peel. But the topper was the grilled lamb
chops with mustard, garlic and rosemary, with a spinach timbale and a walnut,
chick pea and potato herbed pancake. A knife passed through the lamb like
it was butter; the pancake was rich and nutty.<BR>
<BR>
The lunch menu features many of the same items but adds salads, like curried
barbecued shrimp with tropical fruits. Perfectly spiced and laden with exotic
mango and papaya, it boasted a mellowing yogurt-based dressing. Lunch entrees
include a smooth jambalaya, smoky with sausage and chicken. Sandwiches also
defy the norm: a Spanish-style herbed omelette with vegetables and smoked
provolone was the best egg on toast in recent memory; the flour tortilla
filled with grilled flank steak tasted healthy despite its red meat billing.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;People are striving for healthier food,&quot; says Olson. &quot;The
'80s are over.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Not when it comes to dessert. The menu creation isn't left to Henry-Perciner
alone - Olson says the entire staff is encourged to submit items. But knowing
Henry-Perciner's background  as a pastry chef, one detects her influence
on the dessert tray. The triple- decker carrot cake with cream cheese frosting
is richly spiced and moist. Chocolate Regal, a rich torte with raspberry
sauce, is decadent. <BR>
And the Creme Brul&eacute;e rates a 10 - silky inside, on a bed of plumped
raisins and topped with a delicate burnt sugar crust.<BR>
<BR>
As accompaniments, Cafe Azure boasts a nice list of international wines,
starting at $14. There's also live jazz on Wednesday, Friday and Saturday
nights, as well as Sunday brunch. With many of the local jazz community
stopping in and sitting in, says Olson, &quot;You never know what you're
going to find.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
That about sums it up for the menu, as well. And while offering squid ink
pasta raises many eyebrows, let's hope Cafe Azure continues its delicious
mission without a hitch.                    <BR>
<BR>
Cafe Azure<BR>
317 S. Craig Street, Oakland<BR>
681-3533<BR>
<BR>
Hours: <BR>
Mon. - Thurs.: 11:30 a.m. - 2:30  p.m.; 5 p.m. - 9:30 p.m.<BR>
Fri. - Sat.: 11:30 a.m. - 3 p.m.; 5   p.m. - 11 p.m.<BR>
Sun.: 1p.m. - 5 p.m. <BR>
<BR>
Appetizers and Salads: $4.25 - $7.75 <BR>
Entrees: $14 - $25.75<BR>
