<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>People Making News </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Diner.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H10People.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>Carl O. Hughes</FONT></I></B></CENTER>
<P><HR><B>Name: <I>Carl O. Hughes</I> <BR>
Occupation: Chairman, Kennywood Entertainment Corp.<BR>
Age: 74<BR>
Personal: Lives on Mount Washington with his wife, Ann<BR>
Education: BA, Economics, Geneva College, 1943<BR>
Last Book Read: &quot;The Power of Hercules&quot;, by Paul Theroux<BR>
Last Vacation: &quot;I'm on vacation all the time&quot;.<BR>
</B><HR><BR>
They don't go by horse and buggy anymore, but when Pittsburghers are looking
for a little fun and games, they go to Kennywood Park - or to Sandcastle,
or, a little farther afield, to Idlewild. All three are run under the auspices
of Kennywood Entertainment Corp., which recently purchased a share in a
Connecticut amusement park as well. Kennywood, established in 1878, is hailed
as one of the country's traditional amusement parks, and is one of just
two parks with National Historic Landmark status. But it's undergone many
changes over its 103-year ride. Lydia Strohl talked about Kennywood with
Chairman Carl Hughes, who has been around for 40 of those years.<BR>
 <B><BR>
Executive Report: </B>How did you first come to be involved with Kennywood?<B><BR>
<BR>
Carl Hughes: </B>I did the park's publicity for some 10 years and in 1956
was asked to come full-time. After some conversations with my family, I
decided  to give up summers and go with this.<BR>
<B><BR>
ER: </B>What has been the highlight of your 40 years at Kennywood?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>The highlight started in about 1972, when the company was able to
purchase the property. Prior to that it was on a lease basis. Once the property
was purchased, it was possible to make improvements with the knowledge you
wouldn't be giving it up at the end of the lease. That was a significant
thing. <BR>
The other thing was in 1975, when we first got ourselves on our feet after
that purchase, the addition of our    first major defining attraction, the
Log Jammer, and the appointment of Harry Henninger Jr. as manager of the
park. He has since been the guiding influence in the operation of the park,
as well as expansion of the company. <B><BR>
<BR>
ER: </B>The park will be 100 years old in 1998. Are many parks as old as
Kennywood?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>Oddly enough, there are a lot of old amusement parks in the country.
We just purchased a management partnership in the oldest park in the country,
which is 150 years old this year, Lake Compounce, in Connecticut. In addition
to that, we have the third-oldest park in the country, which is Idlewild
near Ligonier. <BR>
<B><BR>
ER:</B> What are the differences between your parks - I guess they're based
on their audiences?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>Oh, sure. Kennywood is geared toward a teenage audience and, in
the larger sense, a family audience. We've been very successful at getting
a large family audience here, with a wide spectrum of ages. I was just at
a luncheon the other day where a man said he hadn't been here for years
and he was just here with his granddaughter. We always figure we get people
three times - when they're kids, when they're parents and when they're grandparents.
<BR>
<BR>
At Idlewild, we strive for a young audience. We try to make that audience
aware of Idlewild's beauty and adaptability to young families. Sandcastle
is strictly a water park. It appeals to the more athletic types, regardless
of age. It's mostly a young person's park.<BR>
<BR>
Sandcastle is the newest. Henny, which is what everybody calls Harry Henninger,
and I had talked for a couple years about the possibility of a water park.
Water parks came into being as stand-alone attractions not 20 years ago;
we talked about bringing one to Pittsburgh. We were held back a little by
the fact that the county has three wave pools, which is generally the key
element of a water park. So we decided to skip the wave pool and make it
successful just on the basis  of slides and other elements. <BR>
<BR>
We had looked at some suburban properties. Normally, these are located near
the interstate. But he had the idea to locate at some old steel mill property.
It was when the steel mills were being torn down, in the second half of
the '80s. Oddly, he found the ideal situation in West Homestead. Steel mill
sites were available at low cost, and being on the river, he thought it
would make an attractive backdrop for the park. If you couldn't have a piece
of property along the interstate, and were going to be in a difficult to
access location, as Sandcastle is, you have to make it pretty.<BR>
 <BR>
It was the first actual reuse of steel mill property that I'm aware of.
We thought more things would happen after that, because the property is
available. I guess there's so much available and so little new building
that it just hasn't happened yet.<BR>
It was difficult because we had a self-imposed schedule that had us opening
the summer after we started construction. That was demanding.<B><BR>
<BR>
ER: </B>What are the main issues in attracting consumers to entertainment
facilities like this?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>The main issue is to provide value for the dollar. To underpromise
and overdeliver - that is basically what we try to do.<B><BR>
 <BR>
</B>The weather, and we have had an example this year, is the No. 1 factor.
Last year we had good weather, and Kennywood had the biggest year it ever
had. But there's no way you can count on that. As far as the other problems,
in this area it is the declining population. And the aging population, because
naturally we rely on young people. So we have had to go out farther and
farther to reach people.<BR>
Group business is the basis of our marketing effort, and we have found that
it is certainly the best thing to ensure the prosperity of the park. Groups
account for over 50 percent of our business.<BR>
<BR>
As far as marketing, we do pretty standard advertising, television, some
local radio, but we've gone farther out. Youngstown, northern West Virginia,
the Johnstown-Altoona area - it's finally paying off.<B><BR>
<BR>
ER: </B>Who are your competitors?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>Cedar Point is our biggest competitor. Cedar Point is in my mind
the finest seasonal park in the country. On the other hand, it's so far
away. People only go there once a year; they come to Kennywood several times.
We've been successful going farther and farther into Cedar Point's Ohio
territory, and getting visitors out of that area.<B><BR>
 <BR>
</B>By far the greatest amount of our attendance is from Allegheny and contiguous
counties - but that incremental attendance is the difference be-tween a
big year and a good year.<BR>
<B><BR>
ER: </B>What's a 'good' year?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>We're a privately held company so we don't give out attendance figures,
but the biggest year we had prior to last year was 1991, when we previewed
the Steel Phantom. In '92, '93, '94, attendance slid at Kennywood. It's
a combination of attractions, weather, luck - all those things enter in.<B><BR>
<BR>
ER: </B>Why buy into the Connecticut park?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>They asked us to participate. The state of Connecticut has put together
a development package for the park. It has been open on a very sporadic
basis for the last five years, and the state had this package that we found
very inviting, an opportunity we could not pass up. We didn't go out looking
for it.<BR>
<BR>
The partner is a family in Connecticut, the Barberino family. Their background
is in the automobile business, but they bought Lake Compounce some 10 years
ago from the family that had owned it for many years. They went into partnership
with Herco, which is the Hershey Entertainment and Resort Co. Herco developed
the park and opened it for a year then pulled out. They pulled out of all
their non-Hershey enterprises. There were a couple of partners since then,
and their luck was bad also, so we hope we can change the luck.<BR>
<BR>
A whole lot of money needs to be spent. We have the money from the state
of Connecticut, as well as the money that this company is putting into it.
Mainly they need a lot of entertainment, which in this business comes down
to rides.<B><BR>
<BR>
ER: </B>In a lot of industries, it's a challenge to keep up with the new
technology. Is that true in the amusement park business? Is there always
a new ride out there?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>There are many new rides, but in many cases they're just new versions
of a very old ride. For instance, the looping coasters, which have become
such a major factor in the last 25 years or so. They're not new - there
was a looping coaster back in the Coney Island days at the turn of the century
that was very successful. Wooden roller coasters are still being built and
are the backbone of the industry. So there is a lot of old concept being
done better, and much more expensively.<B><BR>
 <BR>
</B>There are new things being brought out almost every year. One of the
newest things is the Mag Lev system of propulsion. Mag Lev is being used
for a thrust to send rides out, much like the old Laser Loop - only it used
a mechanical loop. It's just a different propulsion system. The feeling
of being on the ride is probably about the same, I haven't been on one.
The first ones are being opened as we speak. We're going to try some - you
do a lot of that, too. <BR>
<BR>
Kennywood was the first park, despite the fact that we always avoided prototypes,
to get a Sky Coaster. There had been Sky Coasters at resorts and places
like that, but not inside a park, so we didn't put in a prototype. But now
it's a major feature of many parks, which followed us. Usually, we  follow
everybody else - let them figure it out.<BR>
 <BR>
Henny and our general manager at the time saw it at the trade show and decided
it was worth trying. I had some concerns. For the cost of it, and the charge
we had to make, it had such low capacity. It could only take about 10 trips
an hour, and the maximum was three a trip. Normally we look for 1,000 per
hour, on this it was 30. So it didn't make much sense, except if people
were willing to pay the price. The price was $25 for one person, $20 apiece
for two and $15 apiece for three people. I said we're not even going to
advertise this because the prices are so scary. And we didn't advertise
it, but it was a tremendous hit. This is its third season and it hasn't
slowed down yet. Cedar Point just put in a Sky Coaster this year. And they're
all being put in on that basis.<B><BR>
<BR>
ER: </B>How many years does it take to recoup the cost of an attraction?<BR>
<B><BR>
CH: </B>It varies tremendously -  attractions are so expensive now. Used
to be you could recoup the cost in half a season, now you're talking years.<BR>
<B><BR>
ER: </B>How have the costs of rides changed?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>At our trade show each year, everybody's looking for the new attractions.
They're shown, as a design, or maybe a model, and they'll try to find someone
to buy the prototype. The rest of us wait to see if it succeeds.<BR>
<BR>
As an example, the attraction on top of the Stratosphere Tower in Las Vegas
- they put a roller coaster up there. The roller coaster isn't very sensational,
but of course at that height, anything is sensational. And on top of that
they put this tower which shoots people in a chair to the very top, maybe
150 feet or so, then they come down. This is one of the new techniques that
came out of our trade show the year before that. <BR>
<BR>
I'd guess that cost in the $2 million range, f.o.b. as it were. In other
words, you have to take it from there, get it erected, get the engineering
done - usually it's twice what you paid for it.<BR>
<BR>
I remember when I was manager here, we'd buy a kiddie ride for $5,000. I
was manager until 1975, that was 20 years ago. Now you can hardly buy one
for less than $750,000. I mean the most basic. To put it in doesn't cost
a whole lot, you just have to get it here.<BR>
<BR>
When we bought the Laser Loop, we had to pay for it in Swiss francs, because
the company that built it was in Switzerland. And not knowing how the dollar
was going to go, the price was arranged in Swiss francs. Sometimes you win
on that, sometimes you lose. German companies state the amount in deutsche
marks; Italian companies usually quote dollars.<B><BR>
<BR>
ER: </B>How have the liability issues changed over the years?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>They've gotten worse. But now I think the courts, and to some extent
the juries, have gotten more sensible, certainly not more lenient, but more
understanding that the participant has a responsibility to behave. And as
a matter of fact there is a state law in Pennsylvania now called the rider
responsibility act.<BR>
<B><BR>
ER: </B>What is the hardest challenge in this business?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>The seasonal nature is unique, in a sense. We hosted the new CEO
of Six Flags about a week ago. He had come to that organization from Toys
R Us, where he was also CEO. I asked him how the two businesses were similar
and he said they both made their money in three months. You try to hold
down costs and maximize income during the operating season. That's when
rain comes into play.<BR>
<B><BR>
ER: </B>There's a lot more that goes on here besides rides - food, music,
skee ball - has that diversification always been a part of Kennywood?<BR>
<BR>
CH: It's a part of the traditional amusement business. Disney changed the
nature of the entire amusement business when he built Disneyland. He didn't
then and he still hasn't put in any games of skill. As a result, when the
Disney method was copied and theme parks began to proliferate based on Disney,
which they all were and still are, they didn't put in any games, because
Disney hadn't. Then they started looking around at the old-timers like Kennywood
and saw it wasn't hurting them, so they put them in. Now I'd say that games
of skill are in more proliferation at some of the theme parks than they
are at the traditional parks.<BR>
<BR>
Same thing with roller coasters. Disney did not believe in thrill rides:
The Matterhorn was as scary as it got. They still haven't put in wooden
roller coasters, but they are putting in steel roller coasters and more
thrilling rides. It wasn't until one of the traditional park people built
King's Island, outside Cincinnati. They had operated a traditional park
and were subjected to floods every year, so they built King's Island. The
first thing they did was put in games and a roller coaster, and the theme
parks thought, 'Gee, this is okay, we can do this.'<B><BR>
<BR>
ER: </B>Kennywood has a distinct period feeling about it. What is the philosophy
regarding new technology and upgrading here?<B><BR>
<BR>
CH: </B>We try to keep Kennywood current and at the same time old-fashioned.
We are redoing the Noah's Ark this year; unfortunately, it's way  behind
schedule. We got into it much more heavily in stunts than we intended to,
much more technological. Whereas the old Noah's Ark had       only the simplest
of stunts in it - it dated back to 1936 - the Noah's Ark this time will
have some very sophisticated equipment in it, built by a      company in
Hollywood that builds for the movies.<B><BR>
<BR>
ER:</B> What's your favorite ride?<BR>
<B><BR>
CH: </B>My personal favorite is the Log Jammer.<BR>
<BR>
 It was so significant in the history of the park. I don't ride it very
often, because you get wet. But I always    enjoy it. 	<B>			   <BR>
</B><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
