<HEAD>
    <TITLE>HEALTH BEAT </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.People.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H15Health.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Law.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+2>Extra Crispy<BR>
</FONT></I><FONT size =+1>In Reality, There is No Such Thing<BR>
as a Healthy Sun Tan</B></FONT><BR>
<I>By Lydia Strohl</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>There is no such thing as a 'healthy tan'. Tanning is skin's response
to the sun's harmful rays. But it promotes, not prevents, skin cancer -
the most common form of cancer, which afflicts one in seven Americans.<BR>
<BR>
But unlike more deadly forms of the disease, skin cancer is curable if diagnosed
in time, says Dr. Leo McCafferty, chairman of the skin cancer screening
and education committee at Mercy Cancer Institute. <BR>
<BR>
The skin is the body's biggest organ. It has two layers: The top layer,
the epidermis, contains three kinds of cells which can be affected by cancer.<BR>
<BR>
Though skin cancer is generally caused by sun exposure, it can be affected
by a variety of factors, including heredity and environment. Fair skinned,
blue-eyed men and women with northern European heritage are most likely
to contract skin cancer. Environmentally speaking, some studies suggest
that the ozone layer, which filters out the sun's harmful ultraviolet rays,
is depleting, which increases the amount of UV that gets to us. Location
also matters: the thin atmosphere present at higher elevations can't filter
UV as well. On cloudy days, there may be as much as 50 percent lower levels
of UV.  Still, other factors can be responsible for skin cancer.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Pittsburgh years ago was a center for treating acne with radiation,
and we're seeing a lot of these people now who have basal cell cancer,&quot;
says McAfferty.<BR>
<BR>
Basal cell cancer is the most common - and the most benign - of the three
types of skin cancer. It is indicated by a localized growth, most often
on the face, which may have swelling or a scab that doesn't go away. Cancer
affecting the squamous cell is similar to basal cell cancer, but can aggressively
move to other parts of the body. It presents itself as a raised, irregular
and fleshy colored ulcer and is also surgically treated.<BR>
<BR>
By far the most dangerous cancer is melanoma, cancer of the pigment producing
cell that can metastasize quickly to other parts of the body. Any new mole,
change in a mole or a mole that is hard and itchy or swollen should be checked,
usually by biopsy. <BR>
<BR>
<B>Overdone by the Sun</B><BR>
<BR>
Sun exposure is responsible for about 90 percent of skin cancers, so obviously
there are ways to avoid it. Just one bad sunburn can increase your chances
of skin cancer by about             50 percent.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;No one really knows how much sun is too much,&quot; says Mercy's McCafferty.
&quot;If you're just walking 20 minutes to work, it's not as important to
wear sunscreen, whereas if you're gardening or golfing for hours, you definitely
should. But there are all kinds of moisturizers and makeups on the market
with sunscreen in them, so rather than try and predict the weather you can
just use these products.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
McAfferty says that sun damage takes a long time to appear, however. The
leathery and wrinkly skin that is associated with aging is likely in some
part due to sun. Precancerous cells can be found in screenings and treated
with scraping or freezing chemicals. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Typically in the '50s and '60s we start to see patients with lesions,&quot;
says McCafferty.<BR>
<BR>
To protect yourself, avoid the sun, cover up or use sunscreen. Sunscreen
comes in a variety of SPF, or sun protection factor, ratings. SPF 15 means
you can be in the sun 15 times as long as you could with SPF 1. And though
SPFs now go up to 40, that's overkill.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;SPF 15 is strong enough because the sun doesn't shine any longer than
that,&quot; says McCafferty. &quot;Whether it's waterproof or not will matter,
though.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Pay close attention to the ingredients. There are two kinds of UV rays that
burn, UVA and UVB. UVB rays, the most harmful, are most prominent from 10
a.m. until 3 p.m. UVB rays can be screened out with PABA, or Para-amino-benzoic
acid. <BR>
<BR>
PABA is not effective in screening out UVA rays, which are present all day,
but are 1000 times less effective in causing burns. That doesn't make them
okay, though; UVA penetrates the skin more deeply, causing more permanent
damage. UVA can only be blocked with benzophenones or zinc oxide. <BR>
<BR>
It is the UVA rays which are largely responsible for loss of elasticity
in the skin and damage to blood vessels, signs we often blame on 'aging.'
So sunlamps, even those that screen out the UVBs, aren't safe: not only
is UVA more damaging long-term, but the lamps sometimes provide up to ten
times the amount of UVA the sun does. And don't believe boasts of 'tan don't
burn' - if you burn rather than tan in the sun, the same will be true in
the booth. Studies suggest an increase in the chances for skin cancer if
you tan in the sun and with sun lamps than in the sun only.            
                            <BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
