<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Business Law</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Healthbeat.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrTitleBusinessLaw.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Education.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Education or Advice?</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Employers Must Walk a Fine Line When<BR>
Helping Employees Understand 401(K) Options<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Jim Urban</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>When Jeffrey Vinik resigned in late May as the high-profile manager
of Fidelity Investments' Magellan Fund, investors across the country wondered
aloud whether they should pull their money from the nation's largest mutual
fund.<BR>
<BR>
What makes the Magellan fund unique - other than its sheer size and relatively
stellar track record - is the fact that about 75 percent of the        
$56 billion invested in Magellan at the time of Vinik's departure represented
retirement money. And a good bit of that came via 401(k) plans.<BR>
<BR>
But when benefits managers were asked by employees about the significance
of Vinik's departure, none could offer much insight since providing what
amounts to &quot;investment advice&quot; exposes the employer to liability
if the investments go sour.<BR>
<BR>
The scenario illustrates a fine line employers have to walk in setting up
and administering self-directed investment vehicles for employees. Employers
must provide investment education - as well as a range of investment options
- if they want to qualify for the broad protection against liability afforded
by Section 404(c) of Employee Retirement Income Security Act, commonly known
as ERISA. But if they go too far with education - such as putting Vinik's
departure from Magellan into perspective - the dialogue could be characterized
as advice, exposing the employer to liability if investments go sour.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I would stay away from it,&quot; Joseph P. Nicola Jr., a certified
public accountant and attorney with Alpern, Rosenthal &amp; Co. in Pittsburgh,
says of the Vinik scenario.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In effect, you would probably be suggesting that the individual take
action or refrain from taking action, so you've engaged in investment advice.
The focus is on the fine line that separates advice from education.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
One recent study by benefits consultant Hewitt Associates showed that more
than 75 percent of employers surveyed are attempting to educate employees
about choosing investments for their retirement money, and for good reason.
The majority of employees in 401(k) plans aren't Wall Street savvy, so they
tend to pick investment funds conservatively. Some money market funds are
so conservative that by the time an employee reaches retirement, the fund's
rate of return will be outpaced by the rate of inflation.<BR>
<BR>
So while there is a legal obligation to avoid offering investment advice,
some say employers have a moral obligation to make sure employees aren't
being too conservative.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's a catch-22 situation, and for many employers it is frustrating,&quot;
says Joseph Marzano, a field vice president in Pittsburgh for American Express
Financial Advisers. &quot;Most employers would like to help employees, but
they can't go beyond that line.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In June, the Pension and Welfare Benefits Administration, a division of
the U.S. Department of Labor, issued what it calls an &quot;interpretive
bulletin&quot; listing four types of information employers can distribute
that will not be categorized as advisory:
<UL>
  <LI> Plan information: This includes the benefits of both plan participation
and increasing plan contributions, the impact of preretirement withdrawals
on retirement income and the terms and operation of the plan. Descriptions
of plan investment options, including investment objectives, risk and return
characteristics and historical return information also are included. 
  <LI>  General financial and investment information: General investment
concepts such as risk and return, diversification, dollar cost averaging,
compounded return and tax deferral all are considered appropriate. 
  <LI>  Asset allocation models: These are considered one of the most effective
ways to teach participants how to create their own retirement portfolios.
Asset allocation models previously were considered close to the line of
offering advice, and Nicola says some employers will be would to avoid them
for the time being. 
  <LI>Interactive investment materials: This is another type of communication
considered potentially advisory. This safe harbor allows the use of questionnaires,
worksheets, software and similar materials to give participants a way to
estimate future retirement income needs and assess the impact of different
asset allocations.  The materials must be based on generally accepted investment
theories and should include all material facts. 
</UL>
<BR>
&quot;Worker access to reliable and portable pension and savings plans is
essential,&quot; says Olena Berg, assistant U.S. secretary of labor. &quot;But
access alone will not assure retirement security. Workers need education
and information about the importance of saving for retirement, and about
how to take advantage of the available pension and savings vehicles to meet
their retirement income needs.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Safe Harbors</B><BR>
<BR>
Distribution of the following types of investment information is protected:<BR>
1. Plan Information<BR>
2. General financial and<BR>
    investment information<BR>
3. Asset allocation models<BR>
4. Interactive investment<BR>
    materials.<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> 
<ADDRESS>We would like to hear from you. Please give us your <A HREF="../brochure/feedback-form.html">Comments
or suggestions?</A><BR>
&copy; Copyright 1995-2005: Executive Report, Inc.</ADDRESS>
