<HTML>
<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Education </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Law.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H17Education.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Sports.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size =+2>Do Values Sell?</FONT></B><BR>
<B><I><FONT size=+1>Colleges With Religious Affiliation<BR>
Use it to Recruit Prospective Students</FONT></I></B><BR>
<I>By Gretchen McKay</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>When it comes to higher education, it's no secret that every institution
aims to set itself apart from its competitors. Each highlights something
 it believes that only it offers, be it the excellence of its programs,
the quality of its faculty or even the success of its sports teams.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We're all looking for a uniqueness, as well as what's best for young
people as they grow and become adults,&quot; says Dr. JoAnne Boyle, president
of Seton Hill College, a small Catholic, women's liberal arts college in
Greensburg.<BR>
<BR>
But what about faith and spirituality? Can a school attract students because
of  - or in spite of - its religious affiliation? Duquesne University's
slogan of &quot;Mind, Heart and Soul&quot; plays off its affiliation with
the Holy Ghost Fathers. If the growing enrollment at Duquesne and the other
religious institutions in the region is any indication, the answer is a
resounding &quot;yes.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Very few students will tell you they're coming here because [we're
a] Catholic college, but we know, from exit surveys, that's what draws some
of them,&quot; maintains Sister Marie Immaculee Dana, vice president for
academic affairs at Carlow College, a Catholic liberal arts college in Oakland
whose enrollment has jumped 100 percent in the past six years.<BR>
<BR>
Sister Marie credits Carlow's mission statement, which encourages students
to &quot;respond reverently and sensitively to God and others.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Everything we do flows from that mission,&quot; she says. &quot;Students
receive a strong values-focused education in whatever they do, whether it's
medicine, English or history.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It's the same at Seton Hill, where the Catholic identity of the school &quot;permeates&quot;
every class.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We hope that every student's education incorporates a sense of what
it means to give service to others,&quot; says Boyle, &quot;whether it's
in the workplace or the community.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Just as important, she notes, as well as one of the benefits of being a
church-related college, is helping students learn to answer the &quot;big&quot;
questions about why they studied what they did and what they'll do with
it.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We want them to ponder, 'What does it all mean in relation to the
larger world I live in?' &quot; says Boyle. &quot;You can't do that in a
secular institution.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Though it's hard to sort out who's coming to the college because of the
Catholic connection, Boyle says informal contacts with parents and students
affirm that many students look for a school with a Catholic environment.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;They're happy we have chaplains and a daily mass on campus, as well
as a set of values which guide us when we talk about student services,&quot;
she says.<BR>
<BR>
That's not to say undergrads must profess the same faith as a religious
college to be enrolled. In fact, it would     be almost impossible to target
just Catholics, both Sister Marie and Boyle concede, as there are very few
Catholic high schools from which to recruit.<BR>
<BR>
But that fact may actually work to a college's advantage.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's much more exciting to have others here because the dialogue 
is richer,&quot; Seton Hill's Boyle explains. &quot;You ask different questions,
and you think more about your own religious choices when someone else has
chosen something different.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
As for faculty, neither Seton Hill nor Carlow require their professors to
be Catholic, though they are expected to participate in the discussions
that occur in a Catholic community, as well as have some appreciation of
the Catholic perspective.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Nobody gets off the hook,&quot; says Boyle. &quot;You can't sit back
and say 'This isn't my discussion.' &quot; <BR>
It's a slightly different picture at Geneva College, an evangelical Christian
college in Beaver Falls.<BR>
William Katip, vice president for enrollment services, guesses at least
two-thirds of its student body is evangelical Christian, a faith that takes
a literal interpretation of the Bible.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We tend to get students who want a school with values, one that's
a little more on the conservative side,&quot; he says, noting Geneva is
one of just three Christian colleges in Pennsylvania. They also enjoy the
safe environment, where &quot;temptation&quot; is minimized.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I can't say that our students come with drastically different goals
in life, but a healthy number really want to make a difference in the world,&quot;
Katip says, adding there's a &quot;stronger desire [in students] for character
building,&quot; as well as a growing discontent with public education.<BR>
<BR>
At Geneva, the Christian world and life view is a framework through which
students view their classes. But that doesn't mean every class is a bible
class.<BR>
<BR>
While studying B.F. Skinner in a psychology course, for example, students
would study the belief  of determinism, which says a person's life is determined
independent of   one's will, then contrast it with the  biblical view, which
says man was    created in God's image with a purpose in life.<BR>
<BR>
Though observing the same faith is not a prerequisite for admission, students
usually are required to study some theology.<BR>
<BR>
At Carlow, for example, everyone must take at least one theology class,
while at Seton Hill, the core curriculum includes a course in philosophy
and a senior seminar on the values of all religious perspectives. Geneva
students must take three religion courses: Old and New Testament, and Christian
life and world view.<BR>
<BR>
The exception in the Pittsburgh area is La Roche College, a small Catholic
college nestled in the North Hills. No courses in theology are required,
however, humanities is part of the core curriculum.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We're not trying to indoctrinate anyone,&quot; says Monsignor William
Kerr, president, &quot;though we believe theology and philosophy are the
core of a good liberal arts education.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Still, La Roche espouses an approach to education that combines professional
preparation with a values-based liberal arts education.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We encourage the development of spiritual values and ways of life,&quot;
says Kerr. &quot;We let the window of the Catholic tradition inform the
way we think and act, and our courses reflect that wisdom.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
 It's a formula that works, according to Kerr, who says employers like prospects
with values.<BR>
&quot;Our students exemplify an ethical outlook on life,&quot; says Kerr,
&quot;and they carry into the marketplace the values they've developed at
La Roche.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Geneva's Katip would agree that employers are impressed with graduates of
a religious institution.<BR>
&quot;They tend to associate someone from Geneva with solid professionalism,
plus character,&quot; he says. &quot;Our students are trustworthy, honest
and not afraid to work hard.&quot;                        <BR>
