<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Sports Business </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Education.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrTitleSportsBusiness.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.SmallBusinessReport.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Quaint, But it Works</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>The Steelers are Committed to<BR>
St. Vincent College as Their Training Camp Site<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Bill Modoono</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Quaint is hardly an adjective frequently applied to the National
Football League.<BR>
<BR>
And, yet, what better word to describe the arrangement the Steelers and
St. Vincent College in Latrobe have had for 30 years? These days, certainly,
any element of professional sports not involving aggressive pursuit of revenue
 is old-fashioned, to say the least.<BR>
<BR>
The Steelers - like a majority of the 30 NFL teams - hold training camp
each July and August at a small college campus somewhat removed from their
home city. This arrangement, as football tradition holds, helps build team
unity, establishes a needed work ethic and prepares the players for the
rigors of the 16-game season.<BR>
<BR>
What it definitely does not do is produce much revenue for the Steelers,
even though in excess of 50,000 fans are expected to travel  to Westmoreland
County this summer to watch them. &quot;We think people like to come here
to relax with their family without spending any money,&quot; says Don Orlando,
a spokesman for St. Vincent College.<BR>
<BR>
As attractive as that image might be, it is out-of-sync with present-day
pro sports, which seemingly has figured out a way to market every aspect
of its existence. Moreover, in this era of escalating costs and aggressive
marketing in all of sports, being out-of-sync is a luxury few teams can
afford.<BR>
The marketing of the preseason is one area where most major pro sports are
behind baseball. Granted, baseball benefits from holding its preseason workouts
in warmer climes while fans up north are freezing, but, nonetheless, spring
training has become big business, with cities in Florida and Arizona bidding
to be host cities.<BR>
<BR>
The problem with marketing pro football training camps is there is not a
lot to sell. Pro football practice is a tedious endeavor that even at $5
would be overpriced. &quot;Some teams charge admission,&quot; says Joe Gordon,
the Steelers director of marketing, &quot;but we would not consider that.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In the past, Steelers camp has been marketed in limited ways. For example,
companies that sponsor Steeler games on WTAE Radio are often invited to
have special days at Latrobe. Company employees come &quot;inside the ropes&quot;
to watch practice and then have lunch and late-afternoon drinks under a
tent set up adjacent to the practice field.<BR>
<BR>
Gordon says the Steelers are exploring ways of marketing the preseason more
aggressively, including, for instance, selling the name of the field the
team practices on. The large expanse of green has always been known as Rooney
Field, but could be renamed, say, &quot;The I.C. Light/Rooney Field,&quot;
and get signage rights and other privileges for a week, a month or an entire
preseason. Gordon also foresees an increase in merchandising through the
on-site sale of food and souvenirs, &quot;but that's the extent of it.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The Steelers and St. Vincent have worked together for three decades without
a formal, written agreement, but there have been visible signs of commitment.
Last year, the Steelers made a substantial contribution to the school in
the form of Arthur J. Rooney Hall, the new dorm that will house Steeler
players in the summer and students the other 10 months of the year. <BR>
<BR>
At St. Vincent, the Steelers pay room fees for players in line with what
summer students pay - between $10 and $15 per player per night - plus additional
fees for meals and maintenance. Considering how disruptive the Steelers'
presence is to this quiet campus, that might seem a low price, but school
officials don't see it that way.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We value the visitors they draw to St. Vincent,&quot; says Dave Adams,
St. Vincent's director of facilities management. &quot;It gives us a chance
to show off our campus.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
It's a matter of faith at St. Vincent that countless students who attend
the school were exposed to it through the Steelers. Adams calls the arrangement
&quot;mutually beneficial,&quot; but worries about the money the Steelers
have placed into building an indoor facility at Duquesne. Five NFL teams
do not go away to training camp, instead using regular-season practice facilities.
If the Steelers become the sole tenant of Three Rivers Stadium, Gordon says
changes could be made (such as on the abandoned Kaufmann's site) to turn
the North Side into a modern Steelers practice facility. Such a facility
could make going to St. Vincent a costly anachronism.<BR>
<BR>
That seems highly unlikely, but St. Vincent knows better than to take the
Steelers for granted. This year, after the Steelers' opening session in
July, a 30th anniversary celebration was planned for visitors and their
families, complete with fireworks and picnics. Quaint, you could call it.
		  <BR>
