<HEAD>
    <TITLE>Small Business Report</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P><CENTER><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn2Arch.gif" BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../search/wais.cgi"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn3Sear.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="search" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../brochure/Help.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn4Help.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Help" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/0896.Contents.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtn5Contents.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Contents"
ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<A HREF="../zine/0896.Sports.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H16SmlBsnssRprt.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Feature.1.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Banking on Business</FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Regional Banks Back Small Business With<BR>
an Array of Growth-Oriented Products<BR>
</FONT></B><I>By Henry Lipput</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>Leo McDonough remembers one story a banker related about a small
business owner who was inquiring about a loan. The business owner had his
financial information scribbled on the back of a used envelope, hardly proper
documentation. Knowing that, long-time small business advocate McDonough
isn't quick to blame the banks for problems some small business owners run
into with banks.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think it's a two-edged sword,&quot; says McDonough, president of
SMC Business Councils, a small business trade group. &quot;I hear my people
complaining that it's very difficult to get money. Part of that I think,
is not the bank's fault. A lot of times we find out that much of the problem
with small business trying to get money is they're not going in prepared.&quot;
In fact, the banks are probably more helpful than ever to the small business
community, which is viewed as a growth sector of Pennsylvania's economy.
All banks offer the standard financing and checking account services, but
most banks today also will sit down with small business owners to anticipate
situations - such as rapid growth - and identify solutions to potential
        problems.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;A lot of times, I'll sit down with a client and talk about alternatives,&quot;
says Lloyd Gibson, president and CEO of NorthSide bank. &quot;I tell them
to forget for a minute that I am the banker. We'll look six months into
the future, walk through things and anticipate what is going to happen.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Even the giant banks have zeroed in during recent years on the small business
sector. Before being acquired by National City Bank, Integra was a traditional
regional leader in writing Small Business Administration loans, a focus
National City will maintain.  Mellon and PNC, meanwhile, aggressively court
the small businesses, writing loans and rolling out products and services
geared specifically to that market segment. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think Mellon, historically, has been associated with the USXs, the
Alcoas, and whatnot, but for many, many years, Mellon has recognized the
importance of the small business market,&quot; says Andy Paterno, a vice
president and regional manager for Mellon Bank's Business Banking division.
<BR>
&quot;Across the state right now, we have a very large commercial loan commitment
to small businesses: in excess of $1.4 billion in loans to businesses with
less than $10 million in sales. We have a very large commitment in exposure
to the small business market, and we're very interested in trying to deepen
our relationships by attracting them with products that seem to make sense.&quot;
<BR>
 <BR>
&quot;About a third of the loans we make are to startup kinds of companies,&quot;
adds Keith Crytzer, senior vice president at PNC Bank and manager of business
banking. &quot;I think we have provided capital to a segment of small business
that maybe didn't get it before because of the risk involved and how difficult
it was to get a government guarantee for those small loans.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
At Mellon, some small business clients are using the Business Builder line
of credit, which can be made available for up to $250,000 and is a five-year
line of credit.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The customary line of credit is written on demand and can be withdrawn
by the bank technically at its discretion,&quot; Paterno says. &quot;But
on this committed line, we have basically made a five-year commitment to
this company to provide credit provided that they pay as agreed and we're
not made aware of any derogatory information about the company in terms
of its payment behavior.&quot; <BR>
In addition, Mellon, through its affiliation with Dreyfuss, has developed
Easy 401K, a retirement plan for small business customers with less than
$25 million in sales and between four and 200 employees.<BR>
<BR>
PNC, meanwhile, is one of 18 banks in the country piloting FA$TRAK loans,
in which banks can use their own application forms to quickly approve loans
up to $100,000, 50 percent of which is guaranteed by the SBA. Another PNC
staple is the traditional LowDoc (or low documentation) loan, for which
the application is a one-page form.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We have participated for years with the Small Business Administration
to make guaranteed loans,&quot; PNC's Crytzer says. &quot;A lot of the other
banks do the same thing but, I think if you look at our record, we've done
as much if not more than any bank in this area.&quot; <BR>
 <BR>
PNC has recently introduced Business Express/PC, a PC-based electronic banking
product, for the small business market. &quot;Through some software and
a PC and a modem, [you can] find out what your account balances are at any
time. You also can move funds between accounts,&quot; Crytzer says.<BR>
PNC also has products such as Easy Business Lease, which allows small businesses
to finance the lease of office equipment, and offers payroll services through
a company called Paychex.<BR>
<BR>
The traditional leader in small business lending in recent years was Integra,
which was acquired by National City Bank in a transaction completed this
past spring. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The SBA program has been particularly invaluable to us because if
we look at where our future customers are coming from, they're coming from
small business startups, from people that have acquired existing small businesses,
and from small businesses that are expanding,&quot; says National City's
David Slomski, who served as vice president of Integra's small business
resource group before the acquisition. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;When you look at how regulators view loans to startups, to expansions,
there's a serious concern there as far as the lack of a documented history
of cash flow and earnings,&quot; Slomski says. &quot;And this is where the
SBA program comes into play. For the last four years, we were the leading
producer of SBA loans out of the Pittsburgh district [SBA] office. Last
year we produced over $21 million in SBA loans.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We continue to offer a wide variety of loan products other than SBA
loans to all of our small business customers,&quot; adds Slomski, &quot;but
the SBA program in particular has allowed us to aggressively service the
startup, expansion and acquisition market which a lot of banks have elected
not to get involved in.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
The smaller banks often pull small business clients away from giant banks
by painting them as just that: giant. When you deal with a smaller bank,
the service is more personalized, the smaller banks say.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I think our approach is a little different because of the size of
our bank,&quot; says Gretchen Hart, vice president and manager of corporate
services for Dollar Bank. &quot;We don't really design special services
for any particular size of company. Our focus is  building a relationship
with whatever size company we do business with.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We like to think of ourselves as getting to know the small business
person and developing that relationship, both on the loan side and the deposit
side. We design all of our products to be flexible. We're small enough to
do some special processing for the smaller business customer.&quot; <BR>
 <BR>
Dollar Bank offers a state-of-the-art PC-based product called Cash Analyzer,
that can be used by all of the bank's business customers. Using a PC and
modem, customers can dial into the bank and get information that can be
used by them in managing their daily business. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Our main focus is really partnering ourselves with our customers and
understanding their business,&quot; says Hart. &quot;That's what we believe
we do very well.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
The even smaller NorthSide Bank echoes that message.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;All banks are good, but what we provide and some of the smaller banks
provide is personalized service,&quot; says NorthSide's Gibson. &quot;We
get to know the customers, get to know their needs and introduce them to
as many people in the bank as possible. So if they have a problem, more
than just one person can help them out.&quot;		  <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<HR><A HREF="../HomePage.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtn1Home.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><A HREF="../zine/Archives.html"><IMG SRC=
