"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT SIZE=+2></B></FONT><BR>
<FONT SIZE=+>Take it Or Leave it<BR>
</FONT SIZE><BR>
<I>By Jim Urban</I></CENTER>
<P><HR><BR>
<B>That's the Attitude Many Insurers Exhibit When Policyholders <BR>
Seek Coverage of a Claim;<BR>
Businesses Nowadays Often Must Take the Insurer to Court, Settle for Less
Than What They Deserve or Absorb the Loss Themselves</B><BR>
<BR>
At the Gamble Farm Inn, the waiters and waitresses serve gourmet food in
the comfortable atmosphere of a restored, large farmhouse. Some say it's
like eating at a bed 'n breakfast, minus the beds.<BR>
<BR>
But one October evening a few years back, a squirrel preparing for a cold
Pennsylvania winter spoiled dinner for a number of patrons. The squirrel
stored nuts in the flue vent leading from the restaurant's hot water heater,
causing carbon monoxide to back up into the restaurant, which is just outside
of Williamsport in Jersey Shore, Lycoming County.<BR>
<BR>
Some patrons became ill, a few of them heading to local emergency rooms
for outpatient treatment. The inn paid some of the medical bills, but realized
after cutting checks totaling several thousands of dollars that it should
turn the matter over to its insurance carrier, New Jersey-based Selective
Insurance Co.<BR>
<BR>
After all, restaurant management figured, isn't protecting against liability
from this type of incident precisely why the restaurant purchased insurance
coverage?<BR>
<BR>
That's when the Gamble Farm Inn learned first-hand what businesses large
and small across the country are finding out with each passing day: The
insurance industry, in many cases, is doing whatever it takes to minimize
or deny coverage. And often, the business is left to take the insurer to
court, absorb the loss itself or settle for a lesser amount than it probably
deserves.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Clients look at me like I am crazy when I tell them they have two
adversaries: the plaintiff and their insurance company,&quot; says Jennifer
Wilson Hewitt, an attorney at Pittsburgh's Doepken Keevican and Weiss. &quot;They
can't believe that even though they have paid maybe hundreds of thousands
of dollars in premiums, the insurance company won't open its checkbook and
pay a claim.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In the past,&quot; adds attorney Andrew Roman of Pittsburgh's Cohen
&amp; Grigsby, &quot;an insurer might have denied a claim because they had
a serious concern about an issue or two. The atmosphere nowadays is that
once they've made the decision that they will question the claim and not
treat it as an honored claim, the insurers seem very willing to take the
gloves off and play hardball.<BR>
&quot;They assert every conceivable ground they can think of to deny coverage.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
In Gamble Farm Inn's claim, Selective Insurance labeled the carbon monoxide
as pollution and invoked a standard clause in Comprehensive General Liability
policies excluding coverage for pollution-related claims. Simply put, Selective
told the inn it was on its own.<BR>
<BR>
A common pleas court judge eventually ordered the insurer to pay, and that
ruling was upheld on appeal by the Superior Court of Pennsylvania, which
chastised the insurance company for trying to deny coverage under the pollution
exclusion.<BR>
<BR>
But what remains eye-opening to many is the fact that the matter had to
be litigated before the $7,000 claim was paid in the first place. The insurance
company probably spent over $30,000 in legal fees fighting the claim, according
to attorneys familiar with insurance litigation.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The client could not believe it, and I could not believe it. We could
not believe the carrier was serious,&quot; recalls Kristine Waltz, the Williamsport
attorney who represented Gamble Farm Inn.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;[The insurer] really thought, I think, that this was some mom and
pop operation out in the country. 'Are they going to sue us over a $7,000
claim?' &quot; Waltz says.<BR>
<BR>
They sued. They won. Welcome to business insurance and claims in the '90s.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Militant Insurers<BR>
</B><BR>
In fairness to insurance companies, many claims still get paid without much
trouble. But as numerous other cases show, the militant handling of the
Gamble Farm Inn claim was by no means an isolated incident. Consider some
other recent claims and subsequent insurance carrier reaction: 
<UL>
  <LI>When a construction worker was overcome by fumes from a concrete sealant,
the construction company's insurer characterized the fumes as pollution
and cited the policy's pollution exclusion in refusing to pay the claim.
  <LI>When a poultry producer had products ruined by exposure to a chemical
used to resurface a floor, the insurer denied the claim under the pollution
exclusion. 
  <LI>When a child suffered burns due to exposure to formic acid that was
left behind by a carpet dyeing contractor, the insurer invoked the pollution
exclusion to deny coverage. 
</UL>
<BR>
Those are a handful of minor claims. But the practice of citing exclusions
to escape claims goes on in some high profile cases, too. Insurance carriers
for Exxon, for instance, denied coverage of the Valdez oil spill off Alaska,
citing the pollution exclusion.<BR>
<BR>
And most notably, an insurance carrier pulled into claims stemming from
the World Trade Center bombing refused to indemnify the Port Authority of
New York and New Jersey, which operates the Trade Center. The insurer said
the port authority &quot;expected&quot; the 1992 terrorist attack, excluding
the incident from coverage under another standard CGL policy exclusion:
the &quot;expected or intended exclusion.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Most [businesses] are not aware of what they are up against,&quot;
says Cohen &amp; Grigsby's Roman, who focuses part of his practice on representing
companies pursuing insurance claims.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Their attitude is: 'I thought this is why I bought insurance.' They
have been indoctrinated for so many years by the advertising of the insurance
industry. ... 'You're in good hands.' In reality, it can be an adversarial
situation right off the bat.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Why the militancy? Simply because insurance is a business. And just like
any other business, the bottom line is the bottom line.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's an outrage,&quot; says Eugene Anderson, whose Manhattan-based
law firm Anderson Kill Olick &amp; Oshinsky is nationally known for representing
policyholders whose claims have been denied by insurers acting in bad faith.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The insurance companies are now in the hands of the Wall Street financiers,&quot;
Anderson says. &quot;The insurance companies are no longer run by old line
insurance people. This is now a financial flim-flam. What Wall Street discovered
is that you make more money collecting premiums and not paying claims than
you do collecting premiums and paying claims.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The insurance industry does pay $1 billion a year fighting policyholders
in court,&quot; Anderson adds.<BR>
The insurance industry tells a different story. It's not militant, industry
insiders say, just thorough in the claims process because it has to be.
Given, the insurance industry took some mammoth financial hits in the past
seven years due to natural disasters. For instance, the industry paid out
$15.5 billion to cover losses in south Florida caused by Hurricane Andrew
in 1992, when total losses from disasters totaled $23 billion nationally.
Prior to that, the previous national high for annual disaster losses was
$9 million in 1989, when Hurricane Hugo devastated Charleston, S.C. Some
insurance companies, stinging from the Hugo/Andrew bloodbaths, stopped writing
policies in coastal areas and refused to renew existing policies. It got
so bad that some states took measures to prevent the insurers from leaving
longtime policy holders high and dry.<BR>
<BR>
Another factor in the mix is insurance fraud, which takes about $20 billion
from the industry annually, or about 10 cents of every premium dollar paid.<BR>
<BR>
Insurance industry insiders say their industry had no choice but to change
the way it did business. <BR>
What's that mean for business? You still may be in good hands, but those
hands won't be wearing kid gloves, industry insiders say.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;In some respects, it looks like things are getting bogged down, when
in fact the insurance companies are merely processing the claims in a more
diligent and closely watched manner,&quot; says Richard Gilman of the Manhattan-based
Insurance Information Institute.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<B>Business Insurance<BR>
</B><BR>
The first thing any business should realize about insurance policies is
that most of them are standard forms written by the insurance industry.<BR>
<BR>
At the core of any business's insurance coverage is its Comprehensive General
Liability policy, in which the insurance company generally promises to provide
the policyholder with legal representation, at the insurance company's expense,
if a third party makes a claim for injury or damage allegedly caused by
the policyholder. The insurance company also promises to pay for any settlement
or adverse judgment entered against the policyholder in such a claim or
lawsuit. <BR>
Liability policies once were written for a specific hazard, so a policyholder
had to purchase a separate liability policy for each specific hazard against
which the policyholder wanted to insure. That changed in 1941, when the
separate policies were combined into a single standard form all-risk policy
-the earliest version of the comprehensive general liability policy. The
new policy was hailed as a merchandiser's dream for insurance companies.<BR>
<BR>
By 1970, the insurance industry added the pollution exclusion modification
as a mandatory endorsement to the CGL policy, calling it &quot;mere clarification&quot;
of existing coverage. Today, it's a window many insurers use to escape a
claim. Traditionally, however, it was aimed at environmental hazards, not
carbon monoxide emitted from a hot water heater at the Gamble Farm Inn.
Pennsylvania's Superior Court noted as much in its opinion in the case.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;An insurer contracts with an insured to provide coverage for certain
risks, in return for payment of premiums which are calculated based upon
those risks,&quot; Judge Phyllis W. Beck wrote in 1995. &quot;It is reasonable
and understandable that, when issuing an ordinary commercial CGL policy,
an insurer undertakes to cover the risks which may occur within a building
- a finite, measurable space with certain risks, such as fire or flood.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The insurer attaches a pollution exclusion to such a policy because
the damage caused by environmental contamination can be the kind of catastrophe
the coverage of which is not undertaken by the insurer under normal commercial
circumstances; the premiums on an ordinary commercial policy would not reflect
the costly coverage of such a risk. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The pollution exclusion in this case, within the context of an ordinary
commercial CGL policy, understandably protects the insurance company from
having to pay for losses that are in the nature of an environmental catastrophe
- pollution of land, atmosphere, and bodies of water. However, the law does
not permit the insurer, by hiding behind the language of its pollution exclusion,
to eliminate its responsibility to its insured for the type of loss suffered
by [Gamble Farm Inn]. An attempt to apply the exclusion under these circumstances
appears to be an afterthought, based upon ambiguous language, rather than
the express purpose for which the exclusion was drafted. In such cases,
the insured must prevail.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Most CGL policies also carry the &quot;expected or intended exclusion,&quot;
which is at issue in the World Trade Center bombing claims. This excludes
claims for injury or property damage that is not accidental, but rather
&quot;expected or intended from the standpoint of the insured.&quot; World
Trade Center management should have expected a terrorist attack, insurers
argue.<BR>
<BR>
Procedurally, it's the policyholder's burden in court to show insurance
coverage applies. Then it's the insurer's burden to show that the claim
is excluded.<BR>
<BR>
Often, either party will initially go to court seeking a declaratory judgment,
a binding adjudication of the rights of the litigants even though no relief
is awarded. In other words, a judge will decide whether an incident is covered
or not. <BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Is Litigation Inevitable?<BR>
<BR>
As Doepken's Hewitt pointed out, the insurer will not just open its checkbook
and cover a claim. <BR>
That's true not only when a third party is attempting to hold the policyholder
liable for a loss, but also when the policyholder itself is the one experiencing
the loss and wants to invoke business interruption or some other coverage.<BR>
<BR>
Most certainly, expect investigation and delays. Anderson Kill's Anderson
says the claims process has four speeds: slow, very slow, stop and reverse.
He and others point to a common misconception about the insurance industry:
that it makes money by collecting premiums. In reality, the insurance industry
is a huge institutional investor, investing the premiums it collects and
making its money off those investments. So any money the insurance industry
is not paying out to settle claims is making the industry money on Wall
Street.<BR>
<BR>
How do you keep your claim on the fast track, if there is such a thing?
It starts with preparation. Never take a claim lightly.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The carriers are entitled to do their due diligence, and they do,&quot;
says Joseph T. Anastasi, a Price Waterhouse accountant based in San Francisco
who heads the firm's national insurance claims practice. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The carriers form a team including an adjustor retained by the carrier,
maybe a forensic accountant and some others,&quot; Anastasi says. &quot;When
I first became involved in this kind of work, it struck me immediately that
the carrier is well prepared to evaluate a claim on behalf of the carriers.
A risk manager who spends his entire career in the field may only experience
a significant loss once in his career. And even though that fellow is in
the business, the claim may still be a once-in-a-career type of thing. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Meanwhile, the A team is going to be sitting across the table, for
sure,&quot; Anastasi says. &quot;That team sitting across the table, working
for the insurer, is very experienced, going back 15 or 20 years and probably
hundreds or thousands of claims.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Most major casualty liability insurers create special claims handling
units,&quot; adds Cohen &amp; Grigsby's Roman. &quot;These units are assigned
more difficult claims - asbestos or pollution-related claims.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The special coverage units are experts at the different types of claims
that are handled by those units,&quot; Roman says.<BR>
<BR>
The point: expect the other side to have more experience in the claims process
than you have. So prepare your claim like you are preparing for a court
case. Often times, with bigger claims, that means hiring some outside help.
Never leave it up to the insurer to do the majority of the leg work in the
claims process, Anastasi says.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Do you want the IRS to prepare your tax return?&quot; he asks. &quot;You
have to understand that you must advocate your position, collect proof and
support the claim, present it as a compelling story. It's better for you
to present the evidence.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Whenever you do the fact-finding you will find black and white issues
and gray issues, then you have to sort out those gray issues.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Such a strategy works. When the San Francisco earthquake hit during the
1989 World Series, its victims included a special World Series advertising
section that was to be published by a city newspaper. Such sections are
cash cows for newspapers, yet this one never made it to press due to the
earthquake, and there were no hard revenue projections to reference in developing
the claim. Price Waterhouse, in working for the newspaper, was able to estimate
lost revenues by studying a similar supplement produced for one of the Super
Bowls won by the 49ers. It was a reasonable basis for estimating the loss,
for which the insurer eventually paid.<BR>
<BR>
Cohen &amp; Grigsby's Roman says he's seen similar strategies work, including
very recently for one of his clients. You have to prove what you are entitled
to and avoid trumping up the claim, which hurts your own credibility, Roman
says.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;I was convinced at the end of it that we were successful because we
were very professional, very well documented and very credible.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;We didn't go for the stars,&quot; Roman says.<BR>
<BR>
If the insurer still balks, then you can take it to the next level. In some
cases, mediation or arbitration saves costs incurred with no-holds-barred
litigation. <BR>
<BR>
The odd man out at this stage is often the agent who sold the original policy.
It's likely the agent will get a complaint call from the policyholder, who
is wondering why she or he is being hassled about a claim. Sometimes the
agent can help, but most often the agent is pushed out of the loop by the
carrier.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The role of the agent is to explain coverages and make it very clear
[when the policy is sold],&quot; says James L. Cavanaugh Jr., a one-time
regional manager for Employers Insurance of Wausau who now brokers policies
for several carriers as an agent with Concept Insurance Associates on Pittsburgh's
North Side.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;Usually the insurance companies want the agents out of it, but the
agent has a role to represent the client,&quot; Cavanaugh says. &quot;It
really puts the agent in a difficult position. Usually it's best for them
to stay out of it, but there are times when the agent has a role.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;There is no black and white answer,&quot; Cavanaugh says.<BR>
<BR>
Know this: When the carriers do challenge a claim, they do so without consulting
the sales agent, so it may be a waste of time to call to complain. <BR>
<BR>
Instead, focus resources on convincing the carrier that your claim should
be covered. Expect the carrier, as Roman says, to play hardball. <BR>
<BR>
And don't take no for an answer.<BR>
<BR>
The Gamble Farm Inn probably could have absorbed its $7,000 claim, but chose
not to. In the end - through the trial court and the Superior Court - it
was a matter of principal.<BR>
&quot;It was a reach,&quot; says Waltz, the attorney who represented Gamble
Farm Inn, of the insurance company's position in the case.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;This claim probably could have been settled in the very early stages
for about $5,000<BR>
&quot;It pays sometimes to call their bluff,&quot; Waltz says.<BR>
<BR>
