<A HREF="../zine/0896.Feature.1.html"><IMG SRC="../hci/HdrBtnBck.gif"
BORDER="0" ALT="Previous" ALIGN="BOTTOM"></A><IMG SRC="../hci/H1Features.gif"
BORDER="0" ALIGN="BOTTOM"><A HREF="../zine/0896.Supplement2.html"><IMG SRC=
"../hci/HdrBtnNxt.gif" BORDER="0" ALT="Next" ALIGN=
"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>The Green Party </FONT></B><BR>
<B><FONT size=+1>Architects and Building Contractors Have Always Strived
to Maximize Efficiency in the Structures They Erect;<BR>
Today's Movement Toward Green Design Is Taking That Philosophy<BR>
to New Heights in Both<BR>
Commercial and Residential Development <BR>
</FONT></B><BR>
<I>By Cynthia Bent</I></CENTER>
<P><HR>PG headquarters is 1 million square feet of glass, rising straight
into the air in downtown Pittsburgh. It's one of the city's best-looking
buildings, but few would guess PPG Industries' fairy-tale castle is the
most energy-efficient office building in the city as well. Its double-thick
panes are coated with silver that reflects heat and glare, reducing the
need for excessive air conditioning. At the same time, the glass lets in
enough daylight to reduce the need for artificial lighting and heating.
<BR>
<BR>
And now PPG Place pinches even more watts, having signed on with the EPA's
voluntary Green Lights program, aimed at conserving energy through more
efficient lighting in businesses. PPG's savings from revamping its already-thrifty
headquarters with energy-miser florescent lamps, reflectors and motion-sensitive
switches will total about $33,000 per year.<BR>
<BR>
Politically correct? Most definitely. Unique? Not really. Architects have
always tried to build efficiently, using natural resources as best they
could. The catch-phrase &quot;green design&quot; has emerged as high-tech
materials and processes became available for these ends. The aim for green
design advocates is building with minimal impact on the environment that
costs as little as possible to maintain along the way.<BR>
 <BR>
&quot; 'Green' or earth-sensitive architecture is good architecture and
good business,&quot; says Martin Powell, principal architect at the Design
Alliance in Pittsburgh. <BR>
<BR>
Powell says green design, like any design philosophy, works best when it's
pervasive through all decisions. Alcoa, for example, wanted to make maximum
use of daylight to reduce electricity bills in its new building along the
Allegheny River, slated for 1998 completion. High-tech glass<BR>
incorporated into a striking, rolling facade of floor-to-ceiling windows
makes it possible to add light without losing money on heating and cooling.
<BR>
<BR>
Alcoa also saves with a modern heating and cooling system - low- velocity
cool air comes through the floor instead of high-velocity air  blowing through
the ceiling. Cold air rides a &quot;thermal plume&quot; up to exit ducts
near the ceiling, carrying dust with it. Air is exchanged often throughout
the day, providing a more comfortable environment and less absenteeism -
a tangible, proven result. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Air is cooler, perceptibly fresher, and it's a lower cost to operate
and install,&quot; says Powell. &quot;Good architecture and good business
at the same time.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Powell says there is a wealth of information available on sustainability
issues to the architecture trade through trade literature and via the Internet.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;The ideas we used in the Alcoa building were first experimented with
in a Hong Kong bank. Using the Internet, we talked to engineers half an
earth away,&quot; he says. <BR>
<BR>
Al Posti, corporate spokesperson for Alcoa, says they've done a little recycling
already in planning their new headquarters, using ideas from the 31st floor
of their present building. That was reconverted by Design Alliance in 1994
using an open-floored office plan. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;There have been a lot of positive outcomes from that experience up
there. For example, the contact between executive management is better.
There's more interaction between people,&quot; says Posti.<BR>
 &quot;From that experience, one of the things we're doing in the new building,
for example, is the main means of vertical transportation will be escalators,
not elevators. It opens up the building and also makes the trip up part
of the work experience.&quot; The goal? To make employees feel that the
entire building, rather than just a cubicle, is their office.<BR>
<BR>
The building will also be wired for flexibility, so workers can  wheel computers
around and plug in anywhere instead of recabling. Project teams may come
together in one large central of-fice for months at a time, then reassemble
elsewhere on the project's completion. For Alcoa, the open-space design
links multiple goals - increased light efficiency, productivity and flexibility.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Refining Green Design<BR>
</B><BR>
These ideas are examples of advanced office design principles working their
way slowly into corporate America's consciousness. Europe is way ahead of
the game when it comes to planning an office, with astronomical energy prices
and strong worker unions advancing these issues. But there are signs of
life here, such as the Center for Building Performance and Diagnostics at
Carnegie Mellon University. Researchers here, under Director Dr. Volker
Hartkopf, have put all these high-tech concepts under one roof to create
a concrete example (no pun intended) of what  Hartkopf  calls the Intelligent
Workplace. The $3.8 million project, under construction on the roof of the
Margaret Morrison building at CMU, will serve as a real-life laboratory
for everything from revolutionary airflow and temperature systems to better
workplace dynamics.<BR>
<BR>
Supported by the Advanced Building Systems Integration Consortium, the Intelligent
Workplace integrates all these eco- and budget-friendly systems into a model
of the office for the 21st century.<BR>
Hartkopf coaxed some very big guns into ABSIC, including the National Science
Foundation, American Bridge Company, Korea's Hanbo Steel &amp; Construction
Co., Siemens Energy and Automations, Inc., and others. They've all invested
heavily in the workplace of the future, with both dollars and time.<BR>
<BR>
The goal is to set up a system of research and development for the  commercial
building industry, refining what already exists and testing new ideas. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;The commercial building industry spends at most only .5 percent of
its sales in research. If you look at that in comparison to medical research,
you can see that the building industry as a whole (which is twice as large
as the health industry) spends a pittance on research,&quot; says Hartkopf.<BR>
Why is this research worth doing? Hartkopf says with the resulting advances,
businesses can pay back the initially higher investment in under three years
and continue to gain afterwards, just from increases in worker productivity.
Reduced absenteeism alone, he says, can save large companies millions. Not
to mention the energy savings, which because of our lower fuel costs, he
says, Americans take for granted. In Germany, he says, despite the higher
fuel costs, office energy bills are comparable to ours, due to these techniques.
<BR>
<BR>
Hartkopf says the ideas he talks about aren't exactly taking America by
storm, despite well-established evidence that they create great savings
for businesses. He realizes that building design isn't the only key to productivity.
But he believes a well-designed workplace is an essential part of the equation.
It's just convincing American business of the same.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;But I don't mind to be doing Sisyphus work. I'm a happy Sisyphus.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
<B>Residential<BR>
</B><BR>
All this sophistication translates to homebuilding as well as commercial
construction. For several years, builder Keith Scheidemantle has focused
on building himself a potential  high-growth niche in the Pittsburgh market
by &quot;building green&quot; in the residential field.<BR>
<BR>
A couple of examples: Instead of concrete block foundations, a Pittsburgh
standard, Scheidemantle starts with polystyrene block forms on reinforced
steel skeletons. The blocks interlock, almost like hollow high-tech Legos;
concrete is then poured into the forms, but unlike standard poured-concrete
foundations, the forms remain as an integral part of the structure. The
resulting walls have twice the insulating efficiency of traditional materials.
Other benefits include dry basements, greater fireproofing, superior structural
strength and sound reduction. <BR>
<BR>
Similar innovative materials can take the place of conventional building
shells and roofing, saving more on insulation, construction time and natural
resources like wood.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;These are engineered materials,&quot; says Scheidemantle. &quot;They're
actually more stable than the standard 2x4s or 2x10s people use in their
walls.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
Inside the house, Scheidemantle employs techniques like heat pumps and air
exchangers for increased energy efficiency and cleaner, fresher air. Scheidemantle
says all new houses are increasingly airtight. Carpeting, laminates and
formica give off formaldehyde gas; pollutants like smoke and radon also
build up, creating &quot;sick house syndrome,&quot; where residents feel
ill from living in their own homes. Scheidemantle avoids these traditional
hazards with air exchangers and products like non-&quot;off-gassing&quot;
carpeting, made of recycled plastic bottles. <BR>
<BR>
These ideas and materials are relatively new in the United States but are
used extensively in Europe, where the materials have proven themselves,
especially in Scandinavia. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Once people see the houses and do the numbers, there's no problem
selling the ideas,&quot; despite higher initial costs, says Scheidemantle.
&quot;It takes an educational process for the public - people are skeptical
of anything new.&quot; <BR>
<BR>
Scheidemantle built a model home in Cranberry as an educational tool for
people to see an alternative building style and lifestyle. It's identical
in appearance to a conventional home; the materials allow for great creativity
in design. Scheidemantle says he got 40 inquiries from the home's appearance
 in the Parade of Homes Show. But even with the increased enthusiasm lately,
Scheidemantle says Pittsburgh is behind the times when it comes to    residential
construction.<BR>
<BR>
&quot;It just seems like an isolated pocket. Most places do poured-concrete
foundations, for example, and Pittsburgh still uses concrete blocks, because
there's a big block factory here. [Eco-friendly housing] is definitely a
niche to exploit.&quot;<BR>
<BR>
All this eco-friendliness usually adds about 3 to 8 percent to the cost
of the house, Scheidemantle says. But the savings in energy consumption
are immediately apparent. Scheidemantle says most homeowners can save 50
to 70 percent on their energy bills. With most of these homes, payback is
almost immediate to within five years. Some banks are even starting programs
that allow for larger mortgages as the energy efficiency in a house increases,
because they know bills will be lower. <BR>
<BR>
<B>The Big Picture</B><BR>
<BR>
Conservation Consultants Inc., a non-profit, wants to apply all these ideals
even more globally - to efficient neighborhoods. Their efforts, they believe,
could save whole communities valuable resources and money. They're starting
with Pittsburgh's Carrick neighborhood.<BR>
<BR>
Utilities in Pennsylvania are mandated to spend a percentage of their in-come
on low income people with bad debt. One way they do this is to contract
out to companies like CCI who visit homes and show residents ways they can
save energy - insulate the water heater, for instance. Put a brick in the
toilet. Insulate the windows with plastic and caulk. Such quick-fix efforts
can earn over 30 percent savings on energy bills. <BR>
<BR>
So CCI took the project one step further. What if, they thought, they could
consolidate all the surveys in one area, and address the whole community
with sustainable principles? <BR>
<BR>
&quot;Monthly, if you have a $150 heating bill, you're looking at $50 per
month, that's $600 a year that every single house that participates has,&quot;
says Dennis Walton of CCI. &quot;So it's like we have this economic snowball
where a community has more disposable income. Every dollar you spend on
your utility bill, 70 to 80 cents of that leaves the state. Now that money
stays in your pocket. That's the whole idea of this project - to keep more
money in your neighborhood by reducing your bills.&quot; His title, Sustainable
Design Program Coordinator, reflects CCI's aim - to help build communities
that can sustain themselves with a minimum of outside resources and waste.<BR>
<BR>
That's only the tip of the iceberg in Carrick. CCI proposed to provide the
weatherizing and other products for the low income group and to offer free
surveys to higher income brackets, too. Why stop there? they thought, and
offered consultation to local businesses, spreading information about energy-saving
technology. They've offered free services to churches and local schools,
and planted gardens in empty lots. One hope: to lure new businesses to the
area with the combination of enhanced services and a richer community.<BR>
<BR>
The utilities, Columbia Gas and Pennsylvania American Water, bit on the
project. So did the Heinz Foundation. And six local banks have agreed to
offer special low-interest loans to cover improvements. <BR>
<BR>
CCI modeled its activities on a few cities around the country like Chattanooga,
Tenn., and Osage, Iowa. In Osage, 3,000 people started these initiatives;
now the town saves $1 million a year. Industry has grown and stabilized,
businesses stayed, and the biggest manufacturer grew three times in size
because of energy efficiency. There are over 11,000 people in Carrick, so
if you do the numbers, says Walton, you can see what the potential is. Hopefully
the project will expand next year into more Pittsburgh neighborhoods.<BR>
<BR>
It's easy to see why CCI is attractive to benefactors like the Heinz Foun-dation.
As a movement in Pittsburgh, sustainable developers are perhaps the most
impressive, networked and focused in the city. People work with each other
to not reinvent the wheel, coordinating in group projects and associations.
CCI is talking with Scheidemantle, for instance, about coordinating efforts
for resource-efficient, low-income public housing. The market, they all
say, will soon drive itself as people in the area realize they can save
30 percent, 50 percent, and more on residential bills and manufacturing
costs. <BR>
<BR>
&quot;It's no longer a tree-hugger's movement. It's now economically and
socially logical to do these things,&quot; Walton says. &quot;The difference
between those who have gone sustainable and those who have not is going
to be so drastic that you're either going to jump on board or you're going
to get run over.&quot;                                                 
<BR>
<BR>
