"BOTTOM"></A> <BR>
<B><FONT size=+2>Do You Have A Plan </FONT></B><BR>
</CENTER>
<P><HR><B>We Asked a Panel of Financial Planning<BR>
Experts to Walk Us Through a Typical Life;<BR>
Here's Their Advice on the Concerns and Actions One Should Heed From Marriage
<BR>
On Through Family, Career and Finally Retirement<BR>
<BR>
A Special Supplement to Executive Report<BR>
<BR>
</B><HR><BR>
Finance has been known to humankind for thousands of years. In the past,
monarchs control-  led the wealth, using it to finance      their empire
building. Christopher Columbus asked Queen Isabella to finance his voyage
to the New World. Later, men like Mellon, Carnegie and Frick used their
wealth and ideas to finance their own empires -  in the process fueling
western Pennsylvania's industrial revolution.<BR>
<BR>
According to the American Heritage Dictionary, &quot;finance&quot; is the
science of managing money and other assets. Not suprisingly, in the past
finance was often thought of as relevant to a relatively small segment of
the population.  Only individuals and families with great wealth could afford
to employ advisors to help maintain and increase their fortune.<BR>
<BR>
But that's all changed. Today, the need to manage financial affairs has
spawned a whole new industry: financial planning. <BR>
<BR>
Financial planners come from various backgrounds and hold various credentials.
These include Chartered Financial Consultants (ChFC), Certified Financial
Planners (CFP), and Certified Public Accountants (CPA). They're employed
by insurance companies, securities brokerage firms, banks, accounting firms
and independent companies.<BR>
<BR>
One reason for the variety is that individuals and families, like  companies,
need different financial advice as they grow and change. We asked a panel
of financial experts to advise us on the financial components of our most
important life phases.<BR>
<BR>
If you're thinking of hiring a financial advisor, remember that compensation
for these services varies. Some advisors charge a  fee only, while others
charge a fee plus commission or commission only. Still others make assets
under management arrangements. Be certain when employing these professionals
that you have a clear understanding of the services you will receive and
what the compensation arrangement will be.<BR>
<BR>
Here's what they told us. <BR>
<B><BR>
PHASE I:<BR>
MARRIAGE THROUGH CHILDREN'S COLLEGE<BR>
<BR>
Insurance Planning</B><BR>
<BR>
Some of the most difficult questions in financial planning for the young
family surround insurance.  Today these issues can be even more crucial
and confusing because of the  many companies that have downsized not just
employees, but benefit programs. Continually reviewing coverages and changing
needs has, therefore, become even more important. <BR>
<BR>
There are basic types of coverage that need to be purchased. If you are
a driver, you'll need automobile insurance to protect you in the event of
an accident. You will also need renters' or homeowners' insurance to protect
your family dwelling and its contents in the event of disaster or theft.
It makes sense to look into buying auto and home coverage together, as many
companies offer discounts of between 5 and 15 percent.<BR>
<BR>
Although in the past, major medical and healthcare coverage largely have
been provided by employers, over the past 10 years, more employees are being
required to pick up some or all of these costs. It's important to know what
is available and what and how you and your family are covered. Many employers
allow employees to pay their share of these costs through Section 125 Premium
Reduction Plans or cafeteria plans, an excellent tax savings tool that allows
you to permanently avoid paying federal, Social Security and in some cases
state income taxes on health insurance premiums.<BR>
<BR>
The other crucial insurance needs you will face are life insurance and disability
income replacement coverage. Like health insurance, part of these coverages
are sometimes provided by employers. But in today's world it is rare that
either of these risks are covered to the maximum.<BR>
<BR>
Life insurance has many different names and comes in many different types,
but all life insurance falls into two distinct types: temporary and permanent.
Temporary insurance, often referred to as term insurance, is designed for
short-term needs - generally less than 10 years - and is protection without
equity.<BR>
 <BR>
Permanent insurance is designed for longer periods of time or permanently.
Think of it like purchasing a home. While home ownership is generally more
expensive than renting, the monthly costs are fixed and go toward   building
equity in your home. The equity in a life insurance policy can be realized
 either by borrowing against it or surrendering the policy, much like selling
your home or borrowing against the equity in your home. These policies come
in many types, such as whole life, universal life or variable life.<BR>
<BR>
The most important consideration in buying life insurance is getting the
proper amount of coverage. A rule of thumb is 10 times your gross annual
earnings. Many young families purchase large amounts of term insurance and
then convert it as finances allow.<BR>
<BR>
The most overlooked of these basic insurance products is disability income
replacement. How long could your family survive if an accident or sickness
prevented you from earning? If you saved 10 percent of your income for 10
years, one year of disability would wipe out your nest egg. <BR>
An important tip: Don't just assume that if your employer provides disability
insurance  it is adequate. Most group policies have severe limitations and
will cover only the most catastrophic disabilities beyond two years. In
addition, most policies only replace 60 percent of your income. And as 
benefits received from these policies are taxable as ordinary income, your
net benefit after taxes will be somewhere from 35 to 40 percent of your
gross income. However,  if a disability policy is purchased and paid for
with after-tax dollars, benefits will be income-tax-free.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Investing </B>  <BR>
  <BR>
Most young families need to do many things to ready themselves to  save
for their children's college expenses. <BR>
<BR>
The first is to establish an emergency fund harboring three to six months
of family expenses in case of emergency. And if you're thinking about a
house, buy one. It's often the largest investment a family makes, and will
build equity that can be used later. Pay off outstanding loans, such as
college loans, credit cards and bank loans. Any that cannot be paid off
will be on-going expenses, such as a car loan, and should be added to the
family budget.<BR>
<BR>
If, after all these areas have been taken care of, additional income is
available for investment, start planning for your children's college expenses.
First, consider the age of the child and decide whether you're planning
for a public university, private college, graduate or professional school
or a combination of these. With the cost of education increasing at 7 to
10 percent annually, your goals are important, as they tell financial planners
how much money needs to be put away and the interest rate that needs to
be earned to achieve it. <BR>
<BR>
Other factors are important as well. Will the money be deposited monthly
from income, on a sporadic basis as it is available, or annually when company
bonuses are paid or tax refunds arrive?  Lastly, your advisor will help
you to determine your risk tolerance, or how much risk you are willing to
take with your investment.<BR>
<BR>
Next, your advisor will determine where to invest the money. Are savings
bonds at the bank best? Or would a mutual fund be better?  What about cash
value life insurance? Will  the parents be 59 1/2 when the child enters
college, making an annuity an option? <BR>
<BR>
Each has its benefits and disadvantages. Savings bonds are easily purchased
at the bank and are not subject to tax if being used for college. Their
drawback is that they earn between 3 and 5 percent per year. This &quot;interest&quot;
is not paid in cash, but is seen as an increase in the face amount of the
bond. <BR>
For example, a $100 savings bond can be purchased for $50 and matures in
15 years at $100. With savings bonds, it is important to make sure that
the bond matures during the time the child is in college, not five years
after the child graduates. The same holds true for other types of bonds,
but many pay monthly, quarterly or annual interest as well as increasing
the face value of the bond.<BR>
 Next are mutual funds. Some hold stocks, some bonds, some a combination
of both. Maturity dates  are of no concern, as these funds can be liquidated
at any time.  Mutual funds are professionally managed and will hopefully
perform better than market averages, reducing exposure to any one company's
performance by spreading risk over many companies. The No. 1 risk here is
that the market decreases just when money is needed for school and taxes
- for if the funds do well, taxes will be due on the gain. <BR>
<BR>
Part of this problem is solved by structuring the investment to reduce current
market volatility.  An investment professional is the best person to help
structure the funds and to determine any potential tax liability. Also consult
your accountant or tax advisor. <BR>
<BR>
Life insurance is another investment tool. Cash values can either be guaranteed
or variable (similar to investing in a mutual fund). There are ways to access
some of the cash value  to use it for education without paying taxes. A
life insurance professional is best consulted for help. <BR>
<BR>
Lastly, an annuity can be set up with either a guaranteed interest account
or a variable account. <BR>
Though earnings on an annuity accumulate tax deferred, all gains are taxable
when withdrawn. If the parent is not 59 1/2 at the time of distribution,
a 10 percent federal tax penalty applies. Note that the cash value in your
life insurance and annuities is not includable on financial aid forms.<BR>
<BR>
Next, the advisor will help to determine how this account should be titled.
Should the money be  in the parent's name?  Would a Uniform Transfer to
Minor's Account (UTMA) be beneficial? If insurance is the tool, who should
be insured?  Leaving money in the parent's name, either individually or
jointly, allows the parents to have total control of the money no matter
what. They also receive the tax bill. With a UTMA, taxes on the first $1,300
of interest each year can be paid at the child's tax rates, once they attain
age 14. But at 18 or 21 (depending on the state), the child has 100 percent
control of the money.<BR>
<BR>
Sometimes a grandparent, relative or friend wants to make a substantial
gift toward the child's education.  Any person is entitled to gift $10,000
per year with no gift tax liability. If invested in a mutual fund in the
first year of a child's life, $10,000 will yield enough money to pay for
a four-year degree at a public college. Again, consult your tax advisor.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Estate Planning<BR>
</B><BR>
At this stage of life, estate planning is probably simple. A will, power
of attorney and living will declaration are appropriate estate planning
documents for any single person to ensure their assets are managed  by a
person or institution of their choosing during a period of incapacity or
in the event of early death.<BR>
<BR>
Marriage may result in the retitling of most assets into joint names, in
order to ensure that the surviving spouse receives all assets at the other's
death. Death tax planning may not be a serious concern if the family's total
assets are under $600,000, which is the amount - sometimes called the &quot;Exemption
Amount&quot; - that any taxpayer can pass on to children or others free
of federal estate tax. New powers of attorney, living will declarations
and wills should also be signed after marriage.<BR>
<BR>
The birth of a first child is an appropriate time to review estate planning
documents. A guardian for the child should be named and the wills changed
to include a trust for the child if both parents are deceased.<BR>
<BR>
 <B>Tax Planning</B><BR>
<BR>
When it comes to tax planning, many people lose sight of the fact that reducing
your taxes is only one part of the overall financial planning puzzle. It
is important to keep in mind that the overall objective is to maximize after-tax
income, not to reduce taxes to the lowest amount. As many people learned
the hard way in the 1980s, real estate partnerships may have been effective
in reducing their taxes, but many turned out to be less than successful
investments.<BR>
<BR>
The most important step to take is to maximize participation in your company's
401(k) plan. Many company plans match a portion of their employees' contribution;
if you are not contributing to the plan or are not receiving the maximum
company match, you are passing up free money. Any taxes on earnings from
the plan are deferred until you begin to withdraw, which may not occur for
40 years. Given all the tax benefits of these plans, this can be the single
most important tax step you take.<BR>
<BR>
For many young couples, debt becomes a necessary evil; borrowing is necessary
to purchase cars, furnishings for homes and other assets. Frequently, these
purchases are made on credit cards, but remember, interest paid on these
cards is not tax-deductible. Consider a home equity loan to convert the
credit card debt from nondeductible personal interest to tax-deductible
home equity interest. Home equity lines usually offer lower rates of interest
than credit cards, but be careful. A home equity loan should be used only
to reduce borrowing costs, not as a vehicle to increase the amount you can
borrow.<BR>
<BR>
If both husband and wife work, leaving the child in day care, remember to
take advantage of the child care credit. This credit (which is a direct
tax reduction) can reduce taxes for a working couple with two children.
If your employer provides a dependent care account, review how this account
can further reduce taxes.<BR>
<BR>
<B>PHASE II:<BR>
EMPTY NEST UNTIL RETIREMENT<BR>
<BR>
Insurance Planning</B><BR>
<BR>
Many talk of the time when the children fly the coop as a time for a new
life. It's a new stage in your financial life as well.<BR>
<BR>
As we discussed earlier, it is smart to review insurance needs on a regular
basis. It's wise to convert term insurance to permanent insurance as the
need arises for survivor income, pension options or estate planning purposes.
Some products on the market today insure two people but pay on the death
of one of the insured. This ties in with estate tax planning, which is wise
to begin at this time, with a tax advisor and estate planner. Many property
and casualty insurance advisors are convinced of the importance of adding
an umbrella liability policy at this time. Automobile and homeowners' coverages
also should be reviewed.<BR>
<BR>
As retirement nears, find out what corporate benefits will be maintained.
This is also a time to look into nursing home or long-term care coverage.
Decide when to decrease or eliminate disability coverage; if you can comfortably
maintain your lifestyle in the event of a disability on your current assets,
you no longer need this coverage.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Investing</B><BR>
<BR>
Picture this: Your children have finally finished college and have moved
out on their own. You and your spouse are alone again after all these years.
You have probably paid off your house or are considering a smaller one.
You are earning more money now than in years past and have more to keep
for yourselves. <BR>
<BR>
Now's the time to take a long, hard look at what you need for retirement.
Will there be enough money in your corporate retirement plan? How will Social
Security affect you? What do you need to plan for in terms of retirement
expenses and goals (i.e., monthly living expenses, travel, property and
income taxes and inflation)? How can you determine if you are earning enough
money on your savings to provide for yourselves?<BR>
<BR>
    Once you have determined the answers to the above questions, you are
ready for the following questions about your corporate savings accounts.
Does your company have a retirement plan? How much are you contributing
to the plan on a monthly basis? Does the company maintain a defined benefit
plan, which provides a specific amount of money each year of your retirement?
Where are these monies invested now? Do you or does your company have control?
Do you have IRAs? What are they worth? Where are they invested? How are
they performing?<BR>
  <BR>
Now for your personal savings. How much money is there? Where is it, and
how  much is it earning? How much more do you need to contribute to reach
your goal at your current rate of return? Is there anything in your current
plan that can be reallocated to earn more money with fewer risks?<BR>
<BR>
You've now laid out your goals, the retirement plan amounts, savings amounts
and rates of return. Where do you go from here?  An evaluation by a professional
will tell you if you have the correct asset mix, and will determine the
products to fit your needs from an accumulation standpoint and a tax standpoint.
The largest portion of dollars earmarked for retirement, while you have
at least a five-year time horizon, should be invested in stocks to offset
the negative effects of inflation. Annual returns of the S &amp; P 500 Index
over a period of 68 years beginning in 1926 rose to a high of 54 percent
and fell to a low of 43 percent. If you take the same index in a 10-year
holding period, the high is 20 percent and the low is minus-1 percent. Due
to the long-term characteristics of retirement, the subsequent long-term
risk of stocks is palatable to most investors.<BR>
<BR>
Additionally, if you own a small business you should begin thinking about
structuring a succession plan. You need to allow adequate time and preparation
to structure this sale. Please note that lump sum buy-outs are infrequent,
and you may need to live with a 5- or 10-year payout from the new owner.
What if the business is going to your children? <BR>
 <BR>
Please consult your legal and tax advisor on this.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Estate Planning<BR>
</B><BR>
It is appropriate to review estate and lifetime planning documents every
three or four years or as changes occur in family circumstances, level of
assets, etc. At this phase of life, many families find their &quot;net worth&quot;
increasing because they have purchased additional insurance, equity in their
home is increasing, and additions are being made to 401(k)s, IRAs, pension
and profit-sharing plans, and other investment accounts. <BR>
<BR>
An increase in a family's net worth is an appropriate reason to review estate
and lifetime planning documents. As a family's net worth (including life
insurance at its &quot;face&quot; value or death benefit) exceeds the $600,000
Exemption Amount, estate planning documents would normally be changed to
include a planning technique known as a &quot;bypass&quot; trust, designed
to allow each spouse to place his or her $600,000 Exemption Amount into
a trust for the benefit of the surviving spouse, with the trust assets passing
at the death of both spouses to the children without federal estate tax
on the bypass trust assets. This planning technique is designed to ensure
that as much as $1,200,000 (representing the total of both spouses' $600,000
Exemption Amount) is passed down to the children free of federal estate
tax.<BR>
<BR>
The creation of a bypass trust in a will requires the selection of trustees
and successor trustees to administer the trust after the death of a spouse.
Likely candidates to serve as trustees are the surviving spouse; one or
more of the spouses' parents, if they are still &quot;young;&quot; siblings
of one or both spouses; banks or other institutions, etc. Trustees should
be comfortable managing and investing (or supervising others who manage
and invest) significant assets, making decisions about discretionary distributions,
etc. As the trust may continue for many years, it is important to select
successor trustees.<BR>
<BR>
Including bypass trust language in a will also requires changes in asset
ownership or beneficiary designations to ensure that the bypass trust can
be funded at death. Some assets previously titled in the spouses' joint
names are split into one spouse or the other's name. Insurance policies
name the trustee of the bypass trust as beneficiary, instead of naming the
other spouse.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Tax Planning</B><BR>
<BR>
At this point, you will probably be in your highest earning years - and
your highest tax bracket. Maximizing 401(k) contributions is crucial.<BR>
<BR>
An often overlooked planning idea is to make contributions to an individual
retirement plan. Even though the contribution may not be tax-deductible,
any earnings on the account are tax-deferred. Considering the ability to
make contributions for 10 to 15 years, the compounding effect can be significant.<BR>
<BR>
Another strategy is to invest in individual municipal bonds or municipal
bond mutual funds. The interest income is not subject to federal income
tax. Remember, however, the goal is to maximize after-tax wealth. Therefore,
you need to compare the earnings on your municipal investment to what you
would earn on a taxable investment after subtracting taxes. Often, your
marginal tax bracket will not justify investing in tax-free investments.<BR>
<BR>
<B>PHASE III:<BR>
RETIREMENT<BR>
<BR>
Insurance Planning</B><BR>
<BR>
You have finally reached the stage in life that you can begin to enjoy the
fruits of your hard work if you have planned well. The work that you have
done with your advisors should really begin to pay off.<BR>
<BR>
The first insurance issue you will be faced with is health insurance. If
you are still working full-time and your employer offers a health insurance
plan to its employees, you may be able to retain that coverage as your primary
health insurance plan. You may, however, choose  Medicare. <BR>
<BR>
Medicare coverage is part of the Social Security system and begins when
you reach age 65. Your spouse also qualifies for Medicare at age 65. There
are two parts to Medicare - Part A covers hospital expenses and is automatically
provided at age 65 at no cost, while Part B covers physician expenses. There
is an additional cost for Part B coverage, which is elective. But with only
Part A benefits, you pay: 
<UL>
  <LI>	Initial deductible for a hospital stay ($736 annually).
  <LI>  	$184 per day after the first 60 days in a hospital.
  <LI>	$92 per day from the 21st to the 100th day in a skilled nursing facility.
No benefits are available thereafter.
</UL>
<BR>
The supplementary medical insurance - Part B - has a $100 deductible followed
by a payment of 80 percent of the additional allowable charges.<BR>
<BR>
There are many exclusions within Medicare, including routine exams, eye
exams, glasses, hearing aids, dental care, most prescription drugs and most
immunizations<BR>
<BR>
To help supplement Medicare coverage, many individuals purchase insurance
policies. These policies are often referred to as &quot;Medigap&quot; policies
and are sold in ten different standardized plans. Each plan should be reviewed
carefully to select the best fit.  Many HMOs (health maintenance organizations)
now offer Medicare coverage that includes preventive care as well as dental
and eye coverage.<BR>
 <BR>
Another area of insurance that should not be overlooked is long term care.
For many Americans, the fear of going into a nursing home and seeing all
of their assets used to pay for their care is a frightening thought.  Horror
stories about people who saw significant sums of wealth consumed in their
final years in a nursing home abound.<BR>
<BR>
Obviously, if an individual has enough wealth to pay for his or her own
care, these policies aren't needed. If an individual has few assets, he
or she may qualify for nursing home care under Medicaid.<BR>
 <BR>
However, Medicaid limits your choice of nursing homes and requires that
you substantially deplete any assets you may have. Average nursing home
costs vary geographically and depend on the level of care you require. However,
the average in western Pennsylvania is $30,000 &shyp; $45,000 annually.<BR>
Long-term care insurance policies vary widely. As with any insurance policy,
the decision to select a particular policy should be based on a thorough
and careful review with a knowledgeable advisor. The policy that is right
for you depends on a myriad of issues, such as the level of care desired,
the personal desires of the insured, the desire to leave wealth to other
beneficiaries, the degree of independence desired and other factors. And
don't overlook home healthcare. Although nursing home care is the most expensive
portion of long-term care, many of   us are in a better position to afford
it than we are home healthcare. Many policies will cover home healthcare
too.<BR>
<BR>
Your life insurance policies should be reviewed to make sure they are operating
as planned for. Check your ownership and beneficiary designations and make
any appropriate changes. <BR>
<BR>
Another item to take care of is paying off any outstanding policy loans.
Money in a bank account or investment vehicle goes into probate and a portion
could be lost to taxes. Since the proceeds of life insurance will avoid
probate, having the money in an insurance policy will ensure that it gets
to your beneficiaries quickly and will avoid the costs of probate. <BR>
<BR>
How much life insurance you need will depend on your particular situation.
Issues to consider are:
<UL>
  <LI>	Does my spouse need additional income if I die?
  <LI>	Would I be better off having life insurance to continue income to
my survivors, allowing me to maximize my retirement income?
  <LI>	What is the best way to pay estate taxes at my death and my spouse's
to minimize what I owe the government?
</UL>
<BR>
<B>Investing<BR>
</B><BR>
Hopefully you have been successful in realizing your investment objectives.
How do you make sure that you do not &quot;out live&quot; your money?<BR>
<BR>
Structure investments to provide a specific amount of monthly or annual
income to meet your needs. This includes Social Security, pension plans,
401(k) plans and other assets you have accumulated. Most people think they
need to be as conservative as possible with their investments.<BR>
 This is not always the best policy, for inflation decreases the value of
the dollars we have saved. <BR>
How can we keep our income up to speed? Investing a portion of assets  in
equities that appreciate over time will offset increases in the cost of
living. Stocks are a great way to earn positive average annual returns after
taxes and inflation. Discuss portfolio allocations with an investment professional
to obtain a mix tailored  appropriately for you.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Estate Planning<BR>
</B><BR>
Estate and lifetime planning documents should be reviewed in significant
detail at this phase of life. The family's assets have probably continued
to increase, especially after all children have completed college, and the
relative proportions of various assets in the family's portfolio of assets
may change significantly during this phase of life. Pension and profit-sharing
plans, 401(k)s and IRAs may now be the family's largest assets, and their
value may be increasing dramatically because of tax-deferral and strong
market performance. The amount of life insurance may be increasing or decreasing
dramatically, depending on the family's needs. Children are  now adults
and it may be appropriate to name them as successor executors, co-trustees
or successor trustees, replacing the spouse's parents, siblings, banks or
other financial institutions. <BR>
<BR>
Coordination of substantial     non-probate assets (insurance, IRAs, 401
(k)s, pension and profit-sharing plans, annuities, etc.) with the estate
documents is crucial to successful estate planning during this phase of
life. Future income tax consequences of beneficiary designations on tax-deferred
assets (401(k)s, IRAs, lump sums, etc.) must be carefully considered. <BR>
<BR>
Estate plans will often name the spouse as the beneficiary of the tax-deferred
assets because of favorable income tax treatment available only to the spouse
as beneficiary. When a participant in a tax-deferred plan reaches his or
her &quot;required beginning date&quot; (April 1 of the year following the
year in which they are 70 1/2 years old), estate planning documents and
beneficiary designations should once again be reviewed and perhaps changed.<BR>
<BR>
A revocable living trust may be substituted for a will during this phase
or an earlier phase of life, depending on the family's assets and circumstances.
Revocable living trusts avoid probate and offer heightened privacy for the
family's estate plan and assets.<BR>
<BR>
If relocation outside of Pennsyl-vania occurs upon retirement, an estate
planner in the new state should carefully review all estate and lifetime
planning documents to be sure they're in accord with that state's rules.<BR>
<BR>
More sophisticated estate planning techniques might be considered at this
time if the family assets substantially exceed $1,200,000 (the total amount
sheltered by both spouses' $600,000 Exemption Amount). Irrevocable life
insurance trust agreements or other irrevocable transfers of the ownership
of life insurance might be considered to remove these assets from the taxable
estate. <BR>
<BR>
A gifting program designed to take advantage of tax rules allowing $10,000
gifts each year to an unlimited number of donees (children, grandchildren,
etc.) should be considered if there are more than enough assets for the
spouses to live on for the rest of their lives. Gifted assets must be selected
carefully because of possible capital gains tax consequences (to donees
when they sell gifted assets), but gifted assets are thereafter sheltered
from Pennsylvania inheritance tax and federal estate tax at the donor's
death.<BR>
<BR>
Also at this time, review lifetime planning documents (powers of attorney
and living will declarations) to be sure that appropriate successor attorneys
under powers of attorney and successor surrogate decision-makers under living
will declarations are selected. Again, perhaps your children should now
replace siblings, elderly parents, etc., in these roles. <BR>
<BR>
Ensure that your parents (who now may be 85 years old or older) have reviewed
their own estate and lifetime planning documents to be sure powers of attorney
are in place, appropriate tax-saving trusts are utilized, gift giving is
being considered, etc.<BR>
<BR>
<B>Tax Planning</B><BR>
<BR>
At retirement, when all your children have left home, you may consider selling
your home. Remember, the IRS gives you a special $125,000 exclusion  on
the gain from the sale of your principal residence if you are age 55 or
older. This is one of the few &quot;freebies&quot; the IRS gives you.<BR>
At age 70 1/2, minimum distributions need to begin from your retirement
plan accounts. Generally, these may occur over your and your spouse's life
expectancies. You can minimize the yearly distributions by annually recalculating
your life expectancy. However, the recalculation method may cause accelerated
distributions at your deaths. Be sure to evaluate the  method that works
best for you from an income tax standpoint for your life and the life of
future beneficiaries.<BR>
<BR>
As you move through your life, keep in mind that your objective is     to
maximize your after-tax rate            of return and not just minimize
    your taxes. Taxes are just one          component of your overall  
          financial plan and any tax planning must  be evaluated relative
to your other goals.<BR>
<BR>
<B>SUMMARY: <BR>
IT'S YOUR PLAN</B><BR>
<BR>
Financial planning is an integrated process, since a change in one area
invariably changes another. To ensure that the plans you've worked a lifetime
to create are carried out according  to your wishes, it would be prudent
to introduce your heirs to your advisors so that everyone is on the same
page.  <BR>
<BR>
In addition, if your advisors have done a good job for you, they can also
help the rest of your family create their financial plans. <BR>
<BR>
These plans will evolve and change as families grow and mature and their
assets increase. They should be reviewed at least every three to four years
throughout your life.<BR>
 <BR>
It's your plan. Make it reflect your life.                             
                          <BR>
